<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS'-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETTORI GAINS REDEMPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ To American fans, Europe's most flamboyant
jockey might forever have been known for the strange ride he gave
Swain in the 1998 Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday at Gulfstream Park, Frankie Dettori gave us
something better to remember him by.
</P>
<P>
   Dettori gave Daylami a flawless ride as they rallied from
seventh to a 2{-length victory over Royal Anthem in the $2 million
Breeders' Cup Turf. Afterward, the 28-year-old Italian performed
his famous flying dismount and then took off on his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping God would give me a clear path,'' he said,
``because I knew the press was waiting for me to (bleep) up
again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I made a mistake,'' he said of letting Swain drift out in
the final strides of the '98 Classic, seeming to cost the
Arab-owned horse the one-length margin of defeat as he finished
third to Awesome Again and Silver Charm. ``But don't judge me on
one ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Daylami was Dettori's second Breeders' Cup winner. He rode
Barathea in the 1994 Mile at Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time to get over Swain,'' he said. ``Revenge
is a plate you eat cold, and mine is freezing, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough luck: Although Artax equaled Mr. Prospector's track record
and broke Elmhurst's Breeders' Cup with his 1:07.89 Sprint victory,
runner-up Kona Gold might have been better.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped an uncharacteristic four lengths off the pace and
rallied at the rail _ on a day when that style wasn't working _ to
lose by a half-length.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kona Gold) slipped a little bit behind when the gates
opened,'' said jockey Alex Solis, who finished second for the sixth
time without winning in the Breeders' Cup. ``I wish the race had
been 25 yards longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the trend: The Thoroughbred Corp.'s Anees, in the
Juvenile, was the only winner all day to come from off the pace. He
was 14th and last early in the 1 1/16-mile race before contract
jockey Gary Stevens weaved through and around traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned all day long (about the apparent track
bias),'' trainer Alex Hassinger said after the son of 1990 Kentucky
Derby and Breeders' Cup Classic winner Unbridled scored his first
stakes victory. ``We changed the track bias.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger, nephew of Breeders' Cup inventor John Gaines, won the
1992 Juvenile Fillies at Gulfstream with Eliza.
</P>
<P>
   Canani exacta: Julio Canani not only trains Mile winner Silic _
who was coming off a pretty win in the Oak Tree Mile _ but he
trained runner-up Tuzla until an ownership change sent the mare to
Bob Baffert in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fresh horse,'' Canani said after his first Breeders'
Cup win. ``It feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   Send Cash: The $520,000 Juvenile Fillies winner's purse comes at
a good time for Cash Run owner Satish Sanan, the India-born
software magnate whose IMRglobal Inc. stock has dived recently.
</P>
<P>
   Sanan admits cash-flow problems and plans to auction off some
weanlings and broodmares next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market, you and I don't control it,'' Sanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Along for the ride: Jorge Chavez earned his first Breeders' Cup
victory in 20 tries by hanging on as Beautiful Pleasure set a :22
4/5-:46 2/5-1:09 4/5 pace in the Distaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going fast,'' said the 37-year-old Peruvian.
``But there was nothing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Banshee Breeze, written off by workout clockers, became the
threat in the stretch as favorite Silverbulletday faded at the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to show her my stick and she kept going,''
Chavez said of Beautiful Pleasure, who clinched the
fillies-and-mares championship with her third straight Grade I win.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Frankelly: Bobby Frankel blamed jockey Kent Desormeaux
for Keeper Hill's fourth-place finish in the Distaff. Keeper Hill
was closer to the pace than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad (bleeping) ride,'' the trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Phoenix: Soaring Softly's victory in the inaugural Filly
and Mare Turf put a new high in trainer Jim Toner's year of highs
and lows. Toner lost three horses in a Belmont Park barn fire in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Soaring Softly) meant a lot to us this year,'' said Toner,
59, after his first Breeders' Cup victory. ``There was so much
adversity, but we always had her to look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate bought: Frank Stronach announced he has added Golden
Gate Fields, in the San Francisco Bay Area, to holdings that
already included Santa Anita, Gulfstream Park, Remington Park in
Oklahoma and Thistledown in Ohio. He said he has ``expressed
interest'' in Monmouth Park in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The long-rumored Golden Gate Fields purchase from Ladbroke cost
$87 million.
</P>
<P>
   The auto-components magnate and racehorse owner indicated his
tracks won't contribute to the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association until the sport's putative governing body defines a
``clearer mandate.'' The NTRA contracts of 74 NTRA-member tracks
run to April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Fans around the world bet $99.8 million into the
Gulfstream Park pools Saturday, a Breeders' Cup record, beating
last year's. . . . A Lady From Dixie, who would have been a Distaff
long shot, was the only Breeders' Cup scratch. D. Wayne Lukas said
he didn't want to aggravate a tendon problem. . . . Playboy
publisher Hugh Hefner _ with five blondes _ sat near the press box
to watch a colt with his name run 13th in the Juvenile. One of
Hefner's dates stood up during the Filly and Mare Turf and caused
several reporters to miss the race. . . . Nice touch: The Breeders'
Cup jockeys were introduced to the crowd and lined up in the
winner's circle before the first race. . . . ID, please: Frank
Stronach said he was late for a morning press conference because a
Gulfstream Park parking attendant wouldn't let him in. ``It's nice
to know we don't play favorites,'' the track chairman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
