<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-COLORADO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Eyeing a climb in rankings, Kansas State wards off Colorado 20-14
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MANHATTAN, Kan. _ With just more than six minutes remaining
Saturday at KSU Stadium, the public address announcer informed the
50,000-plus Wildcats loyalists watching Kansas State play Colorado
that Minnesota had completed its upset of previously unbeaten Penn
State, news that turned Harley Davidson Day into a Night at the
Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat people had ample reason to cheer, their undefeated and
sixth-ranked heroes seemingly well on their way to beating
Colorado. But some of those present, particularly those wearing
K-State uniforms, became a little queasy, a feeling that
intensified when Colorado scored on a long pass a moment later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about being in the Dome last year, playing A&AMP;M, and
said, `Please, God, don't let it happen again,''' said K-State
defensive end Monty Beisel.
</P>
<P>
   In a performance remniscent of last year's Big 12 title game,
where the then-unbeaten Wildcats lost a 15-point lead to the Aggies
in St. Louis' Trans World Dome after hearing that UCLA's
unblemished record had been ruined by Miami, K-State let a big lead
slip away against Colorado in the fourth quarter but was able to
hang on for a 20-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had a 20-0 cushion before the Buffaloes scored on
passes of 64 and 70 yards from Mike Moschetti to Javon Green in the
final 6:21.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later if the Wildcats had recorded an ``ugly'' win,
K-State coach Bill Snyder was not in a mood to argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was pretty ugly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The K-State offense was beyond ugly at times, producing just 197
yards and 10 first downs. Snyder replaced starting quarterback
Jonathan Beasley with backup Adam Helm one series into the second
half and then went back to Beasley with the game in the balance in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Wildcats' defensive effort was about as
good as it gets. K-State obliterated the Colorado running game,
allowing the Buffs to net only 10 yards, and harassed Moschetti,
sacking him five times and recording three interceptions. Before
Moschetti and Green hooked up on their first scoring play, the
Buffs had recorded only five first downs and had crossed midfield
just two times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the K-State defense) played a great game,'' said
linebacker Mark Simoneau, who finished with nine unassisted
tackles, including two sacks. ``Unfortunately, we gave up those two
long plays. That kind of spoils an exceptional game.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the Wildcats are 9-0 and due to rise in the
rankings as a result of Penn State's loss, a backdrop that will
increase the stakes when K-State faces Nebraska in Lincoln this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't really been tested this season when we had a lead,''
said Beisel, whose sack helped stop Colorado's final drive. ``Going
into Nebraska week, we needed something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops Colorado to 5-4 and 4-2, although the Buffs
should get their sixth _ and bowl-qualifying _ win at Baylor this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't run the ball, things cannot happen,'' CU coach
Gary Barnett said. ``The lack of a running game has hurt us all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the way the K-State defense was swarming, the Wildcats'
20-0 lead looked pretty stout when the PA announcer informed the
purple horde of Minnesota's 24-23 upset of Penn State. But then,
just seconds after the announcement, Moschetti hit Green on a post
route for 64 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The next K-State series went nowhere and consumed less than two
minutes, giving Colorado the ball at its 30. One play later,
Moschetti connected with Green on a short sideline route, and the
junior receiver shook loose for the 70-yard play that made it
20-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two shots at him that I saw,'' Snyder said. ``It was
really an eight-yard gain. We just missed tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   With Beasley back at quarterback but no more effective than he
had been earlier, K-State again failed to produce a clock-consuming
drive and had to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado got the ball at its 38 with 1:59 remaining. On first
down, Moschetti was sacked by Beisel for a three-yard loss.
Moschetti then threw incomplete three times, allowing K-State to
regain possession with 30 seconds showing.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats would live to play another day as an unbeaten,
although it certainly hadn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know next week we'll have to play a whole lot better,''
Beasley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
