<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UH-Tulane-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sanford and run a winning combination for Houston
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
With day having turned into night, University of Houston safety
Kenny Hill knew the last play of the game might be coming his way.
And, with Hill's stop of Tulane receiver Kerwin Jones, the Cougars
survived for a 36-31 victory over the Green Wave on Saturday at
Robertson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ketric Sanford rushed for 212 yards and two touchdowns while
setting Houston's all-time rushing record. Teammate Mike Green
added 118 rushing yards and another TD. But Hill's 75-yard
interception return for a fourth-quarter touchdown finally proved
to be the difference.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a wild, sometimes puzzling 3 hours, 33 minutes, UH
had seen Tulane's run-and-shoot-type passing game amass 27
offense-generated first downs and 531 yards on 97 plays against a
Cougar defense ranked 10th nationally. That production came despite
starting quarterback Patrick Ramsey missing most of the fourth
quarter for Tulane with an injured shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey returned for the final pass from the UH 45, and Hill
dropped Jones at the 27 on fourth down with five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a long way to go and were out of timeouts, so the
main thing was not to let anyone get behind us and then just make a
sure tackle,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford and Green powered the Cougars (5-4, 2-3 in Conference
USA) to a 27-10 lead early in the third quarter, but the offense
then produced just three first downs and 152 yards in the second
half. Tulane dropped to 3-6, 1-4 but not without a fight to the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   While increasing his career rushing total to 3,424 yards with
former record-holder Chuck Weatherspoon watching from the stands,
Sanford also staged the most productive UH rushing performance
since Jermaine Williams ran for 215 yards against SMU in 1995.
Weatherspoon's career total was 3,247 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get the (rushing) record with all the great running backs
that have been through here really means a lot, as much as anything
I've ever done,'' Sanford said. ``It will take some time for it to
set in. The people don't see the work the offensive line did to
make it possible, and Mike is a big bruiser who comes in there and
makes a lot of guys hesitate to try and hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   UH coach Kim Helton was proud of Sanford, whose 26 career
touchdowns rushing leave him one shy of Weatherspoon's school
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone could carry the banner of being the
all-time leading rusher with more prestige,'' Helton said. ``He's
everything you want in a student, in a player and in a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanford's 63-yard run on the first play after halftime set up
Jason McKinley's 13-yard scoring pass to Brandon Middleton, giving
UH a 17-point lead at the 12:41 mark of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramsey's 20-yard scoring strike to Jones enabled Tulane to
rally back following punter Casey Roussel's 28-yard pass to Jones
on a fake punt.
</P>
<P>
   A rare fumble by Sanford, his first in 385 carries, receptions
or kick returns over 19 games, then led to an 18-yard touchdown
pass to Adrian Burnette by Ramsey, who completed 26 of 55 for 360
yards on the day. The Wave's second TD in 47 seconds made it a
27-24 ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Roussel ran down a snap over his head deep in
Tulane's end, turned and kicked the ball through the end zone.
Officials signaled a safety for Houston, then ruled an illegal kick
and awarded UH possession at the 14. The Cougars failed to
capitalize, but, on Tulane's ensuing play, Hill returned a fumble
16 yards for an apparent touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of UH penalties (among 13 for 128 yards in the game)
nullified Hill's TD and the Cougars settled for a 43-yard Mike
Clark field goal and a 30-24 lead with 9:50 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Hill then ended Tulane's next possession with his 75-yard
interception runback, aided by a pair of blocks by Sam Hairston.
But Derrick Joseph, a redshirt freshman who backs up Ramsey,
directed a 70-yard scoring drive, running the final five yards with
2:34 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   More than three hours earlier, the first of Mike James' two
interceptions preceded Sanford's 22-yard burst for the game's
opening score. Green powered for 39 and Sanford gained 29 before
Sanford's three-yard TD run.
</P>
<P>
   Green's eight-yard run made it 20-10 at halftime after Seth
Marler's 48-yard field goal and Ramsey's 12-yard pass to Jones
accounted for Tulane's scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane, playing the Cougars without an injured JaJuan Dawson,
the nation's No. 3 receiver, and starting tailback Toney Converse,
had been outscored 101-14 by Memphis and East Carolina in its
previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can lose by one or you can lose by 50, but a loss is still
a loss no matter how good you play,'' Tulane coach Chris Scelfo
said. ``The previous six quarters we were in a funk, but scoring 31
points and moving the ball the way we did against the 10th-ranked
defense in the country is something to point to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
