<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-IOWAST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Timely defense gets Tech past Iowa St.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ Darren Davis had the football in his hands 874 times over
a span of more than two years without committing a fumble. The Iowa
State tailback was one step away from giving his team the lead over
Texas Tech in the fourth quarter when his amazing streak came to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Tech linebacker Tim Duffie forced the fumble at the one, and
cornerback Antwan Alexander recovered it in the end zone, ending
the threat and helping the Red Raiders earn a 28-16 victory over
the Cyclones Saturday at Jones Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was huge,'' said Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes.
``Davis just doesn't fumble, so you really have to give our guys
credit. I think we played about as solid a football game as you can
play. A lot of people had given up on this team and sold them out,
but our kids are very resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory by Tech (5-4, 4-2 Big 12) set up a showdown vs.
Texas for the Big 12 South lead next weekend at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (4-5, 1-5) trailed 21-16 Saturday when Davis fumbled
for only the second time in his career. His previous fumble came
against Texas A&AMP;M on Oct. 11, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the play was over, but I guess it was my time to let
it go,'' said Davis, the Big 12's leading rusher with 1,260 yards.
``That hurt really bad, but I have to keep my head up and bounce
back from it. I was just trying to reach for the goal line, and it
came out.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the game still was in doubt until the crowd of
41,691 watched Tech tailback Shaud Williams break free on a 47-yard
touchdown run with 6:47 to play. Williams took a sprint-draw
handoff and headed toward the sideline. It appeared he would be
stopped at the ISU 25, but he cut back across the field and raced
to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The man who made the key block on the cut back was Tech
quarterback Rob Peters, who took out two ISU defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about the only block I've had,'' said Peters, a Katy
High product. ``I think those guys were falling down, and I just
got in front of them. I was hustling down field, because I know if
you get in front of Shaud, he can make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Before thwarting Davis in the fourth quarter, the Tech defense
came up with a big goal-line stand in the second. the Raiders led
14-6 when the Cyclones had two chances inside the Tech one.
Surprisingly, Iowa State did not give the ball to Davis on either
play. Quarterback Sage Rosenfels kept it on third down, and
Rosenfels attempted a rollout pass on fourth down that was
deflected by Tech safety Kevin Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   The goal-line stand seemed to inspire the Tech offense, which
marched 99 yards on seven plays to take a 21-6 lead on a 26-yard
pass from Peters to Darrell Jones with 4:14 to go in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State trailed 21-9 at the half, but a seven-yard run by
Davis capped an 83-yard drive in the third quarter to make it
21-16. Davis, who finished with 98 yards on 26 carries, was one
foot away from scoring again when the law of averages caught up
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto is to make the other team put the ball on the
ground,'' said Tech defensive end Taurus Rucker. ``We noticed that
Davis does a lot of spinning, so we felt we could get the ball out
of there. It couldn't have happened at a better time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
