<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-FRESNOST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fresno State displaces Owls in WAC driver's seat 47-18
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FRESNO, Calif. _ There were a lot of words spoken softly in the
Rice locker room on Saturday. The Owls let a key conference road
game get out of hand early and never caught up. And the postseason
ramifications were not lost on the sullen squad in the post-mortem.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State scored 20 first-quarter points, then cruised to a
47-18 win over the Owls before 39,097 at Bulldog Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (7-3) took the lead in the Western Athletic
Conference chase away from the Owls, upping their record in the
conference to 4-1. Running back Derrick Ward rushed for 148 yards,
and quarterback Billy Volek threw three touchdown passes in a
12-for-15 day.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls (5-5, 4-2) continued an unfortunate trend of the three
previous years by losing a key conference game on the road late in
the season. Depth-sapping injuries played a factor this time, as
did as poor tackling and the Bulldogs' controlling the line of
scrimmage on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno outgained Rice 478 yards to 222. And in a rare occurrence
for the Owls, Rice threw for 123 yards while running for just 99 on
46 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real upset,'' said Rice quarterback Chad Richardson, whose
17 carries netted 11 yards, 62 below his rushing average. ``I just
don't really know what happened. I'll have to look at the film. It
just hurts right now. It's been a dream of mine my whole life to
get to a bowl. We were this close again for four years in a row,
and it's hard to take. I am speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice will have to defeat Texas-El Paso on Saturday at Rice
Stadium to have its sixth win and be bowl-qualified. The Owls also
will have to have someone else beat Fresno to give them a chance at
a tie for the WAC championship.
</P>
<P>
   Rice safety Jason Hebert said he ached after the defeat but that
all is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any loss is going to hurt, no matter who it is,'' Hebert said.
``Considering the circumstances, this is a big blow to us. As bad
as it hurts, we have to put it behind us. We need to focus on
getting a winning record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fresno defense delivered a message to start the game. Rice
started from its 18 after the kickoff and had to punt after three
rushing plays netted minus-three yards.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno took over on its 47 and scored eight plays later when
Volek scored on a one-yard plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Rice then started on its 11-yard line and again had to punt
after three plays netted nine yards. Fresno started its second
possession at its 44 and scored nine plays later on a 20-yard pass
from Volek to running back Paris Gaines for a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern continued. Rice started its third drive at its 20
but had to punt on fourth-and-16 from the 14. Fresno then was
pretty much able to knock out the Owls on its next possession _
which lasted only one play and was as embarrassing as anything the
Rice defense has suffered all year.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the Rice 49, Volek handed off to wingback
Rodney Wright _ who had gone in motion behind the quarterback and
had taken a similar handoff for a 21-yard gain around end on
Fresno's initial play of the game. This time, however, Wright
stopped in the backfield and lofted a wobbly pass high into the
air. Bulldogs receiver Saleem Mahdi outjumped two Rice defenders to
pull down the ball around the 20, broke a tackle and then scooted
in for a score. The run for PAT failed, but Fresno had a 20-0 lead
and every bit of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big, a very big play in the game,'' Hebert said.
``It's plays like that that will kill you. You don't want them to
happen, but you just look past it.''
</P>
<P>
   It typified a poor performance by the Rice defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't tackle well,'' said Owls coach Ken Hatfield.
``That's the most disappointing thing. We didn't get off blocks.
They are big and strong, and that was probably the best running
game they have had all year. We were worn out, and it just seemed
to take its toll on us after 10 weeks. We just couldn't get off
blocks. Our kids were worn out. It looked like they were running in
mud.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Crabtree kicked a 27-yard field to get Rice within 27-10
with 2:14 remaining in the second quarter. Fresno then fumbled the
ensuing kickoff at its 18 but managed to recover the ball to keep
the Owls from getting anything more before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno scored on its first possession of the second half, and
the game was over for all intents and purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to keep their chins up, Rice's players remembered they
still have a chance to do next week what hasn't been done since the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win next week means that our seniors will have winning
seasons in three of their four years,'' Hatfield said, ``and that
hasn't happened in many years (since the Owls had three winning
seasons between 1960-63). So we have a lot to play for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
