<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lukas' Breeders' Cup dominance continues
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HALLANDALE, Fla. _ Saturday's Breeders' Cup was supposed to be Bob
Baffert's show. Or a James Bond thriller. But it was neither.
Instead, it was the Ol' Reliable, D. Wayne Lukas, upstaging and
upsetting everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, the modish, hip, laid-back Californian, had eight
entrants going for the $13 million in purses at Gulfstream Park. He
had the best 3-year-old filly, Silverbulletday, and the best
2-year-old, Chilukki, and he had the favorite in the Sprint,
Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   All three lost.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Bond, ready to anoint the mighty Behrens as Horse
of the Year. He was favored to win the $4 million Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But Lukas knocked off Chilukki with a 32-1 shot, Cash Run, and
he shot down Behrens with the recycled Cat Thief, who went off at
19-1 for the 1\-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has won a record 15 Breeders' Cup races, couldn't
resist chortling, ``I guess this Horse of the Year race is turned
upside-down.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Breeders' Cup, which was supposed to resolve the
issue, only created more questions.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption was that if Behrens lost, the mantle would pass
to Silverbulletday, who had won eight of 10 races this year and
$1.71 million in purses, compared with $1.74 million for Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   But Silverbulletday ran like she had lead in her saddlebags. She
finished seventh in the Distaff _ and bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just tried to get too much out of her,'' Baffert
said. ``I was hoping we could get one more race.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no excuse for Behrens, the 2-1 favorite who never had
finished worse than second in eight starts this year. Bond had
trained him judiciously, passing up chances for fat purses to make
sure he was fresh and fit for this race. But like Silverbulletday,
he ran seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes some days,'' said Bond. ``What can you
do?''
</P>
<P>
   You could do like Lukas and just keep trying new techniques to
bring a horse to his potential.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief had been dismissed by most observers as a 3-year-old
colt who could pick up, at most, some place or show money in Grade
I competition. He had won only once in 11 starts this year.
</P>
<P>
   His owner, 82-year-old William T. Young, noted, ``Everyone said
we ran the horse too much and he couldn't run a mile and a
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, 64, said, ``I changed up on this horse a lot. I tried
everything I know to get him to relax. I felt the last three weeks
I finally got the number on this one. You just can't emphasize
enough the experience factor in training horses. You make a lot of
mistakes and you learn from them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his changes was to apply the latest breathing aid, a
nasal strip. Lukas used it on all his horses Saturday. In fact, 28
percent of the Breeders' Cup horses had nasal strips, and 40
percent of the winners had them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen any research on it,'' Lukas said. ``We don't
know if it's good, bad or indifferent. But I figured it couldn't
hurt, so stick them on.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have made a difference in the case of Cat Thief, who had
a tendency to run out of wind after 1[ miles.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's Classic, Cat Thief did his usual quick burst to
the front of the pack, but this time he lasted the distance. He
took the lead from the fading Old Trieste at the mile and stretched
out to a 1\-length victory over the steady-running Budroyale.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief's jockey, Pat Day, said, ``I don't know what Wayne did
differently to prepare him, but he was much more relaxed today than
he was when I've ridden him before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat Thief was the perfect gentleman, the picture of composure.
He got some pressure at the half-mile pole, but then he accelerated
for three or four jumps and then just sort of coasted around the
turn. I was concerned that he was using himself too early, but he
was pulling away at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his $2 million purse for the Classic makes Cat Thief
the No. 1 North American equine earner of the year, at just under
$3 million, his inconsistency rules out Horse of the Year
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   So who, then?
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that if Behrens and Silverbulletday faltered
Saturday, the next candidates were Lemon Drop Kid, General
Challenge and River Keen. But they finished sixth, 10th and 11th in
the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Chilukki, owned by Houstonians Bob and Janice McNair, could have
laid claim to the most coveted of racing awards. But her second
place in the Juvenile Fillies won't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas is touting his Kentucky Derby/Preakness Stakes winner,
Charismatic. But voters are reluctant to support a horse who
retired before the year was half-over.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some consideration will go to Artax, who equaled a track
record with his 1:07.89 for six furlongs in Saturday's Breeders'
Cup Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Artax recently broke track records set by Dr. Fager and Groovy,
and he's best known for taking a punch from a drunken, disturbed
fan during a race on Preakness Day.
</P>
<P>
   Is that enough to make him Horse of the Year? Well, who's left?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
