</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--Texas-OSU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas beats Oklahoma St. to the draw
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
STILLWATER, Okla. _ When you draw something up, it should look
good.
</P>
<P>
   When you dream about how it will work, it should look even
better.
</P>
<P>
   When Greg Davis' draw (play) met Hodges Mitchell's dream on the
first play from scrimmage in Saturday's Texas-Oklahoma State game,
the result was perfection. And perfection indeed looked good.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell took a handoff from Major Applewhite, exploded off the
left side, spun Cowboys safety Adam Edwards like a top at midfield
and raced 80 yards for a touchdown to give Texas the lead after
just 18 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The run was part of a 20-carry, 149-yard effort by Mitchell, who
scored two other touchdowns to lead Texas to a 34-21 win over
Oklahoma State before 44,025 at Lewis Field.
</P>
<P>
   With the win and Texas A&AMP;M's loss to Nebraska, Texas (8-2, 5-1
Big 12) can clinch the Big 12 South title by beating Texas Tech on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud that this team could focus and not think about Tech
and what that could mean for us,'' Applewhite said. ``We were able
to be focused and play well against a dangerous team, right from
the start.''
</P>
<P>
   It began with Davis, the Longhorns' offensive coordinator, and
his quite unusual call of a draw play to open the game. Typically,
draw plays are set up during a game by a team's passing.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the Longhorns' penchant for throwing and Oklahoma
State's similar love for blitzing made the play a good call even as
an opener. When Mitchell was told Friday what play would be run to
start the game, he dreamed about it going the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that all day that's the power of the mind,''
said Mitchell, who became the eighth Texas back to rush for more
than 1,000 yards in a season. ``It (rushing for 1,000 yards) was a
goal of mine at the beginning of the season, but really I didn't
think I would have that many opportunities. I thought I would have
more yards receiving than rushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell does have 29 receptions for 304 yards, making him the
only back in Texas history to post 300 yards receiving and 1,000
yards rushing in the same season. The player many thought could not
replace Ricky Williams has done something Williams never did.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State pulled even at 7 early in the second quarter on a
seven-yard touchdown run by quarterback Tony Lindsay, but the
Longhorns took the lead for good on Mitchell's 17-yard run just
before the half.
</P>
<P>
   The three-play, 44-yard drive was set up by Aaron Humphrey's
second fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite hit freshman tight end Bo Scaife and wideout Montrell
Flowers for a gains of 20 and seven yards before Mitchell followed
fullback Ricky Brown and guard Cory Quye around the right side for
the score.
</P>
<P>
   While Mitchell had a good day, OSU could muster no ground game.
Texas' defense controlled the line of scrimmage, giving up just 84
yards rushing on 41 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Nathan Simmons managed just 21 yards on nine carries
before leaving with a banged up knee. Jamaal Fobbs had a little
more success, with 57 yards on 10 attempts, but 25 came on one
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns had 13 tackles for losses, seven sacks and forced
five fumbles, recovering two. Greg Brown had an interception return
for a touchdown in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's score came on Oklahoma State's first possession after
the half. Humphrey got a piece of a Lindsay pass and Brown stepped
in, bobbled the ball a little but snatched it out of the air and
raced 31 yards for a touchdown to give Texas a 21-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Man, I better catch this, or the guys will
kill me,''' Brown said. ``I don't think I would have ever lived
that down. It's been a long time since the Texas defense scored
(1995) and it's good to get us into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Applewhite (23-of-44, 242 yards) started
finding the mark, completing five straight passes in an eight-play,
65-yard drive, but again Mitchell did the honors and Edwards was
the highlight-film victim.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Mitchell met Edwards in the hole, but spun off him,
leaving him on the ground to put Texas ahead 28-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been his best run,'' Davis said. ``He read the
hole, broke a tackle, spun away and went in standing up. He is
playing with great confidence. He's just playing extremely well.
He's allowed us to be more patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
