<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--Baylor-Kansas-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kansas overcomes Baylor's fast start
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LAWRENCE, Kan. _ After one quarter, the few Baylor fans who made
the trek to Memorial Stadium at the University of Kansas finally
had something to feel good about.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears had matched the first-down total (seven) they achieved
in four quarters of last week's 48-7 loss at Kansas State. They had
bettered their yardage total from that dismal defeat and were
motoring toward the lead, their first in 12 quarters.
</P>
<P>
   By the start of the fourth quarter Saturday, those fans again
were forlorn as the Bears' defense, so strong against the run the
previous two weeks, was destroyed by David Winbush and the
Jayhawks. Baylor surrendered 38 unanswered points in losing 45-10
in a game that pointed up the disarray of the green and gold under
first-year coach Kevin Steele.
</P>
<P>
   Winbush carried 14 times for 111 yards and three touchdowns and
Mitch Bowles had nine carries for 86 and two scores as the Jayhawks
(4-6, 2-4 Big 12) ran for 378 yards, a season high for a Baylor
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the tale of the season,'' Steele said of the Bears
(0-6, 1-8). ``Holes in the dike. You plug one up and another one
springs out over here. You plug that one up, another one springs
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the state of a rebuilding process in the first year.
And some of them are more severe than others. We inherit what we
have, and that's where we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important is how we're going to fix it and how
we're going to get there. But the pain of getting there at this
point in time is pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Goodwrench would look over this machine, throw up his hands
and walk away. The Bears put on a textbook display of how not to
play _ on offense, but particularly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Missed tackles and a lackluster effort characterized all but a
few minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Several halftime adjustments resulted in the Bears giving up
just 76 yards while holding the Jayhawks scoreless in the third
period, but overall Kansas piled up 466 yards to 251 for Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of times and opportunities to be out there and
make plays, and we didn't make plays,'' said defensive coordinator
Brick Haley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed in how we played. The missed tackles
were big for us, and also just letting those guys (Jayhawks) knock
us off the football. I'm very disappointed in that. I know we can
play better than that. I know we're a better defense than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two mistakes _ a fumble after a pass reception by Larry O'Steen
and a poor decision by safety Samir Al-Amin to run an interception
out of the end zone _ didn't help the Bears when they were still
alive late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get penalties and turnovers, it gets you off
track,'' said Steele. ``And that one certainly didn't help any. It
was a midfield turnover, which are the worst kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears got perhaps their best performance of the season in
the first half from quarterback Jermaine Alfred in going on top
10-7. With Alfred throwing for 85 yards and twice converting on
third-and-long, the Bears had 130 total yards and seven first downs
in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the afternoon belonged to Winbush and the
Jayhawks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-MISSOURI     11-07 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA HAMMERS MISSOURI AS TIGERS' OFFENSE GOES IN TANK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ The Oklahoma Sooners brought Missouri into Owen
Field yesterday and conducted a three-hour course in football
futility. All the Tigers passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most embarrassing loss I've encountered in my
whole life,'' said Missouri coach Larry Smith after the Sooners
(5-3, 3-2 Big 12) rolled over the Tigers, 37-0, before a crowd of
74,966. ``Our offense absolutely stunk today. It was the most
pathetic thing I've ever seen in my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense fought their butts off. Other than that, I have no
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Tigers (4-5, 1-5), it was a remarkably miserable day.
Everything they attempted _ passing, running, kicking, defending,
or launching desperate fourth-down thrusts, produced a dreadful
result.
</P>
<P>
   In notable contrast, the Sooners' only problem was field-goal
attempts _ they hit one of five. Beyond that, everything worked so
well that in the fourth quarter, Jarrail Jackson returned a punt 70
yards for a touchdown while OU had only 10 players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, maybe that's a secret weapon for the future,'' said
Jackson, who had 146 yards on six punt returns. ``You think?''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, Oklahoma quarterback Josh Heupel (24 of
43, 260 yards, two TDs) was sitting on the bench, thus missing a
shot at his seventh 300-yard game, settling for the Big 12 record
for touchdown passes (25).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the way we played today,'' OU coach Bob
Stoops said. ``There were a few things we didn't do, but overall we
played well. The entire starting unit on defense got a game ball
for pitching a shutout, because it's hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't something magical, like we had a new defense today.
We just executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they overwhelmed the Tigers, who saw a 10-0 deficit
quickly become a rout in the second half and were stopped on
fourth-and-1 four times _ the last with 1:43 remaining at the OU 15
with several Sooners reserves on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Littrell scored the first of his three touchdowns on a
5-yard reception from Heupel in the first quarter for the Sooners'
only first-half touchdown, and Tim Duncan added a field goal _ OU's
only success _ for a 10-point lead in a game still much in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Matters changed abruptly in the second half when Jackson's
42-yard punt return to the 19 set up an eight-yard scoring run by
Littrell. On the second play after the kickoff, linebacker Roger
Steffen picked off a Jim Dougherty pass, returning it 20 yards to
the 11. Heupel then connected with Damien Mackey for a 24-0 lead
with 10:31 remaining in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until Jackson's punt return made it 30-0
early in the fourth, and Littrell added the final Oklahoma score on
a 26-yard run, capping a 65-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the desperate Tigers turned to freshman
quarterback Justin Gage, who threw three incomplete passes before
Dougherty returned. Gage had been tabbed for a redshirt year.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma had better luck in that regard, as freshman Quenton
Griffin, giving up his redshirt year because of injuries to two
other OU backs, ran 14 times for 69 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous, but I wanted to play,'' he said.
``Coach Stoops came and told me they needed me to help the team,
and that was fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Oklahoma a game closer to a possible bowl bid
for the first time since 1994, but Stoops would not discuss that
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got games to play, a long way to go,'' he said.
``We played well today and really had a great effort, but it
doesn't mean a thing if we can't come back and do it again next
week. We know what we can do when we play well, but we need to be
consistent at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the consistency was more than enough for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, better than we are,'' said Smith. ``But
not 37 points better.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
