r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-IOWA-S     11-07 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-IOWA-ST.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, TECH STAY IN SOUTH TITLE HUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ The South Plains is known for its wide-open
spaces. And after two weeks with little running room elsewhere,
Texas Tech's Shaud Williams again found home on the range.
</P>
<P>
   After being penned for two games, Williams broke loose for 148
yards on 21 carries and scored two touchdowns _ including a
game-clinching 47-yard scoring run _ to lead the Red Raiders to a
28-16 victory over Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to see some daylight again,'' said Williams, held
to 49 yards on 29 carries in two road games after a 230-yard
performance against Colorado in Jones Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been bottled up these last couple of weeks, but I stayed
patient and I knew things would work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept Tech (5-4, 4-2) in the thick of the Big 12
South Division race and rejuvenates the Raiders as they prepare to
play division-leading Texas on Saturday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got a chance to go to Texas and play for the Big 12
South championship,'' said Red Raiders linebacker Tim Duffie, who
caused a rare fumble by Cyclones running back Darren Davis that set
up Williams' long scoring run. ``Just like we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's defense twice had goal-line stands. The Red Raiders held
on downs at the 1 in the second quarter and scooped up only the
second fumble of Davis' career in the end zone in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Both times the Red Raiders' offense responded.
</P>
<P>
   After safety Kevin Curtis swatted away a fourth-down pass in the
end zone on fourth-and-goal from the 1, Tech drove 99 yards to
score when quarterback Rob Peters connected with split end Darrell
Jones for a 26-yard TD pass and a 21-6 halftime lead. The Red
Raiders drove 80 yards in the fourth quarter after Curtis and
Duffie knocked the ball loose from Davis' grasp at the 1 , and
cornerback Antwan Alexander recovered in the end zone for a
touchback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech did a great job of capitalizing on our mistakes,'' Iowa
State coach Dan McCarney said. ``We can't get stopped at the 1 two
times and expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones also set the stage for two other Tech touchdowns
with mistakes in the kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   Tech overcame an early 6-0 defecit when linebacker Kyle Shipley
recovered a muffed punt by ISU return man J.J. Moses at the ISU 9.
Williams scored on a toss sweep on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   On the next series, Cyclones punter Carl Gomez bobbled the deep
snap and Tech took over at the ISU 23. Peters snuck over from the 1
on third-and-goal for a 14-6 lead with 1:15 left in the opening
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State drove 83 yards, ending in Davis' 7-yard scoring run
midway of the third quarter and was threatening to take the lead
after linebacker Ab Turner intercepted Peters' tipped pass at the
Tech 31. The Cyclones drove to the 7 five minutes into the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After Duffie stopped him for a 2-yard loss on first down, Davis
got back to the 4 on the next play. He then ran into heavy traffic
on third down and Duffie's hit caused his first fumble in 707
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought \Rthe play was over\S,'' Davis said. ``But I guess
it was my time to let it go. That hurt really bad ... I was trying
to reach for the goal line and \Rthe ball\S came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech had just moved to its second first down after the fumble
recovery on a 17-yard pass from Peters to flanker Dee Jackson on
third-and-four when Peters handed off to Williams on a sprint draw.
</P>
<P>
   Williams cut outside at the line of scrimmage and hip-faked ISU
cornerback Ryan Sloth off his feet. Williams cut up the left
sideline, ran back to the middle of the field at the ISU 25 and
left the trailing Cyclones behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made the move on that cornerback, I was off to the
races,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes followed the play from a sideline vantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, he's gonna get down to about the 25.' Then I
saw that right turn take place and I said, `My gosh, here we go.'
And there he went.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams carried with him Tech's off-again, on-again hopes for a
berth in the conference title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize it, but we still have a chance to win the
Big 12 South,'' Dykes said. ``I know our kids in the locker room
believe it. We look forward to going down to Austin. It should be a
fun game and a real head-knocker.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
