<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LBP     11-07 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.R.'S HAPPY HOMECOMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ J.R. Redmond got the opportunity to play football
on Saturday. Redmond, in fact, got to play a lot of football.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder - Redmond's coach at Arizona State - made sure of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you have to understand about J.R.,'' Snyder said
after his team extended USC's misery with a 26-16 Pac-10 victory at
the Coliseum, ``is he's probably most natural (and) most
comfortable when he's playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Snyder employed the 6-foot, 220-pound Redmond
as a tailback on 56 plays, a free safety on 29 snaps and as a
special-teams performer 12 times. And when he was through with the
marathon effort, the Carson High graduate, who looked awfully spry
for a player who had just took part in 97 plays, had 148 yards on
34 carries, with touchdown runs of 1, 3 and 14 yards, three catches
for 11 yards, seven punt returns for 39 yards, four tackles and a
wonderful homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the best football players in the United States
and when he's playing, we're that much better,'' Snyder said.
``That's the most, I think, I've had a player play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His effort drew plenty of notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redmond most definitely gets my respect,'' USC linebacker
Markus Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Steele has a lot of company. It's safe to say most of the
53,382 who showed up for USC's homecoming left with a similar
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was supposed to be USC's homecoming,'' Redmond said as he
gazed into the quickly emptying stands searching for family and
friends, ``but it turned into J.R.'s homecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded pretty good to Arizona State quarterback Ryan
Kealy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants it to be his own homecoming then, damn, let it be
his own homecoming,'' Kealy said. ``Because he's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming back home to Southern California particularly to the
Coliseum - has generally brought good results for Redmond. On that
same field a year ago, Redmond had an ASU-best 350 yards on 46
touches in a 35-24 loss to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Snyder said. ``But I do know that
he's played, probably, the two best games I've seen him play here
at the Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   This trip home, though, was more than just another opportunity
for Redmond to help his team win a football game.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it sounds, he needed this game as much if not more
than his team needed him. He needed the chance for a post game hug
with his parents - Joseph Redmond and Carolyn Hux than the Sun
Devils needed his 198 total yards and tireless effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something special about playing in front of
family and friends,'' Redmond said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough couple of weeks for Redmond. He was suspended
by the NCAA and missed last week's 20-17 loss to Oregon for
accepting benefits from an unapproved source. That's a pretty
straightforward way of explaining a situation that is far from that
simple.
</P>
<P>
   The unapproved source is a former part-time employee of the Sun
Devils athletic department, who became Redmond's wife in late
August. At this point, all most of us know about the bizarre tale
comes from Redmond's point of view. The identity of the woman has
not been made public by the university.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of the people sitting behind the Arizona State
bench on Saturday who had heard the he-said version of the couple's
relationship and late-summer trip to Las Vegas for a quickie
marriage to avoid the NCAA violations of accepting financial favors
from the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ````I heard a lot of comments (Saturday) that I don't care to
repeat,'' Redmond said. ``I expected that. It was just angry fans
being angry fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, who filed for divorce last week, declined discussing
the situation any further, saying simply, ``I've learned quite a
bit the past few weeks and want to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said: ``He's had to deal with things at his age that I
certainly never did and will never have to,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Redmond, who turned 22 on Sept. 28, could have solved
some problems with an off-season decision. He would have been a
high first-round draft choice if he would have chosen to flee Tempe
after his junior season. But, his loyalty to Snyder won out over
becoming financially stable for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Ankle and shoulder injuries have slowed him down in his final
season as a Sun Devil, but Redmond still entered Saturday with 959
all-purpose yards and nine touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does so much more than run the ball,'' Kealy said. ``He
lifts the team on his shoulders and carries us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0014 </DOCNO>
