r a BC-EISNER-GRADS-LADN     11-07 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EISNER-GRADS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EISNER HELPS PROMOTE GRADUATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jesse Hiestand  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Michael Eisner, chairman and chief executive of
The Walt Disney Co., stepped to the concrete porch of a small green
house near Los Angeles to personally deliver a contract to
Victoriano Lopez and his 11-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   At stake was a pact that could set the boy on a path to a bright
future, one grounded not in instant stardom or movie glory, but the
promise of a good education and a better shot at college.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez and his son Victoriano Jr. a sixth-grader at San Fernando
Middle School about 20 northwest of downtown Los Angeles, gladly
signed the contract, adding their names to the dozens who joined a
scholarship and study program called Project GRAD, for Graduation
Really Achieves Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity for the kids to have a closer
relationship with their teachers,'' the boy's father said.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and nearly 900 volunteers _ students, teachers, parents
and community leaders _ fanned out into the neighborhood around San
Fernando High School Saturday for a Walk For Success, the project's
first foray into Los Angeles after finding success in other states.
</P>
<P>
   In small teams, the volunteers set out to pitch the program at
the doorsteps of some 3,400 sixth- and ninth-graders in the school
cluster, which has low rates of graduation and college attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to raise the rate at which San Fernando High School
students attend four-year colleges, from just 14 percent now to
perhaps 50 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive, all ninth-graders are guaranteed a scholarship
of up to $6,000 and possibly more if they meet the program's
requirements, which are laid out in a one-page contract signed by
both the student and their parent.
</P>
<P>
   By signing it, the students vow to graduate with at least a 2.5
overall grade-point average, complete all of the University of
California eligibility requirements, take the SAT and other exams
and participate in various Project GRAD programs, among other
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers a chance for all students to turn their dreams into
reality,'' Eisner said at a morning pep rally for the volunteers.
``All of us _ educators, parents and the whole community _ have the
responsibility to provide them with the proper environment and
support to become learners.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner backed up that sentiment with a $1 million grant through
his charitable foundation. That boosted the project's scholarship
pool to more than $6 million, most of which came from federal
grants.
</P>
<P>
   Given their age, the sixth-graders are not offered a college
scholarship. Instead they sign contracts that encourage them to
work hard in school, while their parents promise to get more
involved in their children's education by reading to them and going
to parent-teacher conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Project GRAD was founded in Houston, Texas, in 1993 by Jim
Ketelsen, retired chief executive of Tenneco Inc. The program has
since been expanded to schools in Atlanta, Ga., Nashville, Tenn.,
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Eisner in the walk were state Sen. Richard Alarcon,
D-Van Nuys; Assemblyman Tony Cardenas, D-Panorama City; and Los
Angeles City Councilman Alex Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a false promise _ it is a guarantee that the first
$6,000 and possibly $12,000 or more will belong to you if you put
your best foot forward and say, I will live my dreams,'' Cardenas
told the volunteers, most of whom are seniors and were thus not
eligible for the scholarships but offered their time anyway.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0015 </DOCNO>
