r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     11-07 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S NIGHTMARE CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's bowl hopes, an absurd idea in retrospect,
officially vanished Saturday, but that doesn't mean there isn't one
goal remaining in this increasingly grotesque season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're fighting not to be the worst team in the Pac-10,''
freshman wide receiver Kareem Kelly said. ``I never thought that
coming into this program.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did anyone else, but after USC lost its fifth
consecutive game of the season, a 26-16 setback to Arizona State
before 53,382 at the Coliseum, it's hard to imagine the Trojans
winning another game.
</P>
<P>
   How does 3-9 grab you?
</P>
<P>
   That's a real possibility, because USC is not only losing, it is
confused. Nobody seems to know what is going on. Not the players.
Not the coaches. Nowhere was this more evident than USC's
quarterback crisis _ uh, controversy _ as neither starter John Fox
nor Mike Van Raaphorst could generate any offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we'll do at quarterback,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, making his first start in two years, was asked if he knew
he would be relieved early in the third quarter and never return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think as a player I'm supposed to know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Kelly was more surprised _ or forthcoming _ than
Fox that the fifth-year senior received such an early hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shocked me a lot,'' Kelly said. ``I don't know what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   After five losses, the Trojans (3-6, 1-5) do know one thing:
Things can get a lot uglier. For the first time all season, USC
appeared as if it were resigned to losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the more we lose, the worse we play,'' wide
receiver R. Jay Soward said. ``We give up a touchdown and it's
like, ``Oh, we lost the game. Can we get this over with?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a radical idea, considering the offense put in its
usual 10-point effort.
</P>
<P>
   Some Trojans wondered why they didn't score more points.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who caught nine passes for 170 yards last week, had only
two balls thrown in his direction in the first half, and finished
with 51 yards receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some games have a lot of plays designed for me and the next
week I'm not a factor. I'm like a decoy,'' Kelly said. ``The plays
weren't really designed to me. It's not really my place to question
the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what fans are for, especially when the Trojans' offense
consisted of a first-quarter scoring drive and defensive tackle
Ennis Davis' 30-yard interception for a touchdown. The offense also
managed to set up an Arizona State touchdown, as Fox was
intercepted by Kenny Williams in the second quarter, who returned
it to the USC 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense doesn't exactly deserve to be let off the hook.
It never figured out how to cover tight end Todd Heap (seven
receptions, 100 yards). Heap made one of the game's biggest plays,
when he caught a 37-yard pass over free safety David Gibson on a
fourth-and-1 situation that put the Sun Devils at the USC 3 and put
Arizona State ahead 19-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had coverage problems and tried to work something out
after the half with the tight end, but they came up with something
new,'' linebacker Markus Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sun Devils tailback J.R. Redmond was having his way
with USC again, rushing for 148 yards and three touchdowns. That
was actually an improvement. Last year, he rushed for 214 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was left discussing the quarterback position, which
seems weaker today than at any time this season.
</P>
<P>
   `` The feeling was that (Van Raaphorst) could give us a
change-up, but that wasn't what we needed either,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever a chance Fox would come back in?
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it a couple times, but the feeling was we were
going back and forth and Mike had a little bit of a feel,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: It just added up to a sour homecoming for the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be out partying on homecoming,'' Soward
said. ``Instead we're going home moping and soaking our sores away
in the bathtub.''
</P>
<P>
   Got your tickets for the Louisiana Tech game the day after
Thanksgiving?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
