<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ EJECTED AS LAKERS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ It seems in this new adventure of a Lakers season,
the learning will not be left just to the players, although there
were plenty of lessons for them Saturday night in their 97-82 loss
to the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The big showdown between the West Conference teams who would be
king briefly turned heated in the fourth quarter when Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal was ejected for his second technical in less than
a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, O'Neal left without comment but Lakers coach Phil
Jackson blasted the officials, which will no doubt draw the
attention today of NBA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was getting hammered by rotating Blazers, a pattern
unfortunately familiar to O'Neal but apparently new to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' 7-1, 330-pound center picked up his second technical
after he was bumped hard by Portland's Jermaine O'Neal. Shaquille
O'Neal then shoved the ball into the Jermaine's chest.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neals went face-to-face and exchanged some macho looks and
expressions, but no blows were thrown, probably much to the
betterment of Jermaine O'Neal's health plan, since he weighs some
80 pounds less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed in the refereeing tonight,'' Jackson
said. ``I thought they were awful. To let Shaq be attacked like
that, and then make him the villan for that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, these guys are jumping on his back and basically
flagrantly fouling him and then he simply puts the ball in the
guy's chest after he beats him across the face, and they call him
for a tech on it and run him out of the game. The game was a
seven-point game at that time, and he was basically the force
behind our game, and to eliminate him took the game out of hand.
That was unfortunate for us.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shaquille O'Neal went with the team to the bench on the
ensuing timeout he was still hot, barking heatedly at assistant
coach Jim Cleamons when questioned about throwing the ball at
Jermaine. Ron Harper wrapped his arms around O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers were up 77-70 when O'Neal was ejected. Then Portland
center Arvydas Sabonis suddenly re-entered the game and scored 11
consecutive points for the Blazers. The Lakers were answering with
only a John Salley inside hoop, and Portland was on the way to an
easy win.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson may have been upset with the officials, but also
disappointed that O'Neal had lost his cool, and possibly cost them
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him know after the game how unhappy I was with the fact
that he did not contain himself in the game,'' Jackson said.
``That's his responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of the referees to contain the
ballgame and to make this a legitimate thing. I mean, what did
Portland do, send four guys out there to foul out of the ballgame?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw the way they were throwing bodies at him just to
make sure that he wouldn't score a basket. Anybody else who got hit
like that, it would be a flagrant foul. I mean, it's pretty obvious
they're not playing the ball. All they're trying to do is knock him
down. So he has a right to have a retaliation through his game, the
way they're playing against him. That still doesn't give him a
legitimate excuse to walk out of the ballgame by giving a flagrant
foul. That's what it was about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers got 19 points (17 in the first half), eight rebounds
and five assists from Scottie Pippen. Sabonis finished with 17
points, as did Damon Stoudamire, who constantly posted up Tyronn
Lue.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal left with 21 points and 10 rebounds, but not much help.
Glen Rice cooled off with 14 points and Lue added 12 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers hit only 50 percent of their free throws (17 of
34) and were outrebounded (40-39) despite the Blazers playing
without their two respected power forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Grant is on the injured list with a sore knee and Rasheed
Wallace was a late scratch with a strained groin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
