<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE STUMPEL, GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The wheels continued to come off the Kings joyride
Saturday when they lost top center Jozef Stumpel for three months
because of surgery to repair a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   The news came just hours before the Kings much-anticipated game
with the Philadelphia Flyers, a matchup of two of the NHL's hottest
team that was played in front of a capacity crowd of 18,118 at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But without Stumpel and Luc Robitaille, who learned Friday he is
out at least three weeks with a broken left foot, the Kings'
unbeaten streak ended at six games with a 5-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Flyers' ninth win in 11 games, but it never was much
of a game after the Kings tied it at two late in the first period.
They just didn't have the firepower to match up with the Flyers.
Robitaille was the Kings leading goal scorer with 10, and Stumpel
the club's top assist man with 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is a great loss, but it will be a test of what we
are trying to do here,'' general manager Dave Taylor said. ``We
went through this last year and didn't do well. We feel we are
better prepared this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Kings lost goalies Stephane Fiset and Jamie
Storr during the fourth game of the season and won just two of the
next 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Kings were 9-3-3 before Robitaille and Stumpel
went down and were tied with San Jose for the most points (21) in
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you don't want to have this type of injury,
especially when the team is on a roll,'' Stumpel said. ``It's kind
of bad, but I believe the team is going to continue to play well. I
hope the injury does not interrupt what we are doing as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having Robitaille and Stumpel on the first line and
the power play, the Kings were forced to play rookies Jason Blake
and Marko Tuomainen with their top unit.
</P>
<P>
   Their energy in practice won them the jobs and Tuomainen scored
a power-play goal in the first period against the Flyers that tied
the game at two. But it was clearly not enough. The Kings were
outshot 14-2 and 26-9 during two spans in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   They picked it up in the third when Ziggy Palffy, the only
remaining member of the first line, scored midway through. But it
was not enough against Philadelphia, which got goals from five
different players and none of them captain Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Johnson, the Kings third-line left-winger scored first
with goal at the 3:46 of the first period. But the Kings quickly
trailed on goals by Miakel Andersson and Mark Recchi less than
three minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   Tuomainen, playing for the first time in six games after taking
a stick in the eye, tied the game at 2-2 with a power-play goal on
a cross-ice pass from Palffy with 1:50 left in the period. But by
the time Palffy got his goal, the Flyers scored three more goals
and staked goalie John Vanbiesbrouck to a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Like Robitaille, Stumpel underwent an MRI on Thursday when the
team returned from its three-game Midwest road trip. He said he
isn't sure when he first suffered a hernia. But he struggled with
the injury last season when he was limited to 13 goals and 64
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to feel it in my groin and it has been going to my
stomach lately,'' Stumpel said. ``I have had problems with my back
and my hip flexor since last season started. It felt good during
the summer, but once I started skating, it started to hurt again.
It's early in the season and I should be back to finish what we
started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
