<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-07 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT'S QB STRATEGY IS ODD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forgive us if we're beginning to sound as
repetitious as the USC marching band.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' troupe can strike up ``Conquest'' until the
trombonists are blue in the face and it doesn't matter. The
football team lost for the fifth consecutive week Saturday and
looked so disorganized in doing so _ its offense sabotaging a
victory over Arizona State every which way _ the background ditty
for this 1999 season is fast becoming Inquest.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed inquiry this time centered on the USC coaching
staff's collective decision to give both its healthy quarterbacks
substantial playing time in the 26-16 loss that assured the Trojans
(3-6, 1-5) of no better than a .500 season.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year coach Paul Hackett started John Fox over Mike Van
Raaphorst at the suggestion of offensive coordinator Hue Jackson,
then played Van Raaphorst all but one series in the second half
while Fox stood on the sidelines with his helmet on, the better we
think to hide the steam that had to be coming out of his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Hackett's end-of-the-world strategy, borrowed from
Noah: When staring at a washout of epic proportions, pair
quarterbacks off.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett rationalized his decision to pull Fox after the first
series of the third quarter in favor of the quarterback whose
effectiveness he had spent most of the previous two weeks
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play a new quarterback, sometimes the fine-tuning
isn't there,'' Hackett said. ``We made the change to Mike because
the feeling was Mike had a little bit of a feel. We thought he'd
give us a change-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Trojans were the ones thrown off-balance. Fox and
Van Raaphorst collectively connected on 56 percent of their passes
for zero touchdowns, averaged nine yards a completion and were
intercepted thrice.
</P>
<P>
   Since even before starting quarterback and designated savior
Carson Palmer was sidelined with a broken collarbone, Hackett has
managed to do the very thing the other Pac-10 coaches spent all
summer worrying would be impossible: He has stopped the Trojans'
speedy receiving corps in their vapor tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans now find themselves in an untenable position. They
have three games remaining and two demoralized quarterbacks, a 3-2
count that's not conducive to advancing the offense.
</P>
<P>
   If Hackett were smart, he'd listen to senior receiver R. Jay
Soward, who made perfect sense to us when he said, ``At this point
I think we need to focus on one guy and go with him. If he throws
10 interceptions, so what?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what do the Trojans have to lose, besides three more
games?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if either quarterback was completely inept. Fox
completed a pretty 56-yard pass to senior Windrell Hayes and three
plays later lofted a catchable ball to Soward in the end zone that
Soward lost when he languidly one-handed the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst completed a third-down pass to Kareem Kelly in the
third quarter and in the fourth quarter hooked up with Hayes on an
18-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's not that either quarterback is incapable of finding
his rhythm; maybe neither is getting enough time to locate it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, two weeks removed from linebacking duty, marched the
Trojans 10 plays for a touchdown the second time USC had the ball
for the game's opening score. That was as good as it would get for
Trojan fans in the second-smallest Homecoming crowd of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   On USC's first drive of the second quarter, Fox threw an
interception from inside his own 20 that Sun Devils cornerback
Kenny Williams ran to the USC 1 to set up the first of three scores
by senior J.R. Redmond. The very next series, Fox moved the chains
39 yards before ceding the hot seat to David Newbury, who missed a
47-yard field goal that would have cut ASU's lead to three.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Fox trotted out of the pocket at the first sign his
No. 1 receiver was covered. Instead of scrambling to find any open
man downfield, he did a lot of scrambling for daylight. His
teammates couldn't blame him for feeling uncomfortable under the
Sun Devils' scorching blitz, considering Fox was the blitzer
instead of the blitzee a scant three weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a couple of weeks ago he was a linebacker,'' senior
tailback Chad Morton said of Fox. ``It might be hard to make that
adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   While Fox was busy compiling the second-highest rushing numbers
on the team, Kelly was running free in the Sun Devils' secondary
and getting very frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who had nine catches and one score the previous week
against California, had no catches in a first half that saw
second-string tailback Malaefou MacKenzie snag three passes.
</P>
<P>
   The fabulous freshman on this day was nothing more than a decoy.
``I guess my role this game wasn't to get too many passes,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   It says here it's Hackett's role to pick one quarterback and
stick with him.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only chance the Trojans have of ending the season on a
high note. &QL; 
!hair!!ital!
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a
week. She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
