<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1789 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-     11-07 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ EJECTED, JACKSON ANGRY AS LAKERS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ It seems in this new adventure of a Lakers season,
the learning will not be left just to the players, although there
were plenty of lessons for them Saturday night in their 97-82 loss
to the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The big showdown between the Western Conference teams who would
be NBA king briefly turned heated in the fourth quarter when Lakers
center Shaquille O'Neal was ejected for his second technical in
less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, O'Neal left without comment, but Lakers coach Phil
Jackson blasted the officials, which will no doubt draw the
attention today of NBA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was getting hammered by rotating Blazers, a pattern
unfortunately well familiar to O'Neal but apparently a news item to
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' 7-foot-1, 330-pound center picked up his second
technical after he was hit hard by Portland's Jermaine O'Neal.
Shaquille O'Neal then shoved the ball into the Jermaine's chest.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neals went face-to-face and exchanged some macho looks and
expressions, but no blows were thrown, probably much to the
betterment of Jermaine O'Neal's health plan, what with him weighing
some 80 pounds less. The first technical on Shaq was for throwing
an elbow at Jermaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed in the refereeing tonight,'' Jackson
said. ``I thought they were awful. They let Shaq be attacked like
that, and then make him the villain for that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, these guys are jumping on his back and basically
flagrantly fouling him and then he simply puts the ball in the
guy's chest after he beats him across the face, and they call him
for a tech on it and run him out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shaquille O'Neal went with the team to the bench on the
ensuing timeout he was still upset and barked heatedly at assistant
coach Jim Cleamons when questioned about throwing the ball at
Jermaine. Ron Harper wrapped his arms around O'Neal to try and cool
him down.
</P>
<P>
   What a day for learning. Jackson may have to learn how teams
pound on O'Neal, Cleamons when the right time to instruct him, and
O'Neal to keep his poise.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers were up 77-70 when O'Neal was ejected. Then Portland
center Arvydas Sabonis suddenly re-entered the game and scored 11
consecutive points for the Blazers. The Lakers were answering with
only an outmatched John Salley inside hoop, and Portland was on the
way to an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Shaq left the game, it seemed the right time to feature
(Sabonis) in the offense,'' said Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was upset with the officials, but the Lakers were also
disappointed O'Neal had lost his cool and possibly cost them a
victory in what had otherwise been a struggle of a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him know after the game how unhappy I was with the fact
that he did not contain himself in the game,'' Jackson said.
``That's his responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of the referees to contain the
ballgame and to make this a legitimate thing. I mean, what did
Portland to, send four guys out there to foul out of the ballgame?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw the way they were throwing bodies at him just to
make sure that he wouldn't score a basket. Anybody else who got hit
like that, it would be a flagrant foul. It's pretty obvious they're
not playing the ball. All they're trying to do is knock him down.
So he has a right to have a retaliation through his game, the way
they're playing against him. That still doesn't give him a
legitimate excuse to walk out of the ballgame by giving a flagrant
foul.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal left with a game-high 21 points and 10 rebounds, but no
one else picked up the slack. Glen Rice cooled of with 14 points,
and Tyronn Lue added 12 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But despite playing without either of their two formidable power
forwards _ Brian Grant is on the injured list with a sore knee and
Rasheed Wallace was a late scratch with a strained groin _ the
Blazers had too much balance for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen led them with 19 points, but Damon Stoudamire and
Sabonis each added 17, and Bonzi Wells an unexpected 12 off the
bench (all in the first half).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot just 50 percent from the line (17 of 34).
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have played a lot better, without question,'' said
Lakers forward A.C. Green. ``We have to play better on the road. We
have to keep our poise and do the little things. We're a better
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-PACERS-BO     11-07 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS KNOCKED OFF PACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ New building, business as usual. Do you get the
feeling that these teams could meet in a shirts-and-skins game in a
driveway in Des Moines and the result would still be the same?
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' unblemished record is history, but their futility
with the Indiana Pacers remains, well and aggravating.
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, in the opening event at spectacular Conseco
Fieldhouse, the Pacers weathered a late Celtics blitz to take a
115-108 victory. For those of you still able to keep count at home,
the Pacers have now won 10 straight from Boston, including all
eight under Larry Bird's stoic stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana got a big game from Reggie Miller (29) and then held off
the Celtics with timely contributions from everyone from Al
Harrington to Austin Croshere. The Pacers also were killers from
international waters, knocking down 10 3-pointers, eight in the
first half. Miller ended up with four.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the dagger in our heart,'' coach Rick Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't defend the three. We dug ourselves a big hole (down
15 at the break) and we did come back,'' said Kenny Anderson, who
had 20 points for the 3-1 Celtics. ``If we just had been able to
keep it at six or eight . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't until it was too late. The Celtics left knowing
they shot 52.5 percent, held their own on the boards (39-38), and
still couldn't find a way to beat this team. Antoine Walker led
Boston with 21 points, but he needed 23 shots and had only one
assist. The Celtics' ball movement, crisp and efficient in their
first two games, has been less so in the last two.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the numbers above show, offense was not the problem. The
inability to stop the trey in the first and the inability to make
the key defensive stop down the stretch was critical. The Celtics
got to within 5 in the last four minutes, but that was as close as
Indy would allow. A 3-point play by Rik Smits and a Miller leaner
kept the Pacers afloat, their streak against Boston intact.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was still special beating his old team, Bird said,
``I'd say a little bit. Actually, I'd rather beat them than anyone
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall conditions going into the game were anything but
promising for the Celtics. They were playing their fourth game in
five days _ including the night before, while Indiana was off _ and
the Pacers were opening Conseco amid great fanfare. They brought in
most of the top 50 Indiana hoop legends of all time, including
Oscar Robertson, Walt Bellamy, and John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that,'' said Eric Williams, ``and we still almost made
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't. Again. You have to go back to the 1994-95
season to excavate the last Celtics' win here. And when the
volcanic Miller (7 of 11) erupted for 15 in the first, including
three treys, it looked like it was going to be another Pacer
cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these new rules,'' Pitino said, ``Reggie Miller is one of
the more lethal players in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a kid again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy lead was 8 after one and 15 at the break, as Bird got
great contributions from last season's MIA's Croshere (11) and
Harrington (12.) But the Celtics came back in the third, got to
within 3, and hung around in the fourth as Anderson scored 14 in
the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had one glittering chance down the stretch. A Walker
trey (he had three) cut the deficit to 103-98 with 3:46 to play.
Bird called a timeout and Mark Jackson came out of the break to
knock down the Pacers' 10th and final 3-pointer. After two Anderson
free throws _ there were 21 freebies in the fourth _ the previously
comatose Smits (13 points in the first two games) followed up a
Jalen Rose miss with his 3-point play. Smits finished with 13
points, 7 rebounds, and 2 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson answered with another trey, making it 109-103, and then
Dale Davis bricked two free throws with 1:28 left. There was still
hope. But Paul Pierce (19 points, 5 turnovers) lost the ball in
traffic and killer Miller connected on the leaner, assuring that
the 18,345 in attendance would go home happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
