<HEADER>
A1796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-THRASHERS-     11-07 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-THRASHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECES IN PLACE FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The longer they go, the easier it gets. A jumbled
collection of shattered pieces only a couple of weeks ago, the
repair-on-the-run Bruins rattled off their sixth straight win
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, a 4-2 rubout of the expansionist Atlanta
Thrashers, backed by their nouveau riche netminder, Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Belanger, Darren Van Impe, and Dave Andreychuk (two) all
scored for the Bruins, who hadn't won six straight since
February/March 1994. The current streak is their longest in the
post-Garden era. Four-plus years out of the beloved barn, they have
cracked the combination to the Vault (without the aid of Geraldo
Rivera).
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 16,883 came to Causeway to see the Bruins win for the
fourth straight time on home ice. They now have gone seven straight
without a loss (6-0-1), the victory nudging them over .500 (6-5-4)
for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, playing for the first time since inking his three-year,
$9.45 million deal, had a relatively easy time of it. He stopped 13
of 14 shots in the first two periods _ very light work _ and
carried a two-goal lead into the third period. He finished with 21
stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to have that type of game,'' said
Dafoe, who had Rob Tallas watching from the bench as his trusty
backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a solid game, a building ground for me, and I needed
that, because I know the next game will come very soon and it will
be a lot tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-armed sharpshooting Andreychuk potted goals 10 and 11,
the second coming with 1:05 to play, only 13 seconds after Andrew
Brunette pulled the Thrashers to within 3-2 on a power-play strike.
At this pace, the 36-year-old Andreychuk easily could crack 50
goals, which would make him the first Bruin to do so since Cam
Neely.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some guys (goal scoring) is a little bit of a God-given
thing,'' said Andreychuk. ``But you have to work hard, too. For me,
I'd say some of it's God-given, and getting in the right spot. When
you're in the right spot, the puck just seems to come to you, even
if you aren't having a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger scored the only goal in the first period, providing the
Bruins with a 1-0 lead with only 4:24 ticked off the clock. The
hard-working winger tipped the puck away from Mike Stapleton behind
the Atlanta net, reached out front from behind the goal line, and
stuffed his first goal of the season inside the right post.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe made a couple of nice stops in the period, the first
coming only 15 seconds into the action when hard-shooting Petr
Buzek hammered a slapper from the top of the left circle. Dafoe
steered it to the opposite wing. With 10:20 gone, and the Thrashers
shorthanded, rookie sensation Patrik Stefan broke in on right wing
and snapped off a wrister that Dafoe knocked away with a clever toe
save.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old netminder was showing no signs of rust.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers came back with an early goal in the second to tie
it, 1-1, but the Bruins struck twice in the final two minutes to
carry a 3-1 lead into the third.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:20 gone, only moments after their power play expired, the
Thrashers tied it when Per Svartvadet collected a Johan Garpenlov
feed and flipped an 8-foot wrister under the crossbar. Dafoe didn't
have much of a chance to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were working with a power play of their own at 1:47
when Van Impe struck for his second goal in as many games, again
unloading one of his steaming slappers. The puck came to Van Impe
high in the slot after an Anson Carter (two assists) feed into the
middle slid off Steve Heinze's stick. Van Impe, working the right
point, quickly closed into the middle and hammered in the 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The crusher for the expansionists came with 36 seconds left in
the period when the Goliath-like Andreychuk muscled out from behind
the left post and slid a wraparound shot through Damian Rhodes's
legs. In control behind the net, he first motioned as if he would
come out front from behind the right post, reversed field, and
powered out from behind the left post, carrying Atlanta defenseman
Chris Tamer on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could teach that,'' said Bruins head coach Pat Burns,
``you'd have a lot of 500-goal scorers in the NHL. Some guys have
it. Some don't. He knows the right time to hit it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 0315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     11-07 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE STILL SMOKING BETWEEN THE PIPES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins are complete again. Goalie Byron Dafoe was
back between the pipes Saturday &UR;  &LR; night and made 21 saves in a 4-2
victory over the Atlanta Thrashers that swelled the B's autumnal
winning streak to six games.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe hadn't stopped many shots since May 18, when the Bruins
skated into a long, hot summer after a 3-2 playoff loss at
Buffalo's Marine Midland Arena. During his protracted holdout, he
skated at the Icenter in Salem, N.H., where former Bruin defenseman
Grant Ledyard and assorted plumbers, salesmen, and rink rats took
aim just to help him keep his reflexes sharp .
</P>
<P>
   If we can believe TV commercials, Nolan Ryan can stay sharp by
throwing fastballs to Mrs. Ryan, but there is no way to simulate
NHL action. We can't expect pregnant Kim Dafoe to blast 100 mile
per hour one-timers from the point. Being an NHL goalie is sort of
like being an NFL running back or a heavyweight boxer: You can keep
yourself in shape, but you never know if you're game-ready until
you perform against championship-caliber competition.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:08 Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, Dafoe was back on the New Garden ice
for the first time in almost six months. Seconds into the game, his
first save came on a hard slap shot by Thrasher defenseman Petr
Buzek.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was good,'' Dafoe said after the win. ``It was good to
have that right at the start instead of standing around for five
minutes waiting for the first shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He had six saves in the first 11 minutes, including a nifty toe
save on a Patrik Stefan shorthanded wrist shot. In the second, he
allowed a game-tying doorstep goal to Per Svartvadet, then snatched
a point-blank Yannick Tremblay shot with his glove. The Thrashers
didn't score again until the final 1:18, when Andrew Brunette
flicked home a rebound while the visitors were playing with two
extra skaters.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice return for the holdout goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played very well,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``We expected
that from him. He's a fierce competitor. From the start of the
game, he was alert and ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said, ``My teammates played extremely well defensively in
front of me. I felt better as the game went on. I'm definitely not
100 percent and the last three minutes kind of got to me, but I was
feeling confident and reading plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins fans were predictably forgiving of their 28-year-old
netminder and showered him with applause when he was announced as a
starter (several came armed with supportive signage). Perhaps
because of Hardball Harry Sinden's chilly reputation as the Mr.
Potter of professional sports, B's customers align themselves with
young millionaire athletes. Dafoe ``settled'' for three years at
$9.45 million (sans over $400,000 in lost holdout wages) and
somehow became a martyr. In the end, the talented goalie was the
good guy because he dumped his agent and came back for the love of
the game (and lifetime security). He wanted to play hockey more
than he wanted to prove a point to Sinden or the Players
Association. Fans like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was special,'' Dafoe said when asked about the fan
reaction. ``These are knowledgeable fans. They know what's going
on. I think that's the only time I got louder applause than Ray
Bourque.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted, ``It was tough watching the games on television. I
stayed up late and watched all the games when they were on that
trip. I felt helpless. It's one thing to watch games when you can't
play because you are injured. This wasn't the same. It was
frustrating because I've played with almost all these guys
before.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things have happened since Dafoe's last appearance with
the Bruins. He rejected his chance at salary arbitration _ a
dubious decision. Then there was the usual sabre-rattling between
camps with Hardball Harry firing off the usual salvos about saving
the sport, and Dafoe's agent trying to teach Harry a lesson.
Bourque made some calls on Dafoe's behalf, and in the end Harry and
Byron hammered out a deal in a single afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Management loves this type of agentless negotiation. The late
Walter Brown used to make these deals with his Celtics. Tommy
Heinsohn remembers bumping into Uncle Walter in the old Boston
Garden men's room, then standing side-by-side with the owner, in
front of a trough, talking contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we zipped up, we'd have a deal,'' recalled
Heinsohn.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe's deal took more time and sapped much emotion from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two months have been tough on me and my family,'' he
said. ``Now it's nice to put the Dafoe Contract Story behind.
Hockey is what I like talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't think he was risking injury by returning to the ice
just eight days after signing his contract. He stayed in condition
throughout his work stoppage, never going more than five days
without skating.
</P>
<P>
   And how did he fare against those 30-year-old plumbers,
salesmen, and rink rats?
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a few by me,'' Dafoe said, smiling. ``Hey, you shoot
1,000 pucks, they're going to get a couple past you.''
</P>
<P>
   They got a couple more past him Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. But it wasn't
enough to beat Byron Dafoe. It wasn't enough to beat the hottest
team in town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
