<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PIPEBOMBS-cox     11-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PIPEBOMBS-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEACE TALKS TO PROCEED DESPITE PIPE BOMBING IN ISRAEL
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Peace talks set for today (Monday) remain on schedule
despite the explosion Sunday of three pipe bombs in an Israeli
coastal city. The bombing injured few but is a reminder of the
opposition to any peaceful compromise between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The trio of bombs exploded simultaneously on a busy street
corner in the city of Netanya injuring 27 people. Most were only
slightly hurt and no one suffered serious harm. A fourth pipe bomb
which did not explode was found nearby during a police search.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing came a day after the military wing of Hamas, a
Palestinian group seeking the elimination of Israel, threatened to
unleash a new wave of terror. Israeli police said they suspected
terrorists rather than common criminals for Sunday's bombing. Two
Palestinian suspects were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing appeared to follow a pattern set over several years
in which extremist groups have used terror to try to upset Israelis
and derail upcoming peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis protested against the peace process at the scene
of the bombing and a few members of parties opposing the government
called for a postponement in the talks. However, while bombings did
often stall talks under former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
the current government Sunday pledged to forge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Current Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who heard of the bombings
during his weekly cabinet meeting said, ``We cannot have any
illusions. There will be those who try to stop the process but they
will not succeed.'' He vowed to ``crush terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   He also called on Palestinian leaders to help him keep terrorism
from threatening the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Mitigating the political damage caused by the bombing were
recent Israeli reports of improvements in Palestinian security
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never allow the extremists to veto the peace
process,'' Avraham Burg, speaker of the Israeli parliament, told
Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's stay-the-course response was reminiscent of the approach
used by his mentor, slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who
attempted to pursue peace while fighting terror.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Barak, Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and
President Bill Clinton met in Oslo, Norway to mark the fourth
anniversary of Rabin's death. They resolved to keep the
six-year-old peace process going.
</P>
<P>
   Today's(Monday) meeting is meant to lead to a general
``framework'' for peace by February. That, in turn, is supposed to
lead to a final resolution of all disputes by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Israel is ceding control to the Palestinians of
land in the Gaza Strip and the West Bank that Israel captured in
the 1967 war. Most of the Gaza Strip has been turned over and about
a third of the West Bank is in total or partial Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   But, the new round of talks deals with the toughest issues.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians want Israel to share Jerusalem, the eastern portion
of which Israel captured in 1967. Israeli leaders vow never to
share the city they consider their capital. Most governments,
including the United States, do not recognize the city as the
capital and consider the city's status up for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians also want more than 3 million refugees to be
allowed to return to lands in Israel or the West Bank that they
lost in the wars in 1948 or 1967. While that demand poses huge
practical problems for Israelis now living on their lands, some
type of compensation package could be proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Palestinians want Israel to dismantle Jewish housing
developments settlements established on the conquered West Bank
land.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israel is seeking guarantees that the Palestinians
will not form an army or make alliances with countries hostile to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting was expected to focus on organizational and
scheduling issues for the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
