</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-STOCK (Undated) _ Microsoft has long been, in the
words of one analyst, ``an institutional investor's dream.'' Since
the company went public in March 1986, its market capitalization
has soared to $470 billion, making it the most highly valued
company in the world. But given the severity of Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's findings of fact on Friday, some analysts and
investors say that the future of Microsoft's stock suddenly seems
less rosy. By Sara Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ In Silicon Valley, the
nation's high-technology capital, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
powerful findings in the Microsoft antitrust case have been
received with a sense of vindication but also ambivalence. By John
Markoff with Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ In its 18-month antitrust battle
against Microsoft, the government introduced mountains of e-mail,
documents and testimony from business partners and competitors to
show that the company had a monopoly in computer operating systems
and that it had illegally leveraged that position to muscle its way
into new markets. But proving that the software giant's tactics had
resulted in harm to consumers often seemed the hardest and most
elusive part of the case. Many software users see one of the
government's key complaints -- Microsoft's inclusion of a Web
browser with its Windows operating system -- as a boon. By Amy
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   PITNEYBOWES-ECOM (Undated) _ Pitney Bowes is expanding beyond
copiers, fax machines, postage meters and bulk mailing systems to
move itself _ and its customers _ into the e-commerce era. By
Claudia Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ TV commercials are bypassing jingles
and using hit songs more these days. The reasons: to cut through
the clutter, win the loyalty of target groups, and, the big reason
... artists these days are more willing to sell their souls. By
Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-INTERNET (Undated) _ In an effort to raise money, embrace
supporters and bypass the news media, the Republican National
Committee plans to announce on Monday that it will offer
subscriptions to a ``family friendly'' Internet service that will
deliver the party's messages directly to supporters. By Rebecca
Fairley Raney.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN-TIMESSQUARE (New York) _ What ESPN is up to in its new
Times Square Restaurant. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-CLICKDATA (Undated) _ The E-Commerce Column: On the
Internet, where information is king, some of the most valuable
information is data about user or customer behavior. Of this, one
of the most closely followed measurements is so-called ``click
data,'' which focuses on who has clicked on an advertising banner
or some other particular link. Web site publishers, advertising
agencies and companies who buy those ads have relied heavily on
that data to build their businesses, and until now they have been
generous about sharing it freely with each other. Now one of the
Internet's biggest advertisers is raising the question of whether
that data belongs to anyone but the advertisers, and the resulting
debate could shape the future of the advertiser-publisher
relationship. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   REALNETWORKS (Undated) _ RealNetworks Inc., the multimedia
Internet company, plans to announce soon a new network delivery
service and a new version of its media player, called RealPlayer 7.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   REDPOINT-FUND (San Francisco) _ Redpoint Ventures, the
technology-focused venture capital firm created in August through
the combination of Brentwood Venture Capital and Institutional
Venture Partners, will soon announce that it has raised $600
million in its first fund. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-BANK (London) _ Royal Bank of Scotland is talking to
the Spanish bank BSCH about a joint 26 billion pounds ($42.20
billion) bid for Britain's National Westminster Bank. By Andrew
Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column; details
TK. By Denise Caruso.
