<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PITNEYBOWES-ECOM-ART-     11-07 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITNEYBOWES-ECOM-ART-1140(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITNEY BOWES MAKES ITSELF AN INTERNET PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Conn., Mass., Utah, Mich.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three phrases flash in rapid succession on United
Illuminating &UR;  &LR; Co.'s Web site: No stamps. No checks. No fees.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, the words have alerted the southern Connecticut
utility's customers that they can now get and pay their electric
bills with a click of the mouse. Slowly, but steadily, the
customers are doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been slow, maybe, but I'm certain that it will take
off,'' said Edward Drew, the United Illuminating executive who runs
the Internet billing project.
</P>
<P>
   By rights, that prospect should terrify the folks at Pitney
Bowes Inc. After all, United Illuminating is one of Pitney's
biggest customers, and every electronic bill the utility clocks is
a bill not sent through a Pitney postage meter, or processed
through Pitney's customized bulk mailing systems.
</P>
<P>
   So does that make Pitney _ universally thought of as a
print-on-paper player _ a dinosaur?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. It was Pitney that helped United Illuminating design
the electronic billing program. Pitney runs its bill-paying Web
site and is aggressively looking to teach other big customers the
ways of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Critelli, Pitney's chairman, sees it, Pitney's
business is messages, however they are relayed. And he figures
Pitney, which is based in Stamford, Conn., can make good money
providing the waterwings for companies that are learning to swim in
Internet waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet can deliver data much faster than the old ways,
and we want to help customers use it as a tool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney is not billing itself as an Internet specialist per se.
But in recent years copiers, fax machines, postage meters, envelope
stuffers _ in effect, all the hardware that Pitney sells _ have
moved from stand-alone machines to digital devices that are plugged
into computer networks. Pitney already has a cadre of software
writers who specialize in moving documents around in a digital
environment. So, for Pitney, Internet applications represent a
difference of degree, not kind.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Pitney is making ample use of Internet-savvy partners.
Working with Tumbleweed Communications, Pitney has introduced
iSend, a service that uses encryption, passwords and tracking
features to guarantee the privacy and delivery of e-mail. ISend was
originally aimed at law firms and other small businesses that
traffic in sensitive documents. But Pitney has now teamed with SAP,
the huge software company, to market an industrial-strength version
that would enable corporations to track hundreds of secure files as
they move on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Pitney is ready to roll out ClickStamp, which will
let customers buy postage from the Web. Two start-up companies,
Stamps.com Inc. and E-Stamp Corp., under Postal Service
authorization, already have set up similar sites that are beginning
to attract small-business customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitney is suing both for royalties, claiming that each uses
patented Pitney technology. And some financial analysts say that
Pitney, with an established brand name and a big budget to tout it,
has a better-than-average chance of catching up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guess they could grab 35 percent of the market before
long,'' said B. Alexander Henderson, an analyst at Prudential
Securities Research.
</P>
<P>
   And Pitney has plunged modem-first into the so-called e-tailing
market, as a supplier to companies thatsell goods on the Web. For
example, Pitney is pushing a version of iSend to Internet merchants
as a way to confirm orders and generate bills. And it has developed
software to help e-tailers plot out the best way to deliver
products to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think of shipping as a service you offered
warehouses, but these days a shipper is anyone who realizes there's
stuff in the garage that they can auction online,'' said William
Shannon, vice president of product planning for Pitney's
small-business division.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investors seem skeptical that Pitney can pull off its
metamorphosis into an Internet player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitney is pushing a lot of hype on their Internet
capabilities, but when you crunch the numbers they are not getting
a lot of revenues,'' said James Lundy, a research director at
Gartner Group, a research firm in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 19, when Pitney released third-quarter results, its
shares plunged $4.4375, to $50.25 _ well off a price above $70 as
recently as July. Pitney's earnings were well ahead of the same
period last year, but analysts say that shareholders were
disappointed that revenues had increased by just 8 percent. Pitney
shares closed at $44.875 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pitney executives say they expect Internet-related
products to eventually yield 30 percent of revenues, e-commerce
still remains a tiny part of Pitney's sales. The bulk of revenues
continue to come from postage meter rentals, financing, bulk
mailing systems and services like running mail rooms and handling
direct marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say investors have been wary of Pitney's shares because
of concerns that the Internet will make inroads into basic mailing
products. But Pitney's Wall Street fans _ and there are many _ say
such worries are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Street psychology may be negative, but their fundamentals
are outstanding,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig, an analyst with
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   And the electronic markets that Pitney is chasing are potential
blockbusters. While older meters required a trip to the post office
to buy refill postage, modern meters can be reloaded by telephone.
In both cases, the Post Office, not Pitney, sells the postage. But
Pitney charges higher rentals for newer digital meters, which it
says are more convenient to use. And the company will offer, for a
fee, to buy the postage for customers and reload the meters
remotely.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp., a research firm in Framingham, Mass.,
expects the online market to account for $1.5 billion of postage
sales in three years. On the billing front, Forrester Research
Inc., a firm in Cambridge, Mass., predicts that electronic billing
will account for 13 percent of all consumer bills in five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the pursuit of those markets has Pitney navigating
uncharted, and fiercely competitive, waters. No one yet knows, for
example, whether businesses will prefer to download postage
directly from the Web _ the method used by Stamps.com _ or whether
they will prefer using a lock-box device, as the E-Stamp system
requires. The lock box hooks onto a customer's computers and stores
downloaded postage, which the customer can print out without
connecting to the Internet each time.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney, operating under the names ClickStamp Online and
ClickStamp Plus, is offering both methods. That means it can hedge
its bets until the market chooses one approach over the other, but
it also means Pitney must spread its marketing and research dollars
pretty thin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for electronic billing, Pitney runs the risk that the market
will veer away from being biller-centric _ companies billing all of
their customers electronically _ to a payer-centric model in which
customers pay all of their bills at a single Web site. While Pitney
has pursued the biller-centric business, bill consolidators like
Transpoint, CheckFree and Spectrum are now offering payer-centric
services to consumers. Even some early electronic billers suspect
that the one-stop-shopping approach may be the model that makes it.
``We may want to look at that option in the future,'' said Drew of
United Illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney is keeping its options open here, too. It is talking to
bill consolidators about alliances, and to banks about
payer-centric Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run Web sites that handle billing for all of a
bank's customers,'' said Karl Schumacher, general manager of the
Pitney division that handles high-speed mailings for huge
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest question mark of all is whether Pitney can
successfully woo the small businesses that make up the fastest
growing market for Internet services. Because small businesses
typically have had no need for postage meters or mail room
management, few have dealt with Pitney in the past.
</P>
<P>
   To court them, in September Pitney came out with PitneyWorks, a
compendium of products that includes Personal Post, a digital
postage meter and scale aimed at low-volume users; various
Web-related shipping and direct marketing software programs and
services, and a line of credit for postage. Pitney is also counting
on ClickStamp to generate small business traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 8 million small businesses out there using stamps,
and until now we had no way to get to them,'' said Marc Breslawsky,
Pitney's president. ``If we can get those customers into our store,
we can sell them profitable items like iSend now, and upgrade them
to digital meters as they grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Those upgraded products may not all be Internet related. Unlike
the Internet start-ups it now competes with, Pitney has a stable of
conventional products that yield a steady cash flow to support its
Internet forays. Indeed, although its stock may be slumping, its
sales and earnings have been solid. Its 1998 revenues of $4.22
billion were 8 percent higher than 1997's $3.92 billion, while its
net income of $576.4 million was up 10 percent from the prior
year's $526 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney postage meters still dominate the U.S. market, despite
solid competition from digitally savvy companies like Neopost and
Francotyp-Postalia AG of Germany. And analysts expect Pitney to
garner 30 percent of the international postage meter market by
2004, up from just about 14 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Companies numerous and huge, including US West, Cigna and
General Motors, are using Pitney's equipment to address, stuff,
stamp and mail bills and customized literature. Many others have
hired Pitney to run their mailing operations. In either model, the
client provides Pitney with demographic information about
customers, and Pitney sees to it that, say, a young family's bill
comes with an insert touting products for children, while a retired
widow's bill might include data on care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has certainly not lessened the importance of
personalized content inside an envelope, or of customized printing
on the outside,'' Critelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with paper mailings, computer networks are playing a role.
Pitney now sells systems that help companies glean custom-tailored
mailing lists from e-commerce Web sites, and use them for direct
marketing _ or, in the case of smaller businesses, hire Pitney to
handle the mailing for them. It has database products that
doublecheck the accuracy of addresses and their listed occupants
against post office records, so as to guarantee error-free mailing
lists. And, it is testing a system at General Motors Acceptance
Corp.'s mailroom in Detroit whereby Pitney will scan some of the
nonpersonal incoming mail into a computer, and deliver it to
employees electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paper isn't going away, and only Pitney has the
bricks-and-mortar products to offer a hybrid approach,'' said
Lundy, the Gartner analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney has even figured out a novel way to get the float on a
customer's money. Pitney st up a chartered bank in Utah in 1998.
Then last June, Pitney's Financial Services division started
offering free postage, representing about a 2 percent discount on
postage costs, to customers who put a lump sum into a reserve
account at the Utah bank. Pitney draws from the reserve to pay the
customer's postage bills to the Post Office as they are accrued.
</P>
<P>
   That, in essence, gives Pitney access to funds at well below its
usual 6 percent cost of capital. ``We've effectively coupled
financial services with postage transactions, which means we're
borrowing less expensively,'' said Matthew Kissner, president of
Pitney's small business and financial solutions unit.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney will offer the discount to ClickStamp users as well, a
move that analysts say may help pull small businesses to Pitney's
site _ and in turn, help the company trade them up to more
lucrative products.
</P>
<P>
   It is that kind of cascading effect that keeps many analysts in
Pitney's corner. ``They are in prime position to transition small-
and home-office people from stamps to metering to full mail
services,'' said Henderson, who has kept a strong ``buy''
recommendation on Pitney stock for three years. ``They're using the
Internet as a trojan horse to pull in other services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
