<SLUG> BC-REDPOINT-FUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGY INVESTMENT FUND SAYS IT HAS RAISED $600 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif., Mass., N.J., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Redpoint Ventures, a technology-focused venture
capital firm created in August through the combination of Brentwood
Venture Capital and Institutional Venture Partners, plans to
announce on Monday that it has raised $600 million in its first
fund _ an amount thought to be the largest effort for a first-time
technology fund.
</P>
<P>
   Redpoint, based in Menlo Park, Calif., plans to specialize in
Internet businesses, including companies devoted to broadband, or
high speed, telecommunications technology for Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   Redpoint has already made commitments to several investments,
including a $15 million stake in Reflect.com, a Web-based,
customized beauty business started by Procter &AMP; Gamble, which
contributed $35 million. Tim Haley and Geoff Yang, Redpoint
managing directors, are on the board of Reflect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies that received venture funding from Redpoint's
predecessors include Excite, Ask Jeeves, Tivo, Xylan, Stamps.com
and WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   According to the research firm Venture Economics, the $600
million commitment to Redpoint makes it the largest first fund
raised by a technology-focused venture capital firm. While in part
this reflects investors' interest in new Internet companies, it is
also attributable to the fact that Redpoint is the combination of
two well-known firms rather than an entirely new entity. Brentwood
was founded in 1972 in Southern California, while Institutional
Venture Partners was founded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole premise of this is we're not starting a new fund;
we're building on the platform that IVP and Brentwood had put in
place,'' said Tom Dial, a Redpoint managing director. ``In no case
would we have been able to raise a fund this large without the
history of the two funds and the partners.''
</P>
<P>
   In their August announcement, Institutional Venture Partners and
Brentwood said they would combine their efforts in Redpoint, as
well as a second firm, Palladium, which would be devoted to
biotechnology and other investments related to health care.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosion of the Internet, many diversified venture
capital funds have found it difficult to reconcile the torrid pace
and potentially huge returns of Web startups with the longer time
frames and often smaller returns on new drug companies. Some funds
have virtually abandoned life sciences investments, but Sam
Collela, Institutional Venture Partners' founder, has insisted that
venture capital will have a continuing role in health care. He will
be a managing director of Palladium, while playing a smaller role
at Redpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a diversified fund, there's just less synergy
around the table when the partners get together to talk about these
deals,'' Dial said. ``There's a real advantage to having six or
seven partners around the table, all of whom are really
knowledgeable about the Internet. It just lifts the dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Redpoint's institutional investors are all previous investors in
Brentwood Venture Capital and Institutional Venture Partners,
including ARCO, the Carnegie Corp. of New York, Duke Foundation,
Ford Foundation, Harvard University, the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute, the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, the Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, the Mutual Life Insurance Company of
New York, Princeton University, Rockefeller Foundation, Stanford
University, Pfizer Inc. and Yale University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
