<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-COMMERCE-NYT     11-07 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-COMMERCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE COMMERCE COMPANIES CONTINUE TO SQUANDER PUBLIC'S TRUST
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If dot-com companies are really trying to inspire consumer
confidence as they embark upon what could well be their
make-or-break holiday season, they must be taking oxymoron pills.
Under the hot light of recent scrutiny, their increasingly
questionable business practices are becoming public, casting long
overdue doubt on the credibility of much of the commercial
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Internet allows people and companies to
misrepresent themselves with impunity is well known to online
veterans, who after years of sending and receiving April Fool's
gags and imitation news releases look askance at everything they
get online unless they can verify its source.
</P>
<P>
   But the juggernaut that is now the consumer Internet has foisted
an avalanche of half-truths, lies-by-omission and outright fraud on
a new, more naive online population. Unsophisticated Net users
rarely question who or what is operating behind their computer
screens and, thus, are far easier to snooker.
</P>
<P>
   Their complacency is not completely unwarranted. The Internet,
particularly the Web, looks a lot like a computer version of print
or broadcast media. But it is neither. As a rule, it has not
adopted the kinds of standards and practices that are assumed in
traditional media, where advertisements and paid announcements are
labeled and conflicts of interest are, at least in theory,
disclosed as a matter of course.
</P>
<P>
   These disclosures are what provide readers, listeners and
viewers of traditional media the context to judge what they read,
hear or see. But it is not incumbent upon today's commercial
Internet, either by tradition or law, to provide such context.
</P>
<P>
   The online credibility issue first made international news in
early 1999, when Amazon.com was called to task for accepting money
from publishers for its purportedly independent book reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more examples of online half-truths and lies have
come to light. Most recently, The New York Times and USA Today both
reported that a ``fashion photographer'' was starting an e-commerce
auction Web site, selling fashion models' eggs to would-be parents.
He is also, apparently, an established merchant in soft-core
pornography, a fact that came to light after the global publicity
the stories had generated.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, DrKoop.com, the Web site of the former surgeon
general, Dr. C. Everett Koop, was publicly embarrassed for taking
commissions on products and services sold through the site without
disclosing such financial arrangements. Changes were made on the
site in response to the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Less visible but just as pernicious are the growing number of
``comparison shopping'' sites for products on the Internet, sites
that do not disclose the methods by which their listings are
derived. Although some of these sites are supported solely by
advertising revenues, many listings are based on which companies
paid to be listed with them.
</P>
<P>
   Equally rankling are the portals and search engines that deliver
Web addresses, ostensibly in response to a consumer's query but in
reality based on paid key words. Advertisers buy key words from
portals to make it to the top of the search-results list _ the
functional equivalent of companies that name themselves
``AAAAAAAcme'' for telephone directories _ but portals rarely tell
their users of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to assume that there is an advertising influence
on almost all the content they see online,'' wrote the online
newsletter eMarketer in March 1999, shortly after the Amazon story
broke. ``For instance, here is what comes up on a search for
`digital camera' on Lycos: A (paid) banner for digital cameras; a
(paid) link to an online bookstore offering books on cameras; the
(unpaid) search result links.''
</P>
<P>
   This is business as usual to people who know how the industry
works, but not to consumers, as seen in the Federal Trade
Commission's struggle to investigate hundreds of claims of
fraudulent practices and sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the FTC held a workshop to educate online companies
about disclosure regulations and, in particular, to inform them
that existing consumer protection laws did in fact apply on the
Internet and to explain how the laws would be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet companies are doing a good job of disclosure and,
in fact, are using it as a selling point for their services. For
example, the online bill paying service Paymybills.com, makes
virtually all information about its service, its company, its
policies, partners and business practices available within two
clicks of its home page.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of consumer trust,'' says John Tedesco,
the chief executive of Paymybills.com. ``We consider the language
on our site to be a legal contract with our customers. If it ever
leaked out that we didn't abide by our policies, it would destroy
our business. So we clearly disclose, and we hold by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this with Amazon.com, which promised after its
paid-reviews debacle to make the company's policy more visible.
Amazon has buried its disclosure at the very bottom of its lengthy
``Site Guide'' page, beneath a link called ``Co-Op Disclosure'' _
not exactly a descriptive title, or the first place a consumer
might look for such information.
</P>
<P>
   Credibility of online information is a growing concern both
within and outside the industry. Several organizations _ including
the Internet Content Coalition, the Online Privacy Alliance and the
Pew Charitable Trusts (in which this writer participated) _ have
addressed credibility by producing advertising and privacy
guidelines and projects focused on disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Ziff-Davis founded an industry group called the
Council for Internet Commerce (www.commercestandard.com) to try to
improve the customer experience online by implementing standards
for disclosure of business practices.
</P>
<P>
   James Hake, founder and chairman of the project, said that the
level of agreement between the 200 companies that voted on the
first draft of the standard was ``so high that I need to go back
and make sure they really meant it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I'm afraid they might have been answering from the
point of view of what the consumer wants to hear, instead of what
they were actually willing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But if today's practices continue for much longer _ or, as
eMarketer put it, if the question as to what's fact and what's for
sale is not made clear to consumers _ the use of the Net as a
commercial medium could drop precipitously as consumers realize
they are being gamed.
</P>
<P>
   If dot-coms think it is too much trouble to implement disclosure
practices, they will soon discover it is a lot more trouble to win
back consumer trust once it is lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
