<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ESPN-TIMESSQUARE-ART-     11-07 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-TIMESSQUARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUCH POTATOES WELCOME AT DISNEY'S ESPN ZONES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Conn., Md., Ill., Ga., D.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ESPN Inc. sports empire exists seemingly to
propagate wildly. It has spawned six domestic cable television
networks and 20 more networks worldwide, a magazine, an Internet
service, books, videos, games, a radio network, music, pagers and
pay-per-view programming.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of feeding sports fans mass quantities of
highlights, scores and events, the company, based in Bristol,
Conn., decided the time had come to feed them full of food and
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the first ESPN Zone opened in Baltimore, followed last
July by the second, in Chicago. Baltimore's Zone got nationwide
attention as the site for ``Monday Night Football's'' pregame and
half-time shows, where stage-struck fans chewed behind the host
Chris Berman.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-September, the biggest, loudest, glitziest ESPN Zone
bowed in Manhattan on Broadway at 42nd, near the Disney Store and
the New Amsterdam Theater, two other Manhattan outposts of the Walt
Disney Co &UR; . &LR; , and two blocks south of a third, the new studio for
``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating the ESPN Zone is not a surprise strategy. An
ESPN-themed line of restaurants was on the to-do list of Michael
Eisner, the Disney chairman, when the Mouse Kingdom acquired ESPN's
parent, Capital Cities/ABC, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Eisner vowed to extend ESPN into semi-fine
dining. ``It was a great synergistic brand extension opportunity,''
said Art Levitt, the president of Disney Regional Entertainment,
which designs and runs the ESPN Zones. ``We wouldn't have gotten
into this business without ESPN. It's a world-renowned name and a
natural for this kind of business. Then we had to turn a
one-dimensional TV product into a three-dimensional entertainment
complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports bars are usually small to midsize establishments with
satellite dishes bringing in games to one or two dozen TV sets _
not four-floor monoliths like the Times Square ESPN Zone. Usually,
they are intimate, crowded, memorabilia-packed places with regulars
rooting for their home teams and razzing the few cheering
out-of-town rivals.
</P>
<P>
   There are stand-alone restaurants like the Sporting Club in
TriBeCa or Mickey Mantle's on Central Park South, which trades on
the late Yankee's name, good food and baseball artwork.
</P>
<P>
   There are chains like Hooter's, best known for fried food and
cleavage. And there is the Official All-Star Cafe chain, which has
an outlet on 45th Street and Broadway that pays massive tribute to
the athletes Shaquille O'Neal, Andre Agassi, Joe Montana, Tiger
Woods and Monica Seles who made small investments in the chain. But
its future is uncertain because of the Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing
of its parent, Planet Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, All-Star was very successful,'' Levitt said.
``Even if it had stayed successful, we would have gone forward,
because our brand is so differentiated from anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Krutick, a media and entertainment analyst for Salomon
Smith Barney, said, ``Obviously everything depends on their
execution, but ESPN's existing branding gives them a leg up on the
competition. The restaurants give ESPN a lot of potential for
cross-promotion and licensing opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Disney estimated the average cost of building a Zone at
$15 million to $20 million, but the New York City outlet cost
considerably more. ESPN Zones in Atlanta and Washington are now
being built.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Imagineers who designed the ESPN Zone were chasing a
concept that is reliant on the ubiquitous ESPN name and one that it
hopes will shield it from the shakeout in theme restaurants that
killed the Motown Cafe, Comedy Nation, Television City and the
Fashion Cafe in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   For Disney, the ESPN Zone is a huge, self-referential fun house
with generally good food _ Levitt said food must be the reason for
return business, especially among non-fans _ and an unparalleled
viewing experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never want the fan to be far from the game,'' Levitt said.
``No matter where you are, you have to be connected.''
</P>
<P>
   And it never lets you forget you're on ESPN turf.
</P>
<P>
   At every turn there is the belief that devoted fans possess a
not-so secret desire to frolic in ESPN's headquarters, choose
highlights for ``SportsCenter,'' swap athlete nicknames with Berman
and concoct hip neologisms with Stuart (``Boo-Yah!'') Scott, a
``SportsCenter'' anchor.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN Zone is no mere song of itself; it is a 15-hour-a-day
medley, where patrons dine amid replicas of its studio sets, eat on
place mats with printed scores pulled off the ESPN.com Web site,
and watch games on 220 TV sets _ including those mounted
strategically in rest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Three aspects of the Zone distinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is no memorabilia _ a potentially risky ploy
because autographed artifacts and game-used bats, balls and jerseys
and sticks provide a comfort zone for fans. Instead, artists were
commissioned to create sports oeuvres connected to the cities the
Zones are in. The Manhattan restaurant features the stained-glass
portrait of Jackie Robinson, Joe Namath in the guise of the
Prometheus statue in Rockefeller Center and a portrait of the
former Knick, Walt Frazier, in the style of Thomas Gainsborough's
``The Blue Boy,'' and a computer generated photographic portrait of
Babe Ruth made out of 2,000 Yankee baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is the second-floor viewing room: a huge wall with
a dozen 36-inch monitors and two giant screens contemplated with a
benumbed focus by occupants in 11 leather recliners with speakers
imbedded in the headrests. The denizens of the loungers and those
of upper tiers of tables and banquettes can choose the games they
want to hear by remote control.
</P>
<P>
   But beware: the act of eating from a retractable tray connected
to the custom-made recliner while distractedly trying to choose
from 14 sports events to watch can land the that melted cheese in
your lap.
</P>
<P>
   And gaining entry to these special perches at peak times, like
Sunday afternoons for professional football, requires reservations
and $20 for 1 p.m., 4 p.m. and 8 p.m. games.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the fourth floor, 10,000-foot arena with
interactive games that simulate downhill biking, bass fishing,
horse-racing, parachute jumping, and Indy car racing, and cost
$1.50 to $6.50 to play.
</P>
<P>
   There are tamer games like the stand-in-one-spot Pop-A-Shot
basketball game for fans reluctant to work up a sweat from a
vigorous interactive workout. In all its intensive planning, the
ESPN Zone forgot one crucial element to sports bar cum arena: the
showers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
