<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Nov. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The relatively tranquil weather pattern that has persisted
across much of the country will remain for the next few days as an
area of high pressure aloft stays entrenched across the central and
eastern parts of the nation. Farther west, a series of storms will
move through the Northwest, bringing periods of unsettled weather
to the western states.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will have another cool day Monday, as brisk winds
from the northwest continue to usher cool air into the region. In
addition, there will be some scattered clouds across interior parts
of New England and the Middle Atlantic States as weak disturbances
move quickly across the region. Locations along the northern
Atlantic seaboard will have more sunshine than clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, high pressure just offshore of the Southeast will
promote sunny skies and warm afternoon readings. A jet-stream
disturbance will bring some cumulus clouds to parts of Louisiana.
Meanwhile, increasing winds from the west and southwest over the
northern Plains and central Mississippi Valley will combine with
abundant sunshine to bring record high temperatures into the area.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and mountain snow showers are likely in the
intermountain West in the wake of a cold front. Some of the cool
air will even reach into the Southwest, keeping readings below
seasonal levels. The Northwest will stay cloudy with showers and
periods of snow in the Bitterroots. It will turn rather rainy and
breezy along the Northwest coast, as another Pacific storm
approaches the region.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Warmth in the West
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Boise, Idaho, and Rawlins, Wyo., had their warmest
days ever in November. In recent weeks, numerous air masses have
penetrated the interior West from the Pacific Ocean. These doses of
Pacific air are typically cool and moist when coming off the ocean.
As this air ascends the western ranges, it loses some of its
moisture in the form of clouds and precipitation. Upon descending
the east slopes, this drier air becomes warmer than when it started
its trek across the mountains. A surge of chilly air from the north
will end this warmth across the northern mountains on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
