u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      11-07 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIOGRAPHER IN SEARCH OF A NEW PUBLISHER  
 DUBIOUS CALL AT SMART MONEY  
 ADDRESSING THE PUNDIT PLAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the literary agent Richard Curtis has his way,
there will be one more chapter written in the hand-wringing saga of
St. Martin's Press and its canceled biography of Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the abrupt recall by St. Martin's last month of
``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the Making of an American
President,'' Curtis is trolling for another company that would be
willing to publish the title, which was abandoned after reports
that the author, J.H. Hatfield, was a federal parolee who had been
imprisoned for plotting to kill his boss in a car bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several publishers that are interested in this,''
Curtis said, noting, with understatement, that the talks are
``delicate and complicated because the previous experience was
delicate and complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   After St. Martin's recalled the biography, the rights to publish
the book reverted to the author, which left his agent free to
search for a new taker.
</P>
<P>
   So why bother, given his author's severely damaged reputation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, has the book been discredited?'' said Curtis. ``I'm
asking a question with a question. And so my answer is that I want
to focus on the veracity of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said he was not sure whether a new publisher would
include the book's disputed afterword. ``All I can say for the
moment is that all these things are up for discussion,'' he said.
``When I actually have a deal, and I know what is going to be in
the book, I promise to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   The author, Hatfield, has retreated to his home in Arkansas
without addressing whether his resume includes criminal
convictions. And he has refused to respond to messages left for him
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said the report of a criminal record was a sensitive
topic that he had not discussed with Hatfield, whom he said had
contracts to write four books for other publishers, none of which
he would identify.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jim is ready to discuss his background, I will,'' said
Curtis. He added: ``It's the one area of conversation that I've
refrained from bringing up. It's kind of like, don't ask, don't
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Cover Tests Standards of Magazine Industry
</P>
<P>
   Why would Smart Money, the financial magazine published jointly
by Hearst Magazines and Dow Jones, feature a photograph of the
actor Jerry Orbach on the cover, smiling benignly as he steps out
of a taxi?
</P>
<P>
   Because it is not an actual cover of Smart Money. Instead, it is
an advertisement for TD Waterhouse Investor Services. Inside the
back ``cover'' is an application to open an account.
</P>
<P>
   Although the TD Waterhouse cover was literally a cover wrap, an
extra cover that enclosed the real cover of the magazine's November
issue, it was not easy to distinguish the two. The title ``Smart
Money'' on the cover wrap appeared exactly as it regularly does on
the actual cover, and the tag line that appears on every issue _
``The Wall Street Journal Magazine of Personal Business'' _ was in
its usual spot.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of Smart Money subscribers _ 200,000 of them _
received magazines with the TD Waterhouse cover wrap. It caught the
eye of Marlene Kahan, executive director of the American Society of
Magazine Editors, who called the publishing director of the
magazine, Christopher Ambiase, to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kahan said the cover wrap tested the limits of the society's
guidelines, which for advertising pages and special advertising
sections, read: ``Any page of advertising that contains text or
design elements that have an editorial appearance must be clearly
and conspicuously identified with the words `advertising' or
`advertisement' horizontally at or near the center or the top of
the page in type at least equal in size and weight to the
publication's normal editorial body type face.'' No such disclaimer
appeared on Smart Money's TD Waterhouse cover wrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really goes back to the pressures that all magazines are
facing,'' Ms. Kahan said. ``Everyone tries to be creative and
value-added, but when you sell out on your cover _ even on a cover
wrap that looks like a cover _ it's a bad thing. It erodes
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Magazines, facing an increasingly crowded marketplace, are more
frequently bending to advertisers' demands for more versatile and
conspicuously placed advertising. Earlier this year, the society
stripped This Old House, published by Time Warner's Time Publishing
Ventures Inc., of its nominations for two National Magazine Awards
because an editorial insert featured an advertiser's logo.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiase said the wrap was produced in error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a test of something that advertisers are really asking
for these days,'' he said. ``The final product should not have
appeared that way.'' Ambiase said that somewhere in the last stage
of production the disclaimer was omitted. He said that, as a result
of the foul-up, he and Smart Money's editor in chief and president,
Steven Swartz, had instituted a policy barring publication of such
advertising cover wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to test the waters and address the needs of the
advertiser,'' he said. ``However, this was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Cutting Back on Pundits
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to partly curtail the ever growing crop of pundits
that with each passing year seems to proliferate on cable news
channels like kudzu, MSNBC has signed a deal with National Journal
Group for the coming election year.
</P>
<P>
   National Journal Group publications _ like the political Web
site Hotline, Congress Daily and Congress Daily AM, Greenwire, even
The Almanac of American Politics, along with The National Journal
itself _ will supply MSNBC with statistics and data during the
upcoming political campaign. They will also offer their reporters
as commentators.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Sorenson, MSNBC's general manager, says there is a surplus
of self-styled oracles on cable news and he is tired of it. ``It is
an industry overrun by opinion, to a fault,'' he said. ``One of the
things we want to try to correct in the game of cable news is that
as we swing into the coming political season we want to provide a
lot more fact-based information. And Hotline and National Journal
can do that for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh no! Does this mean the end of Ann Coulter?
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not mean that there won't be a pundit on the air
from time to time on MSNBC during the campaign,'' Sorenson said.
``But we are hoping to have a lot more objective analysis from
people in the field and inside the Beltway.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times and The Wall Street Journal have existing
agreements with MSNBC under which they supply reporters to the
network for interviews and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   John Fox Sullivan, publisher of The National Journal and The
Atlantic Monthly, said MSNBC ``is turning to us as a supplier of
news, data and information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Bloomberg is to the financial business and economic world,
we're trying to be to the political, government and policy
worlds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kelly, editor of The National Journal and The Atlantic
Monthly, has been a frequent guest on MSNBC, as have the National
Journal legal columnist Stuart Taylor and the magazine's political
columnist, Charles Cook.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a second. Aren't those guys, um, pundits?
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said that of the 125 National Journal reporters and
editors, very few could be called pundits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not really an effort on their part to get Stuart
Taylor on more often,'' he said. ``We're giving them reporters who
are nonideological experts on specific things _ what's going on in
Congress _ or segments off of Hotline. They are not in the pundit
business of saying, `This is what ought to happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
