<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS DIFFER ON FUTURE FOR MICROSOFT STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. , Texas.) (rk) 
 By   SARA ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft has long been, in the words of one analyst, ``an
institutional investor's dream.'' Since the company went public in
March 1986, its stock-market capitalization has soared to $470
billion, making it the most highly valued company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But given the severity of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
findings of fact on Friday, analysts and investors say that the
future of Microsoft's stock suddenly seems clouded by uncertainty
about the company's legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are mixed views on how lasting or short-lived the
impact of its legal vulnerabilities will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the stock is going to take some heat, especially on
Monday,'' said Richard Sherlund, a Goldman, Sachs analyst, who
suggested that Microsoft's share price could drop by $5 or more
from its Friday closing price of $91.5625 in regular-session Nasdaq
trading. After hours, Microsoft fell more than $4, to $87, but such
trading is volatile and sometimes not a good indicator of where a
stock will open in the next regular session.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an overhanging cloud,'' Sherlund continued. ``But
I think investors will have a thick skin after an initial negative
reaction. These findings are only a first step, and any legal
ruling by the judge could well be overturned on appeal. After
considering the matter, I think most investors will realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   David Readerman, an equity researcher at Thomas Weisel Partners
in San Francisco, said, ``I think the stock is going to be under
pressure for some period of time. I think the stock will trade more
in line with legal procedures than the underlying fundamentals of
the company. I'm still maintaining a buy recommendation of the
stock, but I think the gravity of what's at stake here will
override underlying fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and money managers pointed to Microsoft's many
positives: The company has consistently posted strong earnings and
has substantial deferred revenue, and even after a long string of
strategic acquisitions, it has a huge war chest in the form of cash
reserves, which could be used for further acquisitions or to buy
back its own stock.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since Microsoft is likely to appeal any negative
verdict, it could be years before the rulings have any impact on
the company.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry T.C. Hu, a University of Texas professor who
specializes in law and finance, said that Microsoft might have a
strong incentive to settle with the Justice Department, given the
severity of the findings. ``The opinion is so pro-government that
it's not clear to me that Microsoft would be unwilling to settle
even with unfavorable terms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another incentive for Microsoft to settle would be to avoid a
verdict declaring the company a monopoly. Since proving that a
company is a monopoly is often the biggest hurdle in civil
antitrust suits, such a verdict could lead to a barrage of suits by
companies that would otherwise consider litigation too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that would scare Microsoft investors is if they
got buried in a lot of civil litigation,'' said Roger McNamee, a
general partner in Integral Capital Partners, a family of
partnerships that invest in expansion-stage private and
growth-stage public companies.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Gordon, president of the John Hancock Global Technology
Fund, which counts Microsoft among it's top 10 holdings, said that
while the finding of fact would be a blow to technology stocks in
the short term, in the long term they would continue to go up. But
he added that Microsoft might no longer outperform the market,
until there is a decision or settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft will continue to edge up, but will not perform as
well as technology stocks in general because of the uncertainty,''
he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   And uncertainty may be the key question for institutional
investors. Since any eventual remedies dictated by the courts could
have a broad impact on Microsoft's business, such investors may shy
away from taking a large position in Microsoft shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there's uncertainty,'' Readerman said, ``there's
volatility in the stock, and where there's uncertainty, there is
generally an unwillingness for investors to make large capital
commitments. Watch the trading volume. This will be the voting
machine that tells you which way Microsoft is going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hu said that this ruling, together with the statement by
Microsoft's president, Steven Ballmer, in September that the stock
was overvalued, indicate that now is not the time to hold Microsoft
stock. ``For long-term investments I would not buy Microsoft,'' Hu
said. ``I have no good way of quantifying how bad it could be. It
makes it a crapshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   But McNamee, whose company has no position in Microsoft stock at
this time, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of institutional investors are hoping the stock
will break down on Monday because they want to buy it,'' he said.
``The opinion of the Department of Justice is important, but I'm
not sure how influential it is on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the uncertainty over the court's final disposition of
the case, a couple of the most extreme antitrust precedents,
involving the forced breakup of companies, suggest that over the
long term those who held stock in such divested companies tended to
do well. The results have varied, but as far back as the breakup of
Standard Oil in 1911 and as recently as the breakup of American
Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Corp. into AT&AMP;T and the Baby Bells in the
mid-1980s, the investors have profited handsomely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
