r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-07 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DINING, DANCING AND FINE ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The famous Dutch club-painter''  &UR; Marthijn de Groot &LR;  is at work
producing a a series of ``live'' paintings at  &UR; Harry Denton &LR; 's
Starlight Room atop the Sir Francis Drake in San Francisco, until
November 13. A picture of the artist at his easel in a nightclub
adorns the invitation to an exhibition of de Groot's work that
opens at the Starlight Room on the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the oeuvre of Marthijn de Groot,'' says the invitation,
``it seems as if the devil and the angel are making love for the
possession of the human soul. ... Fantastic animals on wheels,
floating eyes intently looking at the beholder, candelabras with
wavering candles, scarlet horned figures and fields of delicate
flowers, bathing in an exquisite light are the messengers of a new
belief that integration of opposites can be the bridge to a new
world, where the very notion of religiosity once more acquires its
original meaning, and where humanity lives from the divine in man
instead of a rationally created deity. ... With complete acceptance
and gratitude he places his art in the service of the New Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Among de Groot's works, to be unveiled on November 14, is
`Nightwatch of the Golden Gate Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEW GERMANY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In response to a commission from a German TV network,  &UR; Wolff &LR; 
 &UR; Olins &LR; , corporate identity experts, made some suggestions for
creating a new German image, as cited in Mother Jones magazine:
</P>
<P>
   Put  &UR; Claudia Schiffer &LR;  on a stamp to show the ``exciting and
surprising place'' Germany is. Replace black on the flag with Euro
blue, a color that's friendlier and represents ``responsible
internationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nations today are in much the same position as large
corporations,'' said the company. ``Once uniquely privileged to be
actors on the world stage, nations now need to compete for hearts
and minds, at home and around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Details magazine says that if you've already had the obvious
body parts pierced, the avant garde place to go is the frenum, the
vertical membrane that connects the gum over the teeth with the
inside of the upper lip. A tiny metal ring can thereafter be hung
from the hole, which might come in handy for macrame hangings of
dental floss.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Pat Montandon &LR; 's new book is ``Celebrities and Their Angels''
(Renaissance; $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   - Overheard at Jack's last week: Gossipist  &UR; George Christy &LR;  of
the Hollywood Reporter says that  &UR; Steve Martin &LR;  has bought a flat
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   - The London Daily Mail reports that tough guy  &UR; Steven Seagal &LR; 
is selling a 19,000-acre Montana ranch overrun by knapweed. Said
 &UR; David Schulz &LR; , director of the Madison County Weed Control Board,
``He just didn't consider the noxious weed a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND WHISPERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Danielle Steel  &LR; has received the 1999 Service to Youth Award
from St. Mary's Medical Center, the University of San Francisco and
the Catholic Youth Organization of San Francisco. In ceremonies on
Friday night, Steel was recognized for establishing the  &UR; Nick
Traina  &LR; Foundation in honor of her late son.
</P>
<P>
   The awards part of the evening was followed by a performance by
singer  &UR; Natalie Cole &LR; , who specifically greeted one audience
member, Steel's special friend,  &UR; George Hamilton &LR; , from the stage.
Cole said she and Hamilton had shared many meals and a passion for
soul food.
</P>
<P>
   - Writer  &UR; Susan Parker  &LR; and her husband  &UR; Ralph Hager &LR;  laughed
all through ``New Wrinkles,'' at the Jack Shelton Theater on
Saturday night, but weren't quite as giggly afterward when they
their van, parked on Sutter Street, wouldn't start. Parker
persuaded the very cooperative driver of a nearby car to jump her
battery; onlooker  &UR; Gayle Leyton &LR;  reports he was author  &UR; John Gray &LR; 
of ``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, auto mechanics are probably from Saturn; it took one of
Gray's passengers to know how to connect this to that and that to
this. And they all got home safely.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it attractive when people don't know to talk to other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Jennifer Love Hewitt &LR;  on what she looks for in a man, in
Maxim magazine. Hewitt, who stars in the new TV series ``Time of
Your Life,'' is one of the new genre of three-named actresses, but
not to be confused with Sarah Jessica Parker, Melissa Joan Hart or
Sarah Michelle Gellar.
</P>
</TEXT>
