<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIAL-SECTIONS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NEWSPAPERS SEEK REVENUE WITH NOVEL `EXPERIMENTS'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Minn., Calif., Texas, Ariz.)   (jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jane E. Kirtley moved into her new home in Minneapolis in
September, she found on her doorstep a free weekly supplement to
The Minneapolis Star Tribune. Called The Buyer's Edge, it contained
consumer-friendly articles about things like buying a car online
and ads for things like car dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kirtley, the new Silha professor of Media, Ethics and Law at
the University of Minnesota's School of Journalism, was curious
about the supplement's origins. As a consumer, she found it useful.
As a longtime student of the news business, she wondered who was
doing the writing _ reporters or ad copywriters?
</P>
<P>
   According to John Schueler, Star-Tribune publisher, the
editorial material in ``The Buyer's Edge'' is completely
independent. That is, it is written and edited by journalists. All
the revenue goes to The Star-Tribune, which is owned by the
McClatchy Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it's bad,'' Ms. Kirtley said.``I just moved here,
and I don't know where to get a snowblower.''
</P>
<P>
   But she hesitated as she spoke. Her ambivalence reflects the
suspicions papers can encounter as they create new products, make
alliances with other institutions in their communities or look for
new revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper publishers have long tried experiments to increase
revenue, just as they have long made financial investments in their
communities. But the pressures are greater these days. The
financial underpinnings of the newspaper business are shifting, and
its audience is slowly dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   But every experiment entails a risk. Readers may suspect that
the new sections they are reading are written for advertisers, not
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment suffered by The Los Angeles Times underscores
the risk. Its newsroom erupted when employees heard that as part of
the newspaper's sponsorship of the new Staples sports center, the
local arena would share the profits from a recent Sunday magazine
issue devoted to it.
</P>
<P>
   Though the rebellion at Times Mirror's flagship newspaper may
make publishers more careful, newspapers are not going to stop the
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts have gone on for years. In 1995, The Boston Globe
produced a special section as a guide to the newly opened Fleet
Center arena. As in Los Angeles, the articles were written and
edited solely by the news staff; as in Los Angeles, part of the
revenue from the ads went to the subject of the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treated them as a sales agent and paid them a commission
for ads that they sold,'' said Richard Gulla, a spokesman for The
Globe, which has been owned by The New York Times Co. since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the Globe's arrangement was not part of a deal to
help sponsor the arena. ``The only thing I can say to you is that
it happened. It happened five years ago,'' he said. ``Will it
happen today? No.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is highly unusual for newspapers to share their own
revenue with subjects of news coverage, they and their parent
companies often have financial arrangements with other local
businesses or civic institutions that they cover. Some arrangements
involve forms of financial partnership. Sometimes, newspapers'
parents make investments in local sports teams or arenas _ the A.H.
Belo Corp., owner of The Dallas Morning News, is paying $24 million
for 12.4 percent of the Dallas Mavericks and 6.2 percent of a new
sports arena partly financed by taxpayers. Phoenix Newspapers, the
parent of The Arizona Republic and a unit of Central Newspapers
Inc., has invested $7 million in the Arizona Diamondbacks of Major
League Baseball's National League.
</P>
<P>
   The most common revenue-generating project is the advertising
supplement, a pullout product produced entirely by the advertising
department, with no journalistic input. The sections, labeled as
advertising, appear regularly in many papers.
</P>
<P>
   John Oppedahl, publisher of The Arizona Republic, is proud of
his newspaper's ``vigorous sports marketing effort,'' producing
advertorial sections to send the messages local sports teams want
to send.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, a special section that the paper's ad
department prepared for the Phoenix Coyotes, a National Hockey
League franchise, was used by the team to advocate its position on
a local ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers like The New York Times and The Wall Street Journal
have begun to publish periodic special sections. These sections,
with themes including personal investing, automobiles and health,
draw niche advertising but the editorial content is controlled by
the newspapers' journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new entrepreneurial spirit afoot,'' said Jay Smith,
president of the newspapers unit of Cox Enterprises. ``And it is
essential. It is very tough, in an increasingly competitive world,
where you have got lots of folks fighting for ad dollars that would
otherwise easily have come our way.''
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off the usual suspects: local television, radio, cable
channels, direct mail. ``And somewhere out there is the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast array of World Wide Web sites may indeed be a growing
threat to newspapers' ad revenues. But the Internet may also hold
its own traps as newspapers move to the Web. For example, with
little or no disclosure, links to advertiser sites could be given
favorable placement.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, said he felt lines would blur further between
independent information prepared by journalists and information
bought and paid for by commercial interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the credibility business, not in the advertising
business,'' Rosenstiel said. But ``the blending of news and
commercial, unlabeled, is becoming common on the Web. The great
question about the next Internet era of journalism,'' he said, ``is
not whether Matt Drudge will have a thousand citizen reporters but
whether the Internet is going to become a giant infomercial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
