<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTISH BANK AND SANTANDER ARE REPORTEDLY IN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Royal Bank of Scotland is negotiating with the
Spanish bank Banco Santander Central Hispano about possibly making
a joint bid for National Westminster Bank, executives close to the
talks said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank, which has said it is monitoring the Bank of
Scotland's $34 billion hostile bid for Natwest, has not yet decided
whether it will make a bid, executives stressed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Royal Bank does pursue Natwest with Banco Santander, the
two banks would bid about $42 billion, hoping to trump the Bank of
Scotland's bid, according to executives briefed on the plan. Banco
Santander, which already owns a 10 percent stake in the Royal Bank
of Scotland, would take about a 30 percent stake in Natwest if the
banks move forward with an offer, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Royal Bank of Scotland declined to comment.
A spokesman for Banco Santander could not be reached for comment
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Banco Santander Central Hispano, which was formed earlier this
year by the merger between Banco Santander and Banco Central
Hispano, would most likely add cash to a possible Royal Bank of
Scotland bid in an effort to offer Natwest shareholders a special
dividend, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were reported Sunday in The Sunday Telegraph in
London.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Britain's Takeover Panel ruled that the Royal Bank
of Scotland had to disclose its position in regard to making a bid
for Natwest by Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland had filed a complaint with the panel, which
acts as an arbitrator of sorts, asking it to make the Royal Bank of
Scotland reveal whether it planned to bid for Natwest after
speculation about an offer by the bank was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who have desperately awaited another suitor for
Natwest to emerge, have been disappointed. But analysts note that
Natwest is still trading at a premium over the original Bank of
Scotland bid, leading to speculation that a white knight may still
arrive or that the Bank of Scotland will sweeten its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, though, seemed to think chances were slim that
the Royal Bank of Scotland would make a bid, considering the amount
of time it has had to examine the Bank of Scotland's offer and to
make its own bid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 1749EST &QL; 
