<HEADER>
A1940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-BOMBING-ART-56     11-07 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BOMBING-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPE BOMBS INJURE 14 IN ISRAEL ON EVE OF PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 19 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Three makeshift pipe bombs exploded in the Israeli
coastal town of Netanya on Sunday, wounding 14 people, on the day
before the planned start of Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on a
permanent peace.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but Israeli and
Palestinian officials said they believed the attack was carried out
by Islamic militants bent on derailing peace efforts. The officials
asserted that the efforts would continue unabated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This attack is aimed at sabotaging the peace process,
especially now that we are close to beginning final status talks,''
the Palestinian Authority said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel said talks
with the Palestinians would proceed as planned on Monday in the
West Bank town of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government is determined not to yield to any kind of
terror,'' Barak said. Vowing to ``smash terrorism,'' he added that
his government ``expects the Palestinian Authority to act
effectively to prevent terrorists from harming the chances of
progress in the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombs went off at 10:30 a.m. near a bank on Herzl Street,
the main shopping thoroughfare in downtown Netanya. Witnesses said
they heard three loud blasts followed by a burst of flame and thick
smoke as some people were thrown into the air and others fell
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that the three makeshift bombs, packed
with explosives and nails, had been placed in a shopping cart left
near a garbage bin. A fourth pipe bomb that failed to explode was
later dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials reported that 14 people were treated for
wounds. Most were lightly wounded, they said, adding that four were
in fair condition. Another 15 people were treated for shock, Israel
Radio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting at a crosswalk when suddenly I heard a series of
explosions,'' David Ratzon, who was wounded, said in a radio
interview. ``I was thrown to the middle of the street, lost my way
and ran to the other side. I stood on the sidewalk, full of nails,
my shirt on fire. People laid me on the sidewalk and put the fire
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians in the area were rounded up for questioning, but
later released.
</P>
<P>
   As a police bomb squad and forensic experts combed the blast
site, about 30 protesters gathered nearby. They shouted
``Revenge,'' ``Death to Arabs!'' and ``Barak Go Home.'' Some held
up pictures of the hawkish former prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, whom Barak defeated in elections last May.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing came a day after a leaflet signed by the armed wing
of the militant Islamic group Hamas threatened renewed attacks on
Israelis. However the Israeli police chief, Yehuda Vilk, said that
the makeshift bomb explosions Sunday were not typical of Hamas,
whose suicide bombers have killed scores of Israelis in far bigger
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Ahmad Yassin, the spiritual leader of Hamas, sidestepped
questions on whether his group had a role in Sunday's bombing,
saying only that the latest violence was part of a cycle of
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian talks on a permanent agreement are
expected to begin in earnest on Monday with the declared aim of
reaching a framework accord by February, and a final agreement by
September.
</P>
<P>
   A likely early stumbling block will be the future of Jewish
settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Expansion of settlements will be the first point on the agenda
of the final status talks, and without a halt to settlement
activities there will be no progress,'' said Yasser Abed Rabbo, the
chief Palestinian negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barak has permitted new construction at existing
settlements, he reached an agreement with the settlers' leadership
last month to remove 11 illegal outposts set up, mostly in the past
year, in the West Bank hills.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deadline set by Barak to vacate the remaining outposts
by Wednesday or to face eviction by soldiers, settlers have begun
moving out. At one outpost, however, the settlers are expected
simply to move to a new, authorized trailer site on a hill closer
to an existing settlement. At another, a trailer will be left
behind, pending future approval of building plans by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The army is preparing for possible resistance at Havat Maon, an
outpost south of Hebron, where scores of militants have gathered to
block any attempt to evacuate the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 1753EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-cox-cyber-president-1     11-07 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-cox-cyber-president-110899 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A CYBER-CHALLENGED PRESIDENT TO MAKE 'CHAT ROOM' DEBUT
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS and BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Information Age politics will cross another frontier
Monday when Bill Clinton enters a virtual chat room on the Internet
for an online presidential town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural presidential webcast doesn't call for Clinton to
tap away at a computer keyboard as questions pop up on his personal
monitor. While the White House may be all wired up, the first Baby
Boomer chief executive still isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton will mount an auditorium stage at a local
university, along with some other New Democrats, as well as
cyberspace billionaire Marc Andreesson, who at age 23 created the
Netscape Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   A lucky handful among the 15,000 Web users who successfully log
on for the 90-minute session, from 7 to 8:30 p.m. EST, at
www.townhallmeeting.excite.com will be able to pose their e-mailed
questions to Clinton. He will then answer them via newly developed
</P>
<P>
   streaming video technology.
</P>
<P>
   Up to another 35,000 users will be able watch passively before
the chat room fills up. Participants in both groups whose computers
lack the needed video or audio software can read a continually
updated transcript.
</P>
<P>
   The unique event is being sponsored by the Democratic Leadership
Council, the ``Third Way'' political group that Clinton helped
found while governor of Arkansas, and Excite at Home, an online
service provider that specializes in fast links to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to take some tough questions,'' said Elizabeth
Newman, a White House spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been known to praise the virtues of computer
literacy, White House officials confirm that he has yet to practice
what he preaches by sifting through e-mail messages or surfing the
net in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, this is the president, and he doesn't have a lot of
free time,'' an official said. ``But he understands the uses of the
technology and is certainly interested in its educational and
commercial value.''
</P>
<P>
   A personal computer has yet to find its way into the Oval
Office. Clinton, however, owns a laptop and has been given some
rudimentary lessons on how to run it by Al Gore, the techno-geek
vice president. Still, whenever speech drafts are required, ghost
writers have proven more handy than word processors. Clinton then
edits the printouts by hand.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Clinton joined in an Oval Office demonstration of
computer wizardry for a Saturday morning radio address that
promoted the use of the Internet. But he had Gore at his side for
the whole show and, after a photo op, the gear was quickly whisked
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I become curious, I can always go down to the vice
president's office, because he's a bigger expert than I am, based
on things he pulls up for me on the Internet,'' the president once
told a group of curious fifth-graders at a question-and-answer
session in Clarksburg, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, when Chelsea went off to Stanford University,
Clinton suggested that he would finally learn how to use e-mail so
he could stay in touch with her. But he hasn't, finding it easier
to use the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Clinton spent much of election night peering over
the shoulder of John Podesta at his chief of staff's computer
screen as Podesta, to Clinton's apparent amazement, extracted
voting results from Internet sites before political newscasters
could put them on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also maintains its own highly popular Web site
(www.whitehouse.gov), complete with links to the rest of the
government and an invitation to the public to e-mail their comments
to Clinton to Gore. But any responses go back by ``snail mail.''
</P>
<P>
   As the web site explains: ``Shortly after you send this message,
you will receive an electronic acknowledgment of receipt from the
White House. There will be no further electronic response. If
appropriate, a reply will be sent to you via U.S. mail.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
