<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SELENA-AUDITION-ART-2     11-07 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELENA-AUDITION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELENA'S SPELL LIVES ON IN STAGE AUDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a studio in the theater district this past
weekend, close to 200 girls and young women auditioned for a new
musical. But this was no ordinary open casting call, for the role
being cast was that of Selena, the Tejano singing star whose murder
in 1995 at 23 horrified millions of fans, particularly the young
Hispanic women who saw themselves in her.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Paola Cubides, a 20-year-old New Yorker of
Colombian descent, who said she had first heard Selena perform when
she stumbled upon a homemade cassette tape of her songs in school
one day. Two days later the singer was killed, and Ms. Cubides
would forever feel ``such a connection'' to her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cubides said Selena was her role model _ an American-born,
English-speaking Latina with indigenous features like her own who
did not stray from her cultural roots to be successful. So when Ms.
Cubides' turn came up as No. 68 last Friday to try out for the role
of the adult Selena (there is also a part for Selena as a child),
she closed her eyes, squeezed the microphone hard and poured her
heart into ``Dreaming of You,'' one of Selena's posthumous hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me hope that I'd be able to make it too,'' Ms.
Cubides, an aspiring performer who plans to pursue musical training
next year and apply to Juilliard, said later. ``Right now she would
have been huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena Quintanilla Perez achieved in death the celebrity of an
Elvis Presley or a Marilyn Monroe among Latinos and others, even on
the East Coast and in other areas where she was not as well known
or where Tejano music was not as popular as in Texas, her home
state. Already the subject of movies, documentaries, books, tribute
issues of magazines and a ballet (George Faison's ``Idol
Obsession''), she is about to be memorialized again in ``Selena
Forever,'' a stage musical envisioned as a celebration of her life
and music.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Selena Forever,'' who include the clothing
magnate Jerry Frankel (``Death of a Salesman,'' ``Jekyll and
Hyde,'' ``Charlie Brown''), say they plan to take the show, an
ambitious production with 25 cast members and an estimated cost of
close to $2 million, directly to Selena's audiences with a tour of
30 cities. It is scheduled to begin in San Antonio in March, the
fifth anniversary of her death. Its success on the road will
determine when and if it comes to Broadway, they said.
</P>
<P>
   With live music and an emphasis on the love story between Selena
and her husband, Chris Perez, her band's lead guitarist, the
producers said, the musical will aim for a wider audience than the
1997 film ``Selena,'' which was a financial success but did not
quite cross over to non-Hispanic audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that amazes me is that I speak to people _ to old
people, to young people, non-Hispanics _ and nine out of 10 people
know who Selena is,'' said Frankel, who once owned a company that
had the license to manufacture the singer's line of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will strike a chord,'' he said of the production.
``It's a tragic story, but it's going to end on a high note.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the movie, in which the actress Jennifer Lopez
lip-synched to Selena's recordings, the musical will feature an
actress who will use her own voice for what is mostly an original
score. Only about a third of the music consists of Selena's songs.
</P>
<P>
   But like the upbeat biographical movie, the musical will gloss
over the singer's murder or any of the unsavory rumors that
followed it. There is not even a part in the script for Yolanda
Saldivar, the disgruntled employee and fan club founder who is
serving a life sentence for shooting the singer in the back after
being confronted with allegations of embezzlement by the
Quintanilla family. The stage production's script calls for the
story to start out with a shot and be told in flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Vega, a theatrical booking agent who is a co-producer of
the musical with Frankel and John Quinn, a restaurateur, noted that
after ``West Side Story,'' with its gang warfare, and ``The
Capeman,'' with a murderer as its central character, ``Selena
Forever'' offers the opportunity to build a Latin-themed musical
around a positive figure for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus on all the great things she means to a
lot of people,'' Vega, a Cuban-American, said. ``We think there are
enough negative images around.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena achieved stardom in the United States and Mexico with
Tejano music, a bouncy blend of pop, polka and country rhythms from
the Southwest border dominated by male performers. She performed
since childhood with her siblings in a band that was managed by her
father and eventually included her future husband, and overcame
humble beginnings and language and cultural barriers in the
Hispanic world (she sang in Spanish but spoke it with a Texas
accent) to become known as the ``Queen of Tejano Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Selena, who had won a Grammy Award and earned a gold album, was
poised to release her first record in English and come full circle
in her identity as a Mexican-American artist, when she was shot
during a meeting with Ms. Saldivar in a motel in Corpus Christi,
Texas, her hometown. More than 30,000 people filed past her coffin
as she lay in state, and her posthumous album, ``Dreaming of You,''
made its debut at No. 1 on the Billboard charts.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, said Abraham Quintanilla, the star's father, the
family is deluged by letters ``from all over the world.''
Quintanilla has given ``Selena Forever'' licensing rights and acts
as an adviser to the show. He said he liked the script, by Edward
Gallardo, and loved the original music and lyrics by Gallardo and
Fernando Rivas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost five years after Selena's death, there's an insatiable
hunger for anything having to do with Selena,'' Quintanilla, 61,
said in a telephone interview from Corpus Christi, explaining why
he gave his blessing to the project. ``The public has not forgotten
her. As her father, I try to keep her alive through her music.''
</P>
<P>
   So the search is on for the embodiment of a cultural icon, a
young performer capable of conveying not only Selena's artistry but
also her unpretentiousness, sense of humor and warmth. The
musical's casting director, Stephen DeAngelis, arrived in New York
this weekend after casting calls in San Antonio, Corpus Christi,
Houston, Chicago, Las Vegas and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, the last stop before a choice is made in December, is
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here out of respect,'' DeAngelis told the first group of
50 adults who showed up to audition at a Manhattan studio last
Friday. ``The doors Selena opened, she opened for all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   There were white Selenas and dark-skinned Selenas. Selenas in
jeans and Selenas in the shimmering tight pants and bras the singer
favored. There were off-key Selenas and Selenas who sounded very
much like the real thing, with the sob in the voice.
Dominican-American and Puerto Rican Selenas outnumbered Selenas
with roots in Peru, Honduras and Cuba. Or even French Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a model for me _ her charisma, her positive attitude and
the care she had for her fans,'' said Melanie Lagace, 21, a bank
employee and Latin band singer who rode a bus all night Thursday
from Montreal to make her first audition. ``Whatever the outcome of
the audition, I hope the spirit of Selena remains in every heart.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday red lips and heavy makeup gave way to baby faces as
about 30 prepubescent girls showed up with parents, aunts and other
relatives to try out for the role of young Selena. The girls had to
look between 8 and 11, bear some resemblance to the singer and be
bilingual and ``sensitive and funny with an exceptionally powerful
voice.'' The test: singing ``Somewhere Over the Rainbow'' a
cappella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' Courtnie Beceiro, 9, a fifth-grader at P.S.
188 in Queens, said in a whisper, shaking her head, when a reporter
asked her if she was up to the challenge of playing such a widely
revered figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was beautiful outside and inside,'' Courtnie said. ``She
showed a lot of people, especially Mexicans, Spaniards and so on,
that they can make a difference in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just even thinking about Selena and why somebody would want to
kill her makes me cry,'' she added, becoming teary-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such emotion, it was not lost on the candidates that
Selena, the role, could be the ticket to their own stardom, doing
for them what the movie did for Jennifer Lopez, who now commands
millions of dollars a film. In contrast to the casting calls for
the movie, which attracted thousands of hopefuls in a single city,
DeAngelis has so far tried out only about 1,000 candidates in seven
cities for the more demanding stage role.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them have had little professional experience, but that
does not matter, DeAngelis said, adding that he had already found
strong candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a special girl to play a special girl,'' he
said. ``We're looking to really discover someone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-PRISONER-NYT &LR;      11-07 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STENCH OF HORROR LINGERS IN A PRISON IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBRAVA, Yugoslavia _ The high, red brick walls of Dubrava
prison tell little. Like the modern police buildings outside, they
bear signs of bomb damage from NATO attacks in May this year, but
that is only half the story.
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the prison walls there are piles of abandoned
clothes, drenched by months of rain but still giving off a stench
of human corpses. The smell pervades the prison buildings inside, a
reminder of the horror that gripped the prison for five days in
late spring, when NATO bombing and the Serbian rampage against
Kosovo's Albanians combined to turn this prison into what a former
prisoner and Spanish peacekeepers who now guard the buildings
depict as a site of murderous mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Naser Husaj, a former public prosecutor from the nearby town of
Pec and at the time one of Kosovo's most prominent political
prisoners, was in Dubrava prison in May. Returning to the prison
for the first time since his release a month ago, he described a
terrifying ordeal in which prisoners were trapped first by NATO
bombing, which killed at least 23 prisoners, and then by masked
Serbian police forces, who killed more than 100 other Albanian
inmates in running battles raging through the prison for two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taking advantage of NATO's action,'' he said of the
Serbian guards. ``They wanted to kill us all.''
</P>
<P>
   The blood and smell of death remain, nearly six months later.
Bedding and clothes are strewn all over the extensive grounds where
prisoners dragged them out to sleep outside in an attempt to avoid
the NATO air strikes. And in the basements of the buildings, the
blood lies still sticky on the floor, bullet holes scar the walls,
and impact marks of grenade explosions crater the floors.
</P>
<P>
   Husaj, founder of the Kosovo Albanian nationalist party Balli
Kombetar, was serving a five-year sentence imposed by the Serbian
authorities, for heading what they branded a ``fascist quisling''
organization.
</P>
<P>
   He spent three years in Dubrava from 1995 to 1998, then a year
in a Serbian prison, before being brought back to Kosovo during the
NATO air campaign. Released at the end of his sentence last month,
he returned this past weekend to the prison for the first time and
told his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first attack started on May 19,'' he said of the NATO
bombing. ``They hit pavilion C, a cell block, and three people were
killed. On May 20 there was no bombing, and then on the May 21 at 8
a.m. we heard a plane. The guards ran away, and we ran out into the
middle of the grounds. They were hitting blocks all day.''
</P>
<P>
   He said all the guards had left the compound, including the
watchtowers, though some remained outside and kept strict security
around the prison. Some prisoners who were already out of their
cells for regular cleaning or cooking duties then freed other
prisoners from their cells.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 people were killed that day, he said, pointing out a
bomb crater that still stank of human flesh where several people
had been killed. They carried the bodies up to the far end of the
grounds and laid them out by the sports field. That night the
entire prison population, some 900 men, slept in the grass up by
the sports fields, which is inside the prison compound.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning at 8 a.m. the guards returned to just the
watchtowers, and ordered the prisoners to assemble in a long line
in rows of four to prepare to be transferred to another prison.
Husaj was standing at the back to one side with several fellow
political prisoners when suddenly the guards opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started to shoot with a machine gun at the prisoners,''
he said. ``They threw grenades over the prison walls, and another
machine gun was shooting from a hole in the wall,'' he added,
pointing out the spot. ``Seventy people died in that shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Husaj explained the shooting as Serbs using the NATO bombing as
an opportunity to take revenge and exact punishment on the
Albanians, and pass it off as a NATO atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear whether the guards had full control over the
900 prisoners who were now freed of their cells. The Spanish
peacekeeping soldiers guarding the prison confirm Husaj's account.
But the incident may have begun as a prison riot, they said, and it
was clear from makeshift weapons found later that some of the
inmates attempted to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned and ran down the slope and into that building, block
B,'' he said. ``Who could escape just ran.'' But they were unable
to leave the compound. Hundreds of prisoners fled into the
buildings, hiding in basements and cells, and later bringing in the
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 36 hours, anarchy reigned as masked policemen moved
into the grounds, seeking out and attacking prisoners with
automatic weapons and grenades. Prisoners barricaded themselves
into rooms and basements, seizing wooden bars, metal pipes and
pieces of glass as weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement of the cultural center, under insulated heating
pipes and industrial washing machines, the weapons still lay
around: a spade, metal spikes, wooden bars and stretches of metal
piping, wrapped with rags for a better grip.
</P>
<P>
   Pools of dried blood still stained the floor, amid discarded
clothes. Two small round craters from a hand grenade pockmarked the
cement floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought they wanted to kill us all,'' he said, describing
the state of terror of most prisoners. Only a small percentage of
the prisoners, from one block, were hardened criminals, he said;
the rest were Albanians picked up for minor crimes or for political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Some prisoners trying to escape were shot climbing the walls, he
said. Others finished it for themselves. ``That day four people
went crazy and hanged themselves in their cells,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Husaj himself was nearly killed when three masked policemen
spotted him on the steps of the restaurant building. They fired a
grenade, which hit the entrance wall. He stumbled bleeding down to
the basement, where scores of others were sheltering, and slept
that night in a tiny inner laundry room.
</P>
<P>
   The police stormed the building the next morning. ``They came in
masks, with grenades and machine guns,'' he recalled. ``They
attacked the building with rocket-propelled grenades and shot
through the windows straight into the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   The stench of death from the basement is still overpowering. The
green linoleum floor is still sticky with blood, which has been
smeared around in an attempt to clean it. Husaj moved quickly in
the dark, showing a familiarity with the underground rooms. But
even he gagged as he showed where he saw six people gunned down in
one corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get out of here,'' he said, his face white and gaunt in
the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Serbs shouted that the prisoners, holed up in
the basement, had five minutes to surrender or they would be
killed. The prisoners then gave themselves up, walking out with
their hands on their heads, and they were later transferred to
Lipljan prison in central Kosovo. As they left the, police counted
those missing. It came to 154, he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
