<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-EVANDER08-COX     11-07 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield the champ of sequels
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield took up golf recently and quickly
became a respectable player.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every so often, he will shank a tee shot into a nearby
tree, a shot that could shake the confidence of someone with a
mindset different from Holyfield's. The three-time heavyweight
champion simply takes a mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   And on the courtesy second attempt, Holyfield usually hits the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   It is much the same in his boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   With a second fight, Holyfield tees off on his rematch opponent.
He has not lost in five ``mulligan bouts.'' It is one reason he
thinks that his do-over against Lennox Lewis in Las Vegas on
Saturday will be as sweet as a prodigious Tiger Woods drive with a
3-wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn from my mistakes,'' Holyfield said. ``You can take a
fight _ even if you win _ and build on it and be better in a
rematch. So, I'm confident I've learned enough from the first fight
with Lennox to turn it into victory.''
</P>
<P>
   His record supports his assertion. Just as a golfer can recall
every shot from a recently completed round, Holyfield has fresh
memories of his rematches. In second bouts, he has beaten Dwight
Qwai, Alex Stewart, Riddick Bowe, Mike Tyson and Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield won the WBA cruiserweight championship from Qwai 13
years ago in a 15-round decision. In the rematch 17 months later,
he disposed of Qwai in four rounds. As a heavyweight, he turned an
eight-round technical knockout of Stewart in 1989 into a 12-round
decision four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was his dramatic trilogy with Riddick Bowe. Bowe took
Holyfield's undisputed heavyweight championship in a close 12-round
decision Nov. 13, 1992. But Holyfield handled Stewart in his next
fight in 12 rounds and then regained the title by decision in 12
rounds against Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bowe was a bigger guy,'' Holyfieldsaid. ``I jumped into his
chest. I learned from the first fight that I had to jump on him
right away and counter his shots. I let him get off before me too
much in the first fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The joy of that title was short, for the left-handed Moorer
presented awkward angles and took the belt from Holyfield just five
months after he defeated Bowe. As the nonchampion, Holyfield beat
Ray Mercer in a decision and lost to Bowe in their third bout in
the eighth round. Then he polished off Bobby Czyz in five, which
set up his long-awaited confrontation with Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many people, Holyfield destroyed Tyson and
won by TKO in the 11th. Seven months later, he granted Tyson a
rematch. ``I just flat-out got on top of him,'' Holyfield said.
``The first fight, I didn't know him, so it was kind of learning
and adjusting as I went along. In the second fight, I didn't give
him a chance to gain any confidence. I just pressed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed him to the point that Tyson knew he was beaten. Tyson
sealed his fate by biting Holyfield twice on the right ear;
Holyfield won by TKO disqualification in the third round. ``It
wasn't a difficult fight at all,'' Holyfield said. ``I knew from
the first fight how to slow him down. Just go forward at him from
different angles. Beat him to the punch. Then he doesn't feel like
he's in control or that you're afraid of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still riding the wave of that conquest, Holyfield sought to
avenge the Moorer defeat of three years earlier. ``Being
left-handed, Moorer was different,'' Holyfield said. ``He won the
first fight, but it was very close. But the next time, it was real
simple. I had to get closer to him. So I said, `How do I get
close?' It was simple. I just covered up, and he had to come in to
hit me. He didn't learn from the first fight. I hit him with the
same shots. I got him close to me and hit him with uppercuts.''
</P>
<P>
   He knocked out Moorer in Round 8.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is Lewis, who believes he won the fight that was
judged a draw when the two men fought in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can trick Evander once but not twice,'' his attorney, Jim
Thomas, said. ``As well as making sure that he's in great physical
condition, Evander and (trainer) Don Turner put a lot of time into
watching the tapes of fights, evaluating and coming up with a very
good fight plan. And in rematch situations, Evander feels much
better than his opponent, because he's studied him so much that he
knows him.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has studied his lackluster effort against Lewis
repeatedly. And because of his experience in succeeding in
rematches, he claims confidence. ``I'm a better fighter now than I
ever was,'' Holyfield said. ``I'm better in the art of the game. I
understand the game. I know how to set a man up to get my shots
off. Against Lennox, I threw some punches, but they weren't
effective. He didn't want to fight _ he ran _ and I just wanted to
hit him. So, I followed him around trying to make the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this time to be patient. I know how to conserve my
energy. I know how to set him up by being patient and not chasing
him all the time. Like always, I learned from the first fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
