u e BC-JESUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     11-07 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIRE OF THE EVERLASTING HILLS: ASSESSING THE GIFT-GIVER OF
NAZARETH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is the third volume in Thomas Cahill's projected
seven-volume Hinges of History series, in which the author means to
``retell the story of the Western world as the story of the great
gift-givers'' instead of as a sequence of catastrophes, as history
is often portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   The gift-giver in this case is Jesus of Nazareth, whom Cahill
calls ``the central figure of Western civilization.'' The question
posed here is the one Cahill sees as implied by his title, ``Desire
of the Everlasting Hills,'' which those familiar with the Bible
will recognize from Jacob's blessing on his son Joseph, in Genesis
49:26. (Cahill's translation is from the Latin of Jerome's
Vulgate.) As Cahill puts it: ``Is not the desire of the everlasting
hills that they be saved from their everlastingness, that something
new happen, that the everlasting cycle of human cruelty, of man's
inhumanity to man, be brought to an end?'' Or, to put the issue of
his book another way, did Jesus, with his attempts to affect such
changes, make a difference to the world?
</P>
<P>
   This issue will at once be seen to lack the verve of those
brought up in Cahill's previous books, ``How the Irish Saved
Civilization'' and ``The Gifts of the Jews.'' (The subtitle of the
new book is, quietly, ``The World Before and After Jesus,'' whereas
the subtitles of the previous books are ``The Untold Story of
Ireland's Heroic Role From the Fall of Rome to the Rise of Medieval
Europe'' and ``How a Tribe of Desert Nomads Changed the Way
Everyone Thinks and Feels.'')
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Cahill's answer to his question seems obvious. Of
course Jesus made a difference. At the very least, as the author
concludes, ``though war and injustice continue to rage,'' thanks to
Christ's teachings ``we have at last found words to describe and
condemn these oppressions, rather than praise them as we might once
have been tempted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But posing such an open-ended question also serves as a vehicle
for exploring numerous other matters surrounding Jesus. And Cahill,
the former director of religious publishing at Doubleday, takes
full advantage.
</P>
<P>
   First, he compellingly depicts the world that Jesus arrived in,
painting both the despair of the Jewish people over the dilution of
their culture by conquering overlords and their dreams of a savior,
expressed by the prophecies in the last third of the Book of
Isaiah. (``Comfort ye, comfort ye, my people.'')
</P>
<P>
   Second, he analyzes the books of the New Testament, making
distinct the authors of the Gospels and Epistles _ Mark, Matthew,
Luke and John, and Paul of Tarsus _ and showing how their
backgrounds influenced their varying portraits of Jesus. Third, he
touches on important scriptural controversies, as usual avoiding
the pitfalls of obscureness and making what could easily have been
dull entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, he touches ever so obliquely on the question of whether
Jesus actually existed. Though there are differences in approach,
he notes the underlying consistency of the portraits and remarks
that this ``makes Jesus a unique figure in world literature: never
have so many writers managed to convey the same impression of the
same human being over and over again.'' And he argues at some
length that the genuineness of the Shroud of Turin has yet to be
refuted, although he denies being a ``shroudie.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he presses certain subtler issues emanating from Jesus'
life. One is that in First Corinthians, Paul becomes ``the first
person in history'' to insist on the essential equality of the
sexes. Another is that, in the words of Rabbi Shaye J.D. Cohen,
Christianity is ``a form of Judaism.'' Cahill stresses this point
throughout, arguing that the two religions have more in common than
at odds and that while each has reason to suspect the other, the
more important challenge for the two is to reconcile.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because so much about Jesus remains unresolved and
controversial, ``Desire of the Everlasting Hills'' lacks the full
delight and insouciance of Cahill's earlier books. The strain of
elucidating so many subtleties about the Scriptures may explain why
the prose zigzags somewhat sharply between high seriousness and
sudden bursts of the vernacular like ``the harder the pecs and the
tighter the buns the more spiritual you were'' (speaking of the
Greek attitude toward the body) or ``Earth to Jesus: Hello!''
(responding to Jesus' injunction against looking on a woman with
lust).
</P>
<P>
   And because so much ground is covered and so much information
packed together, you often feel in danger of missing what Cahill is
really saying on a number of subtle subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Desire'' remains divertingly instructive and imparts
gratifying dimension to the beginnings of what later became known
as Christianity. Most important, it makes of Jesus a still-living
literary presence. As Cahill writes: ``What especially makes the
Gospels _ from a literary point of view _ works like no others is
that they are about a good human being. As every writer knows, such
a creature is all but impossible to capture on the page, and there
are exceedingly few figures in all of literature who are both good
and memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   He concludes: ``Yet the evangelists, who left no juvenilia
behind them _ no failed novels, rhythmless poems, or other early
works by which we might judge their progress as writers _ whose
Greek was often odd or imprecise, and who were not practiced
writers of any sort, these four succeeded where almost all others
failed. To a writer's eyes, this feat is a miracle just a little
short of raising the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DESIRE OF THE EVERLASTING HILLS: The World Before and After
Jesus'
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Cahill
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 353 pages. Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
