<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SHOOTING-ARREST08-COX     11-07 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-ARREST08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect in fatal family shooting arrested
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good and Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An airport officer in Chattanooga, Tenn., had two
friendly chats with Kenneth Beamon before learning he was talking
to a suspected killer.
</P>
<P>
   Beamon is accused of killing an Atlanta woman and her two sons
Friday night. The cop's third talk with Beamon was brief and
one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're under arrest,'' Chattanooga Airport Police Officer
Richard Ansel said, handcuffing Beamon, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel arrested Beamon at 12:10 a.m. Sunday. He also detained
Beamon's girlfriend, Shannon Sizemore, 19. The couple had planned
to spend the night inside the airport and catch a bus Sunday
morning at the nearby Greyhound Bus terminal, which was closed for
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Beamon was charged with the murders of Teresa Shoemaker, 32, and
her two sons, Lamar, 14, and Robert, 12, in their southeast Atlanta
home. Police say Beamon also shot Shoemaker's husband, Charles
Shoemaker, 34, who survived despite a gunshot wound to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday evening, Atlanta homicide detectives planned to question
Sizemore, who has not been charged with a crime, said Atlanta
police Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson. Sizemore is Teresa Shoemaker's
niece. Police believe Sizemore had stayed with the Shoemakers
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   They want to ask her why Beamon would kill. They want to know
how. They want to know if anyone else was involved, since a gun and
a knife were used. They want to know what Beamon said as he fled to
Chattanooga with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have the answers soon enough,'' Jackson said. ``He will
have to answer for killing three people.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Shoemaker died of gunshot wounds to her head and chest,
said Al Boudy, a Fulton County Medical Examiner's Office
investigator. Lamar was shot in the chest. Robert was stabbed in
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Shoemaker was shot, then stabbed, said his uncle, Joe
McCollough.
</P>
<P>
   He said Shoemaker told him the gunman shot him in the head,
though it luckily was only a ``glancing blow'' that knocked him out
for a time.
</P>
<P>
   The shooter then apparently ran out of bullets and tried to
finish the job by stabbing Shoemaker with a knife three to four
times in the back and side, McCollough said. Shoemaker regained
consciousness and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Atlanta police obtained warrants for Beamon's arrest
and sent word to police agencies throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel, the airport police officer, first spotted Beamon and
Sizemore as the pair were walking to the airport around 9:45 p.m.
Sunday. Neither had luggage. Sizemore carried a newspaper. Ansel
stopped and asked if they needed help.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're just going to the airport,'' he remembered Beamon
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was courteous and friendly,'' Ansel said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, inside the airport's atrium, Ansel walked up to Sizemore,
who was standing alone. Again he asked if she needed help. She
seemed a little nervous. She said no and Beamon walked up.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel asked if they were waiting on a flight. No, they were
waiting on a bus, Beamon explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Greyhound station is only a half mile from the airport.
People occasionally stay in the airport overnight, waiting for the
bus station to open.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel told them where to buy snacks in the terminal, and the duo
headed that way.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Ansel went into the police office where he
took a telephone call from a police dispatcher. The dispatcher
described a man and his girlfriend wanted in connection with the
Shoemaker slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just talking to them,'' Ansel said.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel called his sergeant, Simon Dean, and soon Beamon and
Sizemore were coming out of the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Beamon was unarmed and did not struggle. He was booked into the
Hamilton County Jail in Chattanooga, where he awaits extradition to
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors on Sunday remembered the Shoemakers as people who
didn't cause any trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of her boys loved their bicycles. ... They were always on
their bikes,'' said Shirley Stegal, a family friend who lives
nearby on Hill Street. The Shoemakers ``mostly kept to themselves.
They were pretty nice people, though.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollough said the Shoemakers were looking to move out of the
neighborhood. McCollough said he last saw the family a month ago,
when he took them house hunting in Henry County.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get into the country,'' he said. ``Where it
would be quieter.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
