<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSULTANT-LEAVES-ART     11-07 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSULTANT-LEAVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE GROUP FOUNDER STEPPING DOWN FOR NEW VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of people out there trying to make a living as
experts and consultants in the technology and communications
businesses. Almost all of them owe something to Howard Anderson,
who practically invented the technology consulting industry when he
founded Yankee Group Research Inc. in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   And now, even Yankee's competitors have a new reason to thank
Anderson: He is leaving. Almost three decades after issuing his
first research report, ``The Unbundling of AT&AMP;T,'' in 1971,
Anderson said on Friday that he would step down from day-to-day
responsibilities at Yankee, based in Boston, to start a new venture
capital operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrific,'' said Anderson, 55, in an interview. ``We've
grown internally and I'm going to be here to help. Helping mentor
the next generation is great fun, and we're bringing in some
terrific talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Berge Ayvazian, 46, is the new chief executive. Ayvazian has
been with the firm for 14 years and was previously Yankee's chief
operating officer. Anderson will remain Yankee's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   From a financial perspective, Anderson deployed his exit
strategy three years ago, when he sold Yankee, of which he was the
sole shareholder, to Primark Corp. for $34 million. Anderson
received additional payments from Primark of about $20 million when
Yankee met certain growth targets.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's new venture, to be called Yankeetek, is putting
together a $50 million fund to invest in start-up companies
focused, naturally, on the Internet and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hot VC in Boston wants to invest,'' Anderson said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This is Anderson's second incarnation as a venture capitalist.
In 1983, he was one of three co-founders of Battery Ventures, which
earlier this year closed its fifth main fund, with a value of $440
million.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson holds the title of special partner at Battery, which
has maintained an affiliation with Yankee since its inception.
Among the companies Battery has invested in are Akamai, Fore
Systems and Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   Both Battery and Yankee have agreed to invest in Yankeetek,
Anderson said, and Yankeetek will fit into the family of
enterprises by helping identify investment opportunities in very
small companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battery does companies where the unit has product, it has
sales, it may or may not have earnings,'' Anderson said. But
Yankeetek, he said, will look only at start-up companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
