<HEADLINE>
SIDEWAYS GLANCE: WHAT'S AN AUTHOGRAPH WORTH TO YA?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, when Jim Lampley was just starting his
professional broadcasting career, ABC had him running around as a
reporter with Billie Jean King and O.J. Simpson for coverage of
``The Superstars'' competition from Rotunda, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The local autograph seekers recognized King and Simpson and kept
shoving pieces of paper under their noses. But Lampley?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell they didn't know who I was,'' said Lampley, ``and
every time I signed an autograph, they wouldn't even look at it,
and then move to the next celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   So as an experiment, every time Lampley was given something to
autograph, he signed it ``O.J. Simpson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have signed more than 100 of them,'' Lampley said.
``True story.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as he didn't leave fingerprints, he should be OK. But as
long as we're on the subject of autograph etiquette, it leads into
our latest ``What Would Jim Lampley Do?'' question:
</P>
<P>
   __ Situation: As you are leaving a restaurant with your family,
you spot a famous athlete sitting at a table across the way.
Although it seems he's there to have dinner, his food hasn't
arrived, and he's talking with others at his table. Is this a good
time to approach this person for an autograph or even for a
handshake?
</P>
<P>
   __ What Jim Lampley would do: ``I've been on both ends of this
situation. And as a rule, I never approach the person unless I'm
absolutely certain they know who I am. As a stranger, I wouldn't do
it. But then, I'm not exactly starving for the opportunity to meet
famous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a style and art and delicacy and sensitivity to
approaching someone you don't know. For me, there are situations
where I could be changing my baby's diaper or trying to buy an
airline ticket, and if someone approaches it the right way, then
it's a pleasure to meet them. But most people don't have that
subtlety to pull off something like that. A lot don't know how to
pull anything off, even if they're at a crowded arena, without
being offensive. I mean, on a plane once, I had someone reach
across me to jostle Bruce Jenner to wake him up to get an
autograph. That's an extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why people want autographs anyway. Wouldn't
it mean more to shake someone's hand and look them in the eye and
say something nice? The people who get the nerve up to ask to have
a picture taken with you have somehow developed the politeness to
get it done. But if you're a no-name celebrity like me, or even if
you're the real thing, people will ask for your autograph and they
don't even know who you are. That's really off-putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't rule out the possibility that I could be sitting there
in a restaurant and someone who approaches is not only charming to
me but to the rest of the table. But most times, it's going to fail
and be awkward. And the famous person isn't going to like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
