<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-NEWSPAPERS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAII FIGHTS TO KEEP A NEWSPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Previously slugged HAWAII-STRIKE) 
(lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Hawaii is no stranger to monopolies. This former
island kingdom is still a place where a handful of landlords own
vast tracts, where entrenched business interests dominate civic
affairs and where the Democratic Party, which has held sway since
the beginning of statehood, controls the governorship, the entire
congressional delegation and roughly 80 percent of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But now the state is fighting to keep Honolulu from becoming a
one-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, the owners of The Honolulu Star-Bulletin, a
scrappy afternoon daily that traces its roots to 1882, announced
plans to close on Oct. 30, without even offering it for sale, and
to accept a payment of $26.5 million to end a joint operating
agreement with its morning rival, The Honolulu Advertiser, which is
owned by Gannett Co. The end seemed inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the Hawaii attorney general sued to block
the deal, arguing that Gannett's payment violated federal antitrust
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started looking into it, and we had a sense that there's
this transaction that's about to be consummated that involves the
payment of a big chunk of change by one competitor to its only
competition to close down,'' said Rod Kimura, a deputy state
attorney general. ``And we felt there was enough there to say:
`Look, why should we just sit back and ponder this? We ought to
bring it before the appropriate body, which is the court.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Judge Alan Kay of U.S. District Court here ruled
that the payment was tantamount to a buyout that would eliminate
``any competition to The Advertiser in this unique island
community,'' and so would run counter to the intent of the
Newspaper Preservation Act, a 1970 federal law that waived
antitrust rules to let newspapers share some operating expenses in
an effort to preserve competition.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kay said, the deal was not exempt from antitrust
scrutiny, and he granted a preliminary injunction barring the
closure.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Justice Department subpoenaed records and began an
investigation into whether the planned closing broke antitrust
laws. Federal lawyers are conducting a similar review of Hearst
Corp.'s purchase of The San Francisco Chronicle, which has been in
a joint operating agreement with The San Francisco Examiner, owned
by Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett has appealed to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in San Francisco, where the injunction is pending, arguing that it
was exempt from antitrust provisions under the Newspaper
Preservation Act, and that forcing it to publish the paper would
violate its First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1962, the Honolulu papers have functioned under a joint
operating agreement in which they shared production, advertising
and distribution costs but maintained separate newsrooms. The
current agreement, entered into six years ago when Gannett sold The
Star-Bulletin to Liberty Newspapers for $15 million and then bought
The Advertiser from a local family, was set to expire in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Phillips, a mainland investor who is a general partner of
Liberty, said in announcing the closing that he could make at least
a 20 percent return by investing in mainland newspapers instead of
the annual return of 12 percent to 17 percent that he was
guaranteed under the joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Liberty's right to sell the paper, which is
profitable, or to close it and let the joint operating agreement
expire. It is Gannett's payment that has raised the hackles of
state and federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a court brief filed last week in support of Hawaii's effort
to block the closing, the Justice Department said the case ``may
present important questions of the extent of antitrust immunity
conferred by the Newspaper Preservation Act and the reach of
antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Munger, a lawyer for Gannett, said the newspaper would have
no further comment until it filed its next brief, on Wednesday, as
did Alan Marx, a lawyer for Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Some time after that, a three-judge panel of the court of
appeals is expected to decide whether to uphold the injunction and
allow a trial on the closing, or lift the injunction.
</P>
<P>
   If the injunction is lifted, all sides expect The Star-Bulletin
to close within days. If the case goes to trial, no one is sure
what would happen, though most experts agree that The Star-Bulletin
would eventually close, because Gannett has already acquired most
of its assets and advertisers will face continuing pressure to
patronize The Advertiser, whose daily circulation is about 105,000
compared with about 65,000 for the Star-Bulletin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   George Chaplin, who was editor in chief of The Advertiser for 28
years until his retirement in 1986, and who retains the title of
editor at large, predicted that The Star-Bulletin could not
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time this happens, it's a real tragedy and it imposes a
real responsibility on the remaining paper to try to fill the gap,
which it never adequately can,'' Chaplin said
</P>
<P>
   The possible closure is a bitter irony for the staff of The
Star-Bulletin, which over the last two years has helped prompt a
small revolution with its aggressive coverage of mismanagement at
the Bishop Estate, a giant trust of former royal lands that has
been the subject of an investigation by state and federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has led to the replacement of the estate's
board of politically connected trustees. The Star-Bulletin sparked
the case by publishing a manifesto by Hawaiian elders criticizing
the trust, after The Advertiser had asked the authors for more time
to decide whether to run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, obviously,'' said the Star-Bulletin's managing
editor, David Shapiro, whose remaining staff rallied last week to
cover the shooting of seven people at a Xerox Corp. warehouse even
as some editors had already begun leaving. ``People are distracted.
Emotions are all over the place, understandably so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Advertiser has said it will have room for perhaps 20 to 25
of the Star-Bulletin's 100 reporters and editors, said Wayne
Cahill, administrative officer of the Hawaii Newspaper Guild, which
represents workers at both papers. He is still hopeful a way can be
found to keep the paper open until at least the end of the joint
operating agreement in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a settlement possibility,'' Cahill said, but he
added: ``If the injunction's lifted, the paper's dead. Then it's
left for lawyers to argue over who did a bad thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
