<P>
   BOEING-TAIL (Newport R.I) _ Hundreds of Boeing 767 airplanes
like EgyptAir plane that crashed off the Massachusetts coast,
killing all 217 people aboard, could be flying with improperly
torqued bolts that hold the vertical tail to the fuselage, the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer has learned. It is not yet clear if the
suspect bolts could be in planes built as far back as 1989, the
year the 767-300 that crashed was delivered to EgyptAir. Boeing
says the bolts aren't likely to pose a safety threat to airplanes
because of the big jet's redundant systems. But the company says it
is considering issuing a service bulletin warning operators of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
