<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' journey of discovery
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Every November they have an NBA season, they send the
Hawks west. However, the first trip of the season has never quite
had all the ramifications of this one.
</P>
<P>
   With stops tonight in Denver, then Vancouver, Portland and Los
Angeles to meet the Lakers, the young Hawks will be asked to run at
a time when they are still stumbling.
</P>
<P>
   They will see some of the best competition in the Trail Blazers
and Lakers after taking on some of the weakest in the West, the
Nuggets and Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   They will encounter their past when Dikembe Mutombo returns to
Denver; when ex-teammate Grant Long, injured and dressed in
civvies, says hello from the western corner of Canada; when Steve
Smith, among the classiest of all who wore the Hawks uniform, goes
after them in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   They will compare their own new Philips Arena to the plush,
bright Pepsi Center here and the Staples Center in Los Angeles.
Hawks-Thrashers-Braves president Stan Kasten and Hawks executive
vice president Lee Douglas will dare to compare in person.
</P>
<P>
   They will encounter the pessimism of a city expecting to lose
its team in Vancouver and the optimism born of a star-studded
roster in Portland, undefeated through four.
</P>
<P>
   With all that as a backdrop, the Hawks will try to at least
break even. If that is to happen, victories tonight and Wednesday
in Vancouver are almost compulsory.
</P>
<P>
   Quite understandably, coach Lenny Wilkens said, ``I feel a lot
better about things'' after the Hawks clobbered the weak Chicago
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The Hawks shot .543 from the field, accumulated 21
assists, 10 steals and committed only 11 errors after 49 violations
in opening losses to Washington and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo, who scored 16 points, grabbed 13 rebounds and blocked
three shots against marginally talented Will Perdue, also took
heart in the 113-97 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we showed how good we can be,'' Mutombo said. ``You
must start someplace and establish yourself if you are going to be
a good team. In our first two games we did not do that, but in this
one we played with much more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our young guys are learning. Young (Chris) Crawford played
better (14 points). (Jason) Terry is improving night after night.
There's a lot more we want to see of him. I think his communication
with Bimbo (Coles) is working very well. I see them talking in the
time-outs, Bimbo telling him what he can do and that makes him
better.''
</P>
<P>
   With the wealth of shooters at their disposal, the Hawks'
success will be in the hands of Coles, a nine-year journeyman, and
Terry, the bright neophyte.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a big step,'' Coles said of Terry, who had 12 points
and five assists against the Bulls and sparked the rally that
turned the game in the second quarter. ``But he's lucky. He's got a
lot of old point guards to each him _ me, Lenny and. . . . then
there's Stan The Man (Kasten).''
</P>
<P>
   They'll all be available on this trek west.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
