<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-NY-MARA-WHEELCHAI     11-07 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARA-WHEELCHAIRS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WHEELCHAIRS, NO STOP SIGNS BUT ALSO NO PRIZE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second time in two years, Miguel Such was the
first to roll across the finish line in the New York City
Marathon's wheelchair event Sunday, and he thrust his fists in the
air and savored victory.
</P>
<P>
   But for Such and several other wheelchair athletes, who have
sued the marathon's organizers for discrimination, the real victory
was that none of them were stopped along the course to let leading
runners pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much better than ever before,'' said Bob Neumayer, a
52-year-old veteran of 14 New York marathons. ``They didn't stop us
at the 59th Street Bridge, and that's the first time since 1986. I
saw progress. There is a long way to go, but I saw progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine wheelchair athletes, including two of the top three men's
finishers Sunday, filed suit against the New York Road Runners Club
in July, alleging that the marathon has discriminated against them
not only by delaying wheelchair racers to let top runners pass, but
also by denying them prize money and medals, which the elite
runners receive.
</P>
<P>
   New York has lagged behind most other cities in Europe and the
United States where wheelchair divisions have become a fixture in
marathons. In the last 20 years, wheelchair racing has developed
from a sideshow into a sport in its own right, with strict rules
about equipment. Some elite wheelchair athletes have become
professionals, attracting sponsorships and living on their purses.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Road Runners Club, however, has never created a
separate division for the wheelchair athletes with prizes and
medals. Nor does the marathon distinguish between the athletes
using racing wheelchairs pushed by hand and those using
hand-cranked chairs, which use bicycle gears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to create an official wheelchair division and then
they can eliminate all these problems,'' Such said, after winning
with a time of 2 hours 39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Such, a broad-shouldered 25-year-old professional racer from
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., said he was happy none of the wheelchair
athletes was detained along the route as some were last year, when
the police held dozens at the Queensboro Bridge for a half-hour to
let the lead runners pass.
</P>
<P>
   But Such noted with some bitterness that there was no ribbon at
the finish line for him, nor would there be any ceremony for the
top three wheelchair finishers, not to mention the lack of purses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the publicity we have here, and go to the runners and
compare the two,'' he said, struggling to get into sweat clothes in
the recovery area. ``There is a huge difference. We should be able
to get the same publicity. We should be able to get some prize
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Nogueira, an artist and professional wheelchair racer from
Glen Ridge, N.J., who came in third in the event (2:01:46) agreed.
``To do 26 miles and have no ribbon?'' he said. ``Come on!''
</P>
<P>
   But other wheelchair athletes said they were satisfied with the
road runners club's response to their complaints. In October, the
organizers agreed in a court-ordered stipulation not to
``unreasonably or unlawfully obstruct'' the wheelchair athletes.
They also agreed not to deflect news media attention from the
wheelchair event.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Guzman, 52, of Queens, was among those stopped at the
Queensboro Bridge last year. ``This year there was no problem,'' he
said. ``They only problem we had this year was there was too much
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wheelchair participants said the high winds and
chilly temperatures slowed their times dramatically. One hundred
forty-five men and women from 30 countries competed, though not all
used racing wheelchairs. The race started at 10:20 a.m., a
half-hour before the runners set off.
</P>
<P>
   Franz Neitlispach, a top wheelchair racer from Switzerland, who
recently won the Chicago marathon, took an early lead, accompanied
closely by his countryman Guido Mueller. Neitlispach was considered
the man to beat in this field.
</P>
<P>
   Such and Nogueira, who often train together, could not close the
gap on the Swiss duo until Mile 14. Wheelchair racing is similar to
cycling, in which competitors draft off the chair ahead of them to
conserve energy and then try to tire their opponents with repeated
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   At the 14th mile it appeared to be a four-man race. But
Neitlispach inexplicably dropped out and finished back in the pack.
Then at the 23rd mile, Such made his move, breaking away. Mueller,
a 40-year-old electronic technician, who finished first here in
1979, found the strength to push past Nogueira in the last two
miles, finishing with a time of 2:01:11, but he could not catch
Such.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard because of the wind,'' he said, slumped over
his chair with exhaustion at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place finisher among women was Helene A. Hines, 51, of
Lido Beach, N.Y., a former physical education teacher who has
multiple sclerosis. It was her first race in a wheelchair, though
she said she had run marathons. Using a hand-cranked chair, she
finished in 2:15:20. ``They told me hold back because it was my
first time,'' she said. ``But I just went for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-place women's spot went to a Canadian, Diane
Rakiecki, a 38-year-old teacher from Kelowna, British Columbia, who
rolled across the finish on a hand-cranked chair with a time of
2:32:23.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman to finish in a racing wheelchair, according to
the official results, was Maria Rosales of Argentina, 34th in
3:31:56.
</P>
<P>
   For the nine plaintiffs in the lawsuit, the day was a step in
the right direction. Still, Such said he longs for a day when a
wheelchair athlete will receive a gold medal on a dais in New York,
as in Boston and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York just hasn't caught up,'' he said, shaking his head.
``You see, it's for that little kid who is sitting at home and just
broke his back and can't look up to a Michael Jordan or a Wayne
Gretzky. But he can look up to a wheelchair athlete.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-A     11-07 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE MICROSOFT, WHITE HOUSE IS STILL CONSOLIDATION FRIENDLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Wash., Calif., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration may have rattled the
house of Bill Gates with its aggressive antitrust case against
Microsoft, but it is in the process of winking at some of the older
economic empires that in an earlier age dominated American
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days President Clinton is expected to sign a financial
services bill repealing the 1933 act that had shattered the house
of Morgan. The administration has already approved deals that have
resurrected big pieces of the old Bell telephone system, and later
this year regulators may approve an $80 billion merger involving
Exxon that would restore a chunk of the old Rockefeller oil empire.
</P>
<P>
   These and other actions from Washington reflect an enduring
legacy of Clinton's tenure. Assuming the president's signature on
new banking legislation that will deregulate Wall Street and usher
in a new wave of corporate consolidations, Clinton and his
administration will go down in history as encouraging the largest
number of business mergers _ and in some industries the greatest
concentration of economic power _ in many years.
</P>
<P>
   While its prosecution of Microsoft for using monopoly power to
squelch competition, and a few other notable exceptions, have shown
the Clinton administration to be more aggressive on antitrust
matters than were the regulators during the Reagan and Bush years,
the administration has also been far more tolerant of business
mergers than officials earlier in the century and in the 1960s. And
the deregulation under Clinton of telecommunications, financial
services and other industries, combined with policies that do not
condemn big mergers for their size alone, has led to an
unprecedented number of corporate deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the greatest merger wave in history, and yet we are
hardly in the greatest litigation wave,'' said John Shepard Wiley
Jr., a professor of antitrust law at the University of California
at Los Angeles. ``There has been a sea change in attitudes toward
large mergers. It's a much different philosophy from the 1960s,
when the polestar was the protection of small business.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 12 years of the Reagan and Bush administrations,
which are widely viewed as among the most permissive antitrust
periods of the century, there were 85,064 corporate mergers valued
at more than $3.5 trillion, according to Securities Data Co. Under
nearly seven years of the Clinton administration, there have so far
been 166,310 deals valued at more than $9.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers tell only a small part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington have already approved deals that have
put back together huge pieces of the old Ma Bell, reducing the
number of regional Bell companies to four from an original seven.
Officials are now considering a merger between Sprint and MCI
Worldcom that would reduce to two the number of dominant American
long-distance carriers, a second deal that will allow AT&AMP;T to
control more than 35 percent of the cable industry, and a third
merger that would give Viacom an ownership interest of at least 35
percent of the broadcast market.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the 1960s, Justice Department officials
successfully challenged many relatively small deals, perhaps the
most notable of which was the Vons grocery company's proposed
acquisition of Shopping Bag Food Stores, in which the combined
entity would have controlled only 7.5 percent of the Los Angeles
market.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration has applied a looser
standard of review of mergers and acquisitions than some previous
administrations, it has been more aggressive in other areas of
antitrust enforcement. It has, for example, brought a number of
major price-fixing cases and initiated many important international
cartel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, its most prominent monopoly case has been the
Microsoft lawsuit, in which a federal judge concluded last week
that the company had bullied competitors and stifled innovation.
The case fits squarely in the tradition of the antitrust action
that the government began in the late 1960s against IBM and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of mergers, Clinton officials say that despite the
number of large corporate combinations and the emergence of more
huge financial conglomerates, the economy is robustly competitive,
and that the economies of scale and scope achieved by some of the
mergers have served consumers well.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are clearly new challenges for regulation in
antitrust,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Thursday in
an interview, ``I suspect that in the majority of industries, the
degree of competition has increased. Because of technology and
openness to trade, in many areas consumers have more choices than
ever before. And clearly one reason that inflation is low is that
businesses today have less pricing power.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers and other officials say that the globalization of the
economy has enlarged the marketplace to more than offset any
potential ill effects caused by the wave of mergers. The treasury
secretary also said that the deregulation of major industries, most
recently financial businesses, would help those who shop for
banking, securities and insurance services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make the economy more efficient and consumers will
benefit from that,'' he predicted. ``As the deregulation of
airlines and telecommunications demonstrates, archaic restrictions
reduce choice and raise prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics questions the policies. In the financial services
area, they ask whether regulators will be able to adequately
oversee new conglomerates that, should they encounter difficulties,
could pose systemwide problems. In telecommunications, they wonder
whether the government has been so permissive as to stifle
competition. And more generally, they ask whether the regulators of
an earlier day had it right in questioning size for size's sake.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Roosevelt is turning over in his grave,'' said Kenneth
Guenther, a top lobbyist for many small banks and savings
associations, recalling Roosevelt's trust-busting instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Through much of the century, Washington viewed big industries
and financial conglomerates with great suspicion, reflecting a
long-held American fear that concentration was not a good thing.
There was also deep distrust of unchecked financial institutions,
particularly during times of economic decline, when they were
blamed for economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, following one of the biggest economic booms of all
times, Washington has become more trusting of Wall Street today, to
the point where it was not considered a big deal when former
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin announced that he would become a
senior official at Citigroup, the nation's largest financial
institution and a major beneficiary of the new financial services
law that Rubin had worked so hard to have adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission,
recalled: ``There used to be a populist attitude abroad and in the
United States that big was bad, that very large companies treated
their workers, their customers and their supplies in ways that
weren't entirely fair. The idea was that small towns were better
served by small enterprises than by big firms from the East Coast.
There is now less mistrust of large companies, and the question is
no longer simply whether a firm is big, but whether its size is
being used unfairly to restrict competition and hurt consumers.
There is less apprehension about bigness than there used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky, a leading antitrust scholar, has been a major
proponent of examining big mergers not just by their size, but also
by exploring what efficiencies they may create that can benefit
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts say that in particular industries, like
financial services, deals that may seem either neutral or
beneficial to consumers in the short run may come with longer-term
costs. Many experts predict that the new financial services
legislation will lead to problems.
</P>
<P>
   The major question is whether regulators will be able to
adequately supervise the new financial behemoths, a process that
one former top official recently likened to ``bloodhounds chasing
greyhounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have in place the protocols to handle the problems,''
said Edward Kane, a professor of finance at Boston College, who in
the 1980s made the most accurate prediction of the impending
decacle of the savings and loan industry, which bankrupted a
federal deposit insurance fund. ``If our government could not
discipline the savings and loan industry in the 1960s, '70s and
'80s, how will it be able to discipline a Citigroup and other
global interests in 2000?''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said that if anything, the new legislation would reduce
certain risks by permitting financial institutions to move into new
areas of business. ``Diversified institutions are less likely to
fail than undiversified institutions,'' he said. ``Financial
institutions that are better diversified have safer portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials, including Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, while broadly endorsing the move to deregulate Wall
Street, have spoken of the need to be particularly vigilant about
the larger financial institutions soon to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The new banking legislation also recognizes the particular
threats to the system posed by the nation's largest financial
institutions by imposing certain new conditions on the 50 biggest
ones if they decide to enter into the securities or insurance
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
