<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NH-INDEPENDENTS-1005(     11-07 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-INDEPENDENTS-1005(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERDOGS WOO INDEPENDENT VOTERS IN KEY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO with ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Michael O'Leary spent his Saturday knocking
on doors for Bill Bradley, the former senator who is running for
the Democratic presidential nomination. Yet O'Leary says he is
considering voting for another candidate in New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation primary in February: Sen. John McCain, the
maverick Republican from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, a 44-year-old building contractor from Lebanon, N.H.,
is one of the state's growing number of independents _ registered
to vote, politically active, but with no allegiance to either
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley is my first pick, but I'm tempted to vote for
McCain, so he can give Bush a run for the money,'' he said,
referring to the presumed Republican front-runner, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In their underdog campaigns for the presidency, McCain and
Bradley are counting on victories, or at least near-victories, in
New Hampshire to give them a shot at knocking off their parties'
front-runners. And as they rise in the polls here, they find
themselves in an odd duel for independent voters like O'Leary, who
are allowed under state rules to cast ballots in the Democratic or
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   It is these independent voters who have given New Hampshire its
tradition of being kind to insurgent, anti-establishment
candidates. Recent polls show that they prefer McCain over Bush,
and Bradley over his lone Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the independents are a growing force in the state's
politics. State officials predict that nearly 40 percent of New
Hampshire's voters will be unaffiliated by the 2000 election,
because the majority of new registrants decline to join a party.
</P>
<P>
   Now those independents could play pivotal roles in both parties'
primaries, raising a difficult question for McCain and Bradley: Is
this a zero-sum game where a surge among independents by one
necessarily hurts the other?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley and McCain are competing against each other for the
undeclared partisans,'' said Lynn Vavreck, assistant professor of
government at Dartmouth College. ``I suspect this contest will be
decided on which party primary these undeclared decide to vote
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts say Gore was thinking about the
possibility of McCain's stealing unaffiliated voters from Bradley
when he recently praised the Republican, saying: ``He's a man of
integrity. I hear an awful lot of independents are taking a look at
him.'' (Gore did say that he thought he could win independent
voters, too.)
</P>
<P>
   McCain's and Bradley's campaigns say they do not expect to
siphon off unaffiliated voters from each other, asserting that many
independents tilt toward one party or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides also note that beyond the two candidates'
agreement on overhauling campaign-finance rules _ an issue of
appeal to independents _ they differ sharply on other issues.
Bradley, for instance, supports gun control and abortion rights,
while McCain has a long anti-abortion record and generally has
opposed gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But even a small shift in unaffiliated voters could make a
difference in a tight race. And many political analysts say they
expect a significant number of independents to vote in the primary
that seems to be the closest contest, on the theory that their
votes would have greater impact. So the fact that McCain pulled to
within 10 points of Bush in one poll here last week has created a
race in both parties. Gore and Bradley are in a statistical dead
heat here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will look and see who is going to win without
their vote and go to the other,'' said Jeffrey Peters, a New
Hampshire resident who is head of a group called We the People that
advocates greater political participation. ``And if it is really
close in both, then I think they will really have to scratch their
heads and decide between Bradley and McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, for instance, said he was closer to Bradley on the
issues, but will vote for McCain in the Republican primary if he
thinks Bradley is way ahead, or hopelessly behind Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what I said about Bradley I think about McCain,'' he
said. ``They come across as decent, honest, stand-up guys.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's crowds in New Hampshire are also often studded with
independents who say they are trying to choose between the two men.
Ernest Vanesse, 79, is one.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the back of a rally on the day McCain made his
formal announcement in a park in Nashua, Vanesse said he was a
former Democrat who became an independent.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was disgusted with the Monica Lewinsky scandal and
would not vote for Gore, because of his loyalty to President
Clinton. But he praised McCain as ``clearly an honest individual.''
And he said he was also attracted to Bradley because he was a ``new
fresh person in the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Smith, director of the University of New Hampshire's
Survey Center, said independents tended to be somewhat younger,
more mobile, more affluent and better educated than other voters.
He also said they tended to be more socially moderate, a factor
that could help Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides acknowledge that social moderates might not like
McCain's anti-abortion stance, but note that he has called for a
dialogue between the two sides of the issue, to see if there is
middle ground on matters like adoption.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 38 percent of New Hampshire's electorate were
registered Republicans, 23 percent were Democrats and 32 percent
were unaffiliated. But by next year, some state officials predict,
independents will be the largest group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you win them over is with the outsider image,'' Smith
said. ``If you are an independent, you don't want to register to a
party. You've indicated you don't want to be part of the club.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley are clearly following that strategy. Both
cast themselves as populists prepared to buck the status quo. And
both promise to fight the entrenched power of lobbyists through
sweeping changes in campaign finance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``When our country has been taken from us by the special
interests, the big-dollar donors, pride is lost to shame,'' McCain
said in his formal campaign announcement in Nashua, in late
September.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Bradley put it to a group of supporters in Somersworth on
Friday: ``I can tell you right now, if we get campaign-finance
reform, it would be like cutting oxygen off for the lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Their campaigns have also heavily focused on reaching out to
unaffiliated voters in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's political director, said the campaign
always invited the entire public, not just Republicans, to McCain's
frequent town hall meetings in New Hampshire. Until Oct. 29 _ the
deadline to change voter registration _ they urged Democrats who
attended those events to reregister as independents so they could
vote for him in the Republican primary. Weaver said he did not know
how many people had done so.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign also includes in its coalition here a nearly
200-member group called New Hampshire Independents for McCain,
which Weaver said included some disaffected members of both major
parties. One of the chairmen, David Lee, is a volunteer accountant
for the Democratic State Committee who changed his registration to
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said they had no plans to form a separate group
for independents. But they have targeted unaffiliated voters in
their door-to-door canvassing, emphasizing an insurgent message
that they think will appeal to independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is more tied to the Democratic establishment,'' said Mark
Longabaugh, Bradley's New Hampshire coordinator. ``That sends a
signal to independent voters.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been efforts by New Hampshire groups that advocate
campaign-finance changes to bring the two candidates together in a
joint event. Though McCain's aides expressed interest in the idea,
Bradley's campaign rejected it _ an indication, perhaps, that the
campaign does not want to promote McCain's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But at a recent event in Florida, Bradley said he thought McCain
had a good chance of winning the Republican nomination. The reason
he gave _ voters are looking for someone they can trust _ is the
same one he offers when asked why he expects to win the Democratic
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not endorsing him, by the way,'' Bradley added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
