<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-ART-N     11-07 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEBET, TWICE THE RUNNER-UP, OVERCOMES THE ELEMENTS TO PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 36-year-old former Portuguese track star intruded
on Kenya's annual dominance of the New York City Marathon on
Sunday, but only until he was inside Central Park, less than two
miles from the finish. From there it was all uphill.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Joseph Chebet, who for two years had run his heart
out here only to have it broken, pulled away from Domingos Castro
in the park's winding, gradual inclines to win the marathon's 30th
running on a bright but chilly, windy day.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Chebet distanced himself forever from his
reputation of the world's second-best marathoner, the way he left
Castro behind and, earlier, his countryman John Kagwe, the two-time
defending champion who faded badly and finished fifth. By winning
in 2 hours 9 minutes 14 seconds, Chebet won $50,000, in addition to
a $20,000 bonus for finishing under 2:10. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chebet, the fifth Kenyan to win New York in six years, also
became the third runner after the Americans Alberto Salazar in 1982
and Bill Rodgers in 1978 to win the Boston and New York City
Marathons in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   American excellence, much less dominance, continued to be
ancient history, as Dan Middleman, a native Long Islander now out
of Raleigh, N.C, ran an American-best 26th, in 2:24:52. Arsenio
Ortiz, a Mexican who lives in Ozone Park, Queens, was 18th
(2:21:35).  &UR;  &LR;  ``One day,'' said Chebet, a whisper of a man with a
slightly stooped but remarkably efficient and consistent stride,
``I was supposed to win in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In the high altitude of the Kenyan hills, Chebet _ a member of
the Marakwet tribe _ didn't exactly leave this to chance. Motivated
by his breakthrough in Boston, where he also finished second in
1998, Chebet said he added an extra month to the 10 weeks he had
trained for this race the previous two years. He created a
now-or-never mind-set, promising himself that if he didn't win this
time around, he would ``never go back to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it became a matter of execution, of figuring out the best
way to put his extended regimen to use. It did not hurt Chebet that
German Silva, the two-time champion from Mexico best known for
winning in 1994 despite taking a wrong turn into the park, was in
the race as a pace setter, or so-called rabbit, though he had said:
``Please do not call me a rabbit. I am a helper.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as a fellow member of Team Fila, Silva's presence
enabled him to assist Chebet, as well as the other Kenyans _
including the third-place finisher, Shem Kororia, a Chebet training
partner _ who were decked in the blue and orange colors of the
aforementioned shoe manufacturer. Besides helping to set the pace
for the first 90 minutes of the race, Silva carried on a running
dialogue with the leaders, particularly Chebet and the other Fila
Kenyans. He served as a shield for Chebet from the
20-to-30-mile-an-hour wind gusts that were often in the runners'
faces, played amateur psychologist for those moments when doubts
crept in and even served up a drink or two when Chebet and his
mates happened to miss a water station.
</P>
<P>
   Silva, not in marathon shape after having a wart removed from
his foot, had said he would drop out with the other pace setters
midrace. But when the leaders left the Queensboro Bridge onto First
Avenue at the 16th mile, there was Silva, running strong, with
Castro, Giacomo Leone of Italy, Abdelkhader el-Mouaziz of Morocco
and five Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
   Had Silva set everyone up, including his soul mates in shoe
sales? No, he said later. He was just waiting for the best place
where he could drop out to watch the rest of the race. He found it
in a television truck, which he jumped aboard, giving the
struggling el-Mouaziz one last directive: ``You stay,'' Silva said.
``I go.''
</P>
<P>
   Safely aboard the vehicle, perched in front of a monitor, Silva
watched as the seven leaders continued on, until they neared
Central Park on Fifth Avenue. The race seemed to have the potential
to be a free-for-all to the finish, the antithesis of the one-woman
women's event won by Adriana Fernandez of Mexico. Then, suddenly,
the leader field was down to Castro, Chebet and Kagwe, the muscular
Kenyan who trains in Valley Forge National Park near Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Looking fashionably cool in a wool cap and dark glasses, Kagwe,
with his long, powerful strides, offered no hint of the fate that
awaited him inside the park. Castro made a move. Chebet calmly went
with him. Kagwe, in a matter of a handful of strides, fell far
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the energy and couldn't do it,'' Kagwe said, later
adding that he didn't feel comfortable after being kicked several
times by ``a Moroccan,'' presumably el-Mouaziz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tripped five times; the guy kept on hitting my right
leg,'' he said. ``I said, `Oh, no, this is a race and if I hit him,
I will be the one that will be sued.''' Later, he decided: ``It is
not a big deal. I forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Chebet, free at last of Kagwe, and Castro, a 1988
Olympian in the 5,000 meters who remade himself as a marathoner,
winning in Paris in 1995 and Rotterdam two years later. His twin
brother, Dionisio, ran 33rd among the men Sunday, but Domingos
Castro's problem in the park was separating himself from Chebet. He
tried once, and Chebet stayed with him. He tried again, a third
time, then a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Chebet instinctively knew his time had come. ``I saw that he was
a bit tired,'' he said. ``So I used a lot of energy, trying to
leave him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Castro, a more animated, less austere runner, began pumping
his arms to keep up, Chebet burst ahead, with about one and
three-quarter miles to go. His 25th mile, run in 4:43, would be the
fastest by anyone in the race. Gabriele Rosa, Chebet's coach, said
later: ``The race went as planned. He moved when I wanted him to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one last chance for Castro, after the right turn onto
Central Park South, a straightaway, before the final turn back into
the park, to the finish. Castro made up a few strides, but not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kenya, Chebet said people had told him to ``keep on
training, keep on going.'' He took that advice, through Boston and
the 26 miles 385 yards of New York. He did not turn his head until
he was just a few yards from home, and then he knew he would never
again have to look back with regret on the last two years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
