<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SKILLFUL ENVOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If an inability to recall the name of the new
strongman in Pakistan is proof of George Bush's lightweightedness,
then we are all lightweights.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point is the presidential front-runner's instinctive
judgment about Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, who just seized power from
the elected government in Islamabad: ``It appears this guy is going
to bring stability to the country and I think that's good news for
the subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it really good news? Going deeper, would ``stability'' be the
lodestar of George W.'s foreign policy?
</P>
<P>
   When his father, President Bush, spoke in Ukraine just before
the breakup of the Soviet empire, he put stability before
democracy. In what was promptly labeled in this space as his
``Chicken Kiev'' speech, the president urged Ukrainians to stay
under Moscow's control _ a monumental misreading of history.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see if George W.'s instinct is right in the recent
military takeover of a corrupt government in Pakistan. To make the
best case for the new Musharraf regime, I turned to the most
skillful diplomat in the world today: Sahabzada Yaqub Khan.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan trots out the retired Yaqub, a former foreign minister
and ambassador to Washington and Moscow, whenever the nation is in
crisis or an especially delicate job is needed. (He helped arrange
Nixon's opening to China.) His mission to the U.S. this week is to
assure us that the military coup was necessary and is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is democracy an end in itself,'' he asks rhetorically, ``or a
means to an end? What do you do when democracy leads ineluctably to
chaos?''
</P>
<P>
   His country was in a terrible mess. Bribery was rampant and
taxes were being routinely evaded. Banks were lending huge sums to
politicians without collateral. Legislators were intimidating
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``And finally,'' says the envoy, ``the prime minister tried to
subvert the army's loyalty to the nation, subjecting it to
political intrigue, attempting to murder the commander in chief.
The very moral fiber of the nation was damaged by its political
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, a group of nonpolitical technocrats has been
appointed to root out the corrupt practices, revivify the rule of
law, devolve power to local constituencies. Musharraf has promised
to return the nation to its electoral process as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistanis accept this. The AP reports from Pakistan that most
of the populace, disgusted with corruption and religious violence,
welcomed the army coup. As a system, popular government became
unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   But the trouble is, I said to Pakistan's veteran diplomat, that
we've heard this same song about a necessary quick fix four times
in 50 years. Is there something endemic in Pakistan that corrupts
government, subverts civil society and makes a coup necessary
almost every decade?
</P>
<P>
   He chewed that over. ``Is it part of our culture? Frankly, I
have no answer to that. So far, as you suggest, each of our
attempts to cure ourselves has failed. But we must continue to try,
and it is in your interest as a democracy to help us succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Americans seem to possess democracy so naturally, and for
us it is so difficult. But it took you centuries; give us a few
years. Be patient with those to whom democracy does not come
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaqub Kahn can be persuasive. But all too often, a man on
horseback takes over from disorderly democrats and promises a
return to democracy _ and, having tasted power, never gives it up.
Freedom disappears in the name of stability. Better for an army to
be patient, to resist the temptation to regularly straighten out
the nation, and to trust the people to express their disgust at
corruption at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the message briefers should advise Bush to send to
whatsisname, Pakistan's maximum leader: Sustained democracy, even
though it goes through periods of corruption, is better for people
than the most benign dictatorship or technocracy. Impress the world
with the speed with which you establish honest, free elections.
Only then can good politicians drive out bad.
</P>
<P>
   This view struck my diplomatic friend as impractical. He
recalled the story about Charles de Gaulle, who overheard a
frustrated reformer cry out, ``Death to all fools!'' Le general
shook his head wearily and observed, ``That is a vast program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
