<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BCS-HNS &LR;      11-07 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Anyone up for a rematch?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first meeting wasn't too shabby, after all. It was a little
sloppy, perhaps, but a fight to the finish just the same back on
Sept. 18, when Florida came away with a 23-21 win over defending
national champion Tennessee at The Swamp in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   As statements go, however, it was hardly an emphatic one. And if
the dominoes fall the right way in the next few weeks, the
Volunteers and Gators just might do it again in the Sugar Bowl,
this time with a national championship on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to believe that if we continue to play the way we have
that we'll be one of the teams considered,'' Vols coach Phillip
Fulmer said after Saturday night's 38-14 rout of then-No. 24 Notre
Dame. ``We'll have an opportunity now, and that's all you can ask
for.''
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity was very much in doubt after the early loss to
their most bitter Southeastern Conference rival, a defeat that all
but assured that Tennessee would not defend its league
championship, much less its national title. In the weeks since, the
Vols (7-1) have taken care of business but still struggled to find
their way back into the national picture.
</P>
<P>
   Then Saturday rolled around, and No. 2 Penn State lost to
Minnesota, effectively finishing Joe Paterno's hopes of making it
to Bourbon Street. No. 3 Virginia Tech, meanwhile, needed a
last-second field goal to get past West Virginia for a second
straight unimpressive win, giving new ammunition to critics who
dismiss the Hokies as products of a weak Big East and subpar
schedule overall.
</P>
<P>
   And what of No. 5 Florida (which passed Tennessee and crept up
to fourth in the Bowl Championship Series standings last week)? The
Gators had to hold off a late Vanderbilt drive to get away with a
13-6 win over the Commodores, another outcome not conducive to
wowing writers, coaches or computers sensitive to margin of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   So meet the Vols, last year's champions and the new BCS Flavor
of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   When the Associated Press writers poll and ESPN/USA Today
coaches survey came out Sunday, Tennessee found plenty to like. In
the AP version, Florida State stayed at No. 1, while Virginia Tech,
Tennessee, Florida and Kansas State each moved up a notch. Penn
State slipped to No. 6, followed by Nebraska, Mississippi State,
Wisconsin and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Among the coaches, the top five were the same, but Nebraska and
Mississippi State each jumped ahead of No. 8 Penn State. Wisconsin
and Texas rounded out the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, then, a pretty good weekend for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the energy,'' Fulmer said of his team's
reaction to the Penn State loss. ``They said I had a 41-inch
vertical jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that helps. It gives us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   When the new BCS rankings come out today, Tennessee should be no
worse than fourth overall, and the Vols' dominant performance
against the Fighting Irish could vault them back over the Gators
and perhaps even close the gap on Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   With Penn State awaiting roadside assistance for its broken-down
bandwagon, the traffic begins to thin out a bit on the way to the
French Quarter, but several teams still have a chance to maneuver
to the front of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the route is smoother than others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Florida State: &LR;  Win out _ no small trick with a Nov. 20 trip to
Florida looming. The Seminoles actually improved their margins in
both traditional polls by taking the weekend off but haven't played
like a solid No. 1 lately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Virginia Tech: &LR;  Win out, but get help to make sure. The latter
is hardly out of the question, especially since the Florida
State-Florida death match will eliminate one of the two. Still, the
Hokies' poor strength-of-schedule score in the BCS formula makes it
imperative that they retain favor in both traditional polls and the
eight computer rating systems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Florida:  &LR; Beat Florida State on Nov. 20. Beat the SEC West
winner in the league championship game. In that scenario, the
Gators eliminate FSU on their own and more than likely would jump
back over Tennessee to be no worse than No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tennessee: &LR;  Barring a South Carolina shocker over Florida, the
Vols are locked out of the SEC title game and an extra chance to
shine. Still, the Florida-Florida State game solves one Tennessee
problem. Virginia Tech remains vulnerable to a late Tennessee rush
and possible sentiment in the writers and coaches polls that a
two-point loss at Florida shouldn't cost the Vols so dearly in
comparison to a team that played a lesser schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In another scenario, Florida beats Florida State, then loses to
a team with at least one loss in the SEC title game. That could
create a Virginia Tech-Tennessee meeting in the Sugar Bowl if each
is able to win out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kansas State: &LR;  The Wildcats continue to be shunned because of a
creampuff non-conference schedule, and Saturday's struggle against
Colorado didn't help their image. Even so, Bill Snyder's team can
make people sit up and take notice with a big finish. K-State
already has a win over rising Texas and a date with Nebraska to
come. The Cats could blow into the Big 12 Championship Game, whip
up on the Longhorns again and make the case that an unbeaten team
from a good conference has to be worthy of a look.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nebraska: &LR;  Sixth in the coaches poll and seventh among the
writers, the Cornhuskers need plenty of help. Wins over K-State and
a Big 12 title victory in a rematch with Texas probably won't be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mississippi State:  &LR; What are these guys doing unbeaten? Well,
schedule helps, for one thing, since Jackie Sherrill's Bulldogs
didn't have to play Tennessee or Florida this year. That's good for
the record, not so hot for schedule strength, making MSU a long,
long shot at best.
</P>
<P>
   For now, everybody is waiting to see who's in the Sugar. After
that, the other BCS bowls revert to traditional tie-ins, with
wiggle room for avoiding rematches or creating more attractive
games.
</P>
<P>
   Six conferences _ the Atlantic Coast, Big East, Big Ten, Big 12,
Southeastern and Pac 10 _ all have automatic bids, leaving room for
two at-large entries.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech was looking good for one of the at-large spots
before losing over the weekend to Virginia. The Big Ten runner-up _
either Penn State or Wisconsin _ may have moved to the front, but
the Nittany Lions will need to win at least one of their last two
(home against Michigan, at Michigan State) to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lions win both, they're going to the Rose, and Wisconsin
becomes an attractive at-large with a likely Heisman Trophy winner
in Ron Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   One possible shakeout:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sugar:  &LR; Florida (SEC) vs. Tennessee (at-large): Everybody but
Steve Spurrier would love to see a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fiesta:  &LR; Nebraska (Big 12) vs. Wisconsin (at-large):
Cornhuskers give the BCS another excuse to ignore Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Orange:  &LR; Florida State (ACC) vs. Virginia Tech (Big East):
Could be the best game of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rose:  &LR; Penn State (Big Ten) vs. Washington (Pac-10): The bloom
is off the Rose this year, since Penn State will consider this a
consolation prize and Washington would be the best of a sorry West
Coast lot.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, everything looked different just a week ago and
could very well change again this week.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's adios to JoePa and Joe Hamilton, and welcome back
to the likes of the Gators and Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Never a dull moment. And if you need an endorsement that this
isn't such a bad thing, just ask the folks in Knoxville how it
feels to be back in the hunt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
