<SLUG> BC-CRASH-MEMORIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES HOLD MEMORIAL SERVICE FOR EGYPTAIR CRASH VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ One week after EgyptAir Flight 990 mysteriously
plunged into the Atlantic from 33,500 feet, relatives bid a sad,
final goodbye to the 217 victims Sunday at a wind-swept park here
overlooking the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Even as those who lost loved ones hugged, wept and placed
flowers at the water's edge in a moving memorial, the U.S. Navy was
far out at sea preparing a second deep-diving drone to help recover
the jet's two black boxes that are the key to finding out what went
wrong aboard the Boeing 767-300.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board,
said the second submersible robot, Magnum, is more maneuverable
than Deep Drone and can be used in rougher seas. It is being
carried aboard the civilian ship Carolyn Chouest.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Grapple, which is the mother ship for Deep Drone,
returned to Newport on Sunday for refueling before heading back out
to the crash site with the drone.
</P>
<P>
   Rough seas have limited efforts since Friday by Deep Drone to
recover the black boxes that investigators hope will give them
their first solid clues to why the Boeing 767 crashed without any
distress call from the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   With calmer seas forecast for Monday, both drones are expected
to be used. Deep Drone has zeroed in on electronic signals emitted
from the two black boxes, but has not seen them. The Navy believes
the boxes, which are about 15 feet apart, could be buried in mud or
under pieces of airplane debris scattered on the ocean bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The water is about 250 feet deep, and Hall said it would be too
risky to use divers.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, frustrated investigators can only hope that Deep
Drone and its more capable reinforcement can recover the voice and
data recorders which have been on the ocean bottom for one week.
</P>
<P>
   Though the focus of the investigation has been the hunt for
those boxes, recovery operations were overshadowed Sunday by the
emotional memorial service, held on a cold, clear afternoon at
Brenton Point State Park overlooking the Atlantic Ocean. The
service was closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Many Newport residents stood along downtown streets to pay their
respects as 14 buses carrying about 250 family members slowly made
their way to the park from a waterfront hotel where they have been
housed.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the memorial, leaders of the Jewish, Christian
and Islamic faiths offered readings, chants and prayers in three
languages.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service was held in a large tent facing the ocean.
At the head table were flags of the United States, Egypt, Canada,
Syria, Sudan, Germany and Zimbabwe, representing the nationalities
of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   As the service ended, relatives were led to the water through a
corridor formed by military personnel and caregivers including
workers from the Red Cross, NTSB and Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Some dropped flowers into the sea, while others placed flowers
in a wicker basket that later was taken away by a military
helicopter. On Monday, the helicopter will drop the flower basket
at the crash site off the Massachusetts coast. The moment will be
videotaped and copies sent to the relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives also were given bottles of sea water from the ocean
where their loved ones now rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your loss is great, your pain deep, but you must find solace
in the memory of those wonderful moments you shared with your loved
ones,'' said Egyptian Ambassador Nebil Fahmy, who read from the
Bible and the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, several of the relatives wailed
uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   One woman could be heard screaming, ``My baby, my baby!''
</P>
<P>
   After the hour-long memorial, four buses carried family members
to the Providence airport where they boarded a plane to take them
back to Cairo. EgyptAir Flight 990 was headed to the Egyptian
capital when it suddenly went down 30 minutes after taking off from
Kennedy Airport in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
