<HEADLINE>
HACKETT SAFE _ FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was a telling moment during the postgame
press conference of USC's 26-16 loss to Arizona State, when coach
Paul Hackett talked about how close the Trojans were to winning the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to four minutes left and being down by three
points against a good team,'' Hackett said. ``That's what you hope
for.''
</P>
<P>
   A 5-4 Arizona State team being described as ``good'' might gall
impartial observers. But imagine the reaction today from the USC
diehards because the coach was pleased to be within three points in
the final minutes against a then-.500 team.
</P>
<P>
   Remarks like that helped get Larry Smith fired seven years ago.
And for the rest of this forgettable season, the speculation will
increase about Hackett's future.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as USC sits 3-6, the job-security issue is fairly
foolish. Hackett is in the second year of his five-year contract,
and while athletic director Mike Garrett might vent from time to
time to friends, firing his chosen successor to John Robinson is
highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   At least this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most people also forget that a final decision comes from school
president Steven Sample and he is still smarting from the beating
his image took when Robinson was fired two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sample, more than anyone else, will want to stay the course for
one more year. He gave Robinson another year after USC went 6-6 in
1996 and would simply hate the idea that he is viewed as a
quick-trigger by firing Hackett. Besides, he and Garrett would look
incredibly foolish by sacking Hackett two seasons after they hired
him.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes down to credibility. Which coaches would want to
come work at USC knowing they would be given a two-year trial
period?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to be viewed as an endorsement of Hackett, just a
reality check.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the same cannot be said for the coaching staff. You can bet
there will be changes next season, even if it just comes down to
someone choosing to leave for another job.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is meant as an excuse for whatever shortcomings
Hackett might have. Truthfully, the Trojan program is in as much or
more turmoil today as at any point of Robinson's reign.
</P>
<P>
   There is no single area that can be spotlighted as the source of
the Trojans' woes. Quarterback John Fox wasn't the answer, although
it was perplexing why he started the game just to be quickly pulled
after one half. That's not much of a tryout when you've gathered
dust for two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the handling of Fox is an indication of the desperation
surrounding the program. This team might equal the six-game losing
streak of the 1991 Trojans, but it is far more talented.
</P>
<P>
   Who would take Reggie Perry at quarterback over Fox or Mike Van
Raaphorst? Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   That is why this season has turned into such an embarrassment.
It's not just about losing, it's about underachievement. And it
might get a lot worse. USC has the possibility of suffering its
longest losing streak in school history if it drops its next two
games.
</P>
<P>
   That is an astounding fact if you consider this could be one of
the easiest schedules ever, since USC is not expected to play a
ranked team this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Defensive tackle Aaron Williams suffered a sprained
neck and is doubtful for the Washington State game. Wide receiver
Marcell Allmond sprained his shoulder and is also doubtful. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
