<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-ROBOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER ROBOT JOINING SEARCH AT CRASH SITE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT NAVAL STATION, R.I. _ It uses sonar for ears and video
cameras for eyes. Its titanium arms have joints in seven places,
its wrists can spin 360 degrees and it can dive more than a mile
and a half in rough seas to grasp things from the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   It is Magnum, a heavy-duty yellow underwater robot that was
installed on a Navy support ship here Sunday as it prepared to take
its turn trying to retrieve the so-called black boxes of EgyptAir
Flight 990 from waters 50 miles south of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope Magnum will succeed in the harsh weather that
has thwarted its predecessor, a robot called Deep Drone. High seas
and whipping winds kept Deep Drone on deck and sent its Navy ship,
Grapple, back to port Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board Chairman James Hall said he
hoped Magnum could be in the water by Monday afternoon after being
sailed to the site aboard the support ship Carolyn Chouest. The
Grapple and Deep Drone will follow when weather permits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope that the boxes, which hold the plane's
cockpit voice recorder and flight data recorder, will help explain
why the Boeing 767 crashed on Oct. 31, killing all 217 aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors allow Magnum to withstand heavier weather than Deep
Drone. The first is its protective steel cage. The second is the
Carolyn Chouest, which has thrusters that enable it to float in a
fixed spot without dropping anchor. On Saturday, heavy surf made it
difficult for the Grapple to stay anchored, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Magnum, which is about the size of a minivan, weighs 8,000
pounds with its cage. Both will be sent down to about 20 feet from
the bottom of the sea. Then two operators aboard the ship will
steer Magnum out of the cage, sending it commands through a
10,000-foot-long umbilical cord.
</P>
<P>
   The robot will be guided by the pinging sound emitted by devices
attached to the black boxes. But officials caution that the pingers
may have been separated from the boxes during the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the boxes appeared to be buried under wreckage, which
might be too difficult for the robots to maneuver through. And
officials now believe it is too dangerous to send divers into a
field of small, jagged pieces that could cut their air tubes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
