</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS, SANDERS READY FOR DUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Sitting at his locker last week at the Cowboys'
Valley Ranch training complex, cornerback Deion Sanders allowed
himself to drift back to days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   It was the time of Wyatt Earp and Billy the Kid, when men were
defined by their reputation as a gunslinger. Challengers would
journey miles to try their hand against the fastest gun.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the Old West is not much different than that island
he has roamed on a weekly basis for the past 11 years as arguably
the best cover cornerback in league history. It's against him that
unknown receivers seek to make a name for themselves and
established guys hope to stamp their greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets motivated to beat the man on top,'' Sanders
said. ``Because of my reputation, guys want to make a name for
themselves by beating me. That's comes with being on top. It's been
like that for years. I'm the fastest gun out here.''
</P>
<P>
   So far in 1999, it's seemingly high noon every week for the
perennial All-Pro Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he rebutted a challenge from the trash-talking
Redskins receiver duo of Albert Connell and Michael Westbrook. Last
week, he suffered a setback of sorts when he was burned for a
40-yard touchdown reception by Marvin Harrison of the Colts. It was
the first long touchdown pass he has giving up in four seasons with
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   However, those were preliminary battles compared to what's set
to take place in the Metrodome tonight when the Cowboys (4-3) face
the Vikings (4-4).
</P>
<P>
   All that's missing from the made-for-television ``Monday Night
Football'' showdown between Sanders and Vikings receiver Randy
Moss, who in just his second season has supplanted Jerry Rice as
the league's most feared receiver, is promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Finally: The Latest (Moss) Vs. the Greatest (Sanders).
</P>
<P>
   Fans were deprived of the matchup last season, as a toe injury
kept Sanders off the field in the Vikings' 46-36 blowout victory.
The then-rookie Moss lived up to his end of the bargain, catching
three passes _ all for touchdowns (51, 56 and 56 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Moss didn't talk after the game, saying later he had nothing to
say because of Sanders' absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was disappointed Deion didn't play. Until the time me
and Deion or the Vikings and Cowboys play, no one will know if he
goes out and makes me look bad. If he does, OK, Deion's the best.
If I go out and make Deion look bad, I'm the best. You're going to
hear that until we finally meet up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss has been mum about the matchup in the days leading up to
the game. However, his seasonlong rhetoric clearly shows that he
has been gearing toward this game for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Before an early-season matchup against Raiders cornerback
Charles Woodson, Moss said, ``I could see if it was Deion Sanders.
I'd be like, well OK, I'm a little shaky, I'm a little nervous
because it's Deion, but man \RWoodson\S is just another guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who spent time at Sanders' house before the 1998 draft,
has a healthy dose of admiration for Sanders' skill and flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his passion and desire to go out there and showboat and
also show you he can still make it happen,'' Moss said. ``I think
that's what I respect most about Deion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who has been studying tape of the Vikings' star all
week, respects Moss as well. However, he said he refuses to get
caught up into the one-on-one matchup partly because Vikings
veterans Chris Carter and Jake Reed are tremendous threats as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Moss is a great player,'' Sanders said. ``But you can't
get into the one on ones. Neither one of us is going to get a win
or loss when we leave this game. This is a team thing. And when you
are talk about the Vikings, you are talking about three great
receivers _ Moss, Carter and Reed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders points out that Moss, who has caught 35 passes for 553
yards and four touchdowns, has been less effective in 1999 because
teams have schemed to take away the deep ball. Carter has made up
for it with a team-leading 46 catches for 601 yards and five
touchdowns. Reed has caught 25 balls for 407 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And, there's some question as to how much Sanders will be
assigned to cover Moss. One aspect of the Cowboys' game plan will
be to double Moss and put Sanders on Carter. There will also be
times when he gets safety help.
</P>
<P>
   However, whenever Sanders gets Moss in bump-and-run coverage,
all eyes will be on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be exciting, that's for sure, with two great
players,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``It'll be interesting
to see how that unfolds. If I weren't so integrally involved in it,
it would be great as a fan to sit back and watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the league,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said.
``I don't think there's any doubt. It's great for the fans. We're
not going to focus on that, though. We know that our agenda is to
try and win the game. We've won games when Randy has caught 10
balls. We've won games when Randy's caught one ball. I don't know
which one it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter is the biggest reason Sanders is trying to downplay
the matchup, as it's a no-win situation for him. If Moss doesn't
have a big game, it won't hurt his reputation and the Vikings can
still win.
</P>
<P>
   If Sanders has a bad game, the Cowboys will certainly lose and
his reputation will take another hit. Even though Harrison's
touchdown reception came as a result of a play fake, people are now
questioning whether Sanders has fully recovered from off-season toe
surgery that forced him to miss the first two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 32, understands that he is judged on a different level
and that his legend, like a lot of gunslingers, is based more on
myth than reality. He also would have it no other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What cornerback doesn't give up any receptions,'' Sanders
said. ``I know it hasn't happened to me a lot. But it's impossible
to shut everybody out. No other cornerback is held to that level
but me. I know its partly because of what I've done. I expect more
of myself that people expect of me. I welcome these challenges
because I'm going to be at the top of the mountain as long as I
play the game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
