<HEADER>
A2066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-NY-MARA-WOMEN-ART     11-07 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARA-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY CHARGE BY THE '98 WOMEN'S WINNER GETS BRUSHED ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Franca Fiacconi felt the only way she could win
Sunday's New York City Marathon was to attack from the start.
Adriana Fernandez felt if she stayed with Fiacconi, she could break
her.
</P>
<P>
   Both were right: Fiacconi attacked, and Fernandez broke her and
won.
</P>
<P>
   Despite headwinds of 20 to 30 mph for much of the race,
Fernandez won in 2 hours 25 minutes 6 seconds. Only 23 women,
including Fernandez, have run a faster marathon. Fernandez's
performance was additionally impressive because this course, with
its sneaky hills, was more trying than such flat courses in
Rotterdam, the Netherlands, London and Chicago that usually produce
fast times.
</P>
<P>
   Fiacconi, the 34-year-old Italian who won in New York last year,
likes to run from the front and maybe steal the race. Fernandez,
the 28-year-old Mexican who was the runner-up last year, would not
let her, and she won by more than half a mile while Fiacconi faded
to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   One race official estimated that the winds made the times two
minutes slower. They were so strong at the start on the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge that Fiacconi ran the first mile in 6:09,
by far the slowest mile of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In setting a Mexican record, Fernandez ran the second-fastest
time by a woman in the 30-year history of this race. Minutes after
the finish, she told a television interviewer: ``At places, the
wind almost stopped me. Without the wind, I probably would have
broken the course record.''
</P>
<P>
   The interviewer, Lisa Ondieki of Australia, nodded and smiled,
knowing that the New York record of 2:24:40 she set in 1992 would
live for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   There were smiles from Fernandez, too, and not only because her
eighth career marathon had produced her second victory (she won in
1996 in Houston). In her previous two marathons, she finished
second in New York last year in 2:26:33 and second in London in
April in 2:24:06. That convinced her she could run with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was second here last year,'' she said through a
translator, ``my confidence level went through the roof. This year,
I led for 21 miles in London. After that, I said I am no longer
going to run fast, but to win.''
</P>
<P>
   To help achieve that, she trained more this year in the
mountains of Toluca, Mexico, at 12,000-foot altitude. She is
coached by Rodolfo Gomez, the runner-up here in 1982 to Alberto
Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Before the race, she was confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style of running is an intelligent one,'' she said. ``I'll
run according to how the race develops.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew Fiacconi had missed three key weeks of training after
breaking an elbow in August. She also knew Fiacconi would take out
the pace and put the burden on the others to stay with her.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez was ready. When the starting cannon finally sounded
after three or four false starts, Fiacconi took off and built a
lead as large as eight seconds, perhaps 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that if I let her go farther and open a bigger
gap,'' Fernandez said, ``she would gain confidence and maybe win
the race from the beginning. I decided to catch up with her, stay
with her and then make a push of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Four miles into the 26.2-mile race through the city's five
boroughs, in Brooklyn, Fernandez caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did,'' Fernandez said, ``I felt very strong. I felt I
could win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the next 11 miles, Fernandez and Fiacconi ran side
by side. Occasionally, Fernandez would slip a stride or two ahead,
and Fiacconi would catch up. Nearing the 15-mile mark, approaching
the Queensboro Bridge, Fernandez ended the game of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to push harder,'' Fernandez said. She did,
Fiacconi could not respond, and soon Fernandez was the only person
in a surreal setting. No woman challenged her and no male runners
were nearby, and for long stretches Fernandez ran by herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised I was alone,'' she said, ``but I was
concentrating on my own pace and my own rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting there, she clicked off miles in 5:30, 5:37, 5:10, 5:15,
5:26, 5:34, 5:33, 5:25, 5:25 again, 5:30 and 5:28 as her lead
became larger and larger. She seemed to be running effortlessly;
Fiacconi was hurting, starting near the 15-mile mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't feeling any problems with the pace,'' Fiacconi said,
``but around 24 kilometers she pushed the pace and I was feeling a
problem with my left foot. So I let her go. I was not able to stay
with her. And at 30 kilometers, my elbow started to bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiacconi drifted back and finished behind 27-year-old Catherine
Ndereba of Kenya (2:27:34), a two-time road runner of the year
competing in only her second marathon, and 38-year-old Katrin
Dorre-Heinig of Germany (2:28:41), running her 43rd marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after she finished in 2:29:49, Fiacconi was so cold
that she was wearing gloves indoors. She said she ran the race the
way she wanted to, except for her finishing place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be in front immediately,'' she said, ``to be
aggressive, to put immediate pressure on the field, not to wait for
anything. I knew when I came here that I was not 100 percent, but I
knew the course very well so I knew that in any case I can run
well.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not run that badly. Neither did Ndereba and
Dorre-Heinig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard New York was the toughest course,'' Ndereba said, ``so
I am very much happy. Second place to me is like winning. People in
Central Park were yelling, `Looking good,' and I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorre-Heinig said she gave away any chance to win because ``the
margin between the first runner and me became too big.''
</P>
<P>
   At any time did she think she could win?
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the race, yes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez thought the same for herself, and she became the first
Mexican woman to win here (three Mexican men have won). She will
leave with $50,000 in prize money, a $25,000 bonus for breaking
2:26, a $25,000 appearance fee and a Mazda Miata worth about
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   She does not know how big a reception she will receive when she
returns to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Mexican soccer team wins,'' she said, ``the people
celebrate. I hope they do that for me for winning such an important
marathon.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
