<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 2 UNCERTAIN TEAMS ARE BLOWING IN THE WIND
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Let's say that last summer you won
tickets to the Arizona Cardinals versus the New York Jets Sunday at
Giants Stadium. Wow! The Jets breezed to the American Football
Conference championship game a year ago and the Cardinals relished
a sweet playoff victory at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   You were excited because you would see one group (Jets) which
was a Super Bowl favorite and another (Cardinals) which should
knock again on the playoff door. You called your friends. You made
plans on that day to arrive at Giants Stadium early and to party
late.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of awful karma happened between claiming your ticket
and settling in for Sunday's kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets lost their starting quarterback to injury and the
Cardinals did, too. The Jets entered with only one victory in seven
games, the Cardinals with two in seven games. Sunday, the teams
would score a total of 19 points in a slumbering, dreary, painful,
error-plagued experience.
</P>
<P>
   This was like winning a $500 gift certificate _ only to later
find that all selections must be made from the blue-light special
section at your corner dime store.
</P>
<P>
   It was like going to see a sexy, glitzy, cutting-edge concert
from the sensational, controversial rapper, Lil' Kim _ and, once
there, finding only video clips of Tiny Tim.
</P>
<P>
   Jets 12, Cardinals 7.
</P>
<P>
   Brrrrrrrrrrrr.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be Vinny and the Jets against Jake the Snake.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde, the wonder quarterback from last season,
against Jake Plummer, one of the National Football League's
brightest, rising stars.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it was Rick Mirer (Jets) versus Dave Brown (Cardinals).
</P>
<P>
   One player should not make a team and two players should not
make a game. This was, however, an excellent example of cutting off
the head and killing the body. The absence of Testaverde and
Plummer meant two laboring, uncertain teams.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Some tried. Now, it was windy at Giants Stadium. It whipped,
swirled and was at 20 miles per hour at game time and no doubt
gusted to higher numbers during the game. When either team had the
ball traveling West, it had the wind to its back and attempted to
use that to its passing advantage. It was tricky. But players on
both sides said that they had played in much worse conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The wind had little to do with the Jets' driving to the Arizona
27, 25 and 12 on three separate possessions and scoring only 3
points. It had nothing to do with Brown's completing a 71-yard pass
play early and then zilch for the rest of the game. Nothing to do
with Arizona allowing six sacks.
</P>
<P>
   And, certainly, little to do with one of the more comical plays
of the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   There was 2 minutes 22 seconds left and Arizona, trailing by
12-7, had the ball at its 25, intent on building a game-winning
drive. On a first-down play, Brown, in shotgun formation, was
stripped of the ball by Jets linebacker James Farrior. What
followed was a football folly, a bouncing ball slapped around by at
least six players. Finally, Arizona pounced on the loose ball at
its 6-yard line. (Mind you, this was a potential game-winning
drive.) Two plays later the Cardinals faced a fourth-and-43 from
their own 2. They punted and the Jets ran out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was making the ball shift in the kicking game,'' the
Jets' Bernie Parmalee said.
</P>
<P>
   Jets tackle Jumbo Elliott said: ``The wind was a dictating
factor in the game _ but it wasn't the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Mirer, who was the better quarterback of the day, for an
apt summation: ``The wind affects some people more than others. The
wind and cold are part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona _ which left 80-degree, nearly windless weather back
home _ led 7-3 at halftime and 7-6 with a little more than five
minutes to play. It simply blew it. Its pass defense let Keyshawn
Johnson slip behind it, against a three-deep zone with five men
underneath, and let him run 43 yards for a touchdown that proved
the game-winner. The Arizona offense for the entire second half had
shown it had already begun heading South. Or West, in this case.
After Johnson's catch and score, the game was over, right there.
</P>
<P>
   For Jets fans, thank goodness for Johnson. He gave them a thrill
just when it seemed everyone in Giants Stadium had fallen fast
asleep. He helped give the Jets their first victory in more than a
month, after three consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   Aeneas Williams is Arizona's premiere, pro-bowl cornerback. He
is a man of pristine vision. He sees the Jets and Cardinals, a
couple of 2-6 teams minus their starting quarterbacks. He sees the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind in this game was not a factor in executing the
running game, making tackles and playing sound football,'' Williams
said. ``I see the Jets and I see a team that looks like it is still
hurting deeply over the loss of its quarterback but a team that is
still fighting and clawing. I don't know if they have the edge they
once had. They are fighting to not lose confidence. They have
suffered a huge drop in expectations. We haven't played a complete
game yet. We're trying to get to level ground. And right now, we're
below ground, which makes that even harder.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
