</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATHCARE-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY OFFER DIFFERING APPROACHES ON HEALTH CARE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debate over health policy now being waged in
the Democratic presidential primary campaign is not simply about
cost estimates, political positioning and appeals to Democratic
constituencies. Health policy experts say Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley have very different visions about how
to deal with the nation's 44.3 million uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, these experts say, were clearly affected by the
failure of President Clinton's health care proposal in 1994. But
they responded to that history in different ways. Bradley is
proposing a big program, without the government mandates and cost
controls of the Clinton plan, and he is being accused of promising
more than he can deliver. Gore chose to build incrementally on
existing programs, and he is being accused of aiming too low.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would create a vast new system of subsidies and tax
credits that would, he says, cover all children and provide access
to affordable coverage to all adults. It would allow anyone to buy
private insurance through the program that insures federal workers,
the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program. And the people who
depend on Medicaid, the 34-year-old program for the poor, for their
health insurance would be ``mainstreamed'' into this broader system
with federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would try to guarantee access to health coverage to
all children by 2005 by expanding eligibility for the Children's
Health Insurance Program, which was established two years ago for
children in families not poor enough for Medicaid but not affluent
enough to buy private insurance. It would also allow their
uninsured parents to enroll in that program. And it would allow
many uninsured Americans ages 55 to 65 to buy into the Medicare
program, a proposal made previously by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   So far, a new survey suggests, the health care debate between
Gore and Bradley is playing to a tiny audience. Only 6 percent said
they were following news of Bradley's proposal very closely, while
only 8 percent were following Gore's, according to a Kaiser Family
Foundation/Harvard study conducted Oct. 22-26.
</P>
<P>
   But health policy experts are taking this debate seriously,
recognizing that the ideas thrashed out in the 1992 presidential
campaign framed the legislative struggle of the following two
years. And many of them said they were thrilled to see the issue
come back _ and eager to see the Republicans follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the story is that a candidate running for president of
the United States has put the issue of the uninsured front and
center in his campaign, five years after every political pundit
said it would be a generation before any politician would be
willing to talk about it again,'' said Robert Reischauer, an
economist at the Brookings Institution who was director of the
Congressional Budget Office during the last health care struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bradley's decision to go for a big, comprehensive health
care program with a price tag he estimates at $65 billion a year,
many analysts see his plan as a departure from past Democratic
orthodoxy. He envisions a major expansion in coverage _ raising the
proportion of Americans with health insurance from 84 percent to 95
percent, and covering virtually all children.
</P>
<P>
   But he rejects past Democratic strategies, like a new government
insurance program or a requirement that employers provide insurance
to their workers _ the so-called employer mandate that was the
cornerstone of the Clinton plan and previous Democratic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bradley proposes a new system of government subsidies
and tax credits to help low-income Americans buy private coverage.
Drew Altman, president of the Kaiser Family Foundation, said,
``Bradley is using what traditionally have been conservative means
to achieve a liberal end.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bradley plan, every child would be required to have
health insurance, but the federal government would provide
substantial assistance with the cost. For children living in
households with incomes under $32,800 (about twice the poverty
level for families of four), the government would make a full
premium payment, estimated at $1,200, to the federally approved
health care plan of the parents' choice.
</P>
<P>
   That subsidy would be tied to income, paid on a sliding scale
and phased out at $49,200 for a family of four. Families and
individuals would also receive a tax break to offset the costs of
health premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley estimates that 84 percent of the nation's 11 million
uninsured children would receive a full or partial subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income adults would also be eligible for subsidies to help
cover insurance premiums, with full annual premium costs up to
$1,800 paid for adults with incomes below $16,400 (for a family of
four) and a partial subsidy available to adults in families with
incomes up to $32,800. People could stay with their current
coverage or buy a plan through the Federal Employees Health
Benefits Program.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley plan would also essentially dismantle Medicaid, the
federal and state program that covers health care for poor people,
including many elderly Americans in nursing homes. The federal
government would take over the acute care portions of the program,
providing full subsidies to purchase insurance for eligible people.
And the states would take over the institutional long-term care
part of the program. This system of subsidies and tax credits would
also cover children in the Children's Health Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   Margy Heldring, the campaign's health coordinator, said the
Medicaid move was an attempt to eliminate the stigma attached to
the program and ``mainstream'' its beneficiaries into the private
insurance market. Already, she said, more than half of the Medicaid
beneficiaries have been moved to managed care plans in the states.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley gets high marks from health policy experts for
recognizing what many consider a crisis in health coverage,
particularly the failure of employer-sponsored insurance to cover
millions of American workers, and for putting serious money on the
table to combat it. But the subsidy and tax credit approach, while
increasingly popular in the past few years as politicians look for
alternatives to employer mandates, is no magic bullet, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In general, many health experts say, such plans can end up
spending a lot of public money for people who already have
insurance, because the subsidy is based on income, not whether they
are insured. ``It's a more inefficient way to do it,'' said Stuart
Altman, a professor of health policy at Brandeis University, and a
longtime supporter of an employer mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Thorpe, a former Clinton health adviser now on the faculty
of Emory University who insisted he was neutral in the race despite
claims of bias from the Bradley campaign, said, ``The bulk of the
kids who fall within these income brackets already have health
insurance.'' Such plans could also, some say, inadvertently
encourage employers to reduce their responsibilities for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's promise of universal access has won praise from many
health care advocates, who are delighted to see an ambitious new
approach to the problem of the uninsured. But the Gore campaign
asserts that Bradley is simply making promises that don't add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd to go making promises on this that literally will
never be kept because the money will never be there,'' said Elaine
Kamarck, a senior Gore adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign takes aim at the Bradley plan on several
fronts: That it drains too much of the projected budget surplus,
and thus shortchanges Medicare, which will need a major infusion in
the coming years; that the overall cost estimate is off; that the
$1,800 premium estimate is unrealistic, thus discouraging
low-income people from participating and making it unlikely that
the plan would meet its 95 percent coverage goal, and that
dismantling Medicaid is dangerous and disruptive for millions of
vulnerable Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore proposal on health care is, his advisers argue, a far
more focused approach. It tries to broaden the Children's Health
Insurance Program, which has had varying degrees of success in the
states, by expanding eligibility to families at 250 percent of the
poverty level, from 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would cover an additional 1 million uninsured children,
Gore advisers say. It would allow uninsured children in families
above 250 percent of the poverty level to buy into the Children's
Health Insurance Program or Medicaid, which would be more
affordable than buying individual policies. And it would escalate
the government's efforts to make sure that children who are
eligible for Medicaid or CHIP are enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would also allow many uninsured people ages 55 to 65, the
fastest growing group of uninsured in the country, to buy into
Medicare. He would create a new 25 percent tax credit for small
employers who join purchasing coalitions to buy insurance for their
workers. And he would provide a 25 percent tax credit for people
without access to employer-sponsored insurance who need to purchase
it on the individual market.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign essentially dismisses Gore's proposal as
far too timid, given the steady rise in the uninsured in the midst
of an extraordinary economic boom. It argues that because Mr. Gore
relies so heavily on CHIP, a voluntary program which has had
serious problems reaching the eligible uninsured, it is unlikely to
end up covering all children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
