<HEADLINE>
WANTED: LEGAL, LOW-LEVEL WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Faced with a dwindling number of workers to fill jobs as
dishwashers, busboys, landscapers and maids, the hospitality
industry in the Phoenix area is mining a new mother lode of
employees: documented workers from countries as far away as Iran
and the Sudan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Competition for legal workers is so fierce among hoteliers that
the indus try is raising wages, helping recruits learn English and
running vans hundreds of miles a day from modest neighborhoods to
fashionable resort cities where there are jobs but little or no
low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   The search for hospitality workers is going on all over the
nation, where a robust economy is siphoning workers from low-level
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   When resorts from Colorado to Nantucket Island couldn't find sum
mer employees to flip burgers or make beds, they imported teenagers
from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's worker shortage has caught the attention of Gov. Jane
Hull, who wants to reinstitute the bracero program, which would
allow thousands of Mexican laborers to get temporary work permits
for jobs in the hospitality, agricultural, custodial and other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Locally, some hoteliers are using recruitment tactics they say
they never dreamed would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are stealing from each other,'' said Judy Dewey, employment
direc tor at the Boulders, an exclusive Carefree resort. ``There is
no one out there willing to do these jobs. That is why refugees are
such a good source.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry can no longer ``just run ads for employees,'' said
Rich New man, Carefree Conference Resort manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the labor pool being as tight as it is, it has made us
think more creatively about how to find more people.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for refugees from coun tries in political chaos
increases every year, said Craig Thoreson, director of Lutheran
Social Minis tries of the Southwest, which aids refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Ashraf Nasr, an employment coun selor for the International
Rescue Committee, said the hospitality in dustry employs about half
the nearly 800 workers his agency placed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria Majok, 41, from Sudan, said he is grateful for his job
as a bellman at the Orange Tree Golf &AMP; Confer ence Resort in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people at Orange Tree have been very good to me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He started work a year ago when he arrived in Phoenix, and has
made enough money to rent a home for his family and buy a car.
</P>
<P>
   John Bergman, employment director of the Hyatt Regency
Scottsdale, began hiring refugees last spring. He remembers a few
years ago when applicants outnumbered jobs 10 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be five openings and 50 applicants would show
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many were Hispanic immigrants, who have long been the backbone
of the hospitality industry's labor force. But now with more
resorts and hotels springing up in the Phoenix area, there are not
enough docu mented Hispanics to fill the increas ing demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That workforce has dried up,'' Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 270 of the resort's 900 employees are Hispanic
immigrants, with 25 others coming from from Cuba, Bosnia, Iran,
Africa, Russia or Croatia and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Because the refugees have immi gration documents, employers are
spared the worry that they are hiring illegals and risking stiff
federal fines.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about competitors, Bergman wouldn't divulge his source
of work ers but said the Hyatt, like other resorts, helps refugees
with transpor tation, handing out bus passes and sending vans for
employees whose shifts don't match bus schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey, of the Boulders, said the resort also operates vans,
making six 60-mile round trips a day to pick up and return certain
workers who live near the Lutheran agency, at 2020 W. Indian School
Road in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Thoreson, the Lutheran agency's director, said transporting
workers ``is a huge, huge problem,'' created by the lack of
low-income housing in resort cities such as Scottsdale and
Carefree.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the agency provided vans, but ``it became a
monumental task and we couldn't continue it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carefree Conference Resort ran shuttles for six months, but
stopped two months ago because recent immigrants are buying cars or
join ing car pools, Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Once workers are on the payroll, resorts fight to keep them by
provid ing translators, helping them with English, promoting them
and raising their wages.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Bergman said the Hyatt raised wages to $8 an
hour from $6.25 for certain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going into the busy sea son,'' he said. ``You have to
attract people from another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Although pay is inching up, Thore son said, it's difficult for
refugee families to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Before fleeing political persecution a year ago, Majok had jobs
as a night hotel manager, accountant, radio operator for an
American oil com pany and consultant for an African studies program
in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is satisfied with his job as a bellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware that to come to America is different, and I
recognize you have to start from zero,'' he said. ``I am sure I
will reach where I want to be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
