<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARA-FIRST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIMER FOLLOWS HER PLAN TO AN EXCELLENT FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By MARC BLOOM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Erica Scheier, 26, a veterinarian from Hoboken, N.J.,
running Sunday's New York City Marathon, has never been a patient
runner, and has never been inclined to wait for anything in life.
She knew she was fast and wore a ``Go, Erica!'' T-shirt to gain
crowd support.
</P>
<P>
   Scheier also knew her aggressiveness could spell trouble in the
marathon, which favored prudence over speed. It was Scheier's first
attempt at the 26.2-mile distance, but she was so strong from
22-mile training runs that she felt it might be hard for her to run
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm competitive,'' she said. ``I'm worried about that. I don't
want to hit the wall and collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scheier had three auspicious goals in mind. One was to break
3 hours 40 minutes and qualify for the Boston Marathon in April.
Another was to break 3:30, a respectable pace of 8 minutes a mile.
A third goal was to break the family marathon record of 3:17, held
by her father, Evan Pickman, a scout for the Los Angeles Clippers
of the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   To go with her goals, Scheier had had three marathon dreams _
all nightmares. In one of them, she stopped to talk to spectators
and missed all her goals.
</P>
<P>
   For Scheier, unlike most new marathoners, there was no time to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Defying convention _ and looking the wall right in the eye _ she
started out fast, hitting eight miles on Brooklyn's Fourth Avenue
in 58 minutes 50 seconds, a pace of 7:21 a mile. ``The pace felt so
comfortable, I decided to keep it up,'' Scheier said. ``Besides,
whenever I slowed down, the crowd picked me up with, ``Go,
Erica!'''
</P>
<P>
   Scheier's plan was working, but perhaps too well. She remembered
that she had collapsed in her last big race in 1996. While an
undergraduate at Dartmouth who ran the campus cross-country course,
Scheier doubled her major to complete her studies early and went on
to the University of Pennsylvania School of Veterinary Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, while working and studying around the clock,
Scheier persisted in running daily and entered a 10-mile race. ``I
went out like a maniac,'' said Scheier, a former gymnast from
Tottenville High School on Staten Island. ``It was very hot, I
didn't stop for drinks and I collapsed at the finish.'' Medics
treated her with intravenous fluids and told her she was lucky to
be alive.
</P>
<P>
   For her marathon buildup, which began in June, Scheier was
careful. She increased her training gradually, to a peak of 50
miles a week, and practiced running with a water bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, she carried a bottle for insurance and her risky pace
from Brooklyn into Queens. Her halfway split on the Pulaski Bridge
was 1:37, close to her best half-marathon race, 1:32, in September.
That meant Scheier was either in over her head or might blow the
lights out of the family record.
</P>
<P>
   Scheier picked up a fresh water bottle from her mother, Marian,
at 17 miles on First Avenue. That was the first rendezvous point
for family members, who had a race of their own to get to the
course. Scheier's father flew to New York on Sunday morning from a
coaching assignment in Raleigh, N.C. Scheier's husband, Adam, an
assistant football coach at Columbia, rushed to the course after
reviewing films of the Lions' victory over Dartmouth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   One other family member, Erica's pet cockatoo, Kramer (named
after the ``Seinfeld'' character for his unruly feathers), remained
at home. ``I left the TV on so he could watch the marathon and
cheer for me,'' Scheier said.
</P>
<P>
   Extra water and cheering were not enough for Scheier, who began
to labor under her ambitious pace. She weakened at 19 miles but
gobbled a banana and felt an immediate energy boost. ``It must have
gone right to my muscles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Scheier, though slowing, had no problems, running
with a veteran's control. Then, in Harlem at the 21st mile, her
spirits rose when she saw Adam riding by on a bicycle. ``That's my
wife!'' he called out. ``That's my wife!'' Then he turned to Erica
and said with awe: ``You're a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool and detached has been Scheier's athletic motif. As a child,
she won camp races but paid her victories little mind. She had more
fun dressing as a dolphin to be the mascot for the College of
Staten Island basketball team, coached by her father. But now, in
Central Park with three miles to go in her first marathon, Scheier
looked every bit the natural.
</P>
<P>
   At the 24th mile, her father, Evan, jumped out on the course to
run alongside for a few strides. ``You're well ahead of 3:30,'' he
told her. ``Just relax and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheier did, breezing through the finish in 3:22:57, an
excellent marathon debut and 166th among the 9,000 women. ``I feel
wonderful,'' she said with her medal draped around her neck. ``But
dazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheier's eyes were clear, her cheeks caked in sweat. Spent, yet
content, she said: ``I know I qualified for Boston. But now that
I've achieved my goal, why run it again?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
