u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-650(2     11-07 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELITE'S CHOICE HEADS TO VICTORY IN MEXICO PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the candidate favored
by the establishment in Mexico's governing party, appeared to be
heading toward a decisive victory Sunday evening in the first
presidential primary ever held by the party.
</P>
<P>
   According to an independent exit poll and less formal soundings
by officials in Labastida's campaign, he was ahead of his closest
rival, former Tabasco state Gov. Roberto Madrazo Pintado, by at
least 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the primary race stands a strong chance to win the
presidential election on July 2 because opposition voters are
divided between two major parties, which have failed to form a
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Moctezuma Barragan, Labastida's campaign manager, began
to claim victory soon after the polls closed at 6 p.m. Alejandro
Valenzuela, a campaign spokesman, said that based on preliminary
results the election seemed to be ``a landslide.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the campaign of Madrazo, who has long experience at
fighting tenaciously when he is behind in a race, insisted that he
had won and appeared to be laying the groundwork for a battle royal
over the results of the election.
</P>
<P>
   The primary broke with seven decades of authoritarian tradition
in which the incumbent president picked his successor in a ritual
known as the finger-tap. Despite the contention over the results,
it was regarded across the political spectrum as a historic advance
toward democracy in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo, who made the decision to abandon the
old practice and allow Mexican voters to choose his party's
candidate, held up two fingers after he cast his own ballot Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This finger is a thing of the past,'' he said, waving the
index finger he opted not to use to tap the presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have this one,'' Zedillo added, showing the indelible
black ink on his thumb which showed that he had voted in the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo did not reveal before the polls closed whom he had voted
for, however. Throughout the campaign he insisted that he was not
backing any of the four candidates. But Labastida's rivals bitterly
questioned the fairness of the race, charging that the party
establishment had guessed that Zedillo was backing his former
interior minister and thrown its power behind Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 57, served as President Zedillo's Interior Minister,
the No. 2 cabinet minister, and has had a steady 37-year career in
government posts. He promised gradual reforms to make the PRI less
corrupt and more democratic, and greater spending on social
programs for the working class if he becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, by contrast, presented himself as a rebel who would
make sweeping changes to break the hold of the Mexico City
political elite on the party.
</P>
<P>
   The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the
PRI, has won every presidential election in Mexico since its
founding in 1929, making it the world's longest ruling party. It
has been weakened by spectacular corruption and disastrous economic
management by recent presidents.
</P>
<P>
   For the PRI, which achieved many of its past electoral victories
by ever more sophisticated methods of fraud and coercion, mounting
a clean primary was a special challenge. The party spent $3.3
million to organize a vote almost as ambitious as a presidential
election, with 64,200 polling stations nationwide and more than
450,000 people involved as officials and poll watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Any Mexican registered to vote was allowed to participate,
whether a PRI member or not. The winner had to take a majority of
300 electoral districts.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Gutierrez Barrios, the veteran PRI politician in charge
of ensuring an honest primary, said fraud was ``almost
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Also running were Manuel Bartlett Diaz, 63, the former governor
of Puebla state, and Humberto Roque Villanueva, 55, a former
president of the party. Bartlett and Roque were expected to draw
small percentages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to two exit polls by TV Azteca and Televisa, the two
major television networks, voters in Mexico City strongly favored
Jesus Silva Herzog, a former ambassador to the United States, to be
the PRI candidate for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Party members savored their first chance to have a real say in
picking the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not imposing leaders anymore,'' said Pedro Corro
Garcia, a 23-year-old engineering student whose family included
several generations of PRI followers. ``They are letting us
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI elections officials said the voting was orderly in most
places, but they reported some ``marginal incidents'' of
irregularities. In a rural village in Puebla, Bartlett's home
state, ballots for 4 polling stations were burned, apparently by
opponents of the PRI. In the Mexico City suburb of Villa Coapa
predawn raiders, also apparently from opposition groups, stole all
of the ballots from one polling station, PRI officials said.
</P>
<P>
   However, complaints flowed in from Madrazo followers around the
country that PRI officials had dispensed hand-outs of food and
promises of government aid, and in some cases resorted to overt
threats, to get PRI followers to turn out and vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   In one town in the state of Queretaro, the PRI mayor threatened
to fire six employees who planned to turn out as poll watchers for
Madrazo, according to Jacaranda Pineda Chavez, a state deputy who
supports Madrazo. Only one stayed home Sunday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Andres Tuxtla, a town in the Gulf Coast state of
Veracruz, an official in charge of a federal aid program for the
lowest-income families warned that they might lose their assistance
if they failed to support Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see where their fanaticism for Labastida has taken them,''
Carmen Sanchez Llano, 30, a dentist who supports Madrazo, said by
telephone from the town.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo gave no sign that he would give up easily and seemed to
be preparing to try to prove to PRI elections authorities that he
had won and, failing that, to assail the election with dozens of
formal complaints about inequities during the campaign and the
voting.
</P>
<P>
   During the day Madrazo's campaign violated PRI bylaws by
distributing e-mail results of impromptu polls showing Madrazo in
the lead. Right after the polls closed in Mexico City, he sent out
a bulletin announcing that he had won 139 districts while Labastida
had won only 69. He did not cite the source of his information.
</P>
<P>
   But Madrazo campaign officials said there was little chance that
he or his followers would leave the party even if he suffered a
conclusive defeat. Instead, Madrazo seemed to be paving the way for
a tough negotiation for positions of power within the party with
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we leave a party that is just as much ours as
theirs?'' said Jose Alberto Aguilar, an adviser to Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   In one surprise, Leonardo Rodriguez Alcaine, the head of PRI's
main national labor federation, announced after he voted Sunday
that he had chosen Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   At the polls many PRI voters said they were dismayed at the
surprisingly acid attacks Labastida and Madrazo leveled at each
other during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let it get personal, all those attacks, `` grumbled Elvia
Fragoso Huerta, 49, a voter in the proletarian Mexico City suburb
of Ecatepec.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
