<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT, MICROSOFT MAY BE WILLING TO SETTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The government doesn't want Microsoft's money.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's top antitrust official said Sunday that the
government is considering a full range of other punishments,
including corporate dismemberment, following a judge's emphatic
conclusion Friday that the Redmond, Wash., software giant is a
monopolist that has harmed consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harshness of U.S. District Judge Thomas Jackson's
findings, both the government and the company expressed a
willingness to consider settling.
</P>
<P>
   The best possible outcome, said computer-industry companies and
associations reached over the weekend, will be the one that cures
any ills caused by Microsoft's monopoly, and prevents their
recurrence, but otherwise leaves unchanged how the industry does
business.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates said the
company is committed to ``a fair and responsible'' resolution. The
company's chief operating officer, Bob Herbold, said on the Sunday
talk shows that ``there's nothing we'd like more than to settle
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, who also appeared on
three television programs, said, ``Obviously settlement is always
an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Klein nor Herbold would suggest what an agreement might
entail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would need a settlement that deals with the very findings
that the court made in this case, a settlement that produces
consumer choice, innovation and competition in the market,'' Klein
said on ``Fox News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited ``serious issues here about law enforcement and the
antitrust laws. And of course if Microsoft were prepared to engage
on those issues, we would be prepared as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gates' letter, which appeared as a full-page advertisement in
The Washington Post, he wrote that ``Microsoft is committed to
resolving this matter in a fair and responsible manner, while
ensuring that the fundamental principles of consumer benefit and
innovation are protected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of this case,'' he said, ``is whether a
successful American company can continue to improve its products
for the benefit of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, addressed ``To Our Customers, Partners and
Shareholders,'' also appeared on Microsoft's Web site, dated
Friday, the day Jackson released his ruling. It was similar to a
statement Gates read on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who presided over 77 days of testimony, declared in a
remarkably blunt decision that Microsoft's aggressive use of its
monopoly status stifled innovation and hurt consumers by limiting
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers, Klein said, are ``doing an analysis that
will look at the full range of remedies.'' Asked if breaking up
Microsoft is among them, Klein said: ``That is in the range, but
... it is premature for us now to get ahead of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   One penalty that he appeared to rule out is a fine. ``Let me
make clear we are not looking for any financial penalties,'' Klein
said on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' ``We're concerned with competition.
This is not a penal action, and we're not going to seek monies.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. Fines would probably suit most computer-industry
companies and associations, many of which fear the cure for
Microsoft's anticompetitive behavior may be worse than the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The findings handed down Friday hint at remedies that some worry
could hamstring the industry more effectively than Jackson found
Microsoft has done.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's news brought no gloom to the Computer &AMP; Communications
Industry Association, a 26-year-old Washington, D.C. group
representing, among others companies, several large Microsoft
opponents. Those include Oracle and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is a rapacious monopoly that should be broken up and
then prevented from colluding further,'' said Ed Black, the
association's president. ``There is a huge fear factor (over
Microsoft) among our members,'' even though many of them embrace
Microsoft publicly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even Black advocates a ``minimally intrusive,
minimally regulatory'' remedy. ``Microsoft raises the specter of
some huge regulatory scheme,'' but that's not necessary to recreate
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Wasch, president of the Software &AMP; Information Industry
Association, congratulated Jackson on the ruling. But, like Black,
he advised caution in fashioning a remedy. His group advocates
creating ``a new relationship between the dominant (operating
system) provider and the rest of the industry, while eliminating
the need for the government to remain as a watchdog of software
business practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Grummon, president of Bellevue-based Chili!Soft, said
nothing in the findings of fact makes him worry for his own
company. In fact, he said, some of the findings criticize Microsoft
tactics that caused hardship to Chili!Soft.
</P>
<P>
   He imagines the case's most likely outcome _ some form of
company break-up _ will affect the software industry much like the
breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1984 affected the telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
   That breakup released a flood of innovation from former Baby
Bells and newly hatched competitors, but it sacrificed the
uniformly excellent service AT&AMP;T customers had enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``in the short term, Microsoft users will have
trouble getting the same level of consistency among various
products; they'll have more chaos and confusion,'' Grummon said.
That problem will exacerbate an already-critical shortage of
programming talent. But in the long term, software will get simpler
and more diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Several other trade groups and businesses were more vociferous
in their objections to the findings of fact and to any forthcoming
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   What monopoly? asked Jonathan Zuck, president of the Association
for Competitive Technology, a 500-member Washington, D.C.
organization founded as a reaction against the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be a monopoly in this industry. We've seen that
in the huge venture capital investments being made in (Windows
rival) Linux, in the way market shares change,'' Zuck said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Windows does dominate the market for Intel-based PC
operating systems, changing that could be disastrous, Zuck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows itself is just a $5 billion business sitting at the
middle of a $500 billion market for products and services that rely
on there being an operating system standard. It could cost up to
$30 billion to fragment that standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings of fact will probably cause a surge in membership
in Zuck's group from companies that haven't paid much attention to
the suit until now _ ``which is how they should be spending their
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Association for Competitive Technology said an October
survey of 907 registered voters showed that 74 percent (with a 3.3
percent margin of error) favor consumer choice over government
intervention as the best marketplace regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sax, president of Sax Software Corp., a 10-person Eugene,
Ore. software developer, said he thinks the judge is ``basically
attacking the way the industry as a whole operates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We compete with Microsoft, and they're incredibly powerful
competitors,'' Sax said. ``But it's possible for small companies to
take them on their weaknesses _ that's what being a company is all
about. Every company wants to drive its competitors out of
business, and there's nothing wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Diamond, chief executive of Corporate Software &AMP;
Technology Inc. in Norwood, Mass., said he's wary of government
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that the government is going to step into this
industry, which is operating at such an effective level, and we're
not supposed to fear that the government won't stumble, scares
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Microsoft an incredibly aggressive competitor? Absolutely.
Does that mean the industry or consumers have been hurt? I don't
believe it,'' he said. ``To say there hasn't been innovation or
reduction of costs to consumers is idiocy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
