<HEADLINE>
JUDGE: HOW MICROSOFT USED ITS MONOPOLY POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said Microsoft used its
monopoly power in several ways to damage competitors. Here are a
few examples:
</P>
<P>
   Intel: On Aug. 2, 1995, Bill Gates told Intel chairman Andy
Grove that Microsoft no longer would support Intel's next
generation of microprocessors if Intel continued developing
platform-level software that competed with Microsoft. Intel agreed
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Apple: Microsoft attempted to convince Apple to abandon plans
for its multimedia playback software for Windows. In a meeting on
June 15, 1998, Apple chief executive Steve Jobs turned down the
offer. Although it was rejected, Jackson said Microsoft was
attempting to limit the development of multi-media content that
would run cross-platform.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks: On July 10, 1997, Microsoft executive Robert
Muglia told RealNetworks that it would be in the best interest of
both companies if RealNetworks only developed software for
Microsoft's multimedia platform. One week later, Microsoft made an
investment in RealNetworks and agreed to distribute a copy of the
company's media player with Internet Explorer; license the source
code for RealNetworks' streaming technology; and develop a common
file format for streaming audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks, the judge wrote, interpreted the agreement
differently from Microsoft and continued developing streaming
software on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's intentions toward RealNetworks show that Microsoft
executives were willing to invest a large amount of cash and other
resources to halt software development, the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   IBM: Microsoft attempted to convince IBM to drop support of
products such as Notes and SmartSuite that competed with Windows
and Office. When IBM refused to cooperate, Jackson wrote, Microsoft
punished IBM with higher prices, a late license for Windows 95 and
the withholding of technical and marketing support.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly damaging, he wrote, was a delayed Windows 95
license that caused IBM to miss out on key holiday sales.
</P>
<P>
   On July, 25, 1995, three days after IBM announced its plans to
bundle SmartSuite on its personal computers, Microsoft told IBM
that it was canceling further negotiations with IBM for a Windows
95 license, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite competed with Microsoft Office. Joachim Kempin, who
oversaw Microsoft's sales to computer makers, told an IBM executive
that Microsoft would consider restoring the license if IBM agreed
to support Microsoft software on IBM personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Because IBM installed SmartSuite on its personal computers,
Judge Jackson wrote, Microsoft was reluctant to help IBM sell more
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq: On May 31, 1996, Microsoft sent a letter to Compaq
saying it would cancel the computer manufacturer's license for
Windows 95 unless it restored MSN and Internet Explorer to their
original positions on the standard Compaq Presario desktop screen.
Compaq agreed. Microsoft was willing to forfeit all Windows sales
with its biggest partner, the judge wrote, in order to enforce its
prohibition against removing Microsoft's Internet-related icons
from the Windows desktop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
