<HEADLINE>
NO STANDOUT FOR HORSE OF YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The morning after the Breeders' Cup, the
North American Horse of the Year campaign turned negative.
</P>
<P>
   The debate among turf writers _ who split the year-end ballots
with Daily Racing Form staffers and track racing secretaries _
focused on the shortcomings of the candidates left standing
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They include Breeders' Cup winners Artax (a one-dimensional
sprinter), Daylami (with one American race), Beautiful Pleasure
(never tested against males) and Soaring Softly (of the narrow
distaff turf division), and Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner
Charismatic (retired in June). Even Silverbulletday _ a Breeders'
Cup loser _ seemed to have some support.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever winds up with thoroughbred racing's top prize in
February, ``It'll be the most undeserving Horse of the Year in my
lifetime,'' said one voter, the New York Daily News' Bill Finley,
38.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of horses had chances to sew up the title in the
eight-race Breeders' Cup at Gulfstream Park. They all lost: Behrens
(seventh), Lemon Drop Kid (sixth), General Challenge (10th) and
River Keen (11th) in the $4 million Classic, won by inconsistent
Cat Thief; Silverbulletday (sixth) in the Distaff; and Chilukki
(third) in the Juvenile Fillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we decided anything,'' said D. Wayne Lukas, who
trains Cat Thief and Juvenile Fillies upsetter Cash Run _ and
trained Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   A quick survey of 10 writers Sunday found five leaning to
Charismatic, three to Artax and one each to Daylami and
Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   Former claiming horse Charismatic nearly swept the Triple Crown,
breaking down while running third in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to remember his heroics,'' said Gene Guidi of
the Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kentucky Derby and Preakness were his only major
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Artax won four major sprints, broke track records held by Dr.
Fager at Aqueduct and Gulch at Belmont Park, and tied the
Gulfstream 6-furlong record with his 1:07.89 Breeders' Cup Sprint
win. He'd be the first dedicated sprinter to win Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's accomplished so much. Why not?'' said trainer Louis
Albertrani.
</P>
<P>
   But he is only 4 for 15 in 1999. He might not even have been
best in the Sprint, because half-length runner-up Kona Gold had to
overcome a bumpy start and an anti-stretch-runner track bias. And
as a sprinter, Artax is, by definition, a horse who failed at tests
of stamina, no small measure of thoroughbred excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Arab-owned, England-based Daylami was widely considered the best
horse in the world after winning major summer turf races in England
and Ireland by five and nine lengths. He ran away with the Turf on
Saturday, ending an 0-for-38 drought for Europe-prepped horses in
Florida Breeders' Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that of the 101 horses who ran in the Breeders'
Cup, he was the one who ran like a champion,'' said Ron Indrisano
of the Boston Globe. ``I'd like to vote for a horse with a touch of
greatness and I think he has that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Turf was the 5-year-old's first race in America this
year. Even All Along, the French filly who was Horse of the Year in
1983, raced twice here.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring Softly, the Filly and Mare Turf winner; Beautiful
Pleasure, the Distaff winner, and Silverbulletday, unbeaten against
3-year-old fillies, are the female candidates worth mentioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says HORSE of the Year. It doesn't say COLT of the Year,''
said Soaring Softly trainer Jim Toner. ``I don't see why we can't
get in the running.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of the females defeated males or posted records
spotless enough to suggest they could.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Hallandale Beach police were investigating the death
of a 45-year-old man who apparently fell 40 feet from a grandstand
catwalk after the races Saturday. The body of Jonathan Lane, a
part-time employee of Miami's Calder Race Course, was discovered by
a Gulfstream maintenance worker. . . . Two-year-old Anees, whose
rally from last to victory in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile signaled a
bright future, will return to Santa Anita and probably begin his
Kentucky Derby preparations there, trainer Alex Hassinger
said.!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
