<HEADLINE>
EXPERT TAKES A STAB AT WHAT'S NEXT FOR MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Friday's findings of fact, handed down by U.S.
District Judge Thomas Jackson in the Department of Justice's
antitrust suit against Microsoft, were just the first step among
several required to resolve the case, according to William Kovacic,
a professor at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic said he's unaware of any proceedings ever structured
like these. But here's his best guess on what could happen next.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusions of law phase:
</P>
<P>
   _ Within the next month or so, both the Department of Justice
and Microsoft will submit proposed conclusions of law. Conclusions
of law result from applying the Sherman Antitrust Act, and the
cases interpreting it, to the judge's findings of fact.
</P>
<P>
   _ Each side will then have a chance to react to the other side's
proposed conclusions in writing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Then each side gets to orally argue its proposed conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   _ The judge writes his own conclusions; likely sometime in
February, Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   Remedy phase:
</P>
<P>
   Then starts the remedy phase, where the judge determines how to
appropriately punish Microsoft and deter future wrongdoing. The
three-step process will likely be repeated, with each side allowed
to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Submit a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rebut the other side's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Orally argue its proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring one month for Jackson to reach his conclusion, this
phase will extend to April or May 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic said possible remedies range from milder punishments
that seek to change behavior, to more radical solutions
restructuring the company.
</P>
<P>
   From mildest to most radical, possibilities include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Court orders that Microsoft not behave in a certain manner,
such as enlisting competitors to compete against another company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring the company to sell off or give away its Windows
source code and related knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dividing up the company, creating an applications division, an
operating-system division, and possibly an Internet services
division.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring the company to clone itself, creating duplicates of
the entire company in miniature that compete with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Appeal:
</P>
<P>
   Then, almost certainly, will come the appeal of whatever remedy
Jackson hands down. (No remedy will go into effect until all
appeals are exhausted.) By the time the U.S. Supreme Court ruled on
the matter, it will be June 2002, Kovacic predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement (anytime):
</P>
<P>
   A settlement at any time could end the trial immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
