<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHEN THE WALL IS INTERNAL AND THE COURSE IS IN THE
HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa.) (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lisa Buster did not run one mile Sunday. But the
gamut of highs and lows she experienced were an emotional marathon
that left her drained at the end of the day. She watched one client
surge toward history, then fade, then surge again, then fade to
fifth. She saw another surge, fade and finish second.
</P>
<P>
   In the multilayered community of marathon running, Buster wears
many hats. She is a runner's agent. Sunday she was a bundle of
nerves and anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   She sat in a private room at Tavern on the Green, watching a
large-screen television with about 30 others, mostly friends and
family of the marathon's elite runners. Buster needed a bird's-eye
view to keep track of her high-profile Kenyan clients: John Kagwe,
the two-time defending champion, and Catherine Ndereba, a top
runner coming off a disappointing performance in the Boston
Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   This was potentially a historic day: a victory here would make
Kagwe, 30, the first man to win back to back to back since Alberto
Salazar won in 1980-82.
</P>
<P>
   For the special occasion, Kagwe's wife, Beatrice, made her first
trip to the United States, leaving their three children at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba's husband, Anthony Maina, a prison warden back home, had
made his first trip the United States as well, leaving their
2-year-old son with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   As the race began, Buster traced the course she had taken to
reach this point: from a career as a radio sports reporter to
television news to doing the weather to managing elite Kenyan
runners in Valley Forge, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Buster did sports radio for five years, covering pro sports in
Washington and North Carolina. When she tried to become a
television sports reporter, Buster said she ran into resistance.
``I had people saying, `Well, I'd never have a woman in my sports
department,''' she said. ``I looked for a job for almost a year in
sports.'' Finally she accepted a job in Montana, where she entered
the world of running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never involved in running,'' she said. ``When I was out
West, working in television, my boyfriend at the time was a runner.
He knew my boss at the station; he saw me on the air and he wanted
to meet me. That was the first time I really ever knew any
runners.''
</P>
<P>
   After she left the station, Buster and her companion went to
Italy for three months, and a couple of his runner friends asked
Buster to see about finding them some races.
</P>
<P>
   She continued to find races for her friends, even after she
moved back to Philadelphia and worked in marketing. Then she
decided to represent runners for a living. ``There weren't a lot of
people doing this in the early 1980s,'' she said. ``It's not
something I thought I would be doing. You don't just wake up and
say, `I'm going to represent runners for a living.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, Adriana Fernandez was dominating the women's
race, but there was no sign of Ndereba. Buster was calm. ``In
Boston, she went out really fast,'' Buster said, ``so I think now
she's being more conservative.'' In the men's race, Kagwe was
running third and his wife seemed concerned. Buster grabbed her arm
giving assurances that her husband had a strong kick.
</P>
<P>
   Buster said there is no mystery to the Kenyan runners' success.
``They work hard and they sacrifice,'' she said. ``They give every
ounce of energy. It's not magic; it's dedication and focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major sacrifice for John to leave his wife and his
children; tremendous sacrifice for Catherine to leave her husband
and their 2-year-old son. They make the sacrifice because they're
looking to build a future. They're not here to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The elite race is nearly over now. Kagwe begins to fade in the
last two miles. There are two more hills. Buster tells Beatrice,
whose expression says she already knows, that John does well on
hills. Perhaps he has one kick left.
</P>
<P>
   He does not. Joseph Chebet of Kenya finishes first; Kagwe
finishes a disappointing fifth.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the first runner finishes, client and wife run an
obstacle course past layers of security in an attempt to reach
Kagwe. When they reach the tent for the elite athletes, he says
that a Moroccan runner, Abdel-khader el-Mouaziz, kicked him in the
back of the leg at several points in the race. El-Mouaziz said they
were accidental. Buster wants to file a protest, but Kagwe waves
her off. The race was lost. The day is over.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the race, Buster is still angry. ``He not only lost
the race but lost a chance for history,'' she said, ``and it wasn't
his fault.''
</P>
<P>
   In her efforts to straighten out the details of Kagwe's race,
Buster missed Ndereba's great finish. Running with the poise and
restraint she lacked in the Boston Marathon, Ndereba surged and
finished second. ``I'm happy for Catherine,'' Buster said.
</P>
<P>
   So now Kagwe and his wife, and Ndereba and her husband, will go
back to Kenya to rejoin their families. Next week sometime, four
more Kenyan clients will join Buster in Pennsylvania to begin the
cycle all over again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
