<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2091 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     11-07 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYOFF SCANDAL COULD JUMP-START REFORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   News flash: The head of the International Boxing Federation was
indicted on charges he took payoffs to improve fighters' rankings.
</P>
<P>
   There's a shock.
</P>
<P>
   This is something boxing insiders have accepted as commonplace _
even at the highest levels of the sport _ since the beginning of
time. The IBF's Bob Lee and others were simply snared as the result
of a federal grand jury inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing now is to seize this opportunity to
eliminate such corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Forces are at work to clean up boxing. Two of the most
vociferous are U.S. senators John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Richard
Bryan (D-Nev.), who have co-authored laws to protect fighters and
the integrity of the sport. However, even they admit that
legislation can do only so much.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the IBF scandal, many in the business are saying
it's time to create a national and/or international organization to
oversee and regulate boxing, a la the major sports in this country
and the organizations that govern soccer and track and field
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The logical choice to take the reins in the United States is the
respected Association of Boxing Commissions. The ABC, composed of
government-appointed commissioners from states that sanction
boxing, already has worked to provide national standards under
which the sport operates. Some envision that one day the ABC, under
the watchful eye of federal regulators, could oversee every aspect
of the sport and actually rank fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, no promoter, manager, trainer or fighter would be
allowed to work unless he or she is licensed _ and monitored _ by
the new organization. Thus, boxing's bad elements would be forced
into line or out on the street and the sport would be rid of the
myriad sanctioning bodies altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would have to give its permission to form such an
organization because of antitrust laws, and it likely would do so
in light of the sport's unsavory reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The goal _ virtually !ital!everyone's goal _ is to create
something that has never been associated with boxing: the
perception of integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen of the America Presents promotional firm, which
wants to take a leading role in reform, envisons a day when the
boxing could be lifted to the level of baseball, football and
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just saw a situation where an umpire blew a call in
(baseball's postseason) and it cost a team a game. No one said,
`The fix is in.' That's what we want for boxing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact boxing is an international sport complicates things.
The two other major sanctioning organizations _ the World Boxing
Council and World Boxing Association _ are based in Mexico and
Venezuela, respectively. Of course, that means they're not bound by
American law unless they operate in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that Bob Lee and Co. were busted because they
have the misfortune of operating out of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the solution? Invite foreign officials to be part of
the ABC and make it a global organization.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA, soccer's governing body, and the IAAF, which runs track
and field, are not perfect, but they've done a credible job and
would be good role models.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike those groups, an international form of the ABC
should be based in the United States because this is where the
sport thrives. Undeniably, the vast majority of fighters seeking
fame and fortune do it here. This, again, would allow federal
regulators to keep an eye on boxing as it makes the transition from
a rogue sport to a legitimate business.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government isn't likely to help in one regard:
funding. That would be up to those inside the business.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious way to support the ABC is to claim a percentage of
the profits or a set fee from each boxing show. As it is now, in
championship fights, promoters must pay to a sanctioning body a fee
for the right to that body's belt. That money could simply be
redirected to the ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Goossen said America Presents already is pursuing
corporate and private sponsorship to fund the ABC and has had
received favorable initial responses.
</P>
<P>
   So, all the elements seem to be in place: the need for a
responsible, government-monitored body to oversee the sport; the
embryo of such an organization (the ABC); and realistic funding
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that now's the time to get together,'' promoter
Bob Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   __ The leaders?: Goossen, who once ran Ten Goose Boxing in Van
Nuys, and America Presents have a specific plan to reform the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   First, the ABC would be given the authority to oversee the
sport. That includes the naming of a commissioner _ selected from
among current state appointees _ like that of the major sports.
Among the commission's duties would be to approve all contracts,
which would protect otherwise vulnerable fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a school for judges and referees would be established.
All officials must graduate from the school and would be evaluated
regularly. They also would have to earn the right to work bouts
based solely on performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like other sports, they would work the biggest events through
merit and not through who you know,'' Goossen said.
</P>
<P>
   American Presents' choice to run the school? Former referee
Mills Lane, who is universally respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make a promise: We will change this business. Period. You
will see boxing reform,'' Goossen said.
</P>
<P>
   __ De La Hoya-Trinidad II: Arum, Oscar De La Hoya's promoter,
said he and Don King, Felix Trindad's promoter, are scheduled to
begin negotiations this weekend for a rematch. He's confident that
two will meet as soon as April in what would be De La Hoya's next
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Arum also said it's possible De La Hoya could fight IBF junior
middleweight champion Francisco Castillejo at Staples Center early
next year and then fight Trinidad around June.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Arum said, Trinidad has no choice but to fight De La
Hoya again because he cannot make anywhere near the money he would
make fighting anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to happen. (King) has a fighter with no earning
potential,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad won a decision in September.
</P>
<P>
   __ No butts about it: After the controversial draw in the first
Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield bout at Madison Square Garden, one
might expect the main concern of Lewis and trainer Emanuel Lewis to
be the judging when the two meet again Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. They're worried most about how referee Mitch Halpern
will do his job.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Steward believe Holyfield purposely butts his
opponents. In fact, Lewis insists Holyfield practices it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually practices it with the heavy bag. He has a ring
(drawn) on the bag and practices head-butting,'' said Lewis, who
didn't say how he would know this.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into these different tactics Lennox is
always bringing up,'' he said. ``He's just trying to get people to
watch me so he can do something even more outrageous.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
