u i BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-COX     11-07 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LABASTIDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAN FAVORED TO WIN FIRST MEXICAN PRIMARY SAID HE DID IT HIS WAY
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOTE: This story is totally embargoed until after 12 a.m.,
Monday, EST. This embargo includes Cox Newspapers customers in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY If he wins this Sunday's presidential primary as
expected, Francisco Labastida Ochoa knows there are two ways
history will judge him in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He could be seen as the first man who had to publicly fight to
win voters' hearts and become the presidential nominee for Mexico's
formidable Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Or he could be seen as yet another candidate selected by the
PRI's clever party managers, who feigned democracy and helped
guarantee him victory in the party's first presidential primary
election this century.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the first votes were cast in Sunday's election, it
was obvious Labastida was trying to bolster his image as a
political figure in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is all this from spontaneous combustion?'' Labastida joked in
an interview with foreign reporters before the primary. ``If memory
serves me well, before I became a candidate I was a federal
secretary (cabinet member) three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is a 57-year-old lifelong PRI member with more than 30
years of service in PRI governments. He was Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo's agriculture secretary and interior secretary
before he quit to run for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If opinion and exit polls are correct, Sunday's vote will make
him the first PRI presidential candidate to be elected by voters
rather than appointed solely by the President of Mexico in the now
infamous ``dedazo,'' or ``big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1929 every president of Mexico has selected the PRI's next
presidential candidate, and, in effect, his successor without the
benefit of input from the party's grassroots sympathizers. Sunday's
election is supposed to bury the so-called ``big finger'' and make
way for a ``new PRI'' - a party that's more democratic, in touch
with disgruntled Mexicans and ready to crack down on notorious
corruption within its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   With a candidate who has proved his appeal to voters in a
primary, the party reasons, it increases its chances of once again
winning the presidency in next year's July 2 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida is fighting a widespread belief among Mexicans
that he's another pampered PRI candidate that the party's apparatus
favored over three other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, those angry accusations are also coming from
Labastida's own comrades within the PRI. The PRI's opposition
parties are already leaping at the chance to echo complaints of
vote buying lodged during the campaign by Labastida rivals Roberto
Madrazo, Manuel Bartlett and Humberto Roque Villanueva.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida says he personally earned the ample support from PRI
union and sympathizers he counted on throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1970 I managed a fourth of the country's budget,'' he said.
``I traveled the country, managing resources related to the
distribution of water . . . education, health, hospitals, etc. Some
of these relationships (forged with people) served me well.''
</P>
<P>
   If Labastida wins the PRI's primary against a backdrop of cries
of fraud from his rivals, he could face a tremendous additional
challenge to his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's chief rival, Roberto Madrazo, will either refuse to
endorse Labastida or break with the party in the event of fraud,
many analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida says he doesn't need Madrazo to win. But he might need
some of Madrazo's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida says he told Madrazo in their last conversation about
a month ago, ``Obviously, the risk of a crisis exists in the party.
Our campaign teams are fired up. If you win, you will need my
people to triumph (in 2000). If I win I'll need your people. If
we're speaking honestly, we need to tell things the way they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
