<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Stewart wins second race, rises to fourth in standings
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Avondale, Ariz. _ Rookie NASCAR driver Tony Stewart doused
race-team owner Joe Gibbs with champagne after winning Sunday's
Dura Lube 500.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of reasons for the two to celebrate. With his
victory at Phoenix International Raceway, Stewart became the second
driver in Winston Cup's modern era to win two races in his rookie
season. Davey Allison was the first to accomplish the feat in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Tony to win just one race this year was incredible, beyond
my wildest dreams,'' said Gibbs, owner of Joe Gibbs Racing. ``For
him to win two as a rookie ... I just can't put it into words.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 28, also has the chance to become the first rookie to
finish in the top five of the Winston Cup points standings since
James Hylton finished second in 1966. Stewart moved from fifth to
fourth in the points standings, passing Jeff Gordon, who finished
10th in Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter much to me that I finish ahead of Jeff
Gordon in the points,'' said Stewart, who also won at Richmond.
``It's probably more important to the fans, based on all the cheers
I get when I pass Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he knew he had the best car in the 43-car field
after about 50 laps of the 312-lap event. He led three times for
150 laps, including the final 39. After crossing the finish line,
he took his car through some doughnut spins and then cruised
backward around the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really needed a good race here,'' Stewart said. ``I told
(crew chief Greg Zipadelli) in victory lane that this was a
personal victory for me. We were in a slump.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin finished second, followed by Bobby Labonte and Jeff
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte gained 15 points on Dale Jarrett, who has a 231-point
advantage in the standings with two races remaining. Jarrett
avoided disaster, blowing a tire early in the race and dropping a
lap down. But he rallied to finish sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to finish eighth or better in Sunday's race at
Homestead, Fla., to clinch the Winston Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely happy about this race,'' Jarrett said. ``I
guess Bobby gained a few points on us, but not too many. If we do
our job (at Homestead) and finish in the top 10, that should pretty
much do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Labonte: ``As far as the points, we've got to go through it
another week. I thought it would be over with by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
