<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCON08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons, unable to protect the quarterback, fall to 2-7
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They were playing the wrong song Sunday in the Georgia
Dome with 1:49 left in the Atlanta Falcons' game against
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The Twisted Sister tune, ``We're Not Gonna Take It,'' was a poor
choice on two counts.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Falcons had no choice but to take it. They were, in
every way, powerless to change the outcome of a 30-7 loss to a
Jacksonville team that looked like a good bet to return in January
for Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the Falcons can't take each other anymore.
</P>
<P>
   This team looks nothing like last year's Super Bowl team, which
had great chemistry; instead, it looks like a team ready to
cannibalize itself.
</P>
<P>
   Thank NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue for the bye week that's
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst exhibition of offense I have ever seen in
my life,'' said wide receiver Terance Mathis, who entered the game
with an NFC-high 47 receptions, and added three harmless catches
for a meager 28 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish (the bye) would have come three or four weeks earlier.
It's a chance for guys to get away from each other, and that's
going to be a welcome relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not such a bad idea, considering we're 2-7,'' he said.
``I mean, shoot, this is not the way we planned for this year to
go. It's a great time for individuals to recap their seasons. I've
been here seven years; I've been through some rough ... stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The first half Sunday could have been rougher. It was a miracle
the Jaguars' lead wasn't more than 17-0 in the second quarter; the
Falcons had three of their four turnovers in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   A few stand-up performances by the defense, including a blocked
field goal by cornerback Ray Buchanan, and an 84-yard drive at the
end of the second quarter pulled the Falcons within 17-7 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting the season, however, Tim Dwight's 99-yard kickoff
return to start the second half was called back because rookie
safety Johndale Carty was penalized for an illegal block.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it was 20-7 Jacksonville, and the supposed sellout crowd,
which included at least 12,000 empty seats, booed the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The day's recipe for defeat? Falcons running back Ken Oxendine
rushed five times and Byron Hanspard four times, each for 11 yards.
Jacksonville's Fred Taylor rushed 27 times for 124 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars had no turnovers. The Falcons allowed Jacksonville a
franchise-high nine sacks, and Atlanta mustered a mere 182 total
yards and 10 first downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had made some progress in the last couple
weeks,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``You name it, we did it (wrong).''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Falcons won, games against Tampa Bay, Carolina and New
Orleans after the bye week might have looked like three possible
steps toward a .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bye looks like a temporary stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was like a playoff game for us,'' Dwight said. ``We just
came up short by, what, 22 points?''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Falcons can't even get their math right.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
