r f BC-NETSCAPE-SPI &LR;      11-07 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETSCAPE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE AT CORE OF JUDGE'S RULING AGAINST MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Begin ital) The federal court's view of the relationship
between Microsoft and Netscape Communications Corp. _ key players
in a so-called ``browser war,'' _ is central to Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's finding last Friday that Microsoft is a
monopolist whose actions hurt both competitors and consumers. (End
ital)
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the summer of 1995, Netscape Communications Corp.
was on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View, Calif., company's Navigator Web browser, well
on its way to 10 million customers, was the standard method of
searching for content on the Internet. An August initial public
offering, just 16 months after the company was founded, raised $140
million. And Netscape's products, including large corporate servers
and Internet tools, were being used by about 70 percent of Fortune
100 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Barksdale, who joined Netscape as chief executive in January
of that year, was predicting big things for the fast growing
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough fight _ I'll grant you that _ but we're brave,''
Barksdale remarked at a Price Waterhouse forum in Seattle on Dec.
8th, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well financed. We believe that God is on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   But in order to survive in the rapidly changing technology
industry, Netscape needed more than divine intervention.
</P>
<P>
   It also needed important technical information from Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   What Netscape wanted in the summer of 1995 was technical
information _ termed Application Program Interfaces or APIs _ that
would allow it to build its Navigator browser to run on Windows 95,
the dominant operating system of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling on Friday said Microsoft
denied Netscape access to that technical information in order to
protect its status as the world's leading software developer. The
judge also said that once Microsoft saw Netscape Navigator as a
threat, it used its monopoly power to retard and extinguish ``the
process by which (Netscape Navigator and Sun's Java) could have
facilitated the introduction of competition into an important
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, which was sold to America Online last November, is at
the crux of Jackson's ruling. It's mentioned throughout the
207-page document. And its saga is central to understanding how
Jackson came to his decision Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the early summer of 1995, Microsoft was running far behind on
the Internet and it needed to move fast to catch up. Microsoft
chairman Bill Gates penned those sentiments in a May 1995 memo
called ``The Internet Tidal Wave,'' in which Netscape was described
as a new competitor born on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That memo was a call to arms at the Redmond software campus. It
also led to an important meeting between Microsoft and Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, 1995, Microsoft officials, including Daniel Rosen
and Thomas Reardon, met Netscape's senior executives in Mountain
View to discuss the possibility of forming a partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The ``special relationship,'' as it is called in Judge Jackson's
finding, would have given Netscape preferential treatment if the
company abandoned its plans for a browser to run on Windows 95. The
Microsoft officials told Netscape it could continue to develop its
browser for the Macintosh operating system, UNIX and 16-bit
Windows. But Windows 95 was off limits if Netscape used its own API
technology to compete with Microsoft's planned browser, Jackson
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Microsoft representatives made it clear ... that Microsoft
would be marketing its own browser for Windows 95, and that its
product would rely on Microsoft's platform-level Internet
technologies,'' Jackson wrote. ``If Netscape marketed its own
browsing software for Windows 95 based on different technologies,
then Microsoft would view Netscape as a competitor, not a
partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Jackson wrote, also indicated that the speed at which
Netscape received the key technology information to build Navigator
for Windows 95 would depend on whether Netscape signed the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape was in a bind. It needed technology from Microsoft. But
it couldn't agree to give up its Windows 95 browser.
</P>
<P>
   When the Microsoft officials sensed that Netscape would turn
down the offer, Microsoft stopped calling the company. Microsoft
also lived up to its promise of delaying the delivery of the API
technical information for three months, wrote Jackson, causing
Netscape to postpone the release of its Windows 95 browser and miss
out on key holiday sales.
</P>
<P>
   The June 21, 1995, meeting was a historic event. Microsoft and
Netscape executives, who testified at the antitrust hearings in
Washington D.C., still dispute what happened. But Jackson, who
listened to lawyers and witnesses from both sides, appears to be
saying in his findings of fact that the type of behavior exhibited
by Microsoft at the meeting is monopolistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``These interactions demonstrate that it is Microsoft's
corporate practice to pressure other firms to halt software
development that either shows the potential to weaken the
applications barrier to entry or competes with Microsoft's most
cherished software products,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also uses the Netscape example as a springboard to tell
how other firms such as RealNetworks, Intel and IBM suffered at the
hand of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   After the June 21 meeting, Microsoft began pouring money and
resources into the development of Internet Explorer. The company
increased the number of developers working on the project from half
a dozen in early 1995 to more than 1,000 in 1999. It also spent
more than $100 million each year developing its new browser, wrote
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the playing field in the browser war began to
shift.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft held just two percent of the browser market in January
1996, compared to Netscape's 71 percent. Two and a half years
later, the market was nearly dead even. Microsoft's Internet
Explorer held 45 percent while Netscape's Navigator held 54
percent. By April of this year, Microsoft was in the lead with 59
percent of computer users relying on Internet Explorer as their
primary browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft used several tactics to gain market share for its
browser. Those cited by Jackson include giving the product away,
dropping the Windows royalty price for computer makers in exchange
for promotion of Internet Explorer, and constricting Netscape's
access to distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's restrictions succeeded in raising the costs to
OEMs (original equipment manufacturers) of pre-installing and
promoting Navigator,'' wrote Jackson, on page 103 of the finding.
``These increased costs, in turn, were in some cases significant
enough to deter OEMs from pre-installing Navigator altogether. In
other cases, ... OEMs decided not to pre-install Navigator after
Microsoft brought more pressure to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the restrictions placed on computer manufacturers
were used to uphold the quality and consistency of Windows, not to
damage Netscape. But Jackson takes aim at that argument as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft would not have imposed prohibitions that burdened
OEMs and consumers with substantial costs, lowered the value of
Windows and harmed the company's relations with major OEMs had it
not felt that the measures were necessary to maximize Internet
Explorer's share of browser usage at Navigator's expense,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ruling, while not defining Microsoft's actions as
illegal, is strong. For many former Netscape employees it is the
first step towards vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``These landmark findings of fact prove Microsoft is one of the
most powerful and stifling monopolies of the century and illegally
abused its operating system software in bid to control the market
for Internet browsers,'' said former Netscape chief executive Jim
Barksdale in a statement released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Misner, who worked at Netscape from 1996 to June of this
year, said he greeted the findings with tempered enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   No champagne toasts.
</P>
<P>
   No tears of joy.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to Netscape has been done, he said. And Microsoft has
already altered some if its aggressive business practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not change the past,'' said the former director of
strategic development at Netscape. ``The thing that I feel really
great about is that all of these startups that have come out of
Netscape in the past six months ... don't have to compete on an
uneven playing field in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0166 </DOCNO>
