u a BC-AIRCRASH-FAMILIES-490     11-07 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-FAMILIES-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH VICTIMS' RELATIVES SEEK SOLACE IN RITUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The roses drifted seaward shortly before sunset
on Sunday, drawn away from the rocky shoreline by a crisp northerly
wind. ``Allahu akbar,'' the mourners wailed in Arabic. ``God is
great.'' Another voice, that of a woman crying in English, carried
out over the stones and surf. ``My baby, my baby, my baby,'' she
screamed, as Red Cross workers nearby wept.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 grieving relatives and friends attended a memorial
service Sunday for the passengers and crew of EgyptAir Flight 990,
which crashed a week ago in waters south of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 990 carried all manner of people when it departed Kennedy
International Airport in New York, bound for Cairo, Egypt, and
climbed through the darkness to 33,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the passengers were Egyptian army officers who had
completed training in the United States, American and Canadian
tourists planning trips to the pyramids and the Nile, Egyptian
students who had been on exchange trips in U.S. schools, and
off-duty airline employees who were returning home after work
around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   They came from seven nations, and observed three faiths. All 217
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families and friends of those we lost never had the
opportunity to bid farewell,'' said the Egyptian ambassador to the
United States, Nabil Al Fahmy. ``So little can be said to relieve
their pain.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, knowing little more about the crash than they did
when they arrived in Rhode Island last week, the victims' families
sought solace in rituals of faith and symbols of grief. They
gathered in a tent near the water at Brenton Point State Park and
participated an interfaith service with Christian, Jewish and
Muslim clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed ElHattab, assistant secretary-general of the Islamic
Society of North America, instructed the mourners to submit to
God's will. ``Lo, we belong to God, and lo, we are returning,''
said ElHattab. ``Let us remember it is God who grants life, and it
is he who takes us back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Marc Jagolinzer, president of the Rhode Island Board of
Rabbis, said the dead would live on in the memories of their
friends and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death cannot rob us of our past _ the years, the dreams, the
experiences we have shared,'' said Jagolinzer. ``What we have had,
we shall always have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Marco Girgis of the St. Mary and St. Mena Coptic
Orthodox Church in Cranston asked God to receive the plane's
passengers in the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open for them, O Lord, the doors of paradise,'' Girgis said,
standing at a lectern that held miniature flags of the victims'
seven homelands: Canada, Egypt, Germany, Sudan, Syria, the United
States and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, the relatives were led from the tent down
what organizers called a ``corridor of honor,'' a road lined by Red
Cross grief counselors, National Transportation Safety Board
employees, U.S. Coast Guard and Navy sailors, and clergy. Each
family member was given a white rose.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As cries began to rise on the wind, some kissed the roses and
placed them in a white wicker basket, which will be flown to the
crash site and have its contents spread over the sea. Others,
accompanied by sailors, walked to the rocky shoreline and tossed
their flowers into the surf. A few, overcome, needed to be propped
up by sailors or other mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The service was held at a point facing south, toward the two
debris fields that the Navy located roughly 110 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage and the passengers' remains rest beyond the shoals
of Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket, and farther offshore still, on
a smooth plateau inside the steep edge of the continental shelf.
</P>
<P>
   As the flowers drifted seaward, the same wind that had created a
menacing ocean swell tugged at the relatives' clothing and hair,
and the horizon seemed to waver, a sign that heavy swells persisted
at the crash site, where the Navy had suspended the latest search.
</P>
<P>
   The service on Sunday marked an end to a week of grief and
repeated disappointment. First, the families were told to expect no
one to have survived the six-mile fall to the sea and the extended
stay in chilly water. Then each day they received news of suspended
or unsuccessful searches.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, when they viewed the tiny bits of wreckage under
tents at the Quonset Point Air National Guard Base, many had come
to realize that they might never even receive their relatives'
remains.
</P>
<P>
   Samir El Shanawany, general manager of EgyptAir's North American
operations, said that 340 relatives and friends had made the
pilgrimage to Rhode Island. With the service over, many were
expected to leave Newport and wait for further news from home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
