<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON COLLEGE FOOTBALL: PENN STATE PLAYS IT TOO CLOSE FOR COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems disrespectful to think of a grand old game like the
Rose Bowl as a consolation prize, but that's what it will amount to
for Penn State. And that is only if the Nittany Lions can qualify
to play the Pacific-10 Conference champion in Pasadena, Calif., no
sure thing now. Ranked No. 2 last week, Penn State fell to No. 6 in
the Associated Press broadcasters' and writers' poll, No. 8 in the
USA Today/ESPN coaches' poll and No. 9 in the New York Times
computer ranking Sunday after losing by 24-23 to Minnesota in Happy
Valley on Saturday. The Nittany Lions (9-1 overall, 5-1 in the Big
Ten) have little chance now to play in the Sugar Bowl in the
national championship game between the two top-ranked schools as
judged by a consensus of ratings in the Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the Lions are in second place in the Big Ten, a
half-game behind Wisconsin's 6-1. Assuming that Wisconsin defeats
last-place Iowa in its season finale on Saturday, the Badgers would
finish with a conference record of 7-1 and an overall record of
9-2. Penn State could clinch the Rose Bowl berth and finish 11-1
overall and in a 7-1 tie for the conference title with victories
over Michigan on Saturday at home and at Michigan State on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The first tie breaker for the Rose Bowl berth is head-to-head
competition, but the Lions and the Badgers do not face each other
this season. The next tie breaker is overall record, which would be
in Penn State's favor, assuming two difficult victories over the
Wolverines and the Spartans. The third tie breaker is that the most
recent Rose Bowl qualifier is eliminated and Wisconsin went last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be difficult for Coach Joe Paterno to rally his team
against two ranked opponents after a loss to the Golden Gophers on
a last-second field goal. Michigan has defeated Penn State in their
last two meetings, by 27-0 in Ann Arbor last season and by 34-8 in
Happy Valley in 1997. Michigan is 12th in The Times ranking and
Michigan State is 17th. Minnesota moved up to No. 21 and Wisconsin
is 10th. All might be even higher if Big Ten teams didn't have to
play each other, forcing someone to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest conference you can play in,'' said
Rashard Casey, one of Penn State's two quarterbacks. ``Any team can
lose at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Rose Bowl, the Florida Citrus Bowl has the second
selection from eligible Big Ten teams. Next in line are the
Outback, the Alamo and the Sun. Both Michigan and Michigan State
have records of 4-2 in the conference and 7-2 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cerimele, the Penn State fullback, said: ``We've got two
tough ones coming up. Next week's very important for us. I think
this team is going to bounce back and come back fighting. This team
is made up of a bunch of fighters and champions. We're not going to
fold. There is no doubt in my mind we are going to come out
fighting. We are going to give Michigan a great game and hopefully
come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerimele admitted that he cried after losing on Saturday on a
32-yard field goal by Dan Nystrom. Also in tears was LaVar
Arrington, the star linebacker who had a career-best 15 tackles.
``Call me selfish,'' Arrington said, ``but I was just thinking
about the Sugar Bowl. I had gotten to the point where I felt we'd
win every close game.''
</P>
<P>
   And this one was close all day. The Gophers held leads of 9-7
and 21-20. Penn State took its third lead of the game at 23-21 with
9 minutes 12 seconds remaining when Travis Forney kicked his third
field goal of the game, his second from 44 yards. His only miss had
been from 50 yards when he hit a goal-post upright with the wind at
his back. Instead of allowing Forney to try the same thing again on
Penn State's last possession, Paterno decided to punt with the line
of scrimmage the Minnesota 33.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Mason, coach of Minnesota, said he was happy about
Paterno's decision ``because Forney is that good of a kicker and I
knew he could hit one from 50 yards out.'' A field goal then would
have put the Gophers down by 5 points and would have forced them to
try for a touchdown. Mason also said he agreed with Paterno's
decision to punt and try to pin the Gophers deep in their own end.
But the punt went into the end zone and Minnesota started the final
drive from its 20, a change of only 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno, reflecting on the decision, later said: ``I don't think
I thought twice about that one. I just figured they're not going to
be able to go the distance. I just didn't think they could. That's
a mistake I made. It never even dawned on me not to punt. I
thought, with less than two minutes to go, we would be able to hold
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But quarterback Billy Cockerham led a winning drive that
included two long gains on pass plays. He, too, defended Paterno's
reasoning. ``Joe Paterno hasn't been in the game for as long as he
has, and been as successful as he has, without knowing what he is
doing,'' Cockerham said. ``We just made a couple big plays.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
