<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-CARDINALS-NY     11-07 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-CARDINALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A MUST-WIN GAME, JETS COME BACK TO BEAT CARDS, 12-7
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Despite Curtis Martin's rushing, the
defense's domination and the special teams' big play, the New York
Jets' offense looked beaten and incompetent as it trudged deep into
the fourth quarter Sunday, desperately seeking to end the first
half of their season with a victory over the Arizona Cardinals. If
not, Monday's second-guessers, and perhaps the Jets themselves,
would be conjuring memories of a 1-15 record of another era.
</P>
<P>
   The boos, the tens of thousands of empty seats at Giants
Stadium, the impatience _ all were reminiscent of the pre-Bill
Parcells period.
</P>
<P>
   And then, suddenly, it happened: Down by 7-6, Jets quarterback
Rick Mirer, facing a third-and-12, looked right for Dedric Ward,
saw him covered, and then spotted the ubiquitous Keyshawn Johnson
in the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly the entire game, Johnson had been blanketed by the
Cardinals' Pro Bowl cornerback, Aeneas Williams. Mirer and Johnson
had hooked up only once, and once Mirer had failed to see a
wide-open Johnson waving his hands in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was no Williams. He was near the sideline in
zone coverage. And this time Mirer not only saw Johnson in the
middle of the field, but also converted a clutch throw. He
connected with Johnson at the Cardinals' 25, and Johnson took it
the rest of the way to complete a 43-yard touchdown play. As is
Johnson's wont, he added some drama to the winning score when he
was tackled at the 1 and just made it over the goal line. The
missed two-point conversion made the final score 12-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Parcells, the Jets' coach, said later, ``nothing's
easy around here, as you can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but there were some encouraging developments. The Jets did
end the first half of the season 2-6. They also made a
fourth-quarter comeback, reversing a disturbing trend that had seen
them blow four fourth-quarter leads this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fresh start,'' special teamer Chris Hayes said at game's
end. He had made a spectacular play, for the third straight game,
as he tackled punt returner Mac Cody at the 6-yard line to pin the
Cardinals back in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no uproar, no fight songs in the New York locker
room. This was not a division opponent, or even a good team. The
rest of the Jets' schedule is daunting. The Cardinals are also 2-6,
but led for most of the game because a pair of former New Yorkers _
Dave Brown, the ex-Giant, and Rob Moore, the ex-Jet, converted on
the longest pass play of their careers, 71 yards, to set up a
second-quarter touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just about all the offensive punch for the
Cardinals, who have not started the same offensive line two
straight games, and who went to Brown at quarterback after Jake
Plummer was sidelined two games ago with a broken finger.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense held their former, popular teammate, Adrian
Murrell to 10 yards on seven carries.
</P>
<P>
   While Murrell was running backward, and even fumbling once,
Martin generated 133 yards on 38 carries, the most times he has run
the ball in a four-quarter game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when it came to keeping the drives going, the Jets faltered
repeatedly. They barely converted 30 percent of the time on third
down, and in one stretch were unsuccessful on five straight
third-down opportunities. Luckily for the offense, the Cardinals
were worse _ in large part because of the Jets defense. That
defense stopped the Cards 10 of 12 times on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, who was nominated by Parcells to start the Jets' next
game, at New England on Monday night, didn't want to talk much
about the weather. Still, he conceded that winds, which reached 23
mph, had affected the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   And Mirer allowed himself a smile _ something he hasn't been
able to wear too often in this topsy-turvy season _ as he
considered how Johnson got open for the pivotal play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you ask him?'' Mirer said. ``He's always open.'' Or
so Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells seemed willing to blame the wind for much of the
offense's headaches Sunday. He sounded exasperated, though, when
asked about Mirer's repeated decisions to run on third down instead
of pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several balls he didn't throw you wish he'd
thrown,'' Parcells said. ``These are passes we've thrown for 10
years and when you don't get them you kind of wonder why he's
pulling the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Jets got out of the opening half was a 44-yard field
goal by John Hall. That wasn't enough to offset a 4-yard touchdown
run by Michael Pittman that followed the long Brown-to-Moore
connection.
</P>
<P>
   This marked the third time in Mirer's six starts that he has
been unable to direct a touchdown drive before halftime. But the
Jets crept to within a point on Hall's 33-yard field goal in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their problems, the Jets had been blessed with good
field position throughout the game. In fact, they started seven
drives in Arizona territory, thanks in part to the short kicks into
the wind by Arizona punter Scott Player.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was the Jets' primary star on offense, but his repeated
running failed to produce points. Then came the almost-desperate
third-down completion to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was open on that play a couple of times earlier, and we
didn't hit for one reason or another,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   And the coverage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what coverage it was,'' he said. ``I only know it
was a touchdown.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
