<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDERED-CHILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A FAMILY VISIT LED TO A 20-YEAR-OLD MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madeline Carmichael could not bear to look at her
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Carmichael's 23-year-old son, Andre, visited her for
the first time since he was a child, she welcomed him to her
apartment in Brooklyn. But when he showed off his 3-year-old
daughter, Ms. Carmichael recoiled as if she had seen a ghost and
ordered him not to bring the girl around again, said Andre
Carmichael's wife, Bronzetta.
</P>
<P>
   The girl bore a strong resemblance to Andre's twin sister,
Latanisha, who disappeared 20 years ago, Bronzetta said she had
learned.
</P>
<P>
   So began the chain of events that led the police on Friday to
charge Madeline Carmichael with murder in Latanisha's death, after
they found the 3-year-old girl's mummified body wrapped in
newspaper and plastic and stuffed into a trunk in a closet in the
woman's home.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a police detective went to a state prison near the
Canadian border to interview Madeline Carmichael's son Gregory, 37,
who is serving time for robbery, a law-enforcement official said.
Gregory was 17 and living at home at the time of Latanisha's death
in 1979, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Carmichael, 60, who the police said has a history of
child abuse and who gave two of her four children up to foster
care, was awaiting arraignment Sunday at Brookdale Hospital Medical
Center in Brooklyn, where she was taken after she fell ill as the
police arrested her.
</P>
<P>
   But officials and children's advocates were trying to determine
how Latanisha became the latest in the heartbreaking roll call of
children _ Lisa Steinberg, Elisa Izquierdo, Sabrina Green _ who
appear to have fallen through a hole in the city's child-welfare
safety net.
</P>
<P>
   To some critics of the child-welfare system, the wonder is that
cases like Latanisha's have not happened more often. In the late
1970s, the system was revealed to be in disarray, with shoddy
record keeping and caseworkers unable to keep pace with rapidly
increasing caseloads.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Robinson Lowry, the executive director of Children's
Rights Inc., a national advocacy group, said that while the
child-welfare system is still bedeviled with problems, it has come
a long way in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer systems, as bad as they are now, were worse
then,'' Ms. Lowry said. ``The tracking was worse then, and the
follow-up just was not there.''
</P>
<P>
   If, as the police have said, Ms. Carmichael voluntarily
surrendered two of her children to foster care _ something
caseworkers often encouraged mothers to do to speed cases through
the system _ the authorities would have been inclined to leave her
alone, Ms. Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   They might have asked Ms. Carmichael to account for Latanisha,
but the police said the woman usually told friends that the girl
had been sent to live with relatives in the South. If she had told
the authorities the same thing, Ms. Lowry said, the chances were
slim that anyone would have checked out her story. ``They couldn't
follow through then,'' Ms. Lowry said, ``so if she had said the
child was elsewhere, they would probably have just accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   The city medical examiner has not yet determined the cause of
the child's death, the Brooklyn district attorney's office said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday at the shelter in Harlem where she lives
with her family, Bronzetta Carmichael recounted in stunned tones
her husband's disturbing visit to his mother, which led to the
discovery of Latanisha's body.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, Bronzetta said, she began urging Andre to
seek ``closure'' with his mother, whom he had not seen since he was
placed in foster care in 1988, at age 11. When Andre made the trip
to Brooklyn, he took along his stepson and the couple's 3-year-old
daughter, Andrea, called Sweet-Sweet by her family.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carmichael welcomed Andre and the boy, but seemed deeply
disturbed by the sight of Andrea, a shy girl with a button nose and
a shock of frizzy hair. Andre's suspicions were further aroused,
the police said, when he contacted an aunt who asked him if he had
also looked up his twin sister. He did remember having one, his
wife said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Andre Carmichael's older sister, Sabrina Carmichael, 29,
who told him that she believed that the twin was dead and possibly
still in their mother's apartment, the police said. Sabrina, who
was also sent into foster care as a child, said that Andre's
daughter looked just like Latanisha, Bronzetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Carmichael's discomfort with young children apparently
extended to Sabrina's children, too, said Johana Rivera, the
superintendent of Ms. Carmichael's apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive woman who lived in a cramped flat filled with
parcels wrapped in cellophane and complained of hearing children's
voices crying in the night, Madeline sometimes allowed Sabrina, who
lives in the Bronx, to visit her, Ms. Rivera said. But when Sabrina
brought her children, Ms. Carmichael would not even open the door.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivera also said Ms. Carmichael spoke of having another
daughter whom she had never named and who was so severely
``handicapped'' that Ms. Carmichael had had to put her in an
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Bronzetta Carmichael said she and her husband hoped that some
good might come of the discovery of Latanisha. ``Everything happens
for a reason,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea, in a blue shirt and blue pants, stood quietly by her
mother's side, uncomprehending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
