<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-MORITZ-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A FADED HOTEL RITZ-CARLTON'S FLAGSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The St. Moritz, the faded old dowager on Central Park
South, is the hotel that every tycoon wants but none has been able
to keep.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's latest suitor is Christopher Jeffries of Millennium
Partners, who completed a deal on Saturday to buy the 69-year-old
hotel from Ian Schrager's hotel company, which had bought it only
18 months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, whose once stylish interior became a place for
bargain-hunting tour groups as the carpets frayed, will get a full
makeover and become the 300-room flagship of the Ritz-Carlton
chain, Jeffries said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Millennium Partners and Schrager's
company will form a joint venture to convert the top 12 floors of
the 35-story building into 14 luxury condominiums, each offering a
panoramic view of Central Park and selling for more than $10
million. The hotel, at the Avenue of the Americas, now has 689
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to position this as one of the great hotels in New
York,'' Jeffries said.
</P>
<P>
   But achieving that goal may not be easy. For nearly a decade,
the St. Moritz has been a white elephant that has alternately
attracted and repelled developers who relish the opportunity to get
in on the Central Park South boom, but face the potentially
daunting costs of renovating the property, which has long been
saddled with financing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location of the St. Moritz is such that it should be one
of the prime hotels in Manhattan,'' said Sean Hennessey, director
of the hospitality practice at PricewaterhouseCoopers, the
accounting firm. ``But every owner for the past decade has found it
a daunting challenge to come up with the necessary capital to
renovate it. The cost of the renovation argues strongly for a
residential component for at least part of the building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
