<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HORSE OF THE YEAR WAITING TO BE CLAIMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ After all the upsets and long shots, the
dreams won and lost in the Breeders' Cup, who is the Horse of the
Year?
</P>
<P>
   Not Behrens, who needed only to win the Classic to reaffirm his
claim but instead ran seventh for his third straight defeat. He may
still be worth consideration, but he certainly did not clinch
anything in the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Not Cat Thief, who won the Classic. After all, he won only one
other race all year and ran in 10 that he did not win, including
the Kentucky Derby (third), the Preakness (seventh), the
Metropolitan Mile (sixth) and the Travers (seventh).
</P>
<P>
   Not Lemon Drop Kid, another smart 3-year-old, who ran sixth in
the Classic, five lengths in front of Behrens. Don't forget, he
finished ninth in the Kentucky Derby before winning the Belmont and
the Travers. But he also ran fifth in the Jockey Club Gold Cup
behind River Keen and Behrens, so he has raced out of the money in
his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Silverbulletday, who won eight consecutive races
against fillies but could not finish better than seventh against
colts in the Belmont. She closed the year by losing to Beautiful
Pleasure in the Beldame at Belmont Park and again lost to Beautiful
Pleasure when she ran sixth in the Breeders' Cup Distaff on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When she was winning the Kentucky Oaks, the Black-Eyed Susan and
the Alabama, all milestone races for a filly, Silverbulletday was
frequently named as one of those rare fillies who should be
considered for Horse of the Year. But now that she has stopped
beating fillies?
</P>
<P>
   So, you ask, who's left?
</P>
<P>
   For people who look to the Breeders' Cup every year for answers
to championship questions, there will be few guidelines this time.
Half of the eight races were won by long shots _ Soaring Softly and
Daylami were the only post-time betting favorites who won. Even Cat
Thief was a 19-1 long shot. One winner (Anees in the Juvenile) paid
$62.60 for a $2 bet. Another (Cash Run in the Juvenile Fillies)
rang down $67.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a vote for Horse of the Year,'' D. Wayne Lukas,
the trainer of Cat Thief and Cash Run, said Sunday. ``The Breeders'
Cup turned things upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one horse who won a Breeders' Cup race probably makes the
short list of candidates for the sport's highest honor: Artax in
the Sprint. He was second choice by a fraction to Forestry in the
betting, and he gave a flying performance, challenging Enjoy the
Moment (who faded to last) before rocketing into the lead and
winning in 1:07 4/5, tying the Gulfstream Park track record for six
furlongs set 26 years ago by Mr. Prospector.
</P>
<P>
   This was his third victory in a row, his second track record in
a row and his third track record in six months. On May 2 at
Aqueduct, Artax broke the track record for seven furlongs set 31
years earlier by Dr. Fager. On Oct. 16 at Belmont Park, he cracked
the track record for six furlongs set 12 years ago by Groovy.
</P>
<P>
   He is owned by Ernie Paragallo and trained by Louis Albertrani,
who said, ``If he breaks cleanly from the gate, they can't beat
him.'' He did, and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In this dashing year at the races, Artax has won four of his 15
starts but has run in the money 10 times. But his speed may put him
in the rare position that Forego held in 1974, when he was both the
sprinter of the year and the Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   And one horse who didn't run in the Breeders' Cup must be judged
in the voting for the Eclipse Award for Horse of the Year:
Charismatic, the former claimer who won the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness for Lukas and ran third in the Belmont after breaking two
bones in his left foreleg.
</P>
<P>
   True, Charismatic's career ended prematurely, but consider what
he accomplished. After being put in a claiming race for $62,500 on
Feb. 11, and not being claimed, he raced two grinding months with
great success: on April 3 he was fourth in the Santa Anita Derby;
on April 18 he was first in the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland; on
May 1 he was first in the Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs at
31-1; on May 15, first in the Preakness at Pimlico, and on June 5,
third in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope,'' Lukas said, ``that Charismatic and Cat Thief
get consideration for 3-year-old champion. But I'm not sure that
anything in racing matches the demands placed on a young horse in
the Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   William Clifton, the co-owner of Behrens, turned to James Bond
when he was saddling Behrens for the Classic, with Horse of the
Year waiting to be claimed, and said, ``We've got a putt to make on
18.''
</P>
<P>
   But golf is a humbling game. And so is horse racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
