<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-L.A.TIMES-NYT &LR;      11-07 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-L.A.TIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TRUTH ACCORDING TO OTIS CHANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Nov. 8:
</P>
<P>
   The startling letter that Otis Chandler wrote last week to the
staff of the newspaper run by his family for over a century may be
remembered as a striking moment in the effort to protect
journalistic integrity from the commercial pressures of a new age
in media economics.
</P>
<P>
   Before retiring as publisher of The Los Angeles Times in 1980,
Chandler turned an uneven, provincial daily into a newspaper with
ambitious news coverage and a national reputation for quality. But
it is also one of many American papers that have struggled in
ensuing years to maintain growth and profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, stockholders in Chandler's family turned to a
former General Mills executive, Mark Willes, to improve the
company's economic status and boost its stock price. In his letter,
Chandler blamed Willes' philosophy of ``breaking down the
traditional editorial/business wall'' for leading to the paper's
current scandal _ a secret sharing of revenues with a professional
sports center that was the subject of a special magazine section.
</P>
<P>
   This thunder from the paper's most revered elder came as the
newsroom staff moved toward open revolt against Willes' approach of
having newsroom business managers help plan coverage that would
drive revenues. And it is that systemic approach, rather than the
paper's obvious mishandling of the Staples Center magazine section,
that holds the greater interest for other mainstream newspapers and
their readers.
</P>
<P>
   Under competitive pressure from broadcasting and the Internet,
all such newspapers have to find new ways of making money. But as
Chandler noted, Willes and his executives lacked newspaper
experience, and they plotted a radical and journalistically
dangerous course.
</P>
<P>
   After first decreeing an unrealistic goal of increasing
circulation by 500,000, they empowered the business side to reach
across the ``wall'' that protects news decisions from commercial
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler characterized this as the novice mistake of
well-intentioned executives who ``have no newspaper experience at
any level.''
</P>
<P>
   His point about experience is important. Tension between the
business and editorial sides is part of life at any newspaper,
including this one. The challenge is to create ways of maintaining
journalistic quality and business viability, both of which are
essential to a thriving newspaper. That means communicating across
the wall without creating an adversary culture or disregarding the
values of either side.
</P>
<P>
   What the Staples Center controversy brought into the open at The
Los Angeles Times was not simply a conquest of business over the
newsroom. It was, more dangerously, a failure to understand the
contribution that an uncompromised newsroom makes to the business
strength of a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Chandler told his former colleagues that ``respect and
credibility for a newspaper is irreplaceable.'' He can hope to be
listened to at the paper he once led. He can be sure he will be
heeded in other newsrooms and circulation and sales offices
throughout the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
