<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES OF CRASH VICTIMS SAY GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Kissing white roses that will be dropped Monday
into the remote waters where EgyptAir Flight 990 crashed last week,
relatives of the 217 victims of the disaster bid goodbye Sunday to
their loved ones at a multifaith memorial service held at Brenton
Point State Park.
</P>
<P>
   One woman repeatedly cried, ``My baby, my baby,'' and others
wailed and wept as they walked to the sea to kneel in prayer or
scatter flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Many intended to return to their homes across America and around
the world Sunday night and Monday, reconciled to the fact that
there will be no bodies to bury and no ready answers to unlock the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   As about 250 relatives mourned, the Navy prepared to double its
efforts to retrieve the critical black boxes hidden in the plane's
wreckage. A more powerful, more versatile underwater robot will
join forces with a drone that has made two dives to the ocean
bottom. Poor conditions prevented any recovery efforts Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as powerful as the prayers and words of condolence
offered in several languages by religious leaders and Egyptian,
Canadian, and US officials at Sunday's service were the physical
symbols that took the place of normal funeral rites.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is giving families, many desperate for any remnant
of the deceased, at least 100 bottles of sea water. Some scooped up
pebbles and sand on the beach to take home.
</P>
<P>
   White, the color of hope, dominated the service. The tent was
white. White carnations, daisies, and roses, set on a white
tablecloth, adorned the podium. Mourners faced the ocean, the sun's
glittering reflection on the water a bright reminder of nature's
awesome power dwarfing human life.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish, Muslim, and Christian spiritual leaders offered words of
comfort and healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chain of love has lost a vital link,'' said Rabbi Marc S.
Jagolinzer, president of the Rhode Island Board of Rabbis. ``Yet
there is so much death cannot take . . .. Death cannot take from us
the love we knew. It is woven into the tapestry of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the family members dropped flowers into a white wicker
basket that a military honor guard carried to a Coast Guard
helicopter. The helicopter hovered briefly by the shore before
departing. It will scatter the flowers at the crash site Monday,
weather permitting, and make a videotape for families.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Brokaw of Winchester, Mass., whose father perished in the
crash, sent two poems to Newport to be attached to the flowers
dropped at sea. The poems _ ``Nothing Golden Can Stay'' by Robert
Frost, and ``The Swan'' by Rainer Maria Rilke _ were chosen,
respectively, in memory of Richard Brokaw, 75, of Strafford, Vt.,
and his wife, Virginia Chaplin, 74, of Georgetown, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had been married for a year and were headed to Egypt
for a two-week educational tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both so alive. They will remain that way for us. He
was a very happy man,'' Susan Brokaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to pay respects, a few Newport residents watched eight
buses take mourners from the Goat Island Doubletree Hotel to
Brenton Point. Some held hands over their hearts as the buses
passed; others lifted hats or simply stood and gazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel desolate and you feel helpless and you think of these
people a lot,'' said Newport retiree Loretta Goldrick, who has been
praying for the families at Mass every morning. ``This is a very
celebratory city, where people come for weddings and parties. This
has been quite a departure. I think there's a terrible sense of
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Dignitaries who attended the memorial included the Egyptian
ambassador to the United States, Nabil Al Fahmy; the deputy prime
minister of Canada, Herbert Gray; and the US transportation
secretary, Rodney Slater. President Clinton sent a letter of
condolence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the recovery effort will receive reinforcements in
the form of a second underwater robot _ called Magnum _ that will
complement the Navy's Deep Drone, which previously had been used
alone in the harsh environment of the 270-foot-deep debris field.
</P>
<P>
   Magnum was scheduled to begin its 12-hour journey to the crash
site about midnight Sunday night on the stern of the Carolyn
Chouest, a civilian vessel leased by the Navy that can use a
special thruster to turn 360 degrees and remain fixed above the
crash site without anchoring.
</P>
<P>
   The two robots, conditions permitting, will be deployed Monday
afternoon to resume the search for the two black boxes of EgyptAir
990. The recovery effort was halted late Saturday night as winds
increased and the USS Grapple, the Navy's premier salvage ship,
starting to drag anchor in worsening seas and returned to Newport
for refueling. The Grapple was expected to rejoin the search effort
in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said Sunday that the operation is too dangerous for divers,
who could spend only 25 minutes on a bottom strewn with potentially
entangling wreckage. He called the recovery operation one of the
most challenging that the NTSB has faced, similar in degree to the
difficulties encountered in the ValuJet crash in the Everglades in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real daunting task ahead of us,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Deep Drone was deployed for about 9 1/2 hours Saturday.
Although the pinging emitted by transponders from the flight data
recorder and cockpit voice recorder were located once again, the
robot could not work its way through the wreckage to reach the
source of the sound, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   If adding the second robot does not clear the obstacles, Hall
said, the Navy might begin hauling wreckage to the surface in hopes
that the black boxes will be retrieved with other debris. However,
he said, this tactic risks damaging the boxes, whose data are
expected to contain critical evidence about the cause of the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
