<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
33 WOUNDED IN ISRAEL ATTACK; PEACE NEGOTIATORS PUSH ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATANYA, Israel _ After a bombing wounded 33 people Sunday,
Israeli and Palestinian officials vowed not to let the attack
disrupt momentum in the peace process, and both sides agreed to go
ahead with talks Monday on the final and crucial aspects of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli deputy minister of defense, Efraim Sneh, told Israel
Radio: ``The attack is another attempt by terrorist organizations
to derail the peace process. The government has no intention to
delay the ongoing process, which is a historical necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said three pipe bombs had been left near a trash can
during the midmorning rush hour, at a busy intersection in this
coastal town north of Tel Aviv. A fourth pipe bomb was defused near
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were reportedly treated for moderate to serious
injuries, and 29 were treated for minor injuries, hospital
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Palestinians were arrested, but all were released
before midnight. Police reinforced patrols on the border with the
West Bank, which runs less than 10 miles from the outskirts of
Netanya.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they were operating on the assumption that the
attack was the work of ``terrorists'' aimed at derailing the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   There were no claims of responsibility as of Sunday night, but
on Saturday the military wing of the Islamic resistance movement
Hamas issued a written warning to media outlets that it would
resume violent attacks to counter Israel's continuing construction
of Jewish settlements in the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh said, ``For some time we have been receiving warnings of
possible atacks designed solely to disrupt the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziad Abu Zayyad, a senior minister in the Palestinian Authority,
condemned the attack and told CNN, ``We are determined to fight
terror, and to isolate terrorists and marginalize them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the peace process is in a precarious spot as
both sides try to renew the confidence in each other that will be
necessary for the further implementation of the ``Wye Two''
agreement. The first Wye River plan was agreed to at Wye
Plantation, Md., in the fall of 1998. Wye Two was signed by the two
sides this fall in Sharm el Sheikh, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most significant attempts to invigorate the peace
process began last week in Oslo, where the 1993 peace plan got its
name and where the broad outlines of an agreement were hammered out
in secret talks.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat, and President Clinton all came together last week to
honor the slain Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was
killed by a Jewish extremist opposed to the peace plan of which
Rabin was a principal architect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear nice words from Mr. Barak, but we need to see more
actions,'' said Zayyad.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Barak is expected to continue with further Israeli
troop redeployments from the West Bank as spelled out in the Wye
Two agreement. And Palestinians and US officials are waiting to see
if he will live up to his promise to dismantle illegal settlements
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he extended the Sunday deadline by several days and the
Israeli media was reporting that several of the more militant
settlements, such as Maon, were digging in and would refuse the
attempts of Israeli soldiers to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Top negotiators for the two sides are set to meet in Ramallah
Monday morning to set the agenda for talks on the so-called final
status issues, which include the final borders between Israel and
the Palestinian Authority, the status of Jerusalem, which both
sides claim as a capital, the return of Palestinian refugees, and
the fate of Jewish settlements that have been hastily erected and
fortified in the West Bank in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One Palestinian commentator warned that Palestinians would judge
Barak's commitment to the peace process based on his approach not
just to these militant settlements, but to the other Jewish
settlements on occupied West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements in the West Bank, that's the main issue for
Palestinians right now,'' said Ali Jarbawai, a political science
professor at Bir Zeit University on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many Palestinians appreciate the final status
talks. They are skeptical about them and have lost faith in the
process because of what they see around them, especially concerning
the settlements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Movement forward in the process has not been easy, but it seems
now to be at a critical juncture. The scene at Sunday's bombing
showed just how high emotions are running in Israel now as the two
sides try to turn this corner.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Israelis shouting anti-Barak slogans clogged the street
after the explosions, jostling to get closer to the spot where the
pipe bombs exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Some shouted, ``Death to Arabs!''
</P>
<P>
   The bombs were left near a rubbish bin on the main street in
downtown Netanya, and the explosions carved a hole in the concrete
wall of a clothing shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly we heard explosions and saw a huge burst of smoke and
fire, and then things were flying through the air, people were
shouting and we were all terrified,'' said Aliza Yom-Tov, owner of
a lingerie shop located a few yards from where the bombs went off.
</P>
<P>
   ``After an attack like this the only thing to do is to stop
talks and not give them anything else,'' said Avraham Levy, a
50-year-old taxi driver who supports the opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the carnage, some Netanya residents said the only
solution was to keep the peace process moving. A municipal official
who would not give his name attributed the bombings to Palestinian
frustration over a peace process that was slow and murky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are attacks because there are no serious talks going on,
and the Palestinians don't know what they will get, and we don't
know what we are giving, and this opens the way for extremists,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
