<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS NEAR TRADE OF GREEN FOR MONDESI 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANA POINT, Calif. _ The engine that the Texas Rangers stoked
last week with the trade of Juan Gonzalez roared into this tiny
resort town on the Pacific Ocean this past weekend and fired up a
contingency deal that has Shawn Green moving from Toronto to Los
Angeles for Raul Mondesi in a four-player swap. The completion of
the deal depends on the Dodgers' ability to negotiate a contract
with Green by midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gonzalez, who went to Detroit in a surprisingly early
trade, Green is a member of a glittering group of players who can
be free agents after next season and have made it virtually
impossible for their teams to sign them to extended contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a variation of free agency,'' one general manager said
Sunday on the first day of the annual general managers meetings.
``The players want to have free agency a year before they can
become free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees jumped into Green's quasi-free agency, knowing what
an attraction he would be in New York as one of the game's best
young hitters and Jewish on top of it. They talked to the Blue
Jays, but Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager, said they offered
``too little,'' declining to identify the players because ``the
Yankees could get back in it.'' That could happen only if the
Dodgers fail to reach agreement with Green on a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ash and Kevin Malone, the Dodgers' general manager, reached
agreement on players Friday, then sought permission from the
commissioner's office for the Dodgers to negotiate with Green and
his agent, Jeff Moorad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a trade,'' Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball's
executive vice president for baseball operations, said Sunday.
``There had to be a trade for permission to be granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the practice that has existed for years, the Dodgers were
given 72 hours to talk to Green and Moorad. The period began at
midnight Pacific time Friday and expires at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Blue Jays were fined by the
commissioner's office for giving the Rangers and the Houston
Astros, who also were fined, permission to talk to Roger Clemens
and his agent after Clemens said he wanted to be traded. The Blue
Jays had not made a contingency deal with either team and had not
gone through the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn quickly,'' Ash said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays, who paid Green $4,575,000 in an expired two-year
contract, offered him $48 million on a five-year contract and were
prepared to go higher, but, Ash said, money was not the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us he wanted to play in a major U.S. city with a large
Jewish population,'' Ash said. Toronto, it was mentioned, has a
large Jewish population. ``But it's not a major U.S. city,'' the
general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Ash declined to talk about the trade. ``I prefer not to say
anything until we know where it's headed,'' he said. Malone also
declined to comment. ``I can't comment,'' he said, ``because any
comment could jeopardize the chances of completing a deal and I
don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   An executive with one of the teams, however, confirmed that the
primary player who would go to the Blue Jays was Mondesi, like
Green an explosive hitter but unlike Green a discontented player.
The executive would not identify the other player who would go to
Toronto but said it was not Ismael Valdes, a 26-year-old member of
the Dodgers' starting pitching rotation, as had been rumored.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's verbal eruptions with Malone and the Dodgers' manager,
Davey Johnson, made him a likely subject for a trade despite his
continued offensive production. The right fielder batted a
career-low .253, but achieved career highs with 99 runs batted in,
33 home runs and 36 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Besides defusing a potentially inflammatory clubhouse, the
exchange would add the kind of left-handed power hitter the Dodgers
have sought for their primarily right-hand hitting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who will celebrate his 27th birthday Wednesday, was among
the American League leaders in a host of offensive categories:
first in total bases (361), extra-base hits (87), doubles (45) and
the season's longest hitting streak (28 games); tied for second in
runs scored (134); fifth in slugging percentage (.588); tied for
fifth in home runs (42); tied for seventh in RBI (123), and tied
for ninth in hits (190).
</P>
<P>
   In trading Green and next Carlos Delgado, their slugging first
baseman, the Blue Jays said they wanted established players in
return, no prospects for them. Mondesi would certainly give them
that. They also do not have free-agency concerns with Mondesi
because he has two years left on a four-year, $36 million contract,
and the club holds two years of options after that.
</P>
<P>
   His salaries for the next two years are $9.5 million and $11
million, then $11 million and $13 million for the option years. The
four-year total of $44.5 million is less than the $48 million that
the Blue Jays offered Green. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
