<HEADLINE>
MARATHON ENTRANTS RAN WITH COMPUTER CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GRACE LICHTENSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time, technology allowed friends,
relatives and anyone with computer access to learn how runners
fared in the New York City Marathon within about 15 minutes of
their crossing the finish line. The quick results were thanks to
the Internet, the Microsoft Network and a computer chip embedded in
a small yellow plastic disc that entrants wore on their sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   The ChampionChip, used in many international races, was part of
each entry kit. It transmitted a signal to a data cable under a mat
at both the starting line and the finish line. The cable then
transmitted the signals to Microsoft computer servers in Redmond,
Wash., which relayed them to computer terminals at the New York
Road Runners Club's trailers in Central Park, as well as to the
official marathon site on the Microsoft Network on the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an entire team working on this,'' said Cindy Spodek
Dickey, a Microsoft marketing executive. ``We tested it up to the
last minute. It means this is the first time the world can access
runners' times almost right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The chips performed as promised, broadcasting precise run times
(the actual time from start to finish as opposed to the time from
when the gun was fired) of everyone in the pack. The chips also
broadcast split times for the elite runners at the 10K,
half-marathon and 20-mile marks. Indeed, by 3:45 p.m., the Web site
was already showing statistics for 18,000 entrants _ more than half
of those who had entered.
</P>
<P>
   For middle-of-the-pack athletes, the chip was especially useful
because the crowd at the starting line on the Verrazano Bridge is
so large that it takes up to 10 minutes for some to cross the
actual starting line. It was also important for runners who were
aiming for times to qualify for other races, such as the Boston
Marathon. The New York Road Runners Club planned to include the net
time as well as the gun time on every certificate sent to
finishers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
