<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLEAN-AIR-NYT &LR;      11-07 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEAN-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLEAN AIR COUNTERATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Nov. 8:
</P>
<P>
   There were two important and potentially far-reaching victories
for clean air advocates last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the federal government announced legal action
aimed at forcing 32 coal-fired power plants in the Midwest and
South to install modern anti-pollution controls or risk severe
monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Gov. George Pataki of New York disclosed that he
would shortly impose new emissions standards on cars and some other
vehicles sold in New York in an effort to force the automobile
manufacturers to produce much cleaner cars on a faster timetable
than required by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few months ago, clean air advocates were on the run,
devastated by back-to-back rulings in the D.C. Court of Appeals in
response to lawsuits brought by the big utilities and a few
Midwestern states. The rulings invalidated new federal air-quality
standards and blocked a carefully negotiated plan that would have
forced 22 states east of the Mississippi to reduce emissions of the
chemicals that cause smog and acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings were particularly devastating for New York and other
Northeastern states that for years have suffered from air pollution
that blows eastward from dirty, coal-fired plants in the border
states and the Midwest. These plants are major sources not only of
urban smog and acid rain, but also of the gases that contribute to
global warming and mercury emissions that are lethal to fish and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the eastern states, led by New York, have
counterattacked. In September, Eliot Spitzer, New York's attorney
general, threatened to sue 17 coal-fired plants in five Midwestern
and border states unless they reduced their emissions. The federal
actions announced Wednesday complement Spitzer's strategy while
doubling the number of plants on the target list.
</P>
<P>
   Both the federal and the state lawsuits are based on a largely
untested provision of the 1970 Clean Air Act. In general, the act
``grandfathered'' older coal-producing plants built before 1970,
exempting them from the law's strict pollution standards in the
mistaken expectation that they would be shut down in a few years.
But the law also specified that plants that were significantly
modernized to produce more energy had to comply with the same
pollution controls as new plants.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer and the federal government claim that the companies
named in their lawsuits deliberately ducked that obligation in
order to save money.
</P>
<P>
   If the suits succeed, the clean air benefits could occur within
a few years. Pataki's plan will take longer to show results, but
they could be huge. Under the new regulations, New York will adopt
California's emissions standards, which are tougher than the
federal government's and will require the industry to produce in 10
years cars that emit only half the pollution they do now.
</P>
<P>
   Since New York and California account for a huge share of the
national market, the super-clean New York-California car could
become the standard for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, some environmentalists feared that the
Clinton administration and politicians with possible national
aspirations, like Pataki, would be reluctant to offend pivotal
Midwestern states and key industries with elections approaching.
Happily, these fears seem to have been unwarranted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-NY-MARA-FAMILIES-     11-07 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARA-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERATIONS APART, FAMILIES RACE TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edward Leitch, 72, traveled more than 5,000 miles
from Cairns, Australia, to New York City to run 26.2 miles Sunday
with his youngest son, Andrew, 38.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Rubenstein, 18, drove more than 200 miles from Worcester,
Mass., to go the distance with his grandfather, Harold Somer, 80,
and uncle, Robert, 37.
</P>
<P>
   There were 30,000 stories in the 30th New York City Marathon:
tales of running for redemption, running for glory, running just
for the sake of it. The Leitches' and Somers' stories are
uncomplicated yarns combining the love of family and sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past two years, I listened to my grandfather and uncle
return home from running the marathon with these wonderful
stories,'' said Rubenstein, who was so enthralled by their colorful
vignettes that he decided to run this marathon as soon as he
reached the eligibility age of 18. ``It made me want to run. Not
just run, but to cross the finish line with two other
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Leitch was the supportive son, standing along roadsides
in Australia, Boston, New York and Portland, Ore., watching his
father compete in what now amounts to 25 to 30 marathons. Andrew
Leitch moved to New York 10 years ago to pursue a career as a
musician but gave up that dream for a steady-paying job as creative
services director for T3, a multimedia company.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when he returned home for his mother's funeral, he
was struck by how fleeting life is and how many special moments
with her he had missed. He vowed not to lose similar opportunities
with his father, no matter how many miles apart they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I decided to run the marathon with him,'' Leitch
recalled Saturday during a reception for runners from Australia and
New Zealand at the Australian Consulate at 158 West 42nd St. ``I
thought this would be something memorable I could do with my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a touch of sweet irony to the Leitch and Somer stories.
In a sport dominated by youth, it is the younger generation that
has the rookies seeking advice from men two times their age, or in
the case of the Somer family, more than four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to take it slowly, go with the pace,'' Edward
Leitch said. ``If he feels good at six miles, then I told him he
could pick up the pace. Oh, I told him he probably wouldn't get a
good night's sleep the night before, because you're always a bit
restless the night before a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Somer offered similar guidance to Justin, whose mother,
Linda, is one of three daughters and two sons in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``No two bodies are the same,'' Somer advised his grandson over
a Saturday night premarathon family dinner of spaghetti and
meatballs and broiled chicken. ``He knows his body. As long as he
paces himself, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leitches made plans to run side by side over the stretch of
five boroughs, while the Somers had no such expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to do just under 3 hours 50 minutes,'' said Robert
Somer, a lawyer now in his 12th New York City Marathon. Rubenstein,
who understands that the triumph is in finishing, said that coming
in an hour behind his uncle would be fine. As for the patriarch of
the family? ``I told them not to wait for me. I'll be in the
five-hour range.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Leitch, one of 135 runners from Australia and among 60
who made the trip just to run in the marathon, said his personal
best was 3 hours 19 minutes, which he achieved at the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to be in the four-hour-plus range,'' he said. Leitch,
a retired metallurgical chemist, began running in his 20s and
continued through the birth of his four sons, Campbell, Bruce,
Robert and Alex, the only nonrunner among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been doing a lot of cross-training,'' Alex Leitch
said. ``The only downside so far was that I got tennis elbow doing
weight training.''
</P>
<P>
   Now for the epilogues:
</P>
<P>
   Robert Somer decided to run with the Achilles Track Club,
helping three wheelchair athletes fight the wind gusts across the
Queensboro Bridge. This added more than an hour to his personal
best, and he finished in 5 hours 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein ended up running the entire distance alongside his
grandfather, and they crossed the finish line together in 6 hours
49 minutes. Justin, a freshman at Colgate University, then headed
back to Massachusetts to make an 11:30 a.m. calculus class.
</P>
<P>
   Edward and Andrew Leitch crossed the finish line in 4:58. Edward
and his son Bruce planned to spend two more days in New York, then
fly to Chicago to see relatives there. They expect to return to
Australia on Friday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
