<HEADLINE>
BREEDERS' CUP JUVENILE A CURSE FOR THE DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The colts and fillies had barely been sponged
off after the biggest race of their 2-year-old lives, and their
owners were already thinking about the first Saturday in May. In
the barn of the Breeders' Cup Juvenile winner Anees, trainer Alex
Hassinger already had Kentucky _ as in Derby _ on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His colt needed to pass all 13 horses in the stretch to capture
the $1 million race after being bumped out of the gate by rival
Forest Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got knocked pretty good. But what was impressive was
watching him in the last five-sixteenths of a mile when he passed
five horses and made up six lengths,'' said the trainer, who
saddled Juvenile fillies winner Eliza in 1992. ``He's a real
intelligent colt and I believe next year can be a big one for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stirring victory for Hassinger's colt, but the
Breeders' Cup Juvenile hasn't meant much in the Triple Crown races
for 3-year-olds. Even if Anees grows without injury into a
3-year-old, continues to learn as he races, he still has history to
buck. No winners of the previous 15 Breeders' Cup Juveniles has
gone on to win the Kentucky Derby _ last year's winner, for
example, Answer Lively, finished 10th at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, New York-based Nick Zito compared the losing statistic
to the curse of the Bambino that befell the Red Sox which some New
Englanders still blame for the team's World Series futility. Zito
skipped the Juvenile and kept Champagne Stakes winner Greenwood
Lake in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in the field will show up in the spring. Chief
Seattle looked like a winner until Anees rocketed by and trainer
John Kimmel said the improving colt will take the winter off. ``I
was very happy with the race,'' said Kimmel of the second-place
finisher.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas took the blame for High Yield's third-place
finish, but was clearly eyeing the spring classics. The colt came
four wide _ a la 1999 Derby winner Charismatic _ around the turn
but ran out of gas the last sixteenth of the mile. But Lukas says
High Yield is hearty enough to improve off heavy workouts in the
spring _ much like Charismatic did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to saddle him, he looked fat to me. He's going to
be a good 3-year-old because he's going to be able to take it,''
Lukas said of hard works. ``He'll dance the dances.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hassinger believes his colt made a case to be named
champion 2-year-old, the 31-1 shot perhaps left that title open for
the East Coast phenomenon More Than Ready. The Todd Pletcher
trained colt won 5 of 5 _ including four stakes _ before finishing
third in the Belmont Futurity and being walloped by more than 13
lengths in the Champagne. He, too, was turned out in Florida to
rest for a 3-year-old campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty clear he is one of the best two years in
history,'' said Pletcher. ``It's up to others to decide where he
fits in the championship picture, but we're confident he is going
to be a 3-year-old to contend with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
