<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS PICK UP PIECES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings had a lot to think about
Sunday after playing their worst game of the season the night
before. They had to ask themselves whether they were ready to move
on without injured stars Luc Robitaille and Jozef Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   The players did very little skating at the team's Iceoplex
training facility. Instead, there were meetings with coach Andy
Murray addressing Saturday night's 5-3 meltdown against the
Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who on Saturday refused to use the losses of Robitaille
and Stumpel as an excuse for the poor effort, said he understands
why the team came out so flat. But he vowed it would not carry over
to Tuesday night's game against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a day of mourning around here,'' Murray said of his
team, which was outshot 26-9 in the first two periods. ``I think
before last night's game the team had come to grips with losing
Luc. But they didn't find out about Stumpy until almost an hour
before the game. Perhaps that was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel had undergone an MRI on Thursday for a tender abdominal
area, but it wasn't until 5:50 p.m. Saturday that the club learned
he would undergo surgery today and could miss up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jason Blake, who was slotted to take Robitaille's spot at
left wing, was moved to center after Stumpel was scratched.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was overwhelmed by the larger Philadelphia forwards and is
not expected to be back with the first line Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very long night for me,'' Blake said. ``It was good
to skate a little today, but I've spent a lot of time looking in
the mirror and wondering what I have to do to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance Blake will be replaced by center Len
Barrie, who was promoted Sunday from the club's minor-league
affiliate in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we didn't know about Stumpy until so late in the day,
we didn't know we needed a center,'' Murray said. ``Even if we did,
it would have been a little hard to get him here since the Ice Dogs
were in Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   But covering the logistics Sunday was not as difficult as
working on the mental part. Murray and his coaching staff met with
captain Rob Blake and alternate captain Garry Galley during the
afternoon. Also in the meeting was Robitaille, who is getting
around on a removable cast.
</P>
<P>
   `I told the veterans on the team that I need them to help us
move on from this,'' Murray said. ``As poorly as we played last
night, the game was still 2-2 after one period. We didn't even
start playing until the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even talk about Edmonton. That will be addressed at
(today's) practice. I think when they hit the ice we'll be able to
see how much they have gotten over what happened Saturday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
