<HEADLINE>
CHARLES SWEET, 81, WHO OVERSAW LABOR MURDER TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., Maine)  (lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Charles G. Sweet, who helped supervise the trials of
several of the nine people charged in the killing of the labor
leader Joseph Yablonski and his wife and daughter 30 years ago,
died on Oct. 31 at a nursing home in Tampa, Fla. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet, who had been living for the last few years in a Tampa
retirement community, was president judge on the Common Pleas Court
in Washington County, Pa., from 1964 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 until 1974, he helped oversee long and complex
criminal proceedings that drew national attention to Washington
County and resulted in charges against nine people in the Yablonski
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yablonskis were shot to death in their Clarksville, Pa.,
home on New Year's Eve, 1969. Three weeks earlier, Yablonski had
lost a bitter battle to unseat W.A. Boyle as president of the
United Mine Workers. Yablonski believed the election had been
rigged and may have been planning to help federal investigators in
an investigation of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nine people who were charged in the killings, Aubran
Martin and Paul Gilly, were convicted of first-degree murder in
trials that Sweet presided over in Washington County. Silous
Huddleston, Annette Gilly and Claude Veale confessed in the case,
and Albert Pass and William Prater were found guilty of murder in
Erie, Pa., after a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet later granted probation to Huddleston and Ms. Gilly and
suspended their sentences because they had cooperated with the
prosecution. He also dropped murder charges against William
Turnblazer, a former United Mine Workers district president, who
testified against Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses at Boyle's 1974 trial in Media, Pa., and a retrial
there in 1977 said Boyle had transferred $20,000 in union money to
pay for the killing of Yablonski and any witnesses. Boyle died in
1984 while serving three consecutive life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sprague, a Philadelphia prosecutor who was appointed
special assistant to the U.S. attorney general and a special
prosecutor to Washington County for the Yablonski murders, said
Sweet was involved in the early trials and confessions, which led
to Boyle's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the prosecutions in Washington County that built up a
foundation for the entire case,'' said Sprague, who is now in
private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Greenleaf Sweet was born in Lewiston, Maine, on Aug. 5,
1918, and grew up in Western Pennsylvania. He graduated from
Pennsylvania State University and Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet served in the Marine Corps in World War II, rising to the
rank of colonel.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Martha; a son, David, of Harrisburg;
a daughter, Barbara Sweet of Washington, D.C.; a stepdaughter,
Meredith Anthony-Light of New York; a stepson, Troy Breese of
Washington, Pa.; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2301EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
