<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      11-07 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MINNEAPOLIS _ The story this year in Minnesota hasn't been Randy
Moss.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been quarterback Jeff George, who took over the reins
three weeks ago because Randall Cunningham wasn't getting it done.
It has been receiver Cris Carter, the beneficiary of Moss' double
teams, who has become the Vikings' leader in catches, receiving
yards and touchdowns. And it has been the ground game, where
often-injured Robert Smith has once again been plagued by health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   None of these, however, will be the story this evening when the
Vikings host the Cowboys on Monday Night Football. There's only one
theme, only one matchup that has NFL fans excited _ Moss meets
Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of eyes on that matchup. I know I'll
be watching to see what happens,'' Cowboys safety George Teague
said. ``Mr. Moss is a great athlete and a great receiver, but we've
got a guy who can handle him, that's for sure. My money's on Prime
Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders watched from the sidelines last year, an injured toe
keeping him from this much-anticipated matchup. Moss stole the
spotlight, catching touchdown passes of 51, 56 and 56 yards before
a national Thanksgiving audience.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Moss declined interviews, insisting his on-field
performance should speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anything to say,'' Moss said about last year.
``What I said was on the field. What did I need to say? Deion
didn't play. Their questions were going to be, `What if Deion had
played?' The other question was going to be, `Did you have a point
to prove because Dallas didn't draft you?' Why stir up something
you already know the answer to?''
</P>
<P>
   This year has been tougher for Moss as defensive coordinators
have double- and triple-teamed him to keep him out of the end zone.
But even with only four touchdowns, Moss remains one of the most
exciting young players to come into the game. Sanders, of course,
remains one of the best to ever play his position, so the game
promises to have plenty of drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be curious to see how often they let Deion go one-on-one
with him,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said.
</P>
<P>
   After his legal troubles in college, there were plenty of teams
that chose to pass on Moss _ 19, to be exact. Some of those teams
had bigger holes to fill. Some, like the Cowboys, could have used
Moss' talent but were afraid of the potential headache.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been one. In his first season, Moss proved to be a
solid pick off the field, staying completely out of trouble. On the
field, he was spectacular, becoming the only first-year player to
earn a spot in the 1999 Pro Bowl after setting an NFL rookie record
with 17 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be his performance tonight against Sanders that
will be the real benchmark, according to many NFL insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Randy has so much ability that just to see him
compete at a young age against the best is a treat,'' Minnesota
running back Leroy Hoard said. ``And to see how he handles it is
going to definitely determine where he makes his mark in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much attention as Moss and Sanders get, it could well be
some other key players who decide tonight's outcome. The Cowboys
(4-3) are coming off a 34-24 loss to the Colts, their third defeat
in four games. They have struggled offensively, particularly in
second halves this season, and have lost three of their four road
games thus far. Quarterback Troy Aikman will be trying to
re-establish the offense, which has plummeted to 17th in the league
with receiver Michael Irvin on the sidelines with a neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings (4-4), on the other hand, have put together
back-to-back wins for the first time this season after making the
switch from Cunningham to George. Carter caught eight passes for
144 yards and two touchdowns last weekend against Denver. Hoard
rushed for 105 yards and one touchdown on 17 carries in a victory
two weeks ago against San Francisco. Add receiver Jake Reed,
George's other weapon, and the Minnesota offense is ranked fifth
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy receives most of the attention, as he should,'' Sanders
said. ``But when you're talking about the Minnesota Vikings, you're
talking about a trio of receivers that are great. After watching
the highlights, Cris Carter is a big-time player. You can't just
emphasize one man.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Moss, who knows that to be a superstar, he
has to be able to compete with the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good chance for me to go against the best and
for Deion to go against the best,'' Moss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
