<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DEUTSCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPI DEUTSCH, 101, HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR WITH REMARKABLE TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pepi Deutsch, a resilient, resourceful woman whose endurance of
the brutalities of the Nazis with her teen-age daughter at her side
was one of the most affecting stories of survival to emerge from
the Holocaust, died on Nov. 5 at Lawrence Hospital in Bronxville,
N.Y. She was 101 years old and lived at her daughter's home in
Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter, Clara Knopfler, said her mother, who had been one
of the world's oldest living Holocaust survivors, died from bladder
cancer that was diagnosed in July.
</P>
<P>
   Few mothers and daughters were able to survive the concentration
camps together. Either a mother was too old for work or a daughter
too young, and one or the other was sent to the gas chambers. Even
when they stayed together, relations frayed under the pressures of
starvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in these circumstances argued over a slice of bread or
a spoon of soup,'' Mrs. Knopfler, 72, said in an interview shortly
before she and her mother were honored in 1998 by the Westchester
Holocaust Commission. ``My mother and I never argued. She didn't
eat her soup, and gave it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Deutsch and her daughter managed to stay together through a
makeshift Hungarian ghetto, deportation, Auschwitz-Birkenau and
bone-wearying work at three other slave encampments. But Mrs.
Deutsch's 19-year-old son, Zoltan, died in Auschwitz, shot to death
in front of her husband, Joseph. Later, Joseph perished in a death
march. In all, 37 of her relatives died, including her mother and
four brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just I am and Clara,'' she said of the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   But that Clara survived told much about the sacrifices her
mother was willing to make. In January 1945, after the two women
weathered months of hunger, cold, lice and savagery from their
guards, Mrs. Deutsch made sure that Clara got to celebrate her 17th
birthday. She hoarded three slices of bread, coated them with
marmalade and produced a birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter repaid her on other occasions, once shaming a young
Nazi guard into an apology of sorts after he struck Mrs. Deutsch
across the shoulders. Clara simply reminded him to think of his own
mother.
</P>
<P>
   The habits of caring for each other were so hardened in the
caldron of the war that when it ended, the two women remained
companions for five decades, through Communist Romania, immigration
to the United States in 1962 and building a new life here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never separate from my mother or she from me,'' said
Mrs. Knopfler. ``I felt in the concentration camps, if we are
separated, we will never be together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Into her 100th year, Mrs. Deutsch pushed her square-shouldered
body through the Scarsdale house, did her own cooking _ she kept
kosher when her daughter did not _ and read a Hungarian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Until the war, Mrs. Deutsch, who was born on June 30, 1898,
lived a comfortable life in a Transylvanian village that shifted
between Hungarian and Romanian control. Her husband owned a shoe
factory.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1944, the Germans took control of Hungary and herded Mrs.
Deutsch, her family and 10,000 other Jews onto the grounds of a
brick factory. From there, they were taken by cattle cars to
Auschwitz-Birkenau. The notorious Dr. Josef Mengele assigned the
youthful-looking Mrs. Deutsch, then in her 40's, to a work group of
younger women that included Clara. A group of women closer to Mrs.
Deutsch's age were gassed.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were soon shipped to a Latvian factory where old
batteries were recycled into gunpowder. They survived there on a
daily ration of three slices of bread and a soup of potato peels.
Transferred to eastern Prussia, they dug anti-tank trenches. Mrs.
Deutsch used her brief rest periods to wash Clara's only dress in a
river.
</P>
<P>
   With the approach of the Russian army, the Germans abandoned
their slaves, and Mrs. Deutsch again saved her daughter. When a
drunken Russian soldier was about to rape Clara, Mrs. Deutsch sat
on her daughter's lap until a Ukrainian pulled the soldier off.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the miseries, Mrs. Deutsch kept her faith, refusing
to eat rations of lard and fasting on Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   Of the slaughter of six million Jews in the Holocaust, she said,
her daughter translating: ``This was not God's fault. This was done
by monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mrs. Knopfler, Mrs Deutsch is survived by a
grandson and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
