r s BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG)     11-07 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEARIN WANTS TO END BLAME GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ It starts at the top, Jeff Kearin said later,
taking responsibility for the remarkable lack of self-control the
Cal State Northridge football team showed Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm taking some bullets for the team,'' said Kearin,
CSUN's interim head coach whose explosive display of anger toward
the officials dulled the Matadors' momentum in the first quarter of
their 34-21 loss to host Portland State. ``I lost my composure
early with the officials. I lost my composure and all of a sudden
we're turning the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin is right. His sideline tantrum, which drew a 15-yard
unsportsmanlike penalty, came in the moments after the Matadors
tied the game at 14. Kearin's antics obviously weren't
inspirational; CSUN didn't score again until late in the fourth
quarter, after the Vikings built a 34-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Kearin is taking too much blame. It was a team effort in the
art of self-destructiveness _ especially when it came to blaming
the Big Sky Conference officials.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone associated with CSUN football _ the coaches, the
players and even some trainers _ didn't like the Matadors' penalty
total of 15. After the game, they made it sound like there were
twice as many penalties than that called against them.
</P>
<P>
   Look, any close observer of CSUN's seven Big Sky Conference
games this season notices the officials' tendency to drop the flag
on the Matadors, even for the most minor infractions. But the
football program needs to shed its ``us-against-the-conference''
mentality. It's a faulty mantra, and this Kearin knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so predictable in that regard,'' he said after the game.
``It's got to stop with me as much as anybody. It's a culture we've
had here for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors also seemed genuinely surprised and intimidated by
Portland State's physical aggressiveness, even though the Vikings
were fired up earlier in the week by CSUN cornerback Chazz Moore's
public prediction of a Matadors' upset.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a Portland resident, said he endured emotional and
physical abuse from the Vikings, which he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long,'' is how Moore described the jeering. ``I
couldn't take a breath without hearing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, Moore kept his cool. But his teammates seemed
genuinely surprised and intimidated by the Vikings' tactics. Most
of the Vikings are from large cities; they understood how to get
under the Matadors' skins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their demeanor is a lot like ours,'' Kearin said. ``Their
style of play is a lot like ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's loss left CSUN (5-4, 4-3) out of the race for the Big
Sky title and a shot at the Division I-AA playoffs. Now, the goal
with two games left should be a winning season.
</P>
<P>
   If the CSUN players think they weren't done any favors by the
Big Sky officials Saturday, they better think about what might
happen this week when they play at Southern Methodist University in
the Mustangs' last home game in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of talking on the field,'' is how CSUN
quarterback Marcus Brady described the game against Portland State.
``That's no excuse for us getting some stupid penalties.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
REPORT CARD &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GAME: 9 &QL; 
RESULT: Portland State 34, CSUN 21 &QL; 
RECORD: 5-4, 4-3 &QL; 
THIS WEEK'S GPA: 2.33 &QL; 
CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.67 &QL; 
NEXT GAME: At Southern Methodist &QL; 
QUARTERBACKS &QL; 
Playing with a sore left ankle, Marcus Brady threw 2 INTs, one of
which was returned for a TD. He completed less than 50 percent of
his passes for the second time this season and didn't play in the
Matadors' final offensive series. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS &QL; 
A rare fumble for Jaumal Bradley came on his last carry of the
game; it was recovered by a teammate. Bradley had 85 of the
Matadors' 89 yards. It was CSUN's second-lowest rushing total of
season. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
WIDE RECEIVERS &QL; 
Where there used to be sure hands, everyone in this unit is now
dropping passes, including Aaron Arnold. Arnold's drop of a long
pass in the end zone could have given CSUN a second-quarter lead.
Only two catches for Drew Amerson. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Awesome on the Matadors' first drive, which featured 31 rushing
yards and a 3-yard TD by Bradley. CSUN later abandoned the run when
it was trailing. Protected Brady well. &QL; 
B &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Only one sack for Big Sky's best sacking team, but PSU's Jimmy
Blanchard took a lot of three-step drops. Vikings had 148 yards on
ground, almost 30 yards less than their per-game average. &QL; 
B &QL; 
LINEBACKERS &QL; 
A combined 10 tackles from Cos Abercrombie and Jack Heaslet (five
each) simply isn't enough. CSUN's safeties still lead the team in
tackling every game, which means LBs aren't doing their job. &QL; 
C- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS &QL; 
These guys weren't burned by Jimmy Blanchard, one of the
conference's best QBs. But PSU receivers, most notably Terry
Charles, dropped several passes that could have gone for long
gains. &QL; 
B &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
A missed extra point, a muffed punt return, yet another bad snap on
a punt . . . the little things aren't getting done. Amerson is
becoming a threat on kickoff returns, though. He was the bright
spot. &QL; 
C- &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
There seems to be a lack of responsibility by the Matadors players
over their committing stupid penalties, and the coaches need to do
something to change that _ immediately. &QL; 
C- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
