u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      11-07 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING PARTY ASKS VOTERS TO CHOOSE PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's ruling party took its biggest step toward
democracy Sunday by asking millions of voters to choose its next
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's primary election for the Institutional Revolutionary
Party marked the first time in the 70 years it has governed Mexico
that the country's dominant political organization has not relied
on a system in which the sitting president picks the party's next
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained unclear whether the primary campaign, which
featured four party stalwarts who often engaged in bitter public
disputes, would leave the party divided and damage its chances in
next year's general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Although official results were not available from PRI officials,
former interior secretary Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who many say
is President Ernesto Zedillo's preferred candidate, was expected to
defeat his closest rival, former Tabasco state governor Roberto
Madrazo Pintado.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates, former Puebla governor Manuel Bartlett
Diaz and former party leader Humberto Roque Villanueva, were
expected to trail far behind the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cynicism among many voters that party leaders have been
working to ensure a Labastida victory, PRI officials said turnout
had been heavy across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, turnout varied by precinct, and there were
scattered reports of polling places that opened late because voting
materials were not delivered on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is proof that the PRI is willing to be more
democratic,'' said Candido Mayen Gonzalez, 66. ``It hasn't been
perfect, but at least they're trying to be more modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's election was open to all of Mexico's 55 million
registered voters, but PRI officials expected that only 6 million
would cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Because most people expect a Labastida victory, the most
pressing question now is whether Madrazo, 47, a self-described
alternative to the party's machine, would leave the party for
another to continue his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   During a gathering with reporters on Saturday, Labastida
predicted a 60 percent chance that Madrazo would split from the
PRI. Even if Madrazo left, Labastida added, the PRI would still be
able to win the general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo officials, however, insisted in a separate meeting
during the weekend that their candidate would not leave the PRI,
arguing that such a move would only benefit Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's decision to hold a primary election was driven largely
by its decision to make the world's longest-ruling political party
seem more democratic and open. Since its founding in 1929, the PRI
has never lost a presidential election, but most Mexicans suspect
the party has often relied on electoral fraud and voter
intimidation to ensure its victories.
</P>
<P>
   With more competition from opposition parties during the last
two years, however, the PRI has experimented with the primaries in
several gubernatorial races. Party leaders found that the process
gave its candidates better name recognition and created the feeling
among voters that the PRI had taken steps to reform itself.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the PRI's record of success with primaries will also
work for next July's presidential election remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's winner will face two formidable opposition candidates:
Francisco Fox Quesada, a former Coca-Cola executive and governor of
Guanajuato state who is the candidate of the conservative National
Action Party; and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the former mayor of Mexico
City, who is the candidate of a leftist coalition led by the Party
of the Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk lately of a possible alliance between the
two opposition parties to ensure a PRI defeat in July, but neither
Fox nor Cardenas seems willing to let the other become the main
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Eckstein, a sociologist and Mexico specialist at Boston
University, said the PRI primary raises the stakes for other
parties in Mexico to appear more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is genuinely opening up the system, then the PRI is
likely to get candidates who can get out the vote,'' Eckstein said.
``Not only does it make the PRI look like the bearer of democracy,
but it increases its chances of having a winning candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
