u a BC-OBIT-GOODHART-NYT &LR;      11-07 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOODHART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM GOODHART, 74, AUTHOR OF HIT PLAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (rk) 
    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Malcolm Goodhart, whose first effort at play writing
became a Broadway hit, died on Oct. 20 at his home on Shelter
Island, N.Y. He was 74. The cause was heart disease, his family
said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodhart achieved the dream of every aspiring playwright when
his comedy, ``Generation,'' opened on Broadway in 1965 and quickly
found an audience. The show, directed by Gene Saks, starred Henry
Fonda as a parent coping with his determinedly unconventional
daughter and son-in-law, who decide to deliver their own baby.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some lukewarm reviews, ``Generation'' settled in for a
long run and was adapted for the screen by Goodhart in 1969. In the
film, David Janssen played the role originated by Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New Haven, Conn., in 1925, Goodhart was a physics major
at Yale University before enlisting in the Army in 1943. After the
war he returned to Yale to study at the drama school and began his
career as a scenic artist and lighting designer. After the success
of ``Generation,'' Goodhart became a writer and producer for Warner
Brothers. His screen credits include ``The Heretic,'' which was a
sequel to ``The Exorcist,'' and ``Cloud Dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Joanne; three daughters, Eliza
Goodhart Denoeux, Amy Goodhart Redburn and Sarah Celeste Goodhart,
and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HIGGINS-NYT &LR;      11-07 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HIGGINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE V. HIGGINS, 59, AUTHOR OF CRIME NOVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.) (ms) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George V. Higgins, a crime novelist best known for his first
published work, the best seller ``Friends of Eddie Coyle,'' was
found dead Nov. 6 at his home in Milton, Mass. He was 59. He
apparently died of natural causes, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The writing skills that Higgins showed in ``Eddie Coyle'' (1972)
prompted an enthusiastic review by Christopher Lehmann-Haupt in The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``In deference to the oblique speaking styles of Eddie Coyle and
his friends, and because I find myself so utterly in thrall to the
mood of George V. Higgins' first novel, let me approach the book's
merits somewhat deviously,'' the review began.
</P>
<P>
   Lehmann-Haupt went on to applaud ``the deftness that is evident
everywhere in this ultrarealistic little slice of criminal life,
written by an assistant U.S. attorney for the district of
Massachusetts, and one of the best of its genre I have read since
Hemingway's `The Killers.'''
</P>
<P>
   The 183-page work, about a hoodlum who becomes an informer for
the police, has settings in Higgins' native Massachusetts and
includes a bank robbery and earthy dialogue that, Lehmann-Haupt
wrote, ``eats at one's nerve endings.'' The book's ironies,
including ``a world in which hoods and cops depend on one another
to eke out their mean livings,'' are ``corrosive enough,'' he
added, and ``the ending is as hard as a set of metal knuckles in
the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Paul Monash, the book became a 1973 movie that
starred Robert Mitchum as Eddie Coyle. Vincent Canby, writing in
The Times, called it ``a good, tough, unsentimental movie,'' and
praised Mitchum's performance in the title role as conveying ``wit
and a certain dignity'' on its less-than-tragic hero.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins' other novels include ``The Digger's Game,'' ``Cogan's
Trade'' and ``A City on a Hill.'' His last work was ``The Agent''
(1999), about an unpopular sports agent. He also wrote columns for
The Boston Herald American, The Boston Globe, and The Wall Street
Journal from 1977 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the mid-1980's Higgins said he had been
influenced by John O'Hara, particularly by his short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins was born in Brockton, Mass., and received a bachelor's
degree from Boston College in 1961 and a law degree from Boston
College in 1967. He was an assistant attorney general and then an
assistant U.S. attorney in Boston from 1969 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Elizabeth Mulkerin ended in divorce. He is
survived by his wife, Loretta, a daughter and a son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
