-- Ray Wylie Hubbard, right, and Jeff Plankenhorn, who accompanied
him on Dobro, absorb some applause during a house concert at the
home of Jimmy Riddle in Columbia. House concerts, as these events
are known, have recently blossomed into a full-fledged national
movement. From Seattle to Waco, Texas, to Queens, N.Y., more than
300 homeowners have become part-time concert promoters, turning
their homes into mild-mannered clubs for a night, and scores of
performers are discovering that they can make good livings simply
by touring these private residences. (Wade Spees/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HOLLWYWOOD -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- BRILLSTEIN-BIO, 11-7 --
Bernie Brillstein, 68, talent agent and now Hollywood manager,
helped oversee the careers of John Belushi, Gilda Radner, Jim
Henson, Dan Aykroyd, Lorne Michaels, Martin Short and numerous
others. In his 45 years as an agent and manager, stretching from
the era of Catskill comedy to ``Saturday Night Live,'' Brillstein
has never been accused of mincing words. His newly published
autobiography will do nothing to challenge his image. The book is
titled ``Where Did I Go Right?'' It is subtitled ``You're No One in
Hollywood Unless Someone Wants You Dead.'' (Edward Carreon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- Nov. 7, 1999 --
UNRESOLVED-RACEMURDERS, 11-7 -- U.S. Attorney Doug Jones, 45, a
Birmingham native, left, and Joseph Lewis, 47, head of the
Birmingham division of the FBI, have led efforts to bring to
justice those who bombed the 16th Street Baptist Church and killed
four black girls in 1963. Across the South, unresolved, racially
motivated killings of blacks from the civil rights era are under
new scrutiny, inspired by the well-publicized conviction in 1994 of
an aging white defendant in the 1963 assassination of the
Mississippi civil rights leader Medgar Evers. (Jeanne Dozier/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- ESPN-TIMESSQUARE, 11-7 --
Patrons of the ESPN Zone in Times Square have four stories of
studio sets and interactive games to wander through, as well as 220
televisions at which to watch sports events. There's also a menu.
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS, 11-7 --
Ray Wu, left, his wife, Mayjean, and their son Ryan shop at a
CompUSA store on Saturday. The Wus say their shares of Microsoft
have tripled in value in the four years since they bought them. As
the Justice Department and some in the technology industry
celebrated a federal judge's finding that Microsoft had hurt
consumers by abusing its Windows monopoly, many software users
around the country are now voicing some apprehension, even
downright distress, at the notion that Microsoft might be punished
for what Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson deemed its direct and
indirect harm to consumers. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WINNERS, 11-7 --
The top three winners from both the mens' and womens' divisions of
the 1999 New York City Marathon from left to right, Portugal's
Domingos Castro, second place in the mens' division, Kenya's
Catherine Ndereba, second in the womens' division, Joseph Cebet of
Kenya, the mens' winner, Adriana Fernandez of Mexico, the womens'
winner, Germany's Katrin Dorre-Heinig, third in the womens'
division, and Shem Kororia of Kenya, third in the mens' division.
(Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-START-3, 11-7 --
On a cool and windy day, thousands of runners from around the world
begin their quest for marathon glory by crossing the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge at the start of the 1999 New York City
Marathon. Joseph Chebet of Kenya used a powerful finishing kick
Sunday to outduel Portugal's Domingos Castro and win in 2 hours, 9
minutes, 14 seconds on a cool, windy day. Adriana Fernandez of
Mexico went on to win the women's division by nearly 2 minutes and
became the first Mexican woman to win an international marathon.
(Vincent Laforet/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-START-2, 11-7 --
In a kaleidoscope of colors, thousands of runners from around the
world begin their quest for marathon glory by crossing the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge at the start of the 1999 New York City
Marathon. Joseph Chebet of Kenya used a powerful finishing kick
Sunday to outduel Portugal's Domingos Castro and win in 2 hours, 9
minutes, 14 seconds on a cool, windy day. Adriana Fernandez of
Mexico went on to win the women's division by nearly 2 minutes and
became the first Mexican woman to win an international marathon.
(Vincent Laforet/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-START-1, 11-7 --
Thousands of runners from around the world begin their quest for
marathon glory by crossing the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge at the
start of the 1999 New York City Marathon. Ending the frustration of
two straight second-place finishes, Joseph Chebet of Kenya used a
powerful finishing kick Sunday to outduel Portugal's Domingos
Castro and win in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 14 seconds on a cool, windy
day. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WOMEN-3, 11-7 --
Adriana Fernandez of Mexico leading a pack of runners through the
streets of Brooklyn in the early stages of the 1999 New York City
Marathon. Fernandez went on to win the women's division by nearly 2
minutes and became the first Mexican woman to win an international
marathon. She was timed in 2:25:06, the second-fastest in the
race's history and only 26 seconds behind the record 2:24:40 by
Australia's Lisa Ondieki in 1992. (William Lopez/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WOMEN-2, 11-7 --
Adriana Fernandez of Mexico running through the streets of
Manhattan in the middle stages of the 1999 New York City Marathon.
Fernandez went on to win the women's division by nearly 2 minutes
and became the first Mexican woman to win an international
marathon. She was timed in 2:25:06, the second-fastest in the
race's history and only 26 seconds behind the record 2:24:40 by
Australia's Lisa Ondieki in 1992. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WOMEN-1, 11-7 --
Adriana Fernandez of Mexico, crosses the finish line of the 1999
New York City Marathon to win the women's division by nearly 2
minutes and became the first Mexican woman to win an international
marathon. She was timed in 2:25:06, the second-fastest in the
race's history and only 26 seconds behind the record 2:24:40 by
Australia's Lisa Ondieki in 1992. (Richard Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-5, 11-7 --
Nearing the final stretch of the 1999 New York City Marathon on the
outskirts of Central Park on Sunday, Joseph Chebet of Kenya, tailed
by Portugal's Domingos Castro, tries to keep his lead on a cool,
windy day. Ending the frustration of two straight second-place
finishes, Chebet used a powerful finishing kick to outduel Castro
and win in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 14 seconds. (Vincent Laforet/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-4, 11-7 --
Running with fresh legs on a cool, windy day, Joseph Chebet of
Kenya, between runners 60 and 40, and a pack of the men's premiere
marathon runners pace themselves at the very start of the 1999 New
York City Marathon on Sunday. Ending the frustration of two
straight second-place finishes, Joseph Chebet of Kenya, second from
rear left, used a powerful finishing kick Sunday to outduel
Portugal's Domingos Castro and win in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 14
seconds. (Vincent Laforet/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-3, 11-7 -- A
pack of the men's premiere marathon runners pace themselves on the
at the very start of the 1999 New York City Marathon on Sunday.
Ending the frustration of two straight second-place finishes,
Joseph Chebet of Kenya, second from rear left, used a powerful
finishing kick Sunday to outduel Portugal's Domingos Castro and win
in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 14 seconds on a cool, windy day. (Vincent
Laforet/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-2, 11-7 --
Joseph Chebet of Kenya crosses the finish line of the 1999 New York
City Marathon on Sunday to become the first marathoner to win in
Boston and New York in the same year since Alberto Salazar in 1982.
The only other runner to sweep those races in the same year was
Bill Rodgers in 1978 and 1979. Chebet used a powerful finishing
kick Sunday to outduel Portugal's Domingos Castro and win in 2
hours, 9 minutes, 14 seconds on a cool, windy day. (Richard Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-MEN-1, 11-7 -- A
pack of the men's premiere marathon runners pace themselves through
the streets of Brooklyn in the early stages of the 1999 New York
City Marathon on Sunday. Ending the frustration of two straight
second-place finishes, Joseph Chebet of Kenya, second from rear
left, used a powerful finishing kick Sunday to outduel Portugal's
Domingos Castro and win in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 14 seconds on a
cool, windy day. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
