<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 11/07/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WHEELCHAIRS-2,
11-7 -- Wheelchair competitors in the 1999 New York City Marathon
giving their all in a race in which for the first time none of them
were stopped along the course to let leading runners pass. Nine
wheelchair athletes, including two of the top three men's finishers
Sunday, filed suit against the New York Road Runners Club in July,
alleging that the marathon has discriminated against them not only
by delaying wheelchair racers to let top runners pass, but also by
denying them prize money and medals, which the elite runners
receive. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARA-WHEELCHAIRS-1,
11-7 -- For the second time in two years, Miguel Such was the first
to roll across the finish line in the New York City Marathon's
wheelchair event on Sunday, and he thrust his fists in the air and
savored victory. But for Such and several other wheelchair
athletes, who have sued the marathon's organizers for
discrimination, the real victory was that none of them were stopped
along the course to let leading runners pass. (Steve Berman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- NY-PRISON-CRACKDOWN-3, 11-7
-- An inmate at Rikers Island sits on a chair designed to scan
inmates and determine if they are hiding weapons in their clothes
or inside their bodies. Using an array of tools and tactics, from a
huge SWAT team to electric stun shields to a program that
aggressively prosecutes inmates for crimes committed inside the
jails, correction officials have cut slashings and stabbings among
inmates by over 90 percent. Stabbing assaults by inmates have
plummeted from nearly 1,100 in 1994 to 78 so far this year.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- NY-PRISON-CRACKDOWN-2, 11-7
-- A guard at Rikers Island searching a cell for drugs and weapons.
Using an array of tools and tactics, from a huge SWAT team to
electric stun shields to a program that aggressively prosecutes
inmates for crimes committed inside the jails, correction officials
have cut slashings and stabbings among inmates by over 90 percent.
Stabbing assaults by inmates have plummeted from nearly 1,100 in
1994 to 78 so far this year. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- NY-PRISON-CRACKDOWN-1, 11-7
-- New York City Department of Corrections Emergency Service Police
prepare for a weapons and contraband search operation at Rikers
Island. Using an array of tools and tactics, from a huge SWAT team
to electric stun shields to a program that aggressively prosecutes
inmates for crimes committed inside the jails, correction officials
have cut slashings and stabbings among inmates by over 90 percent.
Stabbing assaults by inmates have plummeted from nearly 1,100 in
1994 to 78 so far this year. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- PROFILE-LEW, 11-7 -- Jack
Lew, the White House budget director. At Lew's confirmation last
year, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, told him that his dominion over
trillions of dollars would make him ``the second most powerful
person in our whole government,'' a daunting thought, in part since
Lew does not appear to have aged much since college. The power is
real and Lew, knee-deep in politics since he was 12 years old,
wants to use it. ``The purpose of power is to get things done,''
says Lew. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- CONSULTANT-LEAVES, 11-7 --
Howard Anderson, 55, chairman of Yankee Group Research, practically
invented technology consulting. Now, almost three decades after
issuing his first research report, ``The Unbundling of AT&AMP;T,'' in
1971, Anderson says he is stepping down from his day-to-day
responsibilities at Yankee, based in Boston, to start a new venture
capital operation. (Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- SELENA-AUDITION-2, 11-7 --
Ireida Santiago Quiroz, 12, a candidate for the role of Selena as a
youngster in the upcoming musical ``Selena Forever.'' In a studio
in the theater district this past weekend, close to 200 girls and
young women from around the country auditioned for ``Selena
Forever.'' For most if not all of those auditioning, this was no
ordinary open casting call, for the role being cast was that of
Selena, the Tejano singing star whose murder in 1995 at 23
horrified millions of fans, particularly the young Hispanic women
who saw themselves in her. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- SELENA-AUDITION-1, 11-7 --
In a studio in the theater district this past weekend, close to 200
girls and young women from around the country auditioned for a new
musical ``Selena Forever.'' For most if not all of those
auditioning, this was no ordinary open casting call, for the role
being cast was that of Selena, the Tejano singing star whose murder
in 1995 at 23 horrified millions of fans, particularly the young
Hispanic women who saw themselves in her. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) COUMBIA, S.C. -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- HOUSE-MUSICIANS, 11-7
-- Ray Wylie Hubbard, right, and Jeff Plankenhorn, who accompanied
him on Dobro, absorb some applause during a house concert at the
home of Jimmy Riddle in Columbia. House concerts, as these events
are known, have recently blossomed into a full-fledged national
movement. From Seattle to Waco, Texas, to Queens, N.Y., more than
300 homeowners have become part-time concert promoters, turning
their homes into mild-mannered clubs for a night, and scores of
performers are discovering that they can make good livings simply
by touring these private residences. (Wade Spees/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HOLLWYWOOD -- Nov. 7, 1999 -- BRILLSTEIN-BIO, 11-7 --
Bernie Brillstein, 68, talent agent and now Hollywood manager,
helped oversee the careers of John Belushi, Gilda Radner, Jim
Henson, Dan Aykroyd, Lorne Michaels, Martin Short and numerous
others. In his 45 years as an agent and manager, stretching from
the era of Catskill comedy to ``Saturday Night Live,'' Brillstein
has never been accused of mincing words. His newly published
autobiography will do nothing to challenge his image. The book is
titled ``Where Did I Go Right?'' It is subtitled ``You're No One in
Hollywood Unless Someone Wants You Dead.'' (Edward Carreon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
