<HEADLINE>
JACKSON'S COMPLAINTS PROBABLY WON'T HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's hardly a new complaint: Teams pound on
Shaquille O'Neal like it's free time on the pinata.
</P>
<P>
   Del Harris moaned about it. Kurt Rambis complained of it. And
now it's Phil Jackson's turn to try to do something about what has
frustrated other O'Neal coaches to no end.
</P>
<P>
   And best of luck.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal was ejected for a pair of technicals after he lost
his temper when repeatedly fouled hard Saturday night in Portland,
Jackson said: ``I was really disappointed with the refereeing. I
thought it was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   That could bring him a $5,000 fine from the NBA, the league
typically frowning on its coaches ripping the officials. But is
there anything Jackson really thinks can be done to end the
hack-a-Shaq routine favored by so many teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's very simple,'' he said. ``The referees have to
determine whether it's a foul on the ball or the guy is going to
block the shot, or it's a foul just to take him out and prevent him
from scoring. That's a flagrant foul according to the books. I
think focus will come to play on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is treated with the kind of respect other O'Neal coaches
might not have always enjoyed, but referees have never shown an
inclination to protect a guy 7-foot-1 and 330 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Teams figure they can't stop him inside, so they quickly foul
him hard before he can begin his shot. It doesn't help O'Neal's
cause that he's such a weak threat at the free-throw line (10 of 28
entering Sunday's game).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal would not comment after being ejected Saturday night in
Portland, and again refused to talk to the media before Sunday's
game with the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson repeated Sunday that O'Neal had let the team down by
losing his cool and getting ejected, but his public attack of the
officials was old-school coaches' defense of standing by your
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me (it is),'' Jackson said. ``I don't know if any other
coach will do it. It's part of the role of who I am and what I
believe in as far as the players that I coach. They need to know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: The Lakers' one weakness is generally considered to be
at power forward, but Dallas forward and former Laker Cedric
Ceballos figures with A.C. Green the Lakers should be fine: ``You
don't need a big-time four with a guy like (O'Neal). All they need
A.C. to do is rebound and play defense, and that's what he does
best.'' . . . With Derek Fisher in a shooting slump, 5-11 Tyronn
Lue is getting some unexpected playing time at the point. Said Lue:
``I'm more confident because he's giving me opportunity to play.
I'm just trying to build from here and try to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
