<HEADLINE>
VAN NUYS AIRPORT GIVES HOLLYWOOD CONVENIENCE, PRIVACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES -- Whenever Vanna White needs to get out of town
fast, the ``Wheel of Fortune'' letter- and head-turner hops aboard
one of two Learjets she owns at Van Nuys Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The same with actors Dennis Quaid, John Travolta, and Tom Cruise
and Nicole Kidman, who keep jets at Van Nuys Airport. And Robert
Redford, Charlton Heston, Kevin Costner and basketball bad-boy
Dennis Rodman regularly charter flights out of Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   They all have made Van Nuys Airport a veritable Airport of the
Stars, the air hub of choice in Los Angeles because of convenience
and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just show up, get on the plane and take off,'' said White,
whose husband is a pilot. ``There's no waiting on private jets _
and absolutely no luggage problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though a private flight can cost $1,200 to $4,000 an hour,
pilots and charter-plane owners said they have no problem filling
seats with the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed, convenience and privacy'' said Learjet pilot Max
Falahati, who flies top Hollywood talent, high rollers and athletes
with his company Millennium Jets. ``You go on your own timetable.
There are no delays and no cancellations. Also, we can get to
airports that the airlines can't go to.''
</P>
<P>
   The roster of celebrities who use Van Nuys is closely guarded,
but on occasion, a mishap sometimes leads to their disclosure. For
instance, Harrison Ford recently crash-landed a helicopter near
Lake Piru after flying out of Van Nuys. He and a flight instructor
walked away unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   And in February, director Barry Sonnenfeld, whose credits
include ``Wild, Wild West,'' ``The Addams Family'' and ``Men in
Black'' was aboard a Gulfstream II that skidded across a Van Nuys
runway in a hard landing, hitting four parked planes. No one was
hut.
</P>
<P>
   Some said it is unfair that a privileged few get to travel in
such luxury and help make Van Nuys the busiest general aviation
airport in the nation. They bridle at the noise from the roughly
110 private jets and 500 other propeller planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save a little bit of inconvenience on their part, these
people distress tens of thousands of Valley residents,'' said
Gerald Silver, president of Homeowners of Encino and its Stop the
Noise! campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exclusive airport that serves only a handful of
wealthy business executives, rock stars and entertainers who don't
want to be troubled by taking the inconvenience of first-class
travel out of LAX,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White said her planes seek to abide by the voluntary flight
curfew of 10:45 p.m. to 6:45 a.m. and that she and other
celebrities still take commercial flights out of Los Angeles
International Airport for business.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts such as soundproofing homes are under way to trim the
noise but many homeowners said it is not enough and are calling for
a strict phaseout of these jets.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that Hollywood has used Van Nuys since 1929, a
year after the then-named Metropolitan Airport opened. Howard
Hughes, Cecil B. DeMille and Gene Autry were among the stars who
first started flying at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
   In the '30s, Hollywood producers started using the airport for
film locations. Scenes from ``Casablanca'' were shot there and the
airport remains a prime locale for feature films, TV shows, music
videos and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Recent movies shot in part at Van Nuys Airport include
flight-themed ``Con Air'' and ``Air Force One.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get things done on the tarmac and other areas that
could not be done at other airports,'' said Mike Bobenko of the
Entertainment Industry Development Corp., which coordinates filming
locations for Los Angeles city and county.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Pictures and its parent company Viacom are among the
studios that have jets at the airport. The studio's two Gulfstreams
are primarily used for executive travel but have also shuttled
actors to New York for the publicity appearances on David
Letterman's show, or to Los Angeles to be interviewed by Jay Leno,
said David Zagnoli of the corporate aviation department.
</P>
<P>
   White's jets rarely sit idle, as she leases them to celebrity
friends _ household names that she and charter services keep secret
out of privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make reservations far enough in advance I can probably
get it,'' said White, now in her 17th year as co-host of the
popular game show. ``We thought we'd get a second one so we can use
it, but it's always busy flying other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Such convenience is also prized by several corporations that use
the airport, including MGM Grand, Litton Industries, Guess? Inc.,
Hughes Electronics, Anheuser Busch and Dole Foods.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious crash of champion golfer Payne Stewart's Learjet
35 in South Dakota recently has not slaked celebrities' thirst for
a quick escape from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those planes have a great reputation, and I know from paying
the maintenance bill that they're in great shape,'' said White,
whose two Learjet 35s are based at charter provider Clay Lacy
Aviation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
