<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2268 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-BOEING-TAIL-SPI &LR;      11-07 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-TAIL-SPI </SLUG>
  
 MANY BOEING 767s MAY HAVE IMPROPERLY TORQUED TAIL BOLTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Hundreds of Boeing 767 airplanes like the one
that crashed off the Massachusetts coast Oct. 31, killing all 217
people aboard, could be flying with improperly torqued bolts that
hold the vertical tail to the fuselage, the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer has learned.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear if the suspect bolts could be in planes
built as far back as 1989, the year the 767-300 that crashed was
delivered to EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says the bolts aren't likely to pose a safety threat to
airplanes because of the big jet's structure. But the company says
it is considering issuing a service bulletin warning operators of
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing late last month grounded its first 767-400, a plane still
in flight testing, until the tail bolts were replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other planes that were either in final assembly or on the
Everett, Wash., flight line _ five 767-300s and two 767-400s headed
for flight test _ have since had their tail bolts removed and
replaced, a Boeing spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some tail bolts in those eight planes were found to have been
undertorqued.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing spokesman said the company is attempting to determine
the extent of the problem and how long ago it began. ``Because of
redundancy in the structure of the tail fin, we don't believe this
is a safety-of-flight issue,'' said Doug Webb, Boeing's chief
spokesman at the Everett plant where the 767 is built.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the issue said Boeing machinists have
unknowingly used a faulty calibration process to torque 767 tail
bolts since at least 1992, and perhaps longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Friday sent two
inspectors to the Everett plant to audit Boeing's tool calibration
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are performing on-going audits of calibration of tooling
and how it is monitored by Boeing,'' said Vi Lipski, deputy
airplane transport directorate manager in the FAA's Renton office.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 800 of the 767 widebody jets have been built since the
first one entered service with United Airlines in 1982. Today, the
twin-engine 767 is the dominant plane on trans-Atlantic routes
between Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It has a good safety record.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a hijacking that ended in an ocean ditching when the
plane ran out of fuel, only two 767s have been involved in fatal
crashes, including EgyptAir Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators don't know the cause of the latest crash. In 1991,
a Lauda Air 767-300 crashed in a Thailand jungle when an engine
thrust reverser deployed in flight. All 223 people aboard were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Once Boeing has a better understanding of the torque problem, it
is likely to issue a service bulletin to 767 operators,
recommending that the tail bolts be checked and replaced if
necessary. A service bulletin could trigger an airworthiness
directive from the FAA that would make any Boeing recommendation
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as FAA awareness, I would be looking to Boeing to
present us information as to how prevalent this is with planes in
service,'' Lipski said. ``I don't know ...''
</P>
<P>
   Lipski said she could not say, without knowing specific details,
if improperly torqued 767 tail bolts pose a safety concern for the
flying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may have safety implications. But we would have to look
at the conditions ... if there are other redundancies. ... I can't
say what this event would cause. We would have to assess more
information about the design and integrity of the vertical fin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen bolts, each about 4 inches long and 3/4 inch in
diameter, hold the massive tail fin, also called the vertical
stabilizer, to the 767 fuselage. The tail fin is attached to the
fuselage during final body join on the production line. Each of
those bolts must be tightened, or torqued, in foot pounds (the
amount of energy required to lift one pound a distance of one
foot), to engineering specifications. A special set of calibrated
tools is required.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing only recently became aware that 767 tail bolts were being
incorrectly torqued by Everett machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Webb said a 767-300 operator notified Boeing on Sept. 30 that
mechanics had found two undertorqued tail bolts on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   He would not identify the operator.
</P>
<P>
   A source said the operator was American Airlines, and the
undertorqued bolts were discovered by the airline's mechanics
during what is known as a C-check. This is the first major overhaul
a commercial jetliner undergoes after a certain amount of time in
service.
</P>
<P>
   The source said mechanics found the tail bolts were so loose
that they were ``banging around.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was the 700th to roll down the Everett 767 production
line, and was delivered in April 1998. Some 70 more 767s have been
built since that one.
</P>
<P>
   Only the one 767 carrier has reported finding incorrectly
torqued tail bolts, Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   Those 16 tail bolts on the 767 are covered with a seal to
protect them from corrosion. The seal must be scraped away before
they can be checked.
</P>
<P>
   Once Boeing was made aware of the problem, Webb said, the
company launched an investigation to find the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the tools used in the bolt installation could
produce an undertorqued condition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA was notified Oct. 26, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two different tools are used in combination to bolt the tail to
the 767 fuselage at the final body joint station where the work is
performed. Only one set of tools is used by machinists on all
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   One tool is called a nut runner. It is an air-driven torque
wrench that essentially works like the pneumatic lug wrench used by
pit crews to quickly remove and replace tires on a race car.
</P>
<P>
   The other tool is known as a torque multiplier. This device
helps machinists apply the hundreds of foot pounds of torque
required to tighten the bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing said the nut runner was properly calibrated, the
FAA's Lipski said the nut runner and torque multiplier should have
been calibrated together, but were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When used together, the spinning ratios were not accurate,''
Lipski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When independently calibrated, they could result in an
out-of-torque condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipski said it is up to Boeing and not the FAA to make sure
calibration processes, as well as the internal monitoring of those
processes, is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no FAA requirement,'' she said. ``Boeing has a system
in place to monitor this. I would default to Boeing's system and
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Heathers, a 767 spokeswoman, said the nut runner was last
verified to have the proper calibration in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Webb said Boeing does not know how long the two tools have been
used in combination without joint calibration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reviewing all the processes to find out when this
started,'' he said. ``We have been told a number of different
dates.''
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the issue told the Post-Intelligencer the
two tools should never have used in combination without checking
with engineering, and is the result of Boeing having too many
inexperienced people on the 767 line in 1989. Many of the most
senior machinists had been transferred to the 747-400 line because
of production problems with the company's newest version of its
jumbo jet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sucking away the best people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year the EgyptAir 767-300 was built. It was the
283rd plane to roll down the 767 line, though no connection between
the crash Oct. 31 and the bolt problem has been made. The Lauda Air
jet that later crashed was right behind it, plane No. 282. That
crash was blamed on an accidental deployment of a thrust reverser.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one on the 767 line ever went to the tooling engineers to
check if this procedure (for using the two tools in combination
during tail join) was okay,'' the source said. ``They just started
doing it. The machinists say they have been doing this for at least
seven years, but people on the factory floor know it was done the
same way before that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
