<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CLICKS-ONLINE_SFCHRON     11-07 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLICKS-ONLINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   By Tom Stein &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
There's a new twist in the evolution of e-commerce: A handful of
online companies are starting to move offline. They are opening up
physical stores and showrooms as a way to better connect with
consumers, bolster credibility and ultimately drive more traffic
back to their Web sites.
<P>
   Call it the first batch of clicks-to-bricks companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a logical next step for Internet merchants. After all, the
Internet is merely one channel for reaching customers. Analysts
believe online companies must learn to attract consumers everywhere
they live and work, and that includes the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flagship stores are necessary to target mass consumers,'' said
Internet analyst Mike May of Jupiter Communications in New York.
``Their function is not so much to sell products, but to acquaint
and educate consumers about their online counterparts and
legitimize the brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   An upscale online auctioneer called GMBid.com, for one,
simultaneously unveiled its Web site in August along with a
10,000-square-foot showroom just off Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills,
where potential bidders can personally inspect such auction items
as classic Ferraris, Chagall paintings and Cartier watches. Then
they can use Internet terminals in the showroom to place their bids
in cyberspace _ or wait until they get back to their home or
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critically important in terms of building trust to have a
physical location where people can find you and feel the
excitement,'' said Julie Carson, president of GMBid.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to build similar showrooms in other major
metropolitan areas like London, New York and Chicago. The showrooms
will all contain Web kiosks for bidding. The GMBid.com site also
will feature live Web cams so bidders around the world can view
items in the showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Clicks-to-bricks firms are another twist on the so-called
click-and-mortar operations, in which traditional brick-and-mortar
companies like Barnes &AMP; Noble and Toys R Us jumped into the
Internet, combining their physical operations with cyberspace
``clicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pundits readily agree that traditional offline companies
that do not adopt an online strategy will get annihilated in the
new economy. But now they are starting to ponder whether the
reverse is true as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can an e-business be solely an e-business, or will it have to
morph into a clicks-and-mortar play?'' asked Christopher Lochhead,
chief marketing officer at Internet consulting firm Scient Corp. in
San Francisco. ``That question is still up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Gazoontite.com, 800.com, GMBid.com and
Drugstore.com are not taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   Gazoontite.com, which sells such products as air purifiers,
anti-dust-mite bedding and aromatherapy candles, came online this
summer with a Web site as well as a 1,500-square-foot flagship
store in San Francisco's Union Square. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Soon Yu, chief executive of Gazoontite, said it cost about
$200,000 to open his San Francisco store, but he feels that's a
small price to pay in terms of acquiring customers and then leading
them to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   He may have a point. Today, Internet companies are pouring
millions of dollars into TV and print ads in order to raise brand
awareness. Ad spending by Net companies for this year is expected
to top $1 billion. Amazon.com alone has said it will spend $100
million on marketing for this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a per-dollar basis, we are getting a bigger bang for our
buck,'' Yu said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gazoontite.com store, which attracts thousands of tourists
and passers-by each day, boasts Internet shopping kiosks as well as
plenty of signs and logos highlighting its dot-com heritage. ```We
are making the stores very integrated with the Web environment,''
said Yu. ``We are first and foremost a dot-com company.''
</P>
<P>
   Building a strong brand name and consumer trust is vital to any
Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what Yu was thinking about when he originally
dreamed up his company. At first, Gazoontite was going to exist
solely in cyberspace. After all, he reasoned, it's a lot easier _
and cheaper _ to get a virtual business up and running.
</P>
<P>
   But Yu quickly realized his business plan had some major holes.
After conducting some basic market research, he saw that consumers
would be reluctant to buy his offbeat breathing and lifestyle
products without first being able to see, smell and touch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because our products are unfamiliar, people need to experience
them for themselves,'' explained Yu. ``In a Web-only environment,
our products appeared less credible and consumers were less likely
to buy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Investing hundreds of thousands of dollars in physical stores
and showrooms doesn't appeal to all Web-based businesses. But that
just may be the price some companies must pay to attract mainstream
customers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Consumer e-commerce is expected to hit about $30 billion this
year. That may seem like a large number, but it represents only
about 2 or 3 percent of the traditional retail market. Or look at
this way: Last year Barnes &AMP; Noble did $3 billion in sales,
compared with only $610 million for Amazon. To make more money and
compete effectively, Internet companies must broaden their
strategies and learn to play in the world of ``stores with doors.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Online-Offline Team
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com is taking that advice to heart and is teaming up
with Rite Aid, one of the nation's biggest brick-and-mortar
drugstore chains to expand its market.
</P>
<P>
   Through this partnership, Drugstore.com gains an instant offline
presence. Customers can order their drugs online and then pick them
up at their local Rite Aid store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's naive to think you can attract customers with just a
pretty Web site,'' said Drugstore.com chief executive Peter
Neupert.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership with Rite Aid was a matter of survival for
Drugstore.com. That's because it found that many people did not
like the idea of ordering their medications online and then having
to wait several days before they arrived. Also, the company had
trouble establishing relationships with large health insurance
providers, and thus had to turn some customers away because it
could not accept their insurance cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like the convenience of ordering online and then
getting it delivered to their home,'' said Neupert. ``But it's
important to offer multiple channels because there are some items
that people need right away. The Rite Aid partnership fills a real
need in terms of allowing us to move more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Rite Aid partnership goes a long way toward
boosting his company's brand awareness among consumers. Rite Aid,
for instance, has agreed to place the Drugstore.com logo on its
shopping bags, receipts and prescription labels.
</P>
<P>
   Not every Internet company is convinced it needs a
clicks-to-bricks strategy. Amazon.com, arguably the biggest and
most recognizable e-business in the world, said it is not about to
open up retail stores in the physical world anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't found a great reason to go offline,'' said Amazon
spokeswoman Lizzie Allen. ``We can't think of a single way that
opening up a retail store would improve the customer experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of clicks-to-bricks operations point to the
convenience of being able to place a book order online from the
office and then pick it up on the way home at the Amazon
Superstore, thus eliminating the wait as well as those pesky
delivery charges.
</P>
<P>
   To be offline, or not to be? That is the question facing
Portland's 800.com, which sells consumer electronic products such
as TVs, stereos, and DVD players on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done lots of focus groups and concluded that consumers
don't enjoy going to electronics stores,'' said 800.com chief
executive Greg Drew. ``They are actively looking for an
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the company is taking its first baby steps into
the physical world. It recently opened a small retail outlet at its
corporate headquarters in Portland, Ore. On display are hundreds of
products that consumers can test for themselves. There are also Web
terminals where shoppers can select from 800.com's stock of more
than 250,000 products.
</P>
<P>
   But, oddly enough, Drew doesn't want news of his offline plans
leaking out. ``Just forget we have a physical store,'' he pleads.
``It's not really a part of our overall strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
