<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2270 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAUSD-CORTINES-LADN     11-07 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-CORTINES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORTINES READY FOR JOB TURNING AROUND LAUSD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES -- At dawn this morning, when Ramon C. Cortines
plans to walk into the Los Angeles Unified headquarters, he will
usher in a new era for the nation's second-largest school district,
where a culture of incompetence and denial will no longer be
tolerated or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric and the posturing are over, says Cortines _ an
intense, confident, energetic 67-year-old who has closely watched
leaders of the $7.4 billion public school system stumble for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The former Pasadena, New York City, and San Francisco school
chief pledges to focus on the basics _ putting ``the right'' books
in hands of every student, cleaning up sullied and vandalized
bathrooms and building schools in innovative ways.
</P>
<P>
   During a weekend interview, Cortines _ who will formally take
over as interim superintendent when Ruben Zacarias retires Jan. 15
_ said he will ask everyone to get on board and seek out advice
from local elected officials and community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And the message for those who can't or won't go along with his
can-do attitude is clear: get out of the way. &QL; 
``I will get in at 6 a.m., and when it gets rough, I'm sure I will
get up a little earlier,'' Cortines said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be looking for good people. The system needs to
look at the young people and the people that are mid-career. We
should use all of the talent that is here and send a message that
there is not a pecking order anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer who you know. It is about capacity, ability
and talent.''
</P>
<P>
   With many high-level administrators up for retirement or
weighing their future, Cortines said will not ``put a guilt trip on
anyone or hold anyone hostage to their job.'' He promises to listen
to everyone, but ``people should do what is best for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they do what is best for them, they tend to do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines called off a trip to New York that he had scheduled for
this week after being tapped by the school board on Thursday to
advise Zacarias until his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Until Zacarias' exit, he will be formally in charge of all the
district's departments, with Cortines serving as his ``adviser''
and Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller managing the district
facilities and business divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Come Jan. 16, one man is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a collaborator. I try to get everybody involved,''
Cortines said. ``We need to debate and discuss, but when it comes
to the end of the day, while everyone can make recommendations,
someone is going to say: `Cortines, what do you think?' I'm going
to give an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasting no time, Cortines already has drawn up a lengthy
schedule for what he calls ``Week One.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to sit down today with Zacarias and Deputy
Superintendent of Instruction Lilliam Castillo and talk about new
directions for educational programs. And he will huddle with
teachers union president Day Higuchi, local and state politicians
and high-ranking LAUSD administrators before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is penned in for 8:30 a.m. today so he and Cortines can
continue talking about the district's facility and school
construction needs. The two began talking about the district's
overcrowded classrooms last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I both agreed that there is no way to build all the
schools that we need to build in the next 10 years. I suggested
that he come up with a plan for some different ways to use
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   The innovative steps may include purchasing and converting
commercial space into classrooms, renovating warehouses, and using
campuses for different grade levels. All of the strategies were
employed by Cortines during his stint as chancellor of New York
City's public schools in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some of our high schools to be much smaller so we
don't lose kids though the cracks, can better deal with attendance
and drop-out rates, and develop a more personal kind of
relationship between staff, students and their families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines and Miller are investigating the feasibility of
converting several large middle schools into high schools, and
using large elementary schools as middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would allow the district to use nearly $1 billion it
hopes to receive in state funds to build a variety of smaller
campuses and convert existing structures rather than build scores
of giant high schools that hold up to 5,000 students each.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not enough land available, and we want to avoid the
dislocation of residents and others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines plans to set up a variety of task forces to examine and
implement changes. Each will include parents, teachers,
administrators and experts in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at how do we raise the standard. We need to
take existing programs that are very good and that are working, and
say this needs to be the standard across the board. These changes
need to be about the people in the classroom and the people at this
district. This needs to make a statement about what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, Cortines will make unannounced visits to three
to four schools every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to see it and I have to hear it and I have to
internalize what is going on so that I can make the best
recommendations for policy changes to the board or make the best
changes from a management standpoint on behalf of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Cortines plans to meet with Mayor Richard Riordan,
who helped elect a reform-minded majority to the school board
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The role in school reform played by the mayor and his supporters
in the business community has become an issue in the Latino
community.
</P>
<P>
   But Cortines, who has faced many fierce political fights in his
43-year career, feels he can have a good working relationship with
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the mayor should take a more active role. He's done
an outstanding job in creating a renaissance in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines also said he believes he can develop a good
relationship with key Latino leaders, especially state Sen. Richard
Polanco, D-Los Angeles, a powerful force who has thrown his support
behind breaking up the district if he's not satisfied with the
direction LAUSD takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to know who I am. And I need to know who they are,''
Cortines said. ``They need to know from me that I need their help
in improving their school system. I plan to keep them informed, so
they can ask questions and offer constructive criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines also plans to wade into the issue of the
environmentally troubled Belmont Learning Center _ the nation's
costliest high school, a $282 million project if completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of Belmont seems to be way out of line, not that you
can do anything about it now. But I need to understand why it
happened, so we can avoid something similar as we move ahead to
build other schools and procure property.''
</P>
<P>
   With an expanding list of environmental crises, including the
discovery of asbestos problems at several schools, Cortines said he
plans to hold all employees accountable if they fail to protect the
safety of children and staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are internal people within both our maintenance and
safety branches that don't talk to each other. That's not going to
be tolerated. If it's a safety or a health issue, somebody needs to
get everyone at the table and knock heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to allow anyone to play Pontius Pilate and stand
in the corner and wash their hands. If they touched it, they have
responsibility. You can't say I don't make decisions. If you don't
make decisions, you are going to be part of the budget cuts.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
