<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LAD     11-07 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BONE COLLECTOR' STEALS TOP SPOT AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suspense-seeking moviegoers mobbed multiplexes as ``The Bone
Collector'' dominated the nation's box office with an estimated
$17.2 million at 2,589 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period,
studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collector,'' starring Denzel Washington as a paraplegic
detective tracking a serial killer, performed in line with
expectations and reflected the powerful recent market for thrillers
such as ``The Sixth Sense,'' ``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``The
Haunting,'' ``Stigmata'' and ``The House on Haunted Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right genre at the right time,'' noted veteran
industry tracker Arthur Rockwell. ``It's certainly not losing any
steam.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal mounted an extensive marketing campaign that paid off
by attracting 49 percent males and 51 percent females along with an
even split of customers under and over 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely pleased because it plays very well to all
audiences,'' said distribution chief Nikki Rocco.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences were attracted equally by the suspense genre and by
Washington, Rocco said. Reviews were mixed for ``Collector,'' which
also stars Angelina Jolie and was originally slotted for early
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bone Collector'' kept business healthy during an otherwise
moderate weekend, with total receipts at about $78 million _ up 15
percent from the previous weekend, when Halloween held down
moviegoing, but down 38 percent from the same weekend last year
when ``The Waterboy'' opened with a stunning $39.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of ``The Bachelor,'' an update of the 1925 Buster
Keaton film ``Seven Chances,'' led the rest of the pack with $8
million at 2,522 theaters as its promotional campaign _
highlighting a scene where hundreds of women in wedding gowns are
chasing star Chris O'Donnell for a chance to inherit $120 million _
helped overcome mostly negative reviews. ``The marketing of `The
Bachelor' was one of the best this year,'' said Robert Bucksbaum,
president of the Reel Source tracking service. ``Middle America
wanted to see this film.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a close third was Warner Bros.' second weekend of
``The House on Haunted Hill'' with $7.8 million at 2,710 theaters
as last weekend's winner lost slightly more than half its audience
_ not surprising in light of the heavy tie-ins with Halloween and
this weekend's competition from ``The Bone Collector.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's opening of ``The Insider,'' a recap of efforts by a
``60 Minutes'' producer and a tobacco industry executive to expose
the industry's inner workings, came in fourth with a lukewarm $7
million at 1,809 theaters despite strong reviews and the marquee
power of star Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution chief Chuck Viane said results were in line with
studio expectations, adding that the combination of strong viewer
recommendations and possible Academy Award nominations could turn
``The Insider'' into a solid long-term performer such as ``Scent of
a Woman'' and ``L.A. Confidential.'' ``It may take a long time for
`The Insider' to reach its potential,'' he added. Bucksbaum said
``The Insider'' may be one of the few fall films that will remain
in multiplexes as major holiday season releases _ ``Toy Story 2,''
``The World Is Not Enough,'' ``Sleepy Hollow,'' ``End of Days'' _
begin to dominate later this month. ``Most of the fall films will
disappear very quickly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Rockwell said he was skeptical about prospects for ``The
Insider,'' adding, ``People may be tired of hearing about this
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdover films took the six remaining Top 10 slots with each
posting solid business compared with Halloween weekend, which was
one of the slowest of the year. Paramount's seventh weekend of
``Double Jeopardy'' led the rest of the pack in fifth with $4.5
million at 2,722 theaters as the Ashley Judd vehicle reached $104.5
million and became the 15th movie this year and 198th of all time
to top $100 million in domestic grosses.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's third weekend of ``The Best Man'' continued its
solid performance in sixth with $4.3 million at 1,285 sites,
followed by DreamWorks' eighth weekend of ``American Beauty'' with
$3.3 million at 1,553 theaters and Disney's 14th weekend of ``The
Sixth Sense'' with $3.2 million at 1,802 sites. ``Sense,'' which
has topped $264 million, matched last weekend's total even though
it was playing in 249 fewer theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Miramax's second weekend of ``Music
of the Heart'' with $3 million at 1,353 theaters and 20th Century
Fox's fourth weekend of ``Fight Club'' with $2.5 million at 1,607
sites. Battling for 11th with $2 million each were Paramount's
fifth weekend of ``Superstar'' and its third weekend of ``Bringing
Out the Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal's fourth weekend of ``The Story of Us'' continued to
disappoint with $1.9 million at 2,010 theaters, giving the Bruce
Willis-Michelle Pfeiffer vehicle $25.3 million overall or less than
a tenth of what Willis' previous film, ``The Sixth Sense,'' took
in. USA's art-house hit ``Being John Malkovich'' came in 14th with
an impressive $1.85 million at 175 theaters in its second weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bone Collector'' should hold up fairly well against a
quintet of new films this weekend, Bucksbaum said, adding, ``Fall
audiences love thrillers.'' Warner will open ``Pokemon: the First
Movie'' and Fox will debut action-drama ``Light It Up'' on
Wednesday; Sony's epic ``The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc,''
Fox's drama ``Anywhere But Here'' and Lion's Gate comedy ``Dogma''
open Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business crossed the $6.1 billion mark, about 8
percent ahead of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
