<SLUG> BC-WHITE-3S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 B3   scream,c C-O-R-R-E-C-T-I-O-N-S 
BUSINESS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pub Date11/8/99Page:B1 &QL; 
 &LR; see  &LR; _  &LR; VIRTUAL INK: &LR;   &LR; Page B3 Col. 1
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; h,6,36,m  &LR; The Office Whiteboard, Staple of Business Meetings,
Enters the Internet Age
</P>
<P>
   &LR; frm VIRTUAL INK &QL;  &LR; _VIRTUAL INK &QL; 
 &LR; From Page B1  &LR; From Page B1
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; pquote,1  &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; The products work with almost all of the conventional whiteboards
already in use.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
redit,2  &UR; Photos by Deanne Fitzmaurice &LR; /The Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sc,2  &LR; Rafi Holtzman, director of product design for Electronics
for Imaging, used the whiteboard to produce images on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
sc,6p  &LR; An ordinary whiteboard marker fits in a specific pen case to
draw diagrams which also appear on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; h,14p10,36,m  &LR; Boardroom &QL; 
Whiteboard &QL; 
Comes of Age
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ,14p10  &LR; By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  wrapper reset,12p2,2.8i  &LR; The whiteboard, staple of so many
meetings in organizations large and small, is entering the Internet
age.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink, a Cambridge, Mass., startup, last month began
shipping a $499 product, called Mimio, that transmits anything
written on a standard whiteboard to the screen of a nearby PC and
from there over the Internet to the screens of other users anywhere
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Electronics for Imaging of Foster City will announce its
similarly priced entry, called eBeam.
</P>
<P>
   Specialized whiteboards capable of saving scribbled meeting
notes and drawings in digital form have been available for years.
But except for some very small models, they cost well over $1,000
and are small and heavy, compared to their conventional cousins.
Most also require special proce- &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
c,12p2  &LR; dures that cramp some presenters' style, such as requiring
the user to push a button to change colors.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of the two new products is that they work with almost
all of the 40 million to 80 million conventional whiteboards
already in use around the world _ even with ordinary dry-ink
markers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  ``As much as you can call any product a breakthrough, this is
one,'' said Martin Reynolds, vice president of Dataquest, a San
Jose market research company, who so far seen only the eBeam. ``A
lot of good work gets done on whiteboards, and this finally makes
it easy to save and share it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Virtual Ink's hardware consists of a 24-inch-long ``capture bar''
that attaches to the top of any whiteboard up to 4 feet by 8 feet
in size. EFI's eBeam provides two small pods that go in the corners
of a board up to the same dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies also provide plastic sleeves that fit around
conventional marking pens. They use a combination of infrared and
ultrasound signals, sent from the pen sleeves to the capture bar or
pods, to track the pens' location as the user writes or draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found particularly impressive (about the eBeam) was the
astounding accuracy,'' Reynolds said. ``You can write across the
board, then go back to dot your i's and cross your t's, and
everything shows up on the screen in just the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WHITEBD0 (63770 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  For now, both Mimio and eBeam connect to a PC via a standard
serial cable, though both companies are working on future &LR; 
 &LR; versions that will use the newer Universal Serial Bus connection
first and eventually communicate wirelessly. Software on the PC
displays whatever is written on the whiteboard in real time, but
also saves it for later replay, editing and transmission to others.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Both products also come with software that lets remote users
watch the whiteboard in real time over the Internet. Virtual Ink
relies on Microsoft's NetMeeting software, already used in many
companies for long-distance collaboration, to transmit the data,
though users see it displayed in the Mimio application. EFI's sends
the data over the Internet itself, without using NetMeeting.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies permit their customers to distribute copies of
the software to an unlimited number of users.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mimio and eBeam are also easily portable, so employees can
carry them to client sites and off-site conferences. Each product
can be used with any Windows laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Early users say setup is quick and easy. ``It was probably 10
minutes from the time it arrived until we had it up and running,''
said eBeam user Chris Ziener of Noonetime, cq &LR;  a Denver consulting
company. ``And so far I haven't run into anything about that hasn't
worked as advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Ziener got his unit for testing just last week, he said, but he's
already taking it along on client calls, packed in its own
12-inch-by-12-inch-by-3-inch carrying case. At the office he has
he's  &LR; hooked up the eBeam to a large glass window _ because the
window is bigger than his whiteboard and the product works equally
well on the glass, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Brislawn, a Seattle attorney, is equally pleased with the
Mimio prototype he has he's  &LR; been using since last May. ``I love
it,'' he said. ``This is stellar technology.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Brislawn has already used the product in connection with a
projector that puts the contents of his laptop, relayed from the
whiteboard, onto a large display screen, and he's looking forward
to hooking it up with video-conferencing hardware and software,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WHITEBD0 (63770 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  So is Steve Feinstein, a senior analyst on the Web infrastructure
team at Sybase in Emeryville. His group already holds a weekly
video conference with another Sybase team in Concord, Mass.
Starting today, they'll use a Mimio at the Emeryville end, and
after preliminary testing last week, Feinstein said he's seriously
considering ordering another for the Concord staff.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The big benefit for us,'' he said, ``is that we'll have a
record of what we write on the board.'' Users can cut and paste
notes and sketches from the saved Mimio file into e-mail or
standard office applications, or even convert them it &LR;   &LR; into a Web
page.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Virtual Ink also provides a program called MimioMouse, which
converts a whiteboard into a giant point-and-click Windows display
_ in effect, a touch screen _ when a projector is attached to the
PC and pointed at the whiteboard.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink also plans to announce a free software development
kit that will allow developers to create new applications for the
Mimio, such as using sections of the whiteboard as a controller for
lighting, heating and speaker systems.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink has raised more than $10 million in venture capital
since it was formed two years ago by engineers from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of WHITEBD0 (63770 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
