<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELITE'S CHOICE WINS HUGE VICTORY IN MEXICO PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Franciso Labastida Ochoa, the candidate of the
establishment in Mexico's governing party, won a decisive victory
on Sunday in the party's first presidential primary election, rapid
vote counts and early official returns showed. But his main
opponent moved to open a battle over the results.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address to the nation after the polls closed,
President Ernesto Zedillo said his party's first competitive
primary had been generally orderly and ``genuinely democratic,''
and would ``without a doubt strengthen the democracy of the nation
as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   With 27 percent of the votes counted, Labastida was winning 248
out of 300 electoral districts, while his chief rival, Roberto
Madrazo Pintado, was trailing far behind with only 22 districts.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has a strong chance of winning the presidential
election next July 2 because opposition voters are divided between
two major parties that have failed to form a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo campaign officials held a news conference right after
the polls closed at 6 p.m. to declare their candidate the winner.
Madrazo, the former governor of Tabasco state, has long experience
at fighting tenaciously when he is behind in a race, and he seemed
to be preparing for a confrontation with Labastida and party
authorities to challenge the outcome of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The primary broke with seven decades of authoritarian tradition
in which the incumbent president hand-picked his successor in a
ritual known as the finger-tap. Despite the contention over the
results, the vote was regarded across the political spectrum as a
historic advance toward democracy in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who made the decision to abandon the old practice and
allow Mexican voters to choose his party's candidate, held up two
fingers after he cast his own ballot on Sunday morning. ``This
finger is a thing of the past,'' he said, waving the index finger
he opted not to use to tap the presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have this one,'' Zedillo added, showing the indelible
black ink on his thumb that showed he had voted in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo revealed in his speech that to ensure his neutrality, he
had marked the names of all the candidates on the ballot, knowing
that it would invalidate his vote. Throughout the campaign he
insisted that he was not backing any of the four candidates. But
Labastida's rivals bitterly questioned the fairness of the race,
charging that the party establishment had thrown its power behind
the former Cabinet minister, believing him to have Zedillo's
support.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 57, served as Zedillo's interior minister, the
highest Ccabinet minister, and has had a steady 37-year career in
government posts. He promised gradual reforms to make the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, less corrupt
and more democratic, and greater spending on social programs for
the working class if he becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, by contrast, presented himself as a rebel who would
make sweeping changes to break the hold of the Mexico City
political elite on the party. The PRI has won every presidential
race in Mexico since its founding in 1929, making it the world's
longest-ruling party. It has been weakened by spectacular
corruption and disastrous economic management by recent presidents.
</P>
<P>
   For the PRI, which achieved many of its past electoral victories
by sophisticated methods of fraud and coercion, mounting a clean
primary was a special challenge. The party spent $3.3 million to
organize a vote almost as ambitious as a presidential election,
with 64,200 polling stations nationwide and more than 450,000
people involved as officials and poll watchers. Any Mexican
registered to vote was allowed to participate, whether a PRI member
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Gutierrez Barrios, the veteran PRI politician in charge
of ensuring an honest primary, said fraud was ``almost
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Also running were Manuel Bartlett Diaz, 63, a former governor of
Puebla state, and Humberto Roque Villanueva, 55, a former president
of the party. They were expected to draw small percentages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to two surveys of voters by TV Azteca and Televisa,
the two major television networks, voters in Mexico City strongly
favored Jesus Silva Herzog, a former ambassador to the United
States, to be the PRI candidate for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Party members savored their first chance to have a real say in
picking the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not imposing leaders anymore,'' said Pedro Corro
Garcia, a 23-year-old engineering student whose family included
several generations of PRI followers. ``They are letting us
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI elections officials said the voting was orderly in most
places, but they reported some ``marginal incidents'' of
irregularities. In a rural village in Puebla, Bartlett's home
state, ballots for four polling stations were burned, apparently by
opponents of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mexico City suburb of Villa Coapa, predawn raiders, also
apparently from opposition groups, stole all of the ballots from
one polling station, PRI officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints flowed in from Madrazo followers around the
country that PRI officials had dispensed handouts of food and
promises of government aid, and in some cases resorted to overt
threats, to get PRI followers to turn out and vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   In one town in the state of Queretaro, the PRI mayor threatened
to fire six employees who planned to turn out as poll watchers for
Madrazo, according to Jacaranda Pineda Chavez, a state deputy who
supports Madrazo. Only one stayed home on Sunday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Andres Tuxtla, a town in the Gulf Coast state of
Veracruz, an official in charge of a federal aid program for the
lowest-income families warned that they might lose their assistance
if they failed to support Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see where their fanaticism for Labastida has taken them,''
Carmen Sanchez Llano, 30, a dentist who supports Madrazo, said by
telephone from the town.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo gave no sign that he would give up easily and seemed to
be preparing to try to prove to PRI elections authorities that he
had won and, failing that, to assail the election with dozens of
formal complaints.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, Madrazo's campaign violated PRI bylaws by
sending e-mail messages with results of impromptu polls showing him
in the lead. Right after the polls closed in Mexico City, he sent
out a bulletin announcing that he had won 139 districts while
Labastida had won only 69.
</P>
<P>
   In a message directed at Madrazo without mentioning him by name,
Zedillo called on the losing candidates to ``accept the results
with the same democratic conviction with which they participated in
the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo campaign officials said there was little chance that he
or his followers would leave the party even if he suffered a
conclusive defeat. Instead, Madrazo seemed to be paving the way for
a tough negotiation with Labastida for positions of power within
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we leave a party that is just as much ours as
theirs?'' said Jose Alberto Aguilar, an adviser to Madrazo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-07-99 2356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991107.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-07 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2276 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WHITE-BOARD_SFCHRON &LR;      11-07 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-BOARD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   By Henry Norr &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The whiteboard, staple of so many meetings in organizations
large and small, is entering the Internet age.
<P>
   Virtual Ink, a Cambridge, Mass., startup, last month began
shipping a $499 product, called Mimio, that transmits anything
written on a standard whiteboard to the screen of a nearby PC and
from there over the Internet to the screens of other users anywhere
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Electronics for Imaging of Foster City will announce its
similarly priced entry, called eBeam.
</P>
<P>
   Specialized whiteboards capable of saving scribbled meeting
notes and drawings in digital form have been available for years.
But except for some very small models, they cost well over $1,000
and are small and heavy, compared to their conventional cousins.
Most also require special procedures that cramp some presenters'
style, such as requiring the user to push a button to change
colors.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of the two new products is that they work with almost
all of the 40 million to 80 million conventional whiteboards
already in use around the world _ even with ordinary dry-ink
markers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as you can call any product a breakthrough, this is
one,'' said Martin Reynolds, vice president of Dataquest, a San
Jose market research company, who so far seen only the eBeam. ``A
lot of good work gets done on whiteboards, and this finally makes
it easy to save and share it.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink's hardware consists of a 24-inch-long ``capture
bar'' that attaches to the top of any whiteboard up to 4 feet by 8
feet in size. EFI's eBeam provides two small pods that go in the
corners of a board up to the same dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies also provide plastic sleeves that fit around
conventional marking pens. They use a combination of infrared and
ultrasound signals, sent from the pen sleeves to the capture bar or
pods, to track the pens' location as the user writes or draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found particularly impressive (about the eBeam) was the
astounding accuracy,'' Reynolds said. ``You can write across the
board, then go back to dot your i's and cross your t's, and
everything shows up on the screen in just the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, both Mimio and eBeam connect to a PC via a standard
serial cable, though both companies are working on future &LR; 
 &LR; versions that will use the newer Universal Serial Bus connection
first and eventually communicate wirelessly. Software on the PC
displays whatever is written on the whiteboard in real time, but
also saves it for later replay, editing and transmission to others.
</P>
<P>
   Both products also come with software that lets remote users
watch the whiteboard in real time over the Internet. Virtual Ink
relies on Microsoft's NetMeeting software, already used in many
companies for long-distance collaboration, to transmit the data,
though users see it displayed in the Mimio application. EFI's sends
the data over the Internet itself, without using NetMeeting.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies permit their customers to distribute copies of
the software to an unlimited number of users.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mimio and eBeam are also easily portable, so employees can
carry them to client sites and off-site conferences. Each product
can be used with any Windows laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Early users say setup is quick and easy. ``It was probably 10
minutes from the time it arrived until we had it up and running,''
said eBeam user Chris Ziener of Noonetime, a Denver consulting
company. ``And so far I haven't run into anything about that hasn't
worked as advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziener got his unit for testing just last week, he said, but
he's already taking it along on client calls, packed in its own
12-inch-by-12-inch-by-3-inch carrying case. At the office he has
hooked up the eBeam to a large glass window _ because the window is
bigger than his whiteboard and the product works equally well on
the glass, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Brislawn, a Seattle attorney, is equally pleased with the
Mimio prototype he has been using since last May. ``I love it,'' he
said. ``This is stellar technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Brislawn has already used the product in connection with a
projector that puts the contents of his laptop, relayed from the
whiteboard, onto a large display screen, and he's looking forward
to hooking it up with video-conferencing hardware and software,
too.
</P>
<P>
   So is Steve Feinstein, a senior analyst on the Web
infrastructure team at Sybase in Emeryville. His group already
holds a weekly video conference with another Sybase team in
Concord, Mass. Starting today, they'll use a Mimio at the
Emeryville end, and after preliminary testing last week, Feinstein
said he's seriously considering ordering another for the Concord
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big benefit for us,'' he said, ``is that we'll have a
record of what we write on the board.'' Users can cut and paste
notes and sketches from the saved Mimio file into e-mail or
standard office applications, or even convert them into a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink also provides a program called MimioMouse, which
converts a whiteboard into a giant point-and-click Windows display
_ in effect, a touch screen _ when a projector is attached to the
PC and pointed at the whiteboard.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink also plans to announce a free software development
kit that will allow developers to create new applications for the
Mimio, such as using sections of the whiteboard as a controller for
lighting, heating and speaker systems.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Ink has raised more than $10 million in venture capital
since it was formed two years ago by engineers from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
